致我的父母

To my parents

露露

Lulu

我们的出生时间是经过精心预测的，冬日剖腹产的时间恰逢冯医生的午休时间。医生先把我拉了出来，气愤、大骂，就像酒店客人在退房前不熟练地被唤醒和翻腾一样。她紧随其后，而且非常安静，起初他们担心她根本没有呼吸。然后他们拍打她的背，她的哭声加入了我的哭声，他们把我们，男孩和女孩，并排放在一起，这两个水下生物突然被迫让我们的肺部充满寒冷、干燥的空气。

The hour of our birth had been carefully forecast, a winter’s day cesarean timed to coincide with Dr. Feng’s lunch break. The doctor pulled me out first, indignant, squalling, like a hotel guest inexpertly roused and tossed before checkout. She came next, and was so perfectly quiet that at first they worried she wasn’t breathing at all. Then they thwacked her on the back and her cries joined mine and they laid us side by side, boy and girl, two underwater creatures suddenly forced to fill our lungs with cold, dry air.

冯医生为我母亲做了手术，是为了帮我叔叔（他的老同学）的忙。否则我们就会出生在街边的一家医院里，那里有一名妇女去年因剖腹产失败而失血过多而死。一家人在候诊室里待了几个小时，最后准爸爸敲响了手术室的门。当没有人回应时，家人把门推开，发现这名女子已经毫无生气地躺在桌子上，血泊在地上。她孤身一人：手术出错后，工作人员就把墙上写有他们名字的医疗证明剥了下来，然后就逃跑了。

Dr. Feng had operated on my mother as a favor to my uncle, his old classmate. Otherwise we would have been born in the hospital down the street, where a woman had bled to death after a botched cesarean the previous year. The family had been in the waiting room for hours, and at last the father-to-be pounded on the doors of the operating room. When no one responded, the family pushed them open to find the lifeless woman on the table, blood pooling on the ground. She was alone: the staff had stripped the medical certificates that bore their names from the wall and fled as soon as the surgery went wrong.

从一开始我们就很幸运，尤其是因为我们拥有彼此。作为双胞胎，我们没有受到政府计划生育政策的影响，两个眨眼的胎儿在子宫里漂浮。在我们生命的最初几周，我们的头骨在子宫里相互挤压时留下了匹配的凹痕，就像两块互锁的拼图。后来我们分开时，当我想起她时，有时我会用手摸后脑勺，就像在寻找幻肢一样。

From the start we were lucky, not least because we had each other. As twins we’d been spared the reach of the government’s family-planning policies, two winking fetuses floating in utero. For the first few weeks of our life, our skulls had matching indentations from where they’d been pressed against each other in the womb, like two interlocking puzzle pieces. Later in life when we were apart, I’d sometimes touch my hand to the back of my skull when I thought of her, as if seeking a phantom limb.

我们无论如何都不是一个非凡的家庭。我的母亲是一名仓库职员，我的父亲是一名政府卫生规划员。当我父亲四十七岁的时候，他的部门主管——一个充满幻想的人，曾经梦想成为一名艺术家——决定建造一座欧洲钟楼形状的公共厕所。他去过欧洲，厕所的干净和建筑的可爱给他留下了深刻的印象，并想将两者结合起来。和大多数艺术家一样，部门负责人的自尊心很脆弱，在我父亲对项目费用犹豫不决后不久，他就被解雇了。这是他一生中唯一的独立行为，也让他失去了职业生涯。

We weren’t in any way an extraordinary family. My mother worked as a warehouse clerk, my father a government sanitation planner. When my father was forty-seven, his division chief—​a fanciful man who had once dreamed of being an artist—​decided to build a public toilet in the shape of a European clock tower. He’d been to Europe and had been impressed by the cleanliness of the toilets and the loveliness of the architecture and wanted to combine the two. Like most artists, the division chief had a fragile ego, and shortly after my father balked at the project’s expense, he was fired. It was the sole act of independence he’d committed in his life, and it cost him his career.

厕所至今仍矗立在那里，它的拱形混凝土墙污迹斑斑，荒唐可笑，内部又冷又湿，就像管道内部一样，一只浇筑混凝土的鸟从塔顶跳下，仿佛被里面的竞争对手的鸟从窗外射出，事实上，整个厕所都在那里。结构闻起来像一个肮脏的鸟舍。“你不会认为它的建造成本是20万元，也可能没有，”露露说；其中大部分很可能最终落入了部门主管的口袋，艺术腐蚀了生活，生活腐蚀了艺术。

The toilet still stands there today, its vaulting concrete walls stained and ridiculous, the inside chilly and damp like the inside of a pipe, a bird of poured concrete plunging from the tower’s top as if being defenestrated by rival birds inside, and indeed the whole structure smells like a foul aviary. You wouldn’t think it cost 200,000 yuan to build, and probably it didn’t, Lulu said; most of it likely ended up in the division head’s pocket, art corrupting life, life corrupting art.

从她十岁起，我的父母就在露露的祭坛前供奉。她的早熟很早就表现出来了。就像一面旗帜在山顶上猛烈地飘扬。我们的父母都没有受过多少教育，当他们发现自己拥有这样一个女儿时，他们感到很惊讶。

From the time she was ten, my parents worshipped at Lulu’s altar. Her precocity was evident early on; it was like a flag being waved energetically from a mountaintop. Neither of our parents had much education, and it stunned them to find themselves in possession of such a daughter.

小时候，我们一起专心地玩耍。露露是一位伟大的游戏发明者，游戏中经常融入她最近读到的一切：有一天我们是臭虫，寻找合适的叶子产卵，另一天我们是逃离蒙古入侵者的牧民。她比我勇敢：有一次，住在我们对面的老妇人在楼下取邮件时把门半开着，我姐姐甚至偷偷溜进了她的公寓。

When we were small, we played devotedly together. Lulu was a great inventor of games, which often incorporated whatever she’d read most recently: one day we were stinkbugs, looking for the right leaf on which to lay our eggs, another we were herdsmen fleeing Mongolian invaders. She was braver than me: once, when the elderly woman who lived opposite us had left her door ajar while retrieving the mail downstairs, my sister even snuck into her apartment.

“里面全是报纸，堆得有你的头那么高了。”露露兴奋地说，她的眼睛闪闪发亮，冲了回来。“她的沙发上有一幅巨大的橙色十字绣，上面有一朵牡丹和六条鱼。”

“It’s full of newspapers, stacked as high as your head,” Lulu said excitedly, her eyes glowing as she dashed back. “There’s a giant orange cross-stitch on her couch, with a peony and six fishes.”

小时候她总是读书。即使在吃饭的时候，她也会坐下来浏览果汁盒的背面。她一定读过一百万遍：阿斯巴甜、黄原胶和红一号。9. 这不是有意识的事情；而是有意识的事情。当她的眼睛没有固定在书页上时，她似乎会感到不舒服。她也对清单有狂热。十一岁时，她就记住了人体的每一块骨头，晚上当我把枕头放在头上时，她常常用一种怪异的声音向我背诵它们的名字：胸骨、胫骨、漂浮的肋骨。

As a child she was always reading. Even at meals she would sit and scan the back of the juice box. She must have read it a million times: aspartame and xanthan gum and red no. 9. It wasn’t a conscious thing; she just seemed to feel uncomfortable when her eyes weren’t fastened to a page. She had a mania for lists, too. By age eleven she’d memorized every bone in the human body, and she used to recite their names to me at night in an eerie voice as I held a pillow over my head: sternum, tibia, floating rib.

高中时，我通过玩电子游戏来反抗她的才华，玩很多电子游戏，花几个小时在尘土飞扬的土地上来回挥动枪，除了那些想杀你的人之外，没有人。朋友行健的公寓里通常有六七个人，我们轮流互相加油。我们是一支军队，无敌，或者如果我们不是无敌的，我们可以随时重播，这非常接近同一件事。

In high school, I rebelled against her brilliance by playing video games, lots of them, spending hours whipping a gun back and forth across dusty landscapes empty of people, except for those who wanted to kill you. Usually there were six or seven of us at my friend Xingjian’s apartment, and we would take turns and cheer one another on. We were an army, invincible, or if we weren’t invincible we could hit replay at any time, which was pretty close to the same thing.

而露露则是模范生中的模范。她学习如此专注，以至于她的身体变得弓着背，筋疲力尽，就像一名每天跑马拉松的运动员一样，晚上她一言不发地睡着了。我母亲给她喂的是炖蘑菇，蘑菇的茎脱落后看起来就像小大脑；它们对露露的学习有好处，她说。她也给了我一些，尽管那时很明显，学术荣耀的希望都落在她的女儿身上，而不是她的儿子身上，蘑菇的建设性作用见鬼去吧。

Lulu, meanwhile, was a model among model students. She studied so intensely that it left her physically bowed and exhausted, like an athlete running a daily marathon, and at night she dropped off to sleep without a word. My mother fed her stewed mushrooms that looked like tiny brains when their stems fell off; they would be good for Lulu’s studies, she said. She gave me some as well, though by then it was plain that any hopes for academic glory resided with her daughter, not her son, constructive effects of mushrooms be damned.

当我们参加高考时，露露的成绩足够高，可以在乘坐公共汽车、火车和飞机的情况下进入首都的一所大学，这一点没有人感到惊讶。母亲为她所说的幸福而哭泣。“一个学者，”她一直说。“一个学者。” 她喜欢提醒我们，她和我父亲在去工厂工作之前没有学习多久。

When we sat for the college entrance exam, it surprised no one that Lulu scored high enough to earn a place at a university in the nation’s capital, a bus and a train and a plane ride away. My mother wept with what she said was happiness. “A scholar,” she kept saying. “A scholar.” She and my father, she liked to remind us, hadn’t studied long before going to work in the factories.

“我们非常自豪，”我父亲告诉露露。他的表情很强烈，让我感到不安。我们的一本教科书中有一幅黑白插图，画的是一位很久以前的太监在宴席上，饥肠辘辘地盯着皇帝桌上的食物，我父亲的脸上也有这样的表情。

“We are so proud,” my father told Lulu. There was an intensity to his expression that unnerved me. One of our schoolbooks had a black-and-white illustration of a long-ago eunuch serving a feast, staring hungrily at the food on the emperor’s table, and there was something of that look on my father’s face.

露露飞出的那天晚上，天气阴沉，黎明前的暮色呈现出一种奇特的橙色和赭石色的混合色。那天早些时候，我父亲送给她一份礼物：她自己的笔记本电脑。它充满了希望，就像一块厚厚的蛋糕，外面包裹着蓝色的塑料。它不像我们共用的旧电脑，它时断时续、停滞不前，按键上粘满了油脂、面包屑和头发碎片。这把钥匙一碰就会乖乖地松开。我羡慕地看着它，也充满了对言语的渴望。“别担心——当你离开时，你也会得到一个，一模一样的，”我父亲说。

The night Lulu flew out was overcast, the twilight that preceded it a peculiar mix of orange and ocher. Earlier that day, my father had given her a gift: her very own laptop. It was thick with promise, like a fat slice of cake, sheathed in blue plastic. It wasn’t like the old computer that we all shared, which stuttered and stalled, keys sticky with grease and crumbs and bits of hair. This one had keys that yielded obediently when you touched them. I’d stared at it enviously, too filled with longing for words. “Don’t worry—​you’ll get one, too, when you leave, the exact same,” my father said.

在机场，我们的父母做出了适合被遗弃在边境的难民的表情。“露露，乖一点，”我们的父亲说。我尴尬地站在那里，有点怨恨。露露在通过安检时转身打出和平手势，我们看着她的粉色连帽衫和条纹斑马棒球帽退入人群，直到她消失。

At the airport, our parents assumed expressions appropriate for refugees being abandoned at a border. “Lulu, be good,” our father said. I stood there awkwardly, a little resentfully. Lulu turned and flashed a peace sign as she went through security, and we watched her pink hoodie and striped zebra baseball hat retreat into the crowd until she was gone.

一周后，我就出发去上大学了，没有那么大张旗鼓。学校距离学校只有一个小时的车程，给人一种空虚的感觉，仿佛它是多年前雄心勃勃地建立起来的，然后就被遗忘了。冬天，宿舍里很冷，就好像混凝土墙挡住了所有潮湿、寒冷的空气，让它紧贴着你的皮肤。它看起来像是一座足够令人信服的建筑，但感觉就像一个帐篷。

I departed for college a week later, with considerably less fanfare. The school was just an hour’s drive away and had an empty feel to it, as though it had been erected with much ambition years ago and then forgotten. In the winter the dorms were freezing, as if their concrete walls held in all the damp, cold air and kept it close to your skin; it looked like a convincing enough building, but felt like a tent.

我认为大学最好的一点就是宿舍里有互联网。我二楼的房间里还有另外五个男孩，共用一张摇摇晃晃的金属双层床，上面挂着蚊帐，这样既提供了一点隐私感，又可以在夏天防止叮咬。晚上，当我们坐在电脑前时，你可以听到我们周围同样微弱的聊天警报声，从地板、天花板和墙壁发出，就好像成群看不见的电子蟋蟀袭击了这座大楼。

The best thing about college, I decided, was that the dorms were wired for the internet. There were five other boys in my room on the second floor, sharing rickety metal bunk beds draped with mosquito nets, which afforded both a thin sense of privacy and protection from bites in the summer. At night when we sat in front of our computers, you could hear the same tinny chirping of chat alerts all around us, emanating from the floorboards, the ceilings, and the walls, as though hordes of invisible, electronic crickets had stormed the building.

我还没有到想念露露的年龄。不管怎样，每当我登录我的新笔记本电脑时，我都可以看到她的聊天状态，它光滑闪亮，装在与我姐姐的相配的蓝色塑料套中。他们可能会说，学习。去上课了。在某些时候，他们变得更加幻想。顺着绿色的河流漂流而下，有人在阅读。挖掘没有边缘的石头。有时，我在等待我的玩家队友登录时尝试查找它们。其中一些属于老诗人，但其余的，我怀疑，是她自己发明的。

I wasn’t old enough to miss Lulu. Anyway, I could see her chat statuses whenever I logged in on my new laptop, smooth and shiny and housed in a blue plastic sleeve that matched my sister’s. Studying, they might say. Going to class. At some point they got more fanciful. Floating down the green river, one read. Digging into a stone with no edges. Sometimes I tried looking them up while waiting for my gamer teammates to log on. A few belonged to old poets, but the rest, I suspected, she was inventing herself.

那学期我死了好几次，但积累了几百金币，先是术士，然后是法师。我宿舍里的其他男孩也都是瘾君子，我们戴着耳机，激烈地玩到晚上，咒骂，直到午夜，电源被切断。课程是一件微不足道的事情：重要的是你期末考试的成绩，而这些成绩可以通过记住高年级学生出售的十到十五页影印笔记来轻松填满。老实说，我不知道谁真正去上课：我想象老师们拿着笔记本电脑坐在空荡荡的房间前，一只眼睛盯着时钟，也许在玩自己的电子游戏，也许在小睡。

I died repeatedly that semester, but amassed several hundred gold coins and was first made a warlock, then a mage. The other boys in my dorm were addicts, too, and we played fiercely into the evening, cussing, headphones on, until midnight, when the power was cut. Classes were a negligible affair: what mattered were your grades on the final exams, and those could be readily crammed for by memorizing ten or fifteen photocopied pages of notes sold by upperclassmen. Honestly, I had no idea who actually went to class: I pictured teachers sitting with their laptops in front of empty rooms, one eye on the clock, maybe playing video games of their own, maybe taking a nap.

大二的时候，我闲着没事找露露的一个状态，只找到一个结果：一条公众微博，头像是一只打哈欠的黄猫。有几十个帖子，大部分都是露露在她的状态下发布的相同类型的诗歌片段，当我滚动完它们时，我确信这个帐户是她的。她在简历中写了“求是”，引用了共产党的老格言“实事求是”，但她的帐户名称是“求是” ， “寻求碳水化合物”，这让我笑了。你不会怀疑露露是个贪吃者——她可以毫不犹豫地吃下大量的面条或油条。

In our second year of school, I searched idly for one of Lulu’s statuses and found just one result: a public microblog with a profile photo of a yawning yellow cat. There were several dozen posts, mostly the same kinds of snippets of poetry Lulu had been posting to her statuses, and by the time I finished scrolling through them, I was sure the account was hers. For the bio she’d written qiushi, a reference to the old Communist maxim “to seek truth from facts,” but the name of her account was qiu zhushi, “to seek carbohydrates,” which made me laugh. You wouldn’t have suspected it to look at her, but Lulu was a glutton—​she could eat reams of noodles or fried crullers without missing a beat.

有一天，在宿舍里，我敲响了门，发现一位同学对我咧着嘴笑。“你姐姐在这里，”他说。我张口结舌，下了楼。她就在那里，穿着一件老式的蓝色棉袄，五十年代常见的那种。露露把头发扎成两条辫子，肩上挎着一个背包，微笑着。她说，她加入了大学辩论俱乐部，他们正在旅行参加一场比赛。“大哥，”她说——这是她的一个老笑话，因为我只比她早出生一分钟左右——“想请我吃晚饭吗？”

One day in the dorm, I answered a knock at our door to find a classmate grinning at me. “Your sister’s here,” he said. I gaped and went downstairs. There she was, wearing an old-fashioned padded blue coat, the kind common in the fifties. Lulu had her hair in two braids, carried a knapsack slung over one shoulder, and was smiling. She’d joined the college debate club, she said, and they were traveling for a competition. “Big Brother,” she said—​it was an old joke of hers, since I was born only a minute or so before her—​“want to buy me dinner?”

我建议去自助餐厅。她说她有更好的想法，然后挽着我的手臂去了校园入口处的一家咖啡店。这个地方自称为“Pretty OJ”；它的招牌上写着意大利面条。我路过几十次，但从来没有进去过。里面的桌子上铺着玻璃，座位是白色柳条制成的，不舒服，当你移动时，座位会发出噼啪声，还有与之相配的白色花瓶，里面装满了塑料花。露露接过菜单，自信地为我们点了一份披萨和番茄意大利面，就好像她以前做过很多次一样。“请喝咖啡，”她补充道，“给我们拿点面包来。”

I suggested the cafeteria. She said she had something nicer in mind, and took me by the arm to a coffee shop by the campus entrance. The place called itself Pretty O.J.; its sign advertised Italian noodles. I’d walked by dozens of times and never gone in. Inside, the tables were topped with glass and the seats were an uncomfortable white wicker that crackled when you shifted, and there were white vases to match, filled with plastic flowers. Lulu took hold of the menu and confidently ordered a pizza and tomato pasta for us as though she’d done it many times before. “With coffee, please,” she added, “and bring us some bread.”

我盯着她。“你看起来很高兴，”我说。她。她说，她正在向南一小时车程的一所大学进行辩论，并乘公共汽车来看我。我问她我们的父母是否知道，她是否也打算去见他们。

I stared at her. “You look happy,” I said. She was. She was debating at a college an hour’s drive south, she said, and had taken a bus to come to see me. I asked her if our parents knew, if she was planning to see them as well.

“不，”她微笑着说。“我们明天晚上飞回来，但我想来看你。”

“No,” she said, smiling. “We fly back tomorrow night, but I wanted to come see you.”

在她身边，我穿着橡胶凉鞋、T 恤和短裤，感觉自己非常年轻。她询问我的课程和朋友的情况。我告诉她我在笔记本电脑上看很多电视，玩更多电子游戏。最近我和一支由俄罗斯青少年组成的球队一起比赛，他们都非常出色。我们说的语言不同，所以我们用一种洋泾浜英语进行交流：别担心，伙计们，我有幻影公主，不不不，你这个菜鸟，dafuq。

Beside her I felt very young in my rubber sandals and T-shirt and shorts. She asked me about my classes and my friends. I told her that I was watching a lot of television on my laptop and playing even more video games. Lately I’d been playing with a team of Russian teenagers who were pretty good. We didn’t speak the same language, so we communicated in a kind of pidgin English: Don’t worry guys I got phantom princess no no no, you NOOB, dafuq.

“我知道你认为这是浪费时间，”我说。

“I know you think it’s a waste of time,” I said.

“我的学校里也有很多孩子玩这个游戏，”她说道，并没有反驳我。

“A lot of kids play it at my school, too,” she said, not contradicting me.

“你知道，现在这是一种职业，”我说。“他们有比赛，你可以赢得大奖。”

“It’s a profession now, you know,” I said. “They have competitions, you can win big prize money.”

现在我很尴尬地意识到，在那之前，我们整个晚上都在谈论我的生活。我想我没有问过她任何关于她自己的事情，直到最后她才自愿提供了一些事实。她说，她怀孕了两个月，并且非常爱孩子的父亲。

It embarrasses me now to realize that up until that point, we’d spent the whole evening talking about my life. I don’t think I asked her anything about her own, and it was only at the end that she volunteered a few facts. She was pregnant, she said, two months along, and very much in love with the baby’s father.

我被咖啡噎住了。露露等我平静下来，然后告诉我接下来的故事。父亲是东北贫困县人，学会计的高年级学生。不，他们没有留下孩子，尽管她和张伟可能会在几年后再次怀孕，“我们结婚后，”露露说，平静的事实让我震惊。有一天，他们两个希望能够出国旅游。

I choked on the coffee. Lulu waited for me to compose myself, and then she told me the rest of the story. The father, an upperclassman studying accounting, was from a poor county in the northeast. No, they weren’t keeping the baby, though she and Zhangwei would likely get pregnant again in a few years, “after we’re married,” Lulu said, with a calm matter-of-factness that astounded me. Someday, the two of them hoped to travel abroad.

她向我详细介绍了他，措辞谨慎。“他和其他人不一样，”她说。“他非常高贵。” 这是一个奇怪的词，一个老式的词。我只是盯着她。

She told me more about him, choosing her words carefully. “He’s not like other people,” she said. “He’s very noble.” It was a strange word, an old-fashioned word. I just stared at her.

“你确定这一切吗，露露？”

“You’re sure about all this, Lulu?”

“我敢肯定。”

“I’m sure.”

我有一瞬间羡慕她，坐在那里，看上去那么笃定。我什么时候对任何事情有过确定性？对于露露来说，一切都来得如此轻松和自信：作业、考试答案、大学，现在看来，爱情也是如此。

I envied her for a moment, sitting there, looking so certain. When had I ever been sure of anything? For Lulu, everything had always come so easily and confidently: homework, answers on tests, college, and now, it seemed, love as well.

账单到了的时候，我身上的钱不够，所以她付了钱。“谢谢大哥，”我们离开时她说道，起初我以为她是在讽刺，但当她说这句话时，她看起来很高兴。“我没有告诉任何人，”当我们走进蓝色的暮色和周围校园四四方方的混凝土外墙时，她承认道。“我知道我可以信任你。”

When the bill arrived, I didn’t have enough money with me, so she paid. “Thanks, Big Brother,” she said when we left, and at first I thought she was being sarcastic, but she looked glad when she said it. “I haven’t told anyone else,” she confessed as we walked out into the blue twilight, the boxy concrete façades of campus around us. “I knew I could trust you.”

这是我第一次意识到自己是值得信赖的，听到我接受了评估并且没有发现自己的不足，我感到很欣慰。“当然，”我说。

It was the first time it had occurred to me that I was trustworthy, and it was a relief to hear that I had been evaluated and not found wanting. “Of course,” I said.

在接下来的几个月里，我更频繁地查看她的账户。通过这种方式，我对她的生活有了一些闪现的洞察：春天盛开的黄色连翘的照片，还有更多奇怪的诗歌。我想象她在全国各地敲击着她那台一模一样的蓝色笔记本电脑，点击发送。

In the following months, I checked her account more often. I got flashes of insight into her life that way: photos of the yellow shocks of forsythia that blossomed in the spring, more odd bits of poetry. I pictured her tapping away at her identical blue-sheathed laptop across the country, clicking send.

那年秋天，她开始每天发布有关一个名叫徐雷的人的帖子。那时连我都听说过这个名字，有足够多的人在谈论他。他是一名大学生，在一家卡拉 OK 店外被警察抓走，遭到殴打，并在拘留期间死亡。他去世前的照片在网上流传：穿着短裤、戴着眼镜、穿着写着“走吧”的紫色T恤的瘦腿。他和他的朋友唱完卡拉OK后站在外面，有点醉了，当警察让他们走开时，徐雷变得刻薄，警察感到生气。他的朋友们拍摄到他们殴打他，然后把他装进警车。审查人员撤下这段视频后，它又被重新上传。

That fall, she started posting daily about someone named Xu Lei. It was a name that even I’d heard by then, enough people were talking about him. He was a college student who’d been picked up by the police outside a karaoke joint, and been beaten, and died while in custody. Photos of him before his death had circulated online: skinny legs in shorts, glasses, a purple T-shirt that read LET’S GO. He and his friends had been standing outside after singing karaoke, a little drunk, and when police had told them to move along, Xu Lei got caustic and the officers took offense. His friends had filmed them beating him and then loading him into a police van. As quickly as censors took down the footage, it was uploaded again.

大多数情况下，露露只是转发别人的信息，添加她自己的标签，#justiceforXuLei，或者一张愤怒的、皱着眉头的脸。在某个时候，她添加了自己的评论：这个国家，这些警察，简直太黑暗了。

Mostly Lulu was just recirculating other people’s messages, adding her own hashtag, #justiceforXuLei, or an indignant, frowning face. At some point she added her own commentary: This country, these police, are simply too dark.

警方尸检结果出来后发现，徐雷死于心脏病。这个结论很快就遭到了蔑视——他只有十八岁。验尸官的报告称，他死前一直在努力工作，睡眠质量不好。“这是一个年轻人的心脏病发作，”它的结论是，这句话很快在网上流行起来，直到审查机构将其取缔。露露没有留下深刻的印象。“我一生都在努力学习，但我却睡不好，”她写道。我也会心脏病发作吗？

When the police autopsy came out, it found that Xu Lei had died of a heart attack. The conclusion was promptly met with scorn—​he was only eighteen. The coroner’s report said that prior to his death, he’d been working hard and not sleeping well. “It was a young person’s heart attack,” it concluded, a phrase that quickly trended online until censors snuffed it out. Lulu was not impressed. I have studied hard all my life and I don’t sleep well, she wrote. Will I, too, be made to have a heart attack?

此后，Lulu的账号变得更加活跃。起初，她只是转发其他账户的新闻：导致三名婴儿死亡的受污染配方奶粉丑闻、大学招生管理人员被发现收受现金贿赂——这些都是我们都知道并抱怨的事情。

After that, Lulu’s account became more active. At first she was just reposting news from other accounts: the tainted-formula scandal that killed three babies, the college admissions administrator found to be taking cash bribes—​the kinds of things we all knew and groused about.

然而几个月后，她的账户上开始充斥着真正令人惊讶的图片和视频。我不知道她从哪里得到它们。它们是来自全国各地的零星街头抗议活动，有些只是剧照，有些片段可能只有几秒钟，很少超过一分钟。湖北，泸州市，天北县，蒙山村：有人可能会说，10名村民在政府机关外抗议当地妇女的死亡。或者：山东彩光市泰宁县华旗村500名工人罢工三天，抗议拖欠工资。

A few months later, though, she began to flood her account with images and videos that were genuinely surprising. I had no idea where she was getting them. They were of scattered street protests from around the country, some just stills, others clips of perhaps a few seconds, rarely more than a minute long. Hubei, Luzhou City, Tianbei County, Mengshan Village: 10 villagers protest outside government offices over death of local woman, one might say. Or: Shandong, Caiguang City, Taining County, Huaqi Village: 500 workers strike for three days, protesting over unpaid wages.

这样的帖子有几十个，而且通常看起来都很相似：警察穿着淡蓝色衬衫，大声喊叫，人群聚集在街上，偶尔有人在地上被殴打。在一段视频中，几名男子试图翻倒一辆警车。另一张照片中，一群村民大喊大叫，看到一个看起来可怕的人形物体在地上闷烧。

There were dozens of these posts, and they usually looked similar: police in pale blue shirts, lots of shouting, crowds massing in the streets, occasionally someone on the ground being beaten. In one video, several men were attempting to tip over a police van. In another, a group of villagers was shouting as something that looked horribly like a human figure smoldered on the ground.

它们就像是从一个我从未见过的国家发来的消息，让我感到不安和困惑。

They were like dispatches from a country I had never seen, and they disturbed and confused me.

看到自焚视频后，我给她发了信息。你还好吗？我问。

After seeing the video of the self-immolation, I messaged her. Are you okay? I asked.

几个小时后收到回复：嗨，大哥！我很好。

The reply came a few hours later: Hi, Big Brother! I’m doing fine.

你在北京吗？

Are you in Beijing?

当然，我在北京。

Of course I’m in Beijing.

我盯着闪烁的光标。我从来没有告诉她我在网上知道她的身份，我担心如果我说了些什么，她会认为我不值得信任，就好像我一直在监视她一样。

I stared at the blinking cursor. I’d never told her that I knew her identity online, and I worried that if I said something, she’d see me as somehow untrustworthy, as though I’d been spying on her.

北京现在一定很冷，我最后写道。确保穿暖和的衣服。

Beijing must be very cold now, I wrote at last. Make sure you wear warm clothes.

那年二月，我们双双回家看望父母，过春节。我负责包饺子，切碎茴香和韭菜，打碎一个鸡蛋，兴致勃勃地把它转来转去。当时我很开心。前一周，我们队参加了当地的一场比赛，赢得了一个月的方便面供应量和一定的吹牛权。重播，重播：我的手指本能地熟悉这些命令，有时我会在黑暗中醒来，手指抽搐。

That February, we both went home to see our parents and celebrate the Spring Festival. I took charge of the dumplings, chopping the fennel and leeks, cracking an egg and swirling it about with gusto. I was happy. The week before, our team had entered into a local competition and had won a month’s supply of instant noodles and certain bragging rights. Replay, replay: my fingers knew the commands so instinctively that sometimes I’d wake in the dark with fingers twitching.

不过，露露似乎只是部分在场。通常你必须叫她的名字两次才能得到回应。有时我会在半夜起床去洗手间，看到客厅里有灯光，这意味着她醒了，并且正在上网。

Lulu, though, seemed only partly present; often you had to call her name twice to get a response. Sometimes I’d get up to use the bathroom in the middle of the night and see a glow in the living room, which meant she was awake, and online.

一天晚上，我们围在电视机前看春节联欢晚会。这是国家广播公司每年都会上演的传统：俗气的短剧、爱国颂歌、可怕的闹剧——全国都在观看。我告辞并登录查看露露的帐户。最近的帖子是那天晚上，就在我们坐下来吃晚饭之前。这是一行用引号引起来的文字：“如果你想了解自己的国家，那么你就已经踏上了犯罪之路，”上面写道。然后：同志们，春节快乐！

One night we gathered around the television watching the Spring Festival gala. It was an annual tradition put on by the state broadcaster: cheesy skits, patriotic odes, terrible slapstick—​the whole country watched. I excused myself and logged on to check Lulu’s account. The most recent post was from that evening, just before we had sat down to dinner. It was a line of text in quotation marks: “If you want to understand your own country, then you’ve already stepped on the path to criminality,” it read. And then: Happy Spring Festival, comrades!

我浑身一阵颤抖。我注销并走回客厅。我们的父母坐在沙发上，露露坐在他们旁边的凳子上，当我加入他们时，他们的脸在电视闪烁的灯光下显得苍白，偷偷地看了这个陌生的人，我的双胞胎妹妹。

A shiver ran through me. I logged off and walked back into the living room. Our parents sat on the couch, with Lulu on a stool beside them, their faces pallid in the television’s flickering light as I joined them, stealing glances at this strange person, my twin sister.

第二天，我们两个出去给妈妈买了一些食材：面粉、豆瓣酱、肉末。一起步行半英里去超市感觉很奇怪，这是自从她在大学拜访我以来我们第一次单独在一起。

The next day, the two of us went out to buy some ingredients for my mother: flour, fermented bean paste, ground pork. It felt odd to walk the half-mile to the supermarket together, the first time we’d been alone since she had visited me at college.

路上，我们经过了一个小时候玩耍的公园，现在可以听到那里有孩子的声音。天气晴朗，温暖抚平我的皮肤。

On the way, we passed a park where we used to play as children, and we could hear the sound of children there now. It was sunny, and the warmth lulled my skin.

“这句话是从哪里来的？” 我说。“昨晚的那个。”

“Where did that quote come from?” I said. “The one from last night.”

她继续走着。“你是什么意思？”

She kept walking. “What do you mean?”

“我一直在读你的账户。”

“I’ve been reading your account.”

“我不知道你在说什么。” 一个男人带着一只小狗走过，它的脸像香肠的根部一样皱起，当它经过时，露露对它偷笑。

“I don’t know what you’re talking about.” A man was walking by with a small dog, its face scrunched like the heel of a sausage, and Lulu nickered at it as it passed.

“来吧，露露。” 我停下脚步。“我很担心你。”

“Come on, Lulu.” I stopped walking. “I’m worried about you.”

她在我前面几英尺处停下来，站在那里，双臂交叉，没有看我。“你怎么知道？”

She stopped a few feet ahead of me and stood there, not looking at me, arms crossed. “How did you know?”

我解释了这首诗。“其他人知道是你吗？”

I explained about the poetry. “Do other people know it’s you?”

她耸耸肩。“一位教授。还有一些同学。” 当我追问她时，她不情愿地说，有同学向系主任举报了她，她的一位教授把她拉到一边，温和地警告她停止网上活动，以免“影响”她的未来。

She shrugged. “A professor. Some other students.” When I pressed her, she said reluctantly that a classmate had reported her to the department head, and that one of her professors had taken her aside and gently warned her that she should stop her activities online, lest it “influence” her future.

“你知道，他们是对的，”我说。“你不担心这会对你产生什么影响吗？” 我记得她发布的一个视频显示，一名妇女跪在地上哭泣，“政府是叛徒！政府不为人民服务！”

“They’re right, you know,” I said. “Don’t you worry about how this might affect you?” One of the videos she’d posted, I remembered, showed a woman kneeling on the ground and wailing, “The government are traitors! The government doesn’t serve the people!”

露露只是站在那里，盯着我们对面的小购物中心，似乎在努力记住它。这里有一家橙色快餐店、三个考试准备中心和两个房地产经纪人办公室。

Lulu just stood there, staring at the little shopping complex opposite us as if she were trying to memorize it. There was a bilious orange fast-food restaurant, three test-prep centers, and two real estate agents’ offices.

“还是我们的父母？” 我说。他们现在都退休了，但每个人都有一笔微薄的养老金，我想这些养老金可以被拿走，无论如何，露露前途的毁掉将是最大的损失。当我想到自己要独自养活他们的晚年时，我的胃就不高兴地吱吱作响。

“Or our parents?” I said. They’d both retired by now, but each had a modest pension that I imagined could be taken away, and anyway, the ruining of Lulu’s prospects would be the greatest loss of all. When I thought of having to support them on my own in their old age, my stomach creaked unhappily.

她点点头。“当然，”她最后说道。“我不傻。”

She nodded. “Of course,” she said, finally. “I’m not stupid.”

“那你就停下来吧？”

“So you’ll stop, then?”

她看了我一会儿，眼神有些恍惚。“你知道在宋朝，扔掉写有字的纸片是违法的吗？” 她说。“人们不得不去某些设有圣火的寺庙，在那里他们可以焚烧圣火。这就是他们对文字的尊重程度。”

She looked at me for a moment, a little dreamily. “Did you know in the Song Dynasty it was illegal to throw away any pieces of paper with writing on them?” she said. “People had to go to certain temples with sacred fires set up where they could burn them instead. That’s how much they revered the written word.”

我想摇晃她，但我没有。“我不明白这有什么关系。”

I wanted to shake her, but I didn’t. “I don’t see how that’s relevant.”

她又开始走路了。

She started walking again.

“你从哪里得到这些东西？” 我问。她微微挺身，解释说她下载了一个可以解锁海外网站的工具。“这并不难，”她说。“但是东西很快就会被删除，所以我必须不断地重新发布它们。”

“Where are you getting all this stuff?” I asked. She unbent slightly and explained that she had downloaded a tool that unblocked overseas websites. “It’s not hard,” she said. “But things get deleted quickly, so I have to keep reposting them.”

“我不知道会发生这样的事情，”她清醒地补充道。“我们很幸运。”

“I had no idea these kinds of things went on,” she added soberly. “We were lucky.”

“我们并不富有。”

“We weren’t rich.”

“爸爸在政府工作。我们很舒服。”

“Dad worked for the government. We were comfortable.”

我告诉她，我们当然是这样，但很多人也是这样，这并不意味着她必须让自己陷入麻烦。

Of course we were, I told her, but so were lots of people, and it didn’t mean that she had to expose herself to trouble.

“这比整天玩电子游戏要好，”她反驳道，突然对我很生气。“那有什么意义呢？”

“It’s better than just playing video games all day,” she shot back, suddenly angry with me. “What’s the point of that?”

我把手插在口袋里，耸耸肩，多吸了几口气让自己平静下来。看到露露生气很奇怪；她平时都是那么镇定自若。“这很公平，”我说。我们继续走着，没有看对方。在超市里，我们分手了，仿佛松了口气。

I stuck my hands in my pockets and shrugged, taking a few extra breaths to calm myself. It was strange to see Lulu angry; she was usually so even-keeled. “Fair enough,” I said. We kept walking, not looking at each other. Inside the supermarket we parted, as though with relief.

回到校园，春天给树上带来了半透明的白色芽，就像洋葱的小核。窗外的鸟儿变得吵闹、自以为是，整天叽叽喳喳、吵吵闹闹，让我难以入睡。露露已经停止发帖了，我很高兴看到。我开始在市中心的一家餐厅做兼职，这家餐厅提供大型、昂贵的宴会，帮助准备冷切肉、玻璃状胶原蛋白和装饰得像微型孔雀的褶边黄瓜片。我喜欢这种工作的节奏和重复，在晚上结束时洗漱并将东西放回原处时的满足感。

Back on campus, spring brought translucent white buds to the trees, like the tiny cores of onions. The birds grew noisy and self-righteous, clacking and clamoring at all hours outside my window, making it hard to sleep. Lulu had stopped posting, I was pleased to see. I began working part-time at a restaurant downtown that served large, expensive banquets, helping to prepare plates of cold chopped meats, glassy collagen, and frilly slices of cucumber dolled up to look like miniature peacocks. There was a rhythm and a repetition to the work that I liked, a sense of contentment in washing up at the night’s end and putting things back where they belonged.

五月的一天，就在毕业前夕，我再次查看了姐姐的账户。露露已经停止更新她的聊天状态：几个星期以来，它一直在显示，我开始担心。

One day in May, just before graduation, I checked back in on my sister’s account. Lulu had stopped updating her chat status: for several weeks, it had read simply out, and I’d grown worried.

就像几个月前一样：她又开始疯狂地发帖，就好像她失去了控制一样；她又开始疯狂地发帖了。仅一天之内，她就发布了四十三次。全国各地都有同样的抗议明信片，她之前分享过的视频和照片，还有很多简单的文字帖子，一个接一个： 凌晨 3:34：如果这个国家是一种植物，它就会成为一个腐烂的苦瓜。凌晨 3:36：我是一名政府环卫工人的女儿。我知道……的味道。凌晨3:37：对不起，朋友们，今天发了这么多帖子，有点累了。人这一生，也有很多美好的事情。然后她分享了一系列小山羊在空中跳跃的照片，小山羊的蹄子高高地踩在绿草上。凌晨 3:41：好吧，我已经足够安心去睡觉了。晚安，同志们，明天见。

It was as it had been months before: she’d gone back to posting frenetically, as though she’d lost control; in one day alone she had posted forty-three times. There were the same postcards of protests around the country, the videos and photographs she’d been sharing before, and a lot of simple text posts, too, one after another: 3:34 a.m.: If this country were a vegetable, it would be a rotten, bitter melon. 3:36 a.m.: I am the daughter of a government sanitation worker. I know the smell of s—. 3:37 a.m.: I’m sorry, friends, just a little tired today after so many posts. There are many beautiful things, too, in this life. And then she’d shared a series of pictures of small goats leaping in the air, tiny hoofs aloft against green grass. 3:41 a.m.: Okay, I am sufficiently soothed to go to sleep. Good night, comrades, until tomorrow.

这些帖子不断地涌现——自从我停止检查以来，已经积累了数千个帖子。我带着一种越来越强烈的恐惧感滚动着浏览它们，然后又翻了回去，感觉我的胃在翻腾：不知怎的，她已经积累了 800,000 名粉丝。

The posts went on and on—​thousands of them had accumulated in the time since I’d stopped checking. I scrolled through them with a mounting sense of horror, and then paged back up and felt my stomach flip: somehow she’d amassed 800,000 followers.

我疯狂地给她发信息，手指在键盘上乱抓。山羊？

I messaged her frantically, fingers scrabbling at the keys. Goats?

几个小时后，她回复了我。你喜欢他们吗？

A few hours later, she answered me. Did you like them?

他们没事。

They’re okay.

对不起，大哥。我无法停下来。

I’m sorry, Big Brother. I couldn’t stop.

我坐下来看着光标闪烁，就像缓慢的脉搏一样。

I sat and watched the cursor blink, like a slow pulse.

很多人都在关注你。我不知道我是否应该为她感到骄傲，为她担心，还是生她的气；我以为我就是三个人。

A lot of people are paying attention to you. I couldn’t tell if I should be proud of her, worried for her, or angry with her; I supposed I was all three.

是的，他们是。又是一阵长时间的沉默。别难过，大哥。我只是觉得这是我必须做的事情。你不同意吗？

Yes, they are. Another long silence. Don’t be upset, Big Brother. I just felt this was something I had to do. Don’t you agree?

我现在正在工作，我写信给她，希望她能感受到我的愤怒。迟到了，该走了。

I’m working now, I wrote her, hoping she could sense my anger. Running late, got to go.

毕业后，露露搬到北京与男友张伟同住。她创办了自己的匿名网站，源源不断地发布有关全国各地抗议和侵犯人权行为的新闻。有这样一个故事，一名妇女被警察殴打致死，她的女儿花钱将她的尸体在太平间冷冻了六年，不愿提供证据。有这样一个故事：村里的官员半夜拆毁了一位年迈祖母的家，为一座购物中心让路。屋顶倒塌时，她没有收到任何警告，就死在床上。每个帖子都有自己尖刻的标题：冰棒之母；沮丧的睡眠者。

After she graduated, Lulu moved in with her boyfriend, Zhangwei, in Beijing. She started her own anonymous website, a constant stream of news about protests and human rights abuses around the country. There was the story of a woman, beaten to death by police, whose daughter had paid to keep her body frozen in a morgue for six years, unwilling to inter the evidence. There was the story of the village where officials had torn down an elderly grandmother’s home in the middle of the night to make way for a shopping mall; she’d been given no warning and had died in her bed as the roof collapsed. Each post carried its own mordant title: THE MOTHER POPSICLE; THE FRUSTRATED SLEEPER.

一天晚上，他们来找她，来到她和张伟租的三楼公寓。他们毫无预兆地破门而入，并礼貌地告诉她，她应该和他们一起走。“肯定是房东给了他们钥匙，”她后来告诉我，很震惊。奇怪的是，正是这个特殊的细节似乎困扰着她。

They came for her one night, to the third-floor apartment that she and Zhangwei were renting. They burst in through the door without warning and informed her, politely, that she should go with them. “The landlord must have given them the key,” she told me later, stunned. It was that particular detail, oddly, that seemed to haunt her.

半夜时分，露露从警车里给我打电话，说她被带走了。“告诉我们的父母，”她说。“请。对不起。” 她的声音有些沙哑，我差点没认出来。她听起来就像一个在暴风雪中丢失了围巾的孩子。想到这一点比想到替代方案更容易：露露被铐在一辆面包车里，被四个男人带走，他们嘲笑她未婚、与男友同居、试图挑起事端、散布谣言——​可判处七年监禁的犯罪行为。

It was midnight when Lulu called me from the police van to say that she was being taken away. “Tell our parents,” she said. “Please. I’m sorry.” Her voice broke, and I barely recognized it. She sounded like a child in a blizzard who’d lost her scarf. It was easier to think of that than to think of the alternative: Lulu, cuffed into a van and taken away by four men who sneered at her for being unmarried and living with her boyfriend, for trying to stir up trouble, for spreading rumors—​a crime punishable by seven years’ imprisonment.

当他们开始审问她时，情况变得更糟。“这些地方你都去过吗？” 他们不断地问。“在网上传播这些谣言之前，你自己证实过这些事情吗？”

When they began interrogating her, it was worse. “Did you go to any of these places?” they kept asking. “Did you confirm any of these things yourself before spreading these rumors online?”

不，露露说。不。

No, Lulu said. No.

“所以你不知道它们是否属实。”

“So you didn’t know if they were true, then.”

随后，他们将她放在地上，对她拳打脚踢。他们没有骨折，但我还是想象出了她的骨头，每一根骨头都承受着每一击。露露应该都熟记在心：胸骨、胫骨、浮肋骨。

Later, they laid her on the ground and kicked and beat her. They didn’t fracture any bones, but I pictured her bones anyway, each individually absorbing every blow. Lulu would have known all of them by heart: sternum, tibia, floating rib.

我给母亲打电话，母亲听到这个消息后，还在半睡半醒中，脑子一片空白。“你一定是弄错了，”她尖锐地告诉我。“我给露露打电话，把事情弄清楚。” 这是她的一种古老的反射，这种本能地转向她的女儿。

I called my mother, who, on receiving the news, still half asleep, went blank. “You must be mistaken,” she told me sharply. “Let me call Lulu to straighten things out.” It was an old reflex of hers, this instinct to turn to her daughter.

“你可以打电话；“她不会接电话的。”我说，但她已经挂断了电话。当我回电话时，父亲无奈地接受了这个消息，仿佛他早就预料到了。我试图解释露露一直在写的东西，但他打断了我。

“You can call; she won’t answer,” I said, but she’d already hung up. When I called back, my father took in the news helplessly, as though he’d been expecting it. I tried to explain the kinds of things Lulu had been writing, but he cut me off.

“露露是我的女儿。我可以想象，”他说。他的声音里有一种特别沉重的感觉，这让我感到惊讶，这让我觉得他可能比我们其他人更了解她。

“Lulu is my daughter. I can imagine,” he said. There was a particular heaviness in his voice that surprised me, and it made me think that maybe he’d known her better than the rest of us had.

六天后露露获释并返回公寓静养。第二天我们就飞到北京去看她。这是我第一次来到她的公寓，她的客厅墙上贴着前任房客留下的巨大贴花，上面有银色和粉红色的树木和一只粉红色条纹的小猫。你是我的惊喜，朋友们在秋天会更好，上面写着。露露的皮肤看起来很黄，有黑色的淤青，她的右眼里有一个红色的东西，当她看向某个方向时，就会向外窥视。

Lulu was freed after six days and went back to her apartment to convalesce. We flew to Beijing the next day to see her. It was the first time I had been in her apartment, whose living-room wall bore a giant decal from a previous tenant, featuring silver and pink trees and a striped pink kitten. YOU ARE MY HAPPY SURPRISE, FRIENDS ARE BETTER IN AUTUMN, it read. Lulu’s skin looked yellow and darkly bruised, and there was a dart of something red in her right eye that peeked out when she looked in certain directions.

“我很好，”她说。她看到我们似乎非常尴尬。她说，他们只是想让她停止正在做的事情。她是一名好学生，是班上最好的学生之一——她不必毁掉这一切。她告诉我们，这是一个误会。毕竟他们会放她走的。

“I’m all right,” she said. She seemed acutely embarrassed to see us. They’d only wanted her to stop what she was doing, she said. She’d been a good student, one of the best in her class—​she didn’t have to ruin it all. It was a misunderstanding, she told us. They’d let her go, after all.

看来她也想让我们一起去。我们住了一个星期，母亲在他们的小厨房里忙忙碌碌，准备大餐，把东西切成薄片，复杂地切块，然后在大火上煮。“我很好，”露露说，直到我们不再问。

It seemed that she wanted us to go, too. We stayed for a week, our mother fussing in their tiny kitchen, preparing large meals of things sliced and intricately diced and cooked over a high flame. “I’m okay,” Lulu said, until we stopped asking.

我们回家后，露露开始在深夜的奇怪时间和我聊天。反正我通常都是醒着的。毕业后，我搬回家乡，在当地一家酒店的厨房工作。我白天睡眼惺忪地切菜、冲洗，晚上则和队友一起投入在线战斗。那几个月里，她的信息中有些东西强化了。她想知道我们的父母怎么样，是否下雨，我是否吃饭了。她想知道是否可以起诉殴打她的警察。从那以后她就一直胃痛。她想知道我是否还记得我们出生前在我们家附近的医院里去世的母亲的故事。她想知道是否有什么办法可以了解死去母亲的孩子今天的命运——如果它还活着，现在应该和我们这个年纪差不多了。

After we went home, Lulu started chatting me late at night, at odd hours. I was usually awake anyway. Since graduating, I’d moved back home to work in the kitchen at a local hotel. I spent my days chopping and rinsing, bleary-eyed, and my nights with teammates, locked in online combat. There was something that intensified in her messages during those months. She wanted to know how our parents were, if it was raining, if I’d eaten yet. She wondered if she could sue the police who’d beaten her; she’d been having stomach pains ever since. She wanted to know if I remembered the story of the mother who died in the hospital down the street from us before we were born. She wondered if there was any way to learn the fate of the dead mother’s child today—​had it lived, it would be about our age by now.

不久之后，她网站上的帖子又开始出现，又厚又快。我心下一沉，想分散她的注意力。你和张伟什么时候结婚？我试过。你不想生孩子吗？

Soon after that, the posts on her site started up again, thick and fast. I watched with a sinking heart, trying to distract her. When are you and Zhangwei getting married? I tried. Didn’t you want to have a baby?

很快，她说。或许。

Soon, she said. Maybe.

当警察再次来把她带走时，她已经做好了准备；她悄悄地从沙发上站起来，一言不发地跟着他们走了，把钥匙留在了身后。这次当他们允许她使用电话时，她给律师打电话，而不是我。警察突袭了她的公寓，拿走了她的电脑，这是我父母送给她的蓝袖笔记本电脑。他们还留下了一张通知，称她已被正式逮捕并受到指控。

When the police came and took her away again, she was prepared; she got up quietly from the couch and went with them without a word, leaving her keys behind. This time when they allowed her access to a phone, she called a lawyer, not me. The police raided the apartment, taking her computer, the blue-sleeved laptop my parents had given her. They also left behind a notice saying that she was formally being arrested and charged.

庭审时，露露穿着橙色连身裤，头发剪得很短，几乎认不出来了。她直视着检察官，从未看向观众。我们专程飞出去参加这个活动；我们已经六个月没见到她了。她被判处三年徒刑，然后被猛地从法庭另一端的一扇门中带走，仅此而已。

At the trial, Lulu wore an orange jumpsuit, with hair shorn so short that she was barely recognizable. She stared straight ahead at the prosecutors, never once looking out at the audience. We’d flown out for the occasion; we hadn’t seen her for six months. She was given a sentence of three years, then jerked away through a door at the opposite end of the courtroom, and that was all.

在飞机上，妈妈一路哭着回家。“她还想要什么？” 她不停地说。

On the plane, my mother wept all the way home. “What more did she want?” she kept saying.

在她左边，父亲让她安静下来。“我们现在无能为力，”他说。奇怪的是，这个想法似乎安慰了他。

To her left, my father hushed her. “There’s nothing we can do now,” he said. The thought, strangely, appeared to console him.

回到家里，似乎没有人知道我姐姐发生了什么事，也没有人问起。仿佛铺了一层白色的大雪，轻轻地掩盖了所经过的一切。

Back at home no one seemed to know that anything had happened to my sister, and no one asked, either. It was as if a great white blanket of snow had descended, softly muffling everything in its path.

时间流逝，最终我被任命为酒店的副主厨，加薪幅度不大，还戴着一顶略高的新纸帽。当我感到不安或烦躁时（这种情况经常发生），我会登录并在线加入我的队友。

Time passed, and eventually I was made a sous chef at the hotel, with a modest raise and a new, slightly taller paper hat. When I felt restless or agitated, which was often, I’d log on and join my teammates online.

一天晚上，我第一次带女朋友回家。一个月前，我在一个专门销售电子产品的废弃街区的地下室最低层遇见了她：荧光灯照明的迷宫般的小摊位出售二手手机、手机壳、扬声器和移动电源。她叫毛欣，是店里为数不多的几个在柜台后面工作的女孩之一。她可以告诉你100WH和161WH的区别，可以报出不同型号每GB的价格；她羞涩地承认，她在商店里花了这么长时间来弄清楚哪些商品是比较垃圾的，以至于她根本不认为进货其他商品有任何意义。“但那样的话我们可能只会卖六件东西，”她皱着眉头说道。

One night I brought my girlfriend home for the first time. I’d met her the month before on the lowest basement floor of a warrened-out block devoted to the sale of electronics: a fluorescent-lit maze of close-set booths selling secondhand phones, cases, speakers, and power banks. Her name was Mao Xin, and she was one of the few girls working behind the counters there. She could tell you the difference between 100 WH and 161 WH, could quote the price per giga­byte of different models; she’d spent so damn long in the shop figuring out which items were comparative junk, she confessed sheepishly, that she didn’t see any point in stocking the others at all. “But then we’d just be selling maybe six things,” she said with a frown.

事实证明，她是在我乘坐的同一条公交车路线上长大的，而且在我们这样大的城市里，这足以让人感觉像是命运的安排。我们喜欢想象我们小时候在公共汽车上见过彼此，冬天裹得严严实实，夏天则不耐烦地摆动双腿，甚至可能紧紧抓住同一根杆子。

As it turned out, she’d grown up riding the same bus route I had, and in a city as big as ours, that was enough to feel like fate. We liked to imagine that we had seen each other on the bus as children, stiffly bundled in the winter or swinging our legs impatiently in the summer, had maybe even clung to the same pole.

那天晚上吃晚饭时，我们坐着吃着姜猪肉炖土豆，妈妈问毛欣。我看得出她想喜欢她，观察了她帮助切大蒜和切掉细香葱发黄的尖端的方式。毛欣散发出一种仁慈的能力，可以安抚每个人，甚至包括我的母亲，她自从露露受审以来就变得紧张不安，容易重复自己的话，很容易生气。在毛欣的迷惑下，我在公寓里踱来踱去，寻找事情可做。我擦掉浴室柜台上的褐色肥皂残留物，并在没有询问的情况下将垃圾捆绑起来并倒出。

Over dinner that night, as we sat and slurped potatoes stewed with ginger and pork, my mother quizzed Mao Xin. I could see that she wanted to like her, had observed the way she’d helped chop the garlic and cut the yellowing tips off the chives. Mao Xin exuded a kind of benevolent competence that soothed everyone, even my mother, who had grown jittery since Lulu’s trial, prone to repeat herself, easily annoyed. Under Mao Xin’s spell, I paced the apartment looking for things to do. I wiped away browning soap residue from the bathroom counter, and bundled and took out the trash without being asked.

说话间，我看见毛欣好奇的眼睛在四处扫视，最终落在房间对面书架上一张露露的照片上，那张照片高得需要眯着眼睛才能看清。“那是谁？”

As we talked, I could see Mao Xin’s curious eyes flicking around, eventually landing on a photo of Lulu atop a bookshelf across the room, high enough that you needed to squint to really see it. “Who’s that?”

“这是他的妹妹，”我父亲说。这张照片是她在高考数学中获得我们区最高分的那天拍摄的。照片中，她在镜头后面对我父亲疯狂地笑，有点失焦。

“It’s his sister,” my father said. The photo had been taken the day she won our district’s top score for math in the college entrance exam. In it she was grinning maniacally at my father behind the camera, a little out of focus.

“我不知道你有一个妹妹，”她对我说。“她看起来像你。”

“I didn’t know you had a sister,” she said to me. “She looks like you.”

“他们是双胞胎，”我父亲说。

“They’re twins,” my father said.

“她在哪？”

“Where is she?”

“她在东北，准备攻读博士学位，”我母亲说。

“She’s in the northeast, preparing to get her Ph.D.,” my mother said.

后来，当我陪毛欣走到外面，向她解释到底发生了什么事时，她的脸色沉了下来。“哦，”她说。“我很抱歉。” 她说，在她成长的过程中，有一个男人经常驻扎在她家附近街道上的政府办公室外，他穿着破烂的工作服和运动鞋，磨损得像花瓣一样在脚踝处打开。他会告诉任何愿意听的人，军队欠他七年的工资。她说，在她的童年时期，他每天都在那里，直到有一天他永远消失了。

Later, when I walked Mao Xin outside and explained what had really happened, her face fell. “Oh,” she said. “I’m so sorry.” When she was growing up, she said, there was a man who used to station himself outside the government offices down the street from her home, with torn fatigues and sneakers so worn they flopped open like petals around his ankles. He’d tell anyone who would listen about how the army owed him seven years of back pay. He’d been there every day through her childhood, she said, until one day he disappeared for good.

“听起来他疯了，”我说。

“It sounds like he was crazy,” I said.

“我想是的，”她说。“不过一开始也许不是。”

“I think so,” she said. “Maybe not at first, though.”

“你一定很害怕他。”

“You must have been scared of him.”

“更多的是为他感到遗憾，”她说。

“More just sorry for him,” she said.

我们计划在露露出狱后几天举行婚礼，在我工作的酒店最好的大厅里举行了一场热闹的晚宴。那个月我被任命为一名正式厨师，这感觉就像是一份结婚礼物。我们端上一大盘冷肉冻和用萝卜泥做成的天鹅，上面有胡萝卜嘴和黑芝麻眼睛。这本来应该是一个愉快的时刻，我想确实如此，但每当我看着坐在我对面、目光遥远的露露时，我的心就提到了嗓子眼。

We planned our wedding for a few days after Lulu was to be released from prison, a boisterous dinner in the nicest hall of the hotel where I worked. I’d been made a full chef there that month, which felt like a sort of wedding gift. We served big platters of cold jellied meats and swans made of mashed-up radishes, with carrot beaks and black sesame eyes. It should have been a happy occasion, and I guess it was, but whenever I looked at Lulu, sitting across from me with a distant look in her eyes, my heart caught in my throat.

宴会结束时，我父亲穿着租来的燕尾服，不自然地开始剧烈咳嗽。见他没有停下来，张伟就示意一名服务员要水。

As the banquet wound down, my father, unnatural in a rented tuxedo, began coughing violently. When he didn’t stop, Zhangwei signaled to one of the waiters for water.

“喝了。”露露说。他喝干了杯子里的酒，看上去几乎是愤怒的。咳嗽声变得急促，平息了。“你还好？” 她说。

“Drink up,” Lulu said. He drained the glass, almost angrily, it seemed. The coughs sputtered, subsided. “You’re okay?” she said.

他喝了酒，脸色通红，目光突然集中在她身上，似乎很惊讶她在这里。“你觉得你所做的事情有意义吗？” 他说。

He had been drinking, his face was flushed, and his eyes focused suddenly on her, as though surprised she was there. “Do you think what you’ve done is meaningful?” he said.

“我们不谈这个了。”

“Let’s not talk about it.”

“你甚至不认识这些人，”他说。“无论他们的问题是什么，他们都与你无关。”

“You didn’t even know these people,” he said. “Whatever their problems might have been, they had no relation to you.”

露露低头看着自己的盘子，一副没听见的样子。她在监狱里就已经熟练掌握了这一点，或者也许她一直都拥有这种技能：如何将世界划分为清晰的类别，她认为什么值得关注，什么不值得关注。我现在属于后一类。她偶尔会向我点头，并在与我交谈时做出回应，但仅此而已。我尽量不让它让我心烦意乱。

Lulu looked down at her plate, appearing not to hear. She’d grown adept at that while in prison, or maybe she’d always had that skill: how to sort the world into clear categories, what she thought was worth paying attention to, and what wasn’t. I was in the latter category now. She’d nod at me occasionally and respond when spoken to, but that was all. I tried not to let it upset me.

父亲的脸变红了；我们以前从来没有见过他这样。“爸爸，我们还是别管它吧，”我说。附近桌子上的客人都停止了谈话，伸长脖子听。“这是没有用的。”

My father’s face was getting red; none of us had ever seen him like that before. “Dad, let’s just leave it,” I said. Guests at nearby tables had stopped their conversations, craning to hear. “It’s no use.”

“你是我们的女儿，”他恶狠狠地说，无视我。“我们能做的一切，都是为了你。你是我们所有的忧虑，也是我们所有的希望。”

“You are our daughter,” he said fiercely, ignoring me. “Everything we could, we did for you. You were all our worries, all our hopes.”

他又开始咳嗽，喉咙里发出细微的、破碎的声音。露露的表情缓和了一些。“爸爸，多喝点水。听起来你真的病得很厉害。”

He was coughing again, small mangled noises sticking in his throat. Lulu’s expression softened. “Dad, drink more water. It sounds like you’re really sick.”

他无视了她，将玻璃杯放在同一个凝结环中。他突然变成了一个老人，或者也许我只是才注意到。“你觉得我这辈子有你的机会吗？” 他说。“你知道如果我拥有它们我能做什么吗？”

He ignored her, setting the glass down in the same ring of condensation. He was suddenly an old man, or maybe I’d only just noticed. “Do you think I had your chances in life?” he said. “Do you know what I could have done if I had them?”

很难相信他们两个正在打架；这是我以前从未见过的。我和妈妈互相看了一眼，然后移开视线。

It was hard to believe that the two of them were fighting; it was something I hadn’t seen before. Our mother and I looked at each other, then looked away.

“对不起。”露露低声说道。

“I’m sorry,” Lulu said quietly.

“露露，你想帮助别人，但不要欺骗自己，”他说。“你所做的一切都是伤害了自己，伤害了家人。”

“You want to help people, Lulu, but don’t deceive yourself,” he said. “All you’ve done is hurt yourself, hurt your family.”

母亲把手放在他的手上，看了他一眼，让他安静下来。张伟站了起来，似乎要结束这场讨论。这让你意识到他是一个多么高大、英俊的男人，硬挺的黑发在茂密的茅草丛中竖起，薄薄的镜片突出了警惕的棕色眼睛。“我想露露现在最好休息一下，”他对我父母说。他的语气中没有任何不礼貌的地方，但它的结尾让我们想起了他的坚定，他保护我妹妹的决心，我因此更喜欢他。

My mother laid a hand on his and stilled him with a look. Zhang­wei stood up, as though to end the discussion. It made you aware of what a tall, fine-looking man he was, stiff black hair that stood up in a dense thatch, thin lenses highlighting watchful brown eyes. “I think Lulu had better get some rest now,” he said to my parents. There was nothing impolite about his tone, but there was a finality to it that reminded us all of his solidity, his determination to protect my sister, and I liked him the better for it.

“别担心，”他一边告诉我，一边把她领到外面，远离婚礼派对的喧嚣和灯光。“我会照顾她的。”

“Don’t worry,” he told me as he ushered her outside, away from the noise and lights of the wedding party. “I’ll take care of her.”

当我们第一次再次聚集在父母的客厅里时，她说，她在监狱里并没有受到虐待。她怀疑一名女警卫暗恋她，经常给她偷运一包方便面，偶尔还偷偷带上一根口香糖。白天，他们在生产线上工作，组装圣诞灯。晚上他们会看晚间新闻和电视转播的任何体育比赛。但她说她错过了阳光。她想念张伟，想念我们。

She hadn’t been treated badly in prison, she’d said when we were all first gathered again in our parents’ living room. There had been a female guard she suspected of having a crush on her, who used to smuggle her packets of instant noodles and an occasional stick of gum. During the day they’d work on a manufacturing line, assembling Christmas lights. At night they’d watch the evening news and whatever sports match was being televised. But she’d missed the sunlight, she said. She’d missed Zhangwei, missed us.

“谢谢你的来信，”她对我说，我看着地板，远离我们的父母。“没问题，”我低声说道，为他们感到尴尬。我没有想到他们也没有定期写作。

“Thank you for your letters,” she said to me, and I looked at the floor, away from our parents. “It was no problem,” I muttered, embarrassed for them. It hadn’t occurred to me that they hadn’t been writing regularly as well.

露露改变了话题。“所以你要参加上海邀请赛？这真是太棒了。”

Lulu changed the subject. “So you’re playing in the Shanghai invitational? That’s really wonderful.”

就是：一起打了六年，我的队伍终于晋级了。到目前为止，我在四位队友中只见过一位。我向她道谢。

It was: after playing together for six years, my team had finally qualified. Out of four teammates, I’d met only one in person thus far. I thanked her.

“有奖金吗？” 她问。

“Is there prize money?” she asked.

我告诉她是的，一点点。

I told her yes, a little.

“太棒了，”她笑着说道。

“Excellent,” she said, grinning.

我们的父母非常安静。我怀疑他们想要道歉，但也没有得到道歉。当露露说她和张伟要搬到附近的时候，妈妈愣住了，就像有人递给她一个破了的鸡蛋，不知道该怎么办。

Our parents were very quiet. I suspected they wanted an apology, and also that it wasn’t forthcoming. When Lulu said that she and Zhangwei were planning to move nearby, our mother froze, as though she’d been handed a cracked egg and didn’t know what to do with it.

“他认为离家近一点对我有好处。”露露打破了沉默。“至少在我再次习惯正常生活的时候。”

“He thinks it’ll be good for me to be closer to home,” Lulu said, breaking the silence. “At least while I get used to a normal life again.”

“你能在这里做什么？” 妈妈生硬地问道。“你能找到工作吗？”

“What can you do out here?” my mother asked stiffly. “Can you find work?”

露露猛地仰起头，身上又燃起了往日的傲慢。“是的，妈妈。我是当年数学成绩最好的学生，你还记得吗？”

Lulu tossed her head, and a flash of her old arrogance flared in her. “Yes, Mother. I was the top-scoring student in our year for math, don’t you remember?”

“也许毛欣可以给她一份工作，”我妈妈说。这句话并不委婉，但后来我妈妈很爱毛欣，越来越依赖她，这让我想起了她上大学之前和露露的关系。

“Maybe Mao Xin could give her a job,” my mother said. It wasn’t a tactful remark, but then my mother loved Mao Xin, had come to rely on her in a way that reminded me of her relationship with Lulu before she had gone to college.

“当然，”我说，抱歉地看了露露一眼。“无论如何，这是个好消息。我们得庆祝一下。”

“Sure,” I said, with an apologetic glance at Lulu. “Anyway, that’s great news. We’ll have to celebrate.”

她对我微笑，带着一丝悲伤。“谢谢大哥。”

She smiled at me, a little sadly. “Thanks, Big Brother.”

最终，她找到了在商场分发茶样品的工作，这是一家连锁店，招牌上有霓虹绿色的山丘。工作很轻松，老板也没有问她的过去。她说，与此同时，她学习了很多关于茶的知识，包括氧化过程，以及泡不同品种茶的正确方法。

Eventually she found work handing out tea samples at the mall, a chain store with neon-green hills on its sign. It was an easy job, and the boss didn’t ask questions about her past. In the meantime she was learning a lot about tea, she said, about the oxidation process, about the proper way to steep different varieties.

“哇，他们真的在那里训练你，”我们的父亲说。在她获释后的几周里，他已经成为政府的拥护者，不放过任何机会向露露指出自从她离开后道路铺得多么好，商场建得多么宏伟。他说：“现在年轻人有很多机会。” 这是他的一次新抽搐，而且很刺耳。那天早些时候，当我们在附近散步时，他指给我们看对面有一组最近升级的公共厕所。“他们甚至还设置了一个小房间供环卫工人休息，”他说。“它有暖气什么的。你看他们现在对所有工人都照顾得怎么样了？”

“Wow, they really train you over there,” our father said. In the weeks since her release, he had become a champion government booster, missing no opportunity to point out to Lulu how nicely the roads had been paved since she’d left, how grand the malls were that had been built. “There are so many opportunities for young people now,” he said. It was a new tic of his, and it grated. Earlier that day, as we strolled the neighborhood, he’d pointed out a set of recently upgraded public toilets across the way. “They even installed a little room where the sanitation workers can rest,” he said. “It has heating and everything. You see what good care they take of all the workers now?”

我翻了个白眼。

I rolled my eyes.

“不管怎样，这都是暂时的，”露露谈到她的工作时说道，当然，这才是最让我们害怕的。

“Anyway, it’s temporary,” Lulu said of her job, and that, of course, is what scared us most of all.

我看得出来她正在计划着什么。有一次，当她使用我的笔记本电脑时，我回头看到她打开了一份文件，标题是《致全国人民代表大会的公开信》。当她起身去洗手间时，我匆忙地翻阅了文字，看到了一份签有六个名字的名单，其中有她自己的名字，还有几位律师和教授的名字，我从未听说过这些人。我没有对她说什么，但那天下午晚些时候，我把张伟拉到一边，告诉他我的发现。他点了点头。

I could see that she was planning something. Once, when she was using my laptop, I saw over her shoulder that she had a document open, titled “An Open Letter to the National People’s Congress.” When she got up to use the bathroom, I scrolled hastily through the text, seeing a list of half a dozen names signed, her own and those of a few lawyers and professors, no one I’d ever heard of. I didn’t say anything to her, but later that afternoon I pulled Zhangwei aside and told him what I’d found. He nodded.

“我知道，”他说。“你姐姐没变。”

“I know,” he said. “Your sister doesn’t change.”

我不明白他的意思，但我还是有点生气。“她年轻的时候不是这样的，”我说。

I didn’t know what he meant, but I bristled a little anyway. “She wasn’t like this when she was younger,” I said.

“当然不是——那时她还太年轻。”

“Of course not—​she was too young then.”

“你不知道她是什么样的人。”

“You don’t know what she was like.”

“好吧，”他耐心地说，眼睛盯着我身后的门，等着看露露是否会走进来。他总是在心里追踪她的位置，她是世界上最忠诚的猎犬。

“Okay,” he said patiently, his eyes on the door behind me, waiting to see if Lulu would walk in. He was always mentally tracking her location, the world’s most devoted bloodhound.

“我的意思是。她很聪明。她可能是我们学校最聪明的。”

“I mean that. She was smart. She was probably the smartest in our school.”

“你认为她不再聪明了？”

“And you think she isn’t smart anymore?”

“我不是这个意思。”我说，但张伟已经弹掉烟灰走开了，对我很失望。

“That’s not what I meant,” I said, but Zhangwei was already flicking the ash from his cigarette and walking away, disappointed in me.

我独自飞到上海参加季中邀请赛，对毛欣陪我的提议不屑一顾，但当我到达时，我立即希望她在那里，只是为了看看这一奇观。比赛在市中心的一个体育场举行，地板上闪烁着红色和蓝色的 LED 灯带。体育场里挤满了人，当我们戴着耳机、坐在舞台上的软垫座位上比赛时，人群挥舞着红色和蓝色的荧光棒。

I flew to Shanghai for the midseason invitational alone, shrugging off Mao Xin’s offer to accompany me, but when I arrived I immediately wished she was there, just to see the spectacle. The games took place in a stadium downtown, the floor lit up with strips of red and blue LED lights. The stadium was packed, and as we played in padded seats onstage, headsets on, the crowds waved red and blue glow sticks.

我们赢了两轮，并在第三轮击败了韩国队。在背景中，人群在呻吟，他们的声音与我自己的血液噪音混合在一起，我们疯狂地点击，发出大量橙色的火焰。“永不放弃！永不言败！” 人群高呼。

We won two rounds and went on to trounce the South Korean team in the third. In the background, the crowd was moaning, their sounds mingling with the noise of my own blood as we clicked frantically, sending out great gusts of orange fire. “Never give up! Never say die!” the crowd chanted.

比赛结束后，闪烁的记分牌显示我们排名第三。摄像机蜂拥而至地板上，像黑冠鸟一样落在我们身上。我们羞涩地微笑着，说我们是多么自豪，明年我们一定会回来赢得胜利。不知何故，我们被带上领奖台，与其他获胜团队并肩作战。当银色五彩纸屑如雨点般落下时，他们递给了我们一座奖杯，巨大的云彩般精致的平行四边形。当我后来观看视频时，看起来我们就像站在一片刀片雨中。我们五个人将奖杯举到空中。它摇晃着，几乎翻倒了，但我们当中最高的一个把它扶正了，我们让它盘旋在那里，欣赏着它。

When the games were over, the flashing scoreboard had us in third place. The cameras flocked to the floor, descending on us like black hooded birds. We gave sheepish smiles and said how proud we were, how we’d be back next year to win for sure. Somehow we were ushered onto a podium, beside the other winning teams. They handed us a trophy as silver confetti rained down, great clouds of delicate parallelograms. When I watched the video later, it looked as if we were standing in a hail of razor blades. We hoisted the trophy into the air, all five of us. It wavered and nearly tipped, but the tallest among us righted it and we let it hover there, admiring it.

四个月后，露露再次入狱，这次她被指控试图颠覆国家政权，此前她在网上发布了一份请愿书，呼吁所有政府支出透明化。这次监狱不太好，法官判了她十年。我上次见到她时，她瘦了十五磅，看上去瘦了，和高中时的身材一样。

Four months later Lulu went back to prison, this time on charges of trying to subvert state power, after she had circulated an online petition calling for all government spending to be made transparent. This time the prison was not so nice, and the judge gave her a ten-year sentence. The last time I saw her, she had lost fifteen pounds and looked shrunken, the same size she’d been in high school.

入狱几年后，张伟搬回家乡，离父母更近，并与别人结婚。他给我们写了一封道歉信。我看到寄信地址就扔掉了，毛欣却从垃圾桶里捞出来，坚持要我看。“你的妹妹是一个真正罕见的人，我必须带着最大的悲伤继续前进，”他写道。“很抱歉我没能为她提供更多帮助。” 我在那里站了一会儿，欣赏着他的书法，这是我以前从未见过的。它很优雅、平衡——几乎是高贵的，我观察到，然后又把信扔了出去。

A few years after she was jailed, Zhangwei moved back to his hometown to be closer to his parents and got married to someone else. He wrote us a letter apologizing. I threw it away after seeing the return address, but Mao Xin fished it out of the trash and insisted that I read it. “Your sister is a truly rare person, and it is with the greatest sadness that I have to move on,” he’d written. “I’m sorry I couldn’t help her more.” I stood there for a minute, admiring his penmanship, which I’d never seen before. It was elegant, balanced—​almost noble, I observed, before tossing the letter out again.

上海邀请赛结束后，我们队伍开始在国内巡回赛上激烈角逐，时不时赢得实际奖金池。在毛欣的鼓励下，我减少了在酒店的时间，把更多的时间投入到训练中。第二年夏天，我们飞往悉尼参加全球总决赛。这是我第一次出国。那时我们已经有了粉丝，甚至还有赞助商；我们穿着相同的连身裤进入竞技场，胸前印着能量饮料的名称。

After the Shanghai invitational, our team started competing heavily on the domestic circuit, winning actual prize pools now and again. With Mao Xin’s encouragement, I cut back my hours at the hotel and devoted more time to training. The following summer, we flew to Sydney for the global finals. It was my first time abroad. By then we had fans, even sponsors; we entered the arena wearing identical jumpsuits with the name of an energy drink printed across our chests.

在飞机上，我们漂洋过海，向南航行。我拿出相机拍了一张照片，准备写给露露的下一封信。空乘人员分发了耳机，我戴上耳机，突然想家了。我闭上眼睛，想起了姐姐。我祈祷胜利，希望她感到骄傲。

On the plane, we crossed the ocean, heading south. I took out my camera and snapped a photo for my next letter to Lulu. The flight attendants passed out headsets and I slid one on, suddenly homesick. I closed my eyes and thought of my sister. I prayed for victory, and hoped that she would be proud.

热线女孩

Hotline Girl

每年春天，高速公路上都会装饰着数千朵玫瑰。它们有亮粉色和奶油黄色，在中央子午线中呈现出完美的盆栽景象。一年一度的荆棘和花瓣编排通常在四月，冬日阴霾解除后举行。在那些黑暗和令人窒息的几个月里，当局将道路漆成了发光的黄色：为了在灰色时期更好地欢呼和能量！公告就这样来了，一天几十个：

The highways were adorned with thousands of roses each spring. They came in bright pinks and butter yellows, perfect potted visions in the center meridian. The annual choreography of thorns and petals usually came in April, after the winter gloom lifted. During those dark and choking months, the authorities painted the roads a luminous yellow: For better cheer and energy during the gray! The bulletins came like that, dozens of them a day:

注意，他们说。今天下午，短毛猫（它们会出现在屏幕上，大爪子，眨眼，通勤者会抬起头微笑）。

Attention, they said. This afternoon, shorthair kittens (and they would appear onscreen, big-pawed and blinking, and commuters would look up and smile).

注意：枫糖浆是如何制作的（一个人在荒凉的森林里钻进一棵树，灰色的大桶沸腾的液体）。

Attention: how maple syrup is made (a man in a stark forest drilling into a tree, gray vats of boiling liquid).

注意：南山公园周围的银杏叶都变成金黄色了——快来看看吧！

Attention: the ginkgo leaves are turning gold around Nanshan Park—​come see!

等等。

And so on.

那天早上，八一出门时，就像每天早上一样，她脖子上挂着一条红色挂绳，上面挂着身份证。挂绳的颜色证实了她作为这座城市居民的身份，这是在多年的边缘工作后来之不易的。卡片上有她的照片、名字和工作单位。任何进入城市的人都必须佩戴一件。每张卡都与城市的传感器同步并记录持有者的活动。一天结束时，您可以登录并查看您行走的英里数；这是该系统更受欢迎的功能之一。

When Bayi stepped out that morning, like every morning, she slipped a red lanyard with her identification card around her neck. The lanyard’s color confirmed her status as a resident of the city, hard-won after years of jobs at its margins. The card had her picture and name and work unit on it. Anyone entering the city had to wear one. Each card synced with the city’s sensors and recorded the bearer’s activity. At the end of the day, you could log on and see the number of miles you’d walked; it was one of the system’s more popular features.

“我要走在高速公路上，我要走在闪电上，”她在走向地铁时唱道。多年来，她一直想成为一名歌手，试图让自己的声音成为她想要的那样有力、纤细的血管，试图写出一首突破性的热门歌曲。它们都是简短的旋律，只有一些循环重复的副歌；她似乎不知道如何写出一首完整的歌曲，副歌、主歌、桥段。

“I’m going on a highway, I’m going on a lightning bolt,” she sang as she walked to the subway. For years she’d wanted to be a singer, tried to make her voice the strong, slender vessel she wanted it to be, tried to write a breakout hit. They were short melodies, just a few refrains repeated on a loop; she couldn’t seem to figure out how to write a full one, chorus, verse, bridge.

那天早上火车上挤满了人。所有车站在高峰时段都会播放古典音乐。本来是为了缓和情绪，但大家还是互相推搡。无论如何，八一本能地不信任它；所有这些又长又曲折的短语——感觉就像作弊。她希望她的音乐准确、有道理。

The trains were packed that morning. All the stations piped in classical music at rush hour; it was supposed to soothe tempers, but everyone still pushed and elbowed one another. Bayi distrusted it instinctively, anyway; all those long, meandering phrases—​it felt like cheating. She wanted her music precise, to have a point.

当她挤过人群，乘电梯上七层楼，进入办公室时，她能看到屏幕上乔英油腻的头发。“今天早上我请了一名水管工来，”她耸耸肩说道，而他则站起来皱着眉头看着她。“他们总是迟到。”

When she’d pushed her way through the crowds, up the elevator seven floors, and into the office, she could see the oily bristles of Qiaoying’s hair over his screen. “I had a plumber come this morning,” she said, shrugging, as he stood and frowned at her. “They’re always running late.”

她没有道歉。她很早就意识到，道歉是让巧英认定你是软果子、容易被欺负的最可靠的方式。其他女孩不明白这一点。当他经过他们的车站时，他们低垂着眼睛，几乎可以明显地把身子移开。每当他走近他们的走廊时，一个女孩就会跳起来躲在浴室里，那个女孩上贴着一个牌子，上面写着“热线女孩”。

She didn’t apologize. She’d realized early on apologies were the surest way for Qiaoying to decide that you were ruan shizi, soft fruit, easily picked on. The other girls didn’t get that. They kept their eyes lowered, almost visibly leaning away as he passed their stations. One girl would spring up and hide in the bathroom any time he approached their corridor, the one that bore a sign saying HOTLINE GIRLS.

“我们已经接到二十七个电话了，”她的朋友苏琪低声对她说。两人不自觉地看着坐在最后一排的女孩，叹了口气。这位名叫娟梅的女孩被评为今年的办公室劳动模范。原因不明，只知道她有着令人愉悦的容貌，长发如丝般的黑雨般垂落在脸上。几个月来，她光辉灿烂的形象覆盖了地铁和全城的广告牌：热情、温柔、有能力：政府工作人员可以帮助您解决任何问题、任何担忧。请立即致电满意度办公室：12579。

“We’ve already had twenty-seven calls,” her friend Suqi whispered to her. They both looked automatically at the girl sitting at the row’s end and sighed. The girl, Juanmei, had been picked as this year’s office Model Worker. It wasn’t clear why, except that she had pleasing features and long hair that fell in a silky black rain about her face. For months her glowing image had blanketed the subway and billboards across town: WARM, GENTLE, CAPABLE: GOVERNMENT WORKERS CAN HELP YOU RESOLVE ANY QUESTION, ANY CONCERN. CALL THE SATISFACTION OFFICE TODAY: 12579.

当总机响起的时候，没有人再看娟梅了。自从获奖后，她就一直懈怠，为其他女孩创造了更多的工作。所有呼叫都必须在四十五秒内得到答复。所有聊天都必须在二十秒内回复。就是说，当娟梅戴着耳机坐在那儿的时候，八一他们却手忙脚乱，接、按、接、嘟囔、按键盘回车，飞快地打字。刚来这座城市时，八一曾在快餐店工作过一段时间。这也是同样复杂的舞蹈，你的头脑中同时保持十个命令，旋转，转身，重新开始。

When the switchboard pinged, no one looked to Juanmei anymore. Ever since her award she’d been slack, creating more work for the other girls. All calls had to be answered within forty-five seconds. All chats had to be replied to within twenty seconds. It meant that while Juanmei was sitting idly there with her headset on, Bayi and the others were scrambling, picking up, pressing hold, picking up, muttering, pressing return on their keyboards, typing fast. When she first came to the city, Bayi had worked for a time in fast food. It was that same complicated kind of dance, keeping ten orders in your head simultaneously, twirl, turn about, begin again.

总机再次响起，八一打开聊天屏幕，面对的是一连串的弹窗。最简单的就是发送笑脸。她所有的谈话都是这样开始的。有设置笑脸的编程键，另一个键会吐出：您好，满意度办公室，有什么可以帮您的吗？

The switchboard pinged once more as Bayi opened up her chat screen and faced a barrage of popups. The easiest thing was to send a smiley face. She started all her conversations that way. There were set programmed keys for smiley faces, and another key that spat out: Hello, Satisfaction Office, what can I help you with?

总机一直在响，红色数字的大计时器正在倒计时。如果当数字为零时没有人接听，蜂鸣器就会响起，每个人的评级都会被扣掉。尽管如此，其他女孩还是没有让步。他们正在等她接电话。大家都知道她刚来。她烦躁地猛拉耳机。“您好，满意度办公室，有什么可以帮您的吗？”

The switchboard kept pinging, the big timer with its red numerals counting down. If no one picked up by the time the number hit zero, a buzzer sounded and everyone’s rating was docked. Still, the other girls didn’t budge; they were waiting for her to take the call. Everyone knew she’d just arrived. She jerked on her headset irritably. “Hello, Satisfaction Office, what can I help you with?”

一大堆话语笼罩在她的耳边，一种刺耳的连接。听起来就像是大风天在屋顶上打电话一样。

A swarm of words enveloped her ear, a raspy connection. It sounded like the person was dialing from a rooftop on a windy day.

“对不起，我没听清。” 。。你想要一套住房——抱歉，请重述一遍。你被驱逐了？” 她现在正在猜测，有一半的时间你可以自己填空。有人抱怨腐败官员，有人质疑社会补贴。那里都是孤独的人，日复一日地给政府打电话，想要倾诉，有老人，有精神衰弱的人，其中许多人的抱怨永远得不到解决。一位母亲定期打电话询问十年前失踪的女儿的情况：她确信是被绑架了。一名焦躁的男子连续几个月打电话给他们的办公室，抱怨他大楼对面的树上有白蚁；他确信他们会进入电线并导致邻居触电。他们派了一名检查员，但什么也没发现。他们派了一个假装喷水的人，让他的心得到安息，但这并不能让他满意。最后他们派人把整个东西砍掉了，他就不再打电话了。

“Excuse me, I didn’t catch that . . . You want a housing—​I’m sorry, please restate the matter. You’ve been evicted?” She was guessing now, half the time you could fill in the blanks yourself. There were complaints about corrupt officials, questions about social subsidies. There were all the lonely people who dialed the government day after day, wanting to talk, the elderly or mentally infirm, many with complaints that would never be resolved. One mother called regularly to inquire about a daughter who had gone missing ten years before: kidnapped, she was sure. One agitated man called their office for months, complaining there were termites in the tree opposite his building; he was convinced they’d get into the wires and electrocute the neighborhood. They’d sent an inspector, who’d found nothing. They’d sent someone who’d pretended to spray, to set his heart at rest, but it didn’t satisfy him. At last they’d sent someone to chop the whole thing down, and he stopped calling.

“对不起，不是住房——您想举报某人吗？。。。未注册的菜刀？让我把它记下来。”

“Excuse me, not a housing—​you want to report someone? . . . An unregistered kitchen knife? Let me take that down.”

她开始打字，同时在弹出的四个不同窗口上按下“告诉我更多”按钮。一名妇女抱怨法院的判决，称法官与被告有关系。另一名男子声称当局对其餐厅非法征税。一名高年级学生表示，他没有收到应得的增加的养老金。

She began typing, simultaneously pressing the button for Tell me more on four different windows that popped up. One woman was complaining about a court verdict, saying the judge was related to the defendant. Another man claimed authorities were illegally taxing his restaurant. A senior said he hadn’t been getting the rise in pension payments he was owed.

她的肩膀开始疼痛，她揉了揉眼睛，盯着周围的电脑海洋。她总是惊讶于时间过得如此之快，记下笔记，发送链接，用颜色标记案件的紧急程度。八一有几次给打电话的人寄红包，只是为了平息事态。对于那些拒绝挂断电话的特别烦人的案件，有一个共同的预算。“我要把你举报给你的主管机构——哦，我刚刚收到通知——谢谢你的好意。不，我知道你只是想帮忙。” 令人惊讶的是，有多少居民只是需要感觉他们从电话那头提取了一些东西，任何东西，即使只是 10 或 20 元。

Her shoulders were starting to ache and she rubbed her eyes, staring out at the sea of computers around her. It always surprised her how quickly time passed, taking down notes, sending links, marking case urgency by color. A few times Bayi routed red compassion packets to callers, just to smooth things over; there was a common budget for that, for the particularly obstreperous cases who refused to hang up. “I’m going to report you to your supervising agency—​oh, I just received a notification—​thank you for your good intentions. No, I know you are only trying to help.” It was astonishing how many residents just needed to feel they’d extracted something, anything, from the other end of the line, even if it was only 10 or 20 yuan.

中午，送货员到了外面，卸下了两百盒盒饭，白色的盒子里装着米饭或面条，还有蔬菜和肉丝。选项几乎相同，但无论如何，每个人都疯狂地挤满了狭窄的大厅，油脂使纸板变成橙色和半透明。

At noon the deliveryman arrived outside and unloaded two hundred boxed lunches, white containers of rice or noodles with vegetables and shredded pork. The options were nearly identical but everyone crammed the narrow hall in a frantic rush anyway, the grease turning the cardboard orange and translucent.

等待的时候，苏琪伸出腿，露出一只靴子，她和八一尖叫起来。“你得到了他们！”

As they waited, Suqi stretched out her leg and showed off one boot, and she and Bayi squealed. “You got them!”

“我做到了。”苏琪自豪地说。“你觉得我疯了吗？”

“I did,” Suqi said proudly. “Do you think I’m crazy?”

“有一点。”八一说。这双靴子是用柔软的棕色皮革编织而成的，上面镶嵌着小贝壳的螺纹，售价相当于一个月的工资。苏琪的奖金是公司里最高的。她的满意度非常高，而且几乎从未收到重复的回电。也不是因为她用了红包，而是因为她用了红包。苏琪的做法实在是太合理、太能干了——她从不争论，对政府的运作有着百科全书式的了解，知道自己能提供什么资源，真正善于帮助别人。她也是一个勤奋的人：晚上她在运输行业加班。

“A little,” Bayi said. The boots were knitted from soft brown leather, studded with the whorls of tiny seashells, and cost a month’s salary. Suqi had the office’s highest bonuses; her satisfaction rate was extraordinary, and she almost never got repeat callbacks. It wasn’t because she used the red packets, either; there was just something so reasonable and capable in Suqi’s manner—​she never argued and had an encyclopedic knowledge of the government’s workings, knew just what resources she could offer, was genuinely good at helping people. She was a hard worker, too: in the evening she picked up extra shifts working in transport.

下午 2 点左右接到了电话，当时他们已经回到了自己的岗位，正午时分电话逐渐减少，你很难睁开眼睛。一名排队的女孩在附近放了一个喷雾瓶，定期在脸上喷水以保持警惕。八一感觉很懒，有些聊天内容只是发个点头表情，这又耽误了一分钟才回复。

The call came around 2 p.m., when they’d settled back into their stations, into that midday stretch when calls ebbed and it was hard to keep your eyes open. One of the girls on the line kept a spray bottle nearby, periodically misting her face to stay alert. Bayi was feeling lazy, dealing with some chats by simply sending a nodding face, which bought another minute before you had to reply again.

总机“叮”的一声响了，八一等到计时器还剩十秒，才用力一拳，直起身子。“您好，满意度办公室，有什么可以帮您的吗？”

The switchboard pinged, and Bayi waited until the timer showed ten seconds left, then punched firmly and straightened up. “Hello, Satisfaction Office, what can I help you with?”

一阵沉默。她又开口了，语气不耐烦。“你好？” 和“你好？”

There was a silence. She spoke again, impatiently. “Hello?” and “Hello?”

八一对着听筒皱起了眉头。偶尔，极少数情况下，你会喘口气。有时他们可能会说一些不恰当的话：问你穿什么，是否已婚，是否有男朋友。

Bayi frowned into the receiver. Occasionally, very rarely, you’d get a heavy breather. Sometimes they might say inappropriate things: ask what you were wearing, if you were married, had a boyfriend.

她刚要挂断电话，就听到一个声音：“哇，终于了。”

She was about to hang up when she heard a voice: “Wow, at last.”

“对不起？”

“I’m sorry?”

“八一。这就是我。”

“Bayi. It’s me.”

她往后一靠，把耳机拿开一会儿，然后捂住耳机，闭上眼睛。然后，等她平静下来后，又把它放了回去。“是的先生。你为什么——我的意思是，请说明此事，”她说。

She sat back, pulled her headset away for a moment and cupped the earpiece, eyes closed. Then, when she’d composed herself, she put it back again. “Yes, sir. Why are you—​I mean, please state the matter,” she said.

“我今天已经打了大约六十次电话，”他说。“我不确定我是否能得到你。”

“I called probably sixty times already today,” he said. “I wasn’t sure I’d ever get you.”

她环视了一下线路上的其他女孩，语气中立。“有什么我可以帮你的吗？”

She looked around to the other girls on the line and spoke neutrally. “Is there something I can help you with?”

一阵沉默。“是这样吗？” 他说。

There was a silence. “Is that it?” he said.

“这是政府的路线，”她冷冷地说。“有什么事情需要帮忙吗？”

“This is a government line,” she said coldly. “Is there a matter that requires assistance?”

“是的，”他说。“我希望你能见到我。我在这里，我就站在外面。”

“Yes,” he said. “I wish you would see me. I’m here, I’m standing outside.”

八一自动挂断了电话，就像看到蟑螂在里面爬进来时鞋子掉下来一样。她吸了一口气，回到屏幕前，匆忙又接到了两个电话：一个是受虐待的妻子，一个是一个男人在抱怨邻居的垃圾。下午 5 点，她再次将挂绳套在脖子上，从后面的服务电梯出去，动作很快，尽量不让人看见。

Bayi hung up automatically, the way one might drop a shoe at the sight of a cockroach scuttling inside. She breathed in, went back to her screen and picked up two more calls in a hurry: an abused wife, a man complaining about trash in his neighborhood. At 5 p.m., she slipped the lanyard about her neck again and exited through the service elevator around the back, moving fast, trying not to be seen.

她摇摇晃晃地回到家，给自己准备了饭菜。她整个晚上都感到焦躁不安，就像一只蜂鸟被困在胸口一样。最后，她走到外面踱步了一会儿，才坐在垃圾桶对面的长凳上。二十分钟后，一只野猫走了过来，蜿蜒地爬到了她的腿上，她不由自主地抚摸着它。她责备地盯着灌木丛，仿佛它们可能会掩盖有人在监视她。

She went home shakily, fixed herself a meal. She felt agitated all evening, like a hummingbird was trapped in her chest. At last, she went and paced outside for a while before sitting on the bench opposite the trash cans. After twenty minutes, one of the alley cats came up and snaked itself into her lap, and she petted it automatically. She stared into the bushes accusingly, as though they might conceal someone watching her.

第二天他又打来电话。

The next day he called again.

“这太过分了，”他说。“我不该过来的。我很高兴找到你。”

“It was too much,” he said. “I shouldn’t have come over. I was just so excited to have found you.”

她清了清喉咙。“我没有迷路。”

She cleared her throat. “I wasn’t lost.”

“不，当然不是，”他说。

“No, of course not,” he said.

他们都沉默了。她记得，他从来不善于交谈。有时他们几乎完全沉默地一起吃饭，奇怪的是，这似乎从来没有打扰过他。她放松了一点。和 Keju 在一起一直都是一门艺术。这意味着关闭你的大脑，比如举重或入睡。感觉并不像听起来那么糟糕。坚强很重要，睡觉也很重要；你需要两者才能生存。

They were both silent. He had never been good at making conversation, she remembered. Sometimes they’d eat their meals together in almost complete silence, which, oddly, never seemed to bother him. She relaxed a little. There had always been an art to being around Keju. It meant turning off your mind, like lifting weights or falling asleep. It didn’t feel as bad as it sounded. It was important to be strong, it was important to sleep; you needed both to stay alive.

“你在这里？” 她说。“我的意思是，我知道你是昨天的。你是来拜访的，还是——？”

“You’re here?” she said. “I mean, I know you were yesterday. Are you visiting, or—?”

这个城市有3200万人口，其中没有一个是科举人；他应该在六百英里之外。

The city was 32 million people, none of whom were Keju; he should have been six hundred miles away.

“只是来拜访。”科居急忙说道，似乎是为了让她放心。

“Just visiting,” Keju said hastily, as though to reassure her.

他们又沉默了，她看着屏幕亮起并闪烁。“我现在真的不能说话，”她说。

They were silent again, and she watched her screen light up and flash. “I really can’t talk now,” she said.

“别挂断电话，”他说。“今天我花了两个小时才找到你。没有我可以直接拨打的电话，知道您会接听吗？”

“Don’t hang up,” he said. “It took me two hours to reach you today. Isn’t there a direct line I can call, to know that you’ll pick up?”

“这样不行。”

“It doesn’t work that way.”

“你是满意度办公室的吧？” 他说，试图开个玩笑。“在与你交谈之前我不会满意。”

“You’re the Satisfaction Office, aren’t you?” he said, trying to make a joke of it. “I’m not going to be satisfied until I get to talk to you.”

她默默地点击了另一个电话，并将其转接到政府的法律部门。几分钟后，他还在那里。

She silently clicked over to another call and transferred it to the government’s legal division. A few minutes later, he was still there.

“你知道，我确实有抱怨，”他说。“我可以告诉你关于他们的事。”

“I do have complaints, you know,” he said. “I could tell you about them.”

“美好的。” 她打开了一张表格。

“Fine.” She opened a form.

“他们拆掉了旧校舍，”他说。“他们带来了一个破坏球。”

“They tore down the old schoolhouse,” he said. “They brought in a wrecking ball.”

她熟悉这座建筑，能想象它的样子。他们开始约会后不久，他就带她去了那里，这是他们第一次一起去他的老村庄。那是一所废弃的小校舍，只有两个房间，就像是历史照片里的东西。他们手牵着手漫步在空荡荡的房间里，声音很奇怪。几个月后，他们把这里当作私人聚会地点。那样的地方已经没有人上学了；事实上，已经没有人真正住在那样的地方了，那里的路很糟糕，耕地也很小，干涸了。在他长大的时候，科居的家人是最后的顽固分子之一，他们贫穷但非常自豪。

She knew the building, could picture it. He’d brought her there shortly after they’d started dating, on their first trip together to his old village. It was a small abandoned schoolhouse, just two rooms, something out of a historical photograph. They’d wandered it hand in hand, their voices strange in the empty rooms. For months afterward they used it as their private meeting spot. No one attended school in places like that anymore; actually, no one really lived in places like that anymore, with their bad roads and tiny dried-out plots of cultivated land. By the time he was growing up, Keju’s family was one of the last holdouts, poor and very proud.

“我不记得了，”她撒谎道。

“I don’t remember it,” she lied.

“你确定吗？” 他说道，语气里带着戏谑。“我知道我会的。”

“Are you sure?” he said, and his voice was teasing. “I know I do.”

她感觉脸颊开始发热。“这不是真正的抱怨，”她说。“下一个。”

She felt the heat rise in her cheeks. “Not a real complaint,” she said. “Next.”

“我只是想见见你，八一。”

“I just want to see you, Bayi.”

她不置可否地发出了一声声音。

She made a noncommittal noise.

“我还有一个，”他说。

“I have another,” he said.

“好的。” 她向新聊天发送了一个笑脸。她将如何提交举报人报告的说明复制到另一个反复闪烁的窗口中，然后点击“发送”。

“Okay.” She sent a smiley face to a new chat. She copied instructions on how to file a whistleblower report into another window that was flashing repeatedly, and hit send.

“我的父母过得不好，”他说。“自从我们搬家以来，我父亲的精神一直很差。我认为政府应该对此采取一些措施。”

“My parents aren’t doing well,” he said. “My father’s spirits have been bad ever since we were relocated. I think the government should do something about it.”

“像个医生一样。”

“Like a doctor.”

“不像医生。他看过医生。”

“Not like a doctor. He’s seen doctors.”

“那么，怎么样？”

“Like what, then?”

“我正在考虑赔偿。” 她扬起了眉毛。这是新的。十年前，当克居十四岁的时候，他的家人从农村搬到了他们老家以西二十英里的一个城市。虽然不远，但也可能是另一个国家。有一百万人居住在紧密相连的街区，有公交线路和超市；那些带有水景的公园会在整点亮起灯光并喷出弧线。那是他们两个高中时认识的地方。

“I was thinking compensation.” She raised her eyebrows. This was new. Keju’s family had been relocated from the countryside a decade ago, when he was fourteen, to a city twenty miles west of their old home. It wasn’t far, but it might as well have been another nation. It was a million people living in closely set blocks, with bus lines and supermarkets; it was parks with water features that lit up and sprayed arcs on the hour. It was where the two of them had met, back when they were in high school.

“听说他表现不佳，我感到很遗憾，”她说道，事实确实如此。她一直很喜欢科居的父亲。他痴迷于收集葫芦。他在村子里就养成了这个习惯，而在城市里，他很难找到工作，这已经成了一种习惯。他们的公寓有两个黑色书架，几乎全是葫芦，大的像水瓶，小的像玩具陀螺，有的画了，有的雕刻了。有些是他自己雕刻的。

“I’m sorry to hear he’s not doing well,” she said, and she was. She had always liked Keju’s father. He was obsessed with collecting gourds. He’d started the habit back in their village, and in the city, where he struggled to find work, it had become a fixation. Their apartment had two black bookshelves filled almost wholly with gourds, big ones like water bottles, small ones like toy tops, a few painted, others carved. Some he’d carved himself.

“拆迁补偿申请有两年的诉讼时效，”她皱着眉头说道。“你可以尝试一下烈酒管理委员会；他们经常有他可以申请的补贴。你应该给他当地的满意度办公室打电话，”她说。“他们会帮助你的。”

“There’s a two-year statute of limitations for petitions on relocation compensation,” she said, frowning a little. “You might try one of the spirit management committees; they often have subsidies he could apply for. You should call his local satisfaction office,” she said. “They’ll help you.”

“谢谢你，”他说。

“Thank you,” he said.

“很抱歉我不能做得更多，”她说，而且是认真的。她喜欢他的家人。她喜欢他母亲让厨房散发出香味的方式，将红色和绿色的甜椒切成像素，与猪肉末和切碎的粉丝混合作为午餐。她喜欢他父亲了解季节、南瓜如何生长以及如何挑选最甜的瓜的方式——她不知道它们有雄性和雌性样本（雌性的，顶部有轻微的酒窝） ，更甜）。

“I’m sorry I can’t do more,” she said, and meant it. She had liked his family. She liked the way his mother made their kitchen fragrant, dicing red and green bell peppers into pixels, mixing them with ground pork and bits of chopped vermicelli for lunch. She liked the way his father knew the seasons, how squash grew and how to pick the kinds of melons that were sweetest—​she’d had no idea they came in male and female specimens (the female ones, with their slight dimple up top, were sweeter).

“没关系，”科居说。他听起来很悲伤。到最后，即使他打了她（从来没有那么用力，不需要医生；有些女孩的情况更糟），事后他还是非常悲伤和抱歉，她发现自己拍着他的手，发出嘘声，承诺他们会渡过难关，她当然知道这是一个谎言，因为即使在那时，她也知道科朱是一块有毒的海带，它会一直粘在她身上，她需要逃跑，即使这意味着切断他紧握的肢体。尽管如此，她还是想念他的家人。

“That’s okay,” Keju said. He sounded sad.
