Toward the end, even when he’d struck her (never so hard, nothing requiring a doctor; there were girls who’d had it worse), he’d been so terminally sad and sorry afterward that she found herself patting his hand, making shushing noises, promising they’d get through it, which of course she knew was a lie, because even then she knew that Keju was a toxic piece of sea kelp that was going to cling and cling to her, that she needed to escape, even if it meant cutting off the limb he clung to. Still, she missed his family.

她的屏幕上闪烁着未回复的信息；她用眼角的余光看到乔英正起身。“我真的得走了。”她绝望地说。“请别再打电话了。每当有人这么快回电时，我的评分都会受到影响。给当地的满意度办公室打电话，好吗？”

Her screen was flashing with unanswered messages; out of the corner of her eye she saw Qiaoying starting to rise. “I really have to go,” she said desperately. “Please stop calling. It hurts my rating whenever someone calls back so quickly. Call your local satisfaction office, okay?”

“八一，你能稍等一下吗？” 他的声音现在变得愤怒、尖锐。

“Bayi, would you just hold on a moment?” His voice was getting exasperated now, bladed.

“我希望你在这里过得愉快。”她急忙补充道。“今晚屏幕上有电影。你可以在中央广场观看。检查手机上的公告。”

“I hope you enjoy your time here,” she added hurriedly. “There’s a movie tonight on the screens. You can watch it in the Central Square. Check your phone for the bulletins.”

“八一——”

“Bayi—”

“非常感谢。再见！”

“Thanks so much. Goodbye!”

下班后，她和其他一些女孩一起骑着摩托车去市中心的购物中心。第二天要举行阅兵式，这意味着政府已经提前清理了道路，所有的街道都是长长的、光荣的空柏油路，他们可以骑着摩托车下来，感觉像女王一样，可以到处曲折如果他们高兴的话。温暖的夕阳照在建筑物的钢铁和玻璃上，将它们包裹成金色。

After work, she rode her scooter with some of the other girls to the mall downtown. There was a military parade scheduled for the next day, which meant the government had cleared the roads in advance and all the streets were long, glorious stretches of empty asphalt that they could ride their scooters down and feel like queens, could do zigzags all over if they pleased. A warm sunset light caught the steel and glass of the buildings and encased them in gold.

在商场里，他们吃了韩国菜，然后走进了数十家按小时出租房间的照相馆之一。里面摆满了不同的道具和服装，巨大的泡沫饺子和紫色褶皱长袍，卡通猫面具和彩色遮阳伞，有点脏但很便宜，你可以换进换出不同的背景，绿色的泻湖，泛光灯照明的舞台，舞厅，无论你想要什么。女孩们挤在一个房间里，互相拍照，八一打扮成封建公主，苏琪打扮成老虎。

At the mall, they ate Korean food and stopped into one of the dozens of photo parlors that rented rooms by the hour. They were full of different props and costumes, giant foam dumplings and purple ruched gowns, cartoon cat masks and colorful parasols, a little dingy but cheap, and you could swap in and out different backgrounds, a green lagoon, a floodlit stage, a ballroom, whatever you wanted. The girls squeezed into one room and took repeated shots of one another, Bayi dressed as a feudal princess, Suqi as a tiger.

她没有告诉任何人关于科居的事，或者关于动物的事。有一次，他们开始约会六个月后，她在他房间的盒子里发现了一只死老鼠。它柔软、颓然、灰色，四肢僵硬，前部沾满血迹：有人部分切断了它的一条腿。

She hadn’t told anyone about Keju, or about the animals. There was the time, six months after they’d started dating, that she’d come across a dead mouse in a box in his room. It was soft and slumped and gray, stiff-limbed, front crusted with blood: someone had partially severed one of its legs.

当她面对科朱时，他说这只是一只老鼠，作为学校科学实验的一部分将被杀死。他给了它几天的自由，但他无法保留它，所以他不得不杀死它；这只是人道。这个解释令人不安，但可能合乎逻辑，所以她试图把这个想法放在一边。

When she’d confronted Keju, he’d said it was just a mouse, it was going to be killed as part of a school science experiment. He’d given it a few days of freedom but he couldn’t keep it, and so he’d had to kill it; it was only humane. The explanation was disturbing but possibly logical, and so she’d tried to put the thought aside.

然后是邻居的狗。这是一只毛茸茸的金色生物，没有脖子，像鲨鱼一样，眼睛通常半闭着睡着，一副昏昏欲睡的样子。有一次，他们坐在楼下的院子里，她对着它咕咕叫，抓着它的耳朵。“你比我更喜欢那只狗，不是吗？” 科居说过，当她反应不够快时，他用一只靴子踩在它的脖子上，笑着推了推。狗吱吱地叫着。它的喉咙里发出刺耳的声音，喉音，呜咽声。八一恳求他停下来，最后他停下来了。“放松，”他说。“我不想伤害他。” 此后，他每次看到那只狗，就像瞄准一个流浪的足球一样随意地踢它，只是为了逗弄她。

Then there was the neighbor’s dog. It was a shaggy golden creature with no neck, like a shark, and eyes usually half-closed in slumber, a somnolent thing. Once, they’d been sitting in the courtyard downstairs and she’d been cooing at it, scratching its ears. “You like that dog better than me, don’t you?” Keju had said, and when she hadn’t responded fast enough, he’d planted one boot on its neck and pushed, laughing. The dog squeaked. It made a raspy noise in its throat, guttural, whining. Bayi had pleaded for him to stop, and at last, he did. “Relax,” he’d said. “I wasn’t going to hurt him.” After that, every time he saw the dog he kicked at it, casually, as though aiming at a stray soccer ball, just to tease her.

几个月后，一只潜伏在他们高中外面的半野猫躺在柏油路上，科朱抚摸着它，直到它吓到了他，咬了他一口，流了血。几天来，科居开玩笑地说要给猫报仇，每个人都翻白眼（他喜欢这种关注），直到有一天下午，他把八一拉到一边，给她看了一把牛排刀。“我要去抓那只猫，”他说道，眼睛闪闪发光。

A few months later, one of the semi-feral cats that lurked outside of their high school had been lying on the asphalt, Keju stroking it, until it had startled and bitten him, drawing blood. Keju had talked jokingly of getting revenge on the cat for days, and everyone had rolled their eyes (he liked the attention), until one afternoon he’d pulled Bayi aside and showed her a steak knife. “I’m going to get that cat,” he’d said, eyes glinting.

“你疯了，”她说。

“You’re crazy,” she said.

“它先攻击我，”他说。

“It attacked me first,” he said.

“这是一只猫， ”她说。

“It’s a cat,” she said.

没关系。他手里拿着刀，追着猫跑，时而摇动手指，试图让它靠近，时而猛扑过去。八一看着他，几乎要哭了。她终于走开了。第二天，她看到了这只猫，它没有受伤，但一周后它就消失了。Keju没有主动提供任何信息，她也没有询问。很容易想象他会说：“我们都是动物”，诸如此类的愚蠢之语。

It didn’t matter. He’d chased the cat around, knife in hand, alternately waggling his fingers, trying to get it to approach, and lunging at it. Bayi had watched him, near tears. She’d finally walked away. The next day she saw the cat, unhurt, but a week later it disappeared. Keju didn’t volunteer any information, and she didn’t ask. It was easy to imagine what he would say: “We’re all animals,” something stupid like that.

然后有一次在看电影时，他以为她在和另一个男孩调情，他变得很刻薄，野蛮地摇晃着她。事情就是这样开始的。从那天起，他们之间发生了一些变化。有一天，午餐时，他在朋友面前翻起自己的衬衫，说道：“看，她和我一样平淡。”然后笑了。一周后，她取笑他经常用手指梳理头发，这是他紧张的抽搐，他还打了她的脸颊。每一次，他都会感到慌乱、道歉，有时还会哭泣。“我不是故意的，你只是让我不高兴，”他会说。“你是我经历过的最好的事情。”

Then there was that time at the movies when he thought she was flirting with another boy and he’d turned mean and shaken her, savagely. That was how it began. From that day on, something changed between them. One day at lunch in front of his friends, he’d flipped up his own shirt and said, “Look, she’s as flat as I am,” and laughed. A week later, she’d teased him about the way he often ran his fingers through his hair, a nervous tic of his, and he’d struck her across the cheek. Each time, he’d get flustered, apologize, occasionally weep. “I didn’t mean it, you just upset me,” he’d say. “You’re the best thing that’s ever happened to me.”

她还没有勇气和他断绝关系。相反，在她离开家追求歌手梦想后，她逐渐不再接听他的电话，也不回他的信息。最终她听说他退学了。

She wasn’t brave enough to break it off with him. Instead, after she left home to pursue her ambitions as a singer, she gradually stopped answering his calls, or returning his messages. Eventually she’d heard that he’d dropped out of school.

 

两天后，办公室的电话再次响起。

The phone rang again at the office, two days later.

“我明天就走，”科居说。“我想让你知道。”

“I’m leaving tomorrow,” Keju said. “I wanted to let you know.”

“好吧，”她一边说，一边在屏幕上随意画出鲜花和笑脸的图案，并打算将其发送给下一个给她发消息的收件人。有时她会用不同的花制作出极其精致的花束：郁金香、向日葵、玫瑰、牡丹。她特别喜欢把这些寄给老年接收者，喜欢想象他们满是皱纹的脸在看到它们时变得柔和并微笑着；它打破了这一天的单调。

“Okay,” she said, idly composing a pattern of flowers and smiley faces on her screen, which she planned to send to the next recipient who messaged her. Sometimes she made impossibly elaborate bouquets of different flowers: tulips, sunflowers, roses, peonies. She liked to send those to elderly recipients in particular, liked to imagine their wrinkled faces softening and smiling to see them; it broke up the monotony of the day.

“今天下午我没有别的事可做，”他说。“我在你办公室外面等。”

“I don’t have anything else to do this afternoon,” he said. “I’ll wait outside your office.”

然后，当她没有回答时：“别这样，八一。我走了很长的路。”

And then, when she didn’t reply: “Don’t be like that, Bayi. I came a long way.”

她让其中一个聊天窗口闲置了一分多钟，思考着，然后她的屏幕愤怒地闪红了。她低声咒骂道。

She let one of her chat windows sit idle for more than a minute, considering, and her screen flashed red angrily. She swore softly under her breath.

“八一？”

“Bayi?”

“什么？”

“What?”

“请。让我给你买杯咖啡吧。我不会再给你打电话了。”

“Please. Just let me buy you a coffee. I won’t call you again.”

“你保证？” 她说。

“You promise?” she said.

“我保证。”

“I promise.”

那天晚上下班后，他们在对面的商场广场见面。广场的喷泉被激活，孩子们尖叫着跳进跳出。“我从来不明白这有什么好玩的，”八一说，只是想说点什么。现在科居在那里，他静静地站着，看着她。他比她记忆中的矮，但也更壮实。他戴着廉价的太阳镜和一件天蓝色的衬衫，四四方方，而且太短了。

They met that evening after work, in the plaza of the mall across the way. The plaza’s fountain was activated, and kids were skipping in and out of it, screaming. “I never understood what was so fun about that,” Bayi said, just to have something to say. Now that Keju was there, he stood silently, eyeing her. He was shorter than she remembered, and stockier. He wore cheap sunglasses and a sky-blue shirt, boxy and too short.

她突然意识到他似乎有些不对劲，当他转身面对她时，她发现他失去了右臂。“哦，”她惊讶地说，然后停了下来。原本用来固定右臂的袖子被折叠起来，并用安全别针固定，就像洋娃娃的毯子一样。

It struck her that something seemed wrong with him, and as he turned to face her she saw he was missing his right arm. “Oh,” she said, surprised, then stopped herself. The sleeve that would have held his right arm was folded over and fastened with a safety pin, like a doll’s blanket.

他捕捉到了她的目光，然后移开了视线。“一场意外，”他说。

He caught her gaze and looked away. “An accident,” he said.

“我懂了。已经过去这么久了，”她说道，试图掩饰自己的震惊。

“I see. It’s been so long,” she said, trying to cover her shock.

“谢谢你来，”他说。

“Thanks for coming,” he said.

“没关系，”她不安地说，保持着距离。“你想喝点什么吗？”

“That’s okay,” she said uneasily, keeping her distance. “Did you want to get something to drink?”

他们在一个摊位前停下来，在昏暗的灯光下喝了一杯柠檬水。她付了钱。站在那里，他给人一种熟悉的感觉，就像一个远房表亲，或者一个老同学：在她的记忆中，他是一个成熟的人，但却是一个陌生人。她尽量不去看他身体旁边的空白。

They stopped at a stall and drank a lemonade in the fading light. She paid. Standing there, he felt familiar in the way of a distant cousin, or an old school acquaintance: full-fledged in her memory, but a stranger. She tried not to look at the blank space beside his body.

“那你为什么在这里？” 她问。

“So why are you here?” she asked.

“我以前从没去过，”他说，她点点头，仿佛这是一个答案。

“I’d never been before,” he said, and she nodded as though it were an answer.

她坐立不安，扫视着周围的场景，有点想知道是否有同事在附近观看。“你还和学校里的人保持联系吗？” 她茫然地说。“我一直想回去看看。” 有一段时间，她想过拜访那位鼓励她才华的音乐老师，尽管时间已经过去了，她想知道他是否还记得她。

She fidgeted, scanning the scene around them, half wondering if any of her coworkers were nearby, watching. “Do you still keep up with anyone from school?” she said inanely. “I keep meaning to go back to visit.” For a while she’d thought of visiting the music teacher who’d encouraged her talents, though enough time had passed that she wondered if he’d remember her.

科居没有回答：他的目光不断地在她身上交错，全神贯注地看着她。这让她敏锐地意识到自己衣服的形状、腰带将她系在腰间的方式、凉鞋中裸露的脚部。

Keju didn’t reply: his eyes kept crisscrossing her, absorbing her. It made her feel acutely conscious of the shape of her clothes, the way her belt held her about her waist, the exposed parts of her feet in their sandals.

“你看起来不一样了，”他说。“你看起来很好。”

“You look different,” he said. “You look nice.”

她向他道谢。“可居，你怎么了？”

She thanked him. “Keju, what happened to you?”

他定定地注视着她。近距离她可以看到他下巴上的胡茬和眼袋。他的嘴周围和脖子上出现了以前从未有过的皱纹。看到他们，她突然感到悲伤，意识到已经过去了多少英里和岁月。

He was watching her steadily. Up close she could see the stubble on his chin, the bags under his eyes. There were lines around his mouth and on his neck that hadn’t been there before. The sight of them made her feel suddenly sorrowful, aware of the miles and years that had passed.

“这是一次工厂爆炸，”他说。“一场火灾。”

“It was a factory explosion,” he said. “A fire.”

“我很抱歉。” 她可以想象：橙色的火球升上天空，居民拍摄的摇晃的镜头；每隔几周就会发生这样的事故，一些地方被忽视了，工厂检查员得到了回报，规划了从未进行过的研究。总是同样的原因。

“I’m so sorry.” She could picture it: the orange fireball going up into the sky, shaky footage shot by residents; there were accidents like that every few weeks, places that had been neglected, factory inspectors paid off, planning studies that had never been done. Always the same reasons.

“这个地方已经四年没有接受过检查了，”他说。“我们在轮班期间被锁在里面。这是一个火陷阱。”

“The place hadn’t been inspected in four years,” he said. “We were locked in during our shift. It was a firetrap.”

她同情地摇摇头。出于习惯，她发现自己想告诉他，这是正在解决的问题，政府正在制定计划，新的法律正在起草，但话到嘴边却戛然而止。

She shook her head sympathetically. Out of habit, she found herself wanting to tell him it was something that was being addressed, that there were government programs and new laws being drafted, but the words died on her lips.

“情况可能更糟，”他说。“我差点没成功。在狭小空间里躲了好几个小时。”

“Might have been worse,” he said. “I almost didn’t make it. Hid in the crawl space for hours.”

火不是什么值得躲避的东西，她想，但又无法开口说话。她不知道在他身边还能说什么。他们分道扬镳后，她惊讶地发现他竟然这么快就从她的生活中消失了，共同的朋友也没有了他的消息。后来她意识到，她是极少数与他关系密切的人之一，也许是唯一的一个。

Fire isn’t something to hide from, she thought, but couldn’t bring herself to speak. She didn’t know what she could say around him anymore. After they’d parted ways it surprised her how quickly he’d faded from her life, as did the absence of news of him from mutual friends. It occurred to her later that she had been one of very few who’d been close to him, perhaps the only one.

“我惊慌失措，”他说。“甚至没有注意到时间已经过去了多少。感觉就像我再也无法动弹了。”

“I panicked,” he said. “Didn’t even notice how much time had gone by. It felt like I’d never be able to move again.”

他背对着广场上方的屏幕站立，广场上被一条旋转的橙色螺旋照亮，仿佛太阳从他的头顶升起。你是十亿以上的人之一，这不重要吗？一个播音员在说，某种广告。没关系——​你是我们中的一员。

He was standing with his back to the screen above the square, which was lit with a swirling orange spiral, as though the sun were rising out of his head. Doesn’t it matter that you are one of a billion plus? an announcer was saying, an advertisement of some kind. It doesn’t matter—​you are one of us.

“你打断我的电话后，我变得有点疯狂。辍学了，”他说。“你从来没有告诉过我我做错了什么。”

“After you cut me off, I went a little crazy. Dropped out of school,” he said. “You never told me what I did wrong.”

八一张了张嘴，欲言又止。“那是很久以前的事了，”她说。人群源源不断地涌向屏幕。再过二十分钟，舞会就要开始了。各地区每天晚上都举行活动；这些活动是免费的，主要由退休人员参加，每个人都在一个精心设计的团体中一起摇摆。公告称，本周的主题是加勒比海。

Bayi opened her mouth to speak, then paused. “It was so long ago,” she said. There was a steady drift of the crowd moving toward the screen. In another twenty minutes, the dance party would start. The districts held them every evening; they were free and principally attended by retirees, everyone shimmying together in a choreographed group. This week, the bulletins had said, the theme was Caribbean.

“我们在一起很好，”他说。他用吸管把柠檬水喝干了，那声音让她皱起了眉头。在他身后，远处，孩子们互相追逐，尖叫着。她想知道他是否能够系鞋带、开车、切一块肉。

“We were good together,” he said. He drained his lemonade through the straw, and the sound of it made her wince. Behind him in the distance, kids chased one another, shrieking. She wondered if he was able to tie his shoes, drive a car, cut a piece of meat.

“你有没有想过那些日子？” 他说着，伸出手捧住她的脸，摸起来很粗糙。她尽量不后退或移动，而是屏住呼吸，直视前方。

“Do you ever think about those days?” he said, and reached out and cupped her face with his hand, rough to the touch. She tried not to recoil or move and instead stared straight ahead, holding her breath.

“请不要，”她声音沙哑地说。

“Please don’t,” she said, voice cracking.

他似乎没有听到：他的手现在伸进了她的头发，抚摸着她的头皮。他倾身向前，仿佛想要一个吻，温柔地低声唤着她的名字，直到她回想起自己，猛地走开。

He didn’t seem to hear: his hand was in her hair now, fingering her scalp. He leaned in as though for a kiss, tenderly murmuring her name, until she recalled herself and jerked away.

“不，”她说，语气比她本想的更加有力。

“No,” she said, more forcefully than she meant to.

他的脸就像一个被击中的孩子，有一瞬间她为自己的反应感到后悔。但随后科举转过头来面对广场的屏幕，她看到他的脸平静下来，重新整理了一下，就像什么都没有发生过一样。他很自豪。这是她一直喜欢他的一点。

His face was that of a child who’d been struck, and for a moment she regretted her reaction. But then Keju turned to face the plaza’s screen, and she saw his face smooth and rearrange itself, as though nothing had happened. He was proud. It was something she’d always liked about him.

他们静静地看着人群：远处响起了鼓声。她用眼角的余光看到他在看着她，但她坚定地盯着前方。

They watched the crowd silently: a distant sound of drumbeats was starting up. Out of the corner of her eye, she could see him looking at her, but she stared determinedly ahead.

“不管怎样，我很高兴见到你，”他最后说道，仿佛这个城市有一定数量的景点，而她也在名单上。

“Anyway, I’m glad I got to see you,” he said finally, as though the city had a set number of attractions and she was on the list.

“这里很好，不是吗？” 她语气缓和了。

“It’s nice here, isn’t it?” she said, relenting.

他的目光超越了她：这是一个令人愉快的场景，孩子们跑来跑去，一群退休人员穿着鲜艳的裙子和亮片上衣，准备跳舞。外围是穿着黑色制服的保安人员，其中有几个人随意地与穿过广场的游客交谈，还有几个人对着对讲机说话。

He looked beyond her: it was a pleasant scene, the kids running around, the crowds of retirees in their bright skirts and sequined tops, getting ready to dance. On the perimeter were the black-uniformed security officers, a couple of them casually talking with tourists crossing the plaza, a few speaking into walkie-talkies.

“说实话，这让我感到毛骨悚然，”科朱说。

“To be honest, it gives me the creeps,” Keju said.

“我想这需要习惯，”她僵硬地说。她看着他脖子上挂的挂绳，绿色的绳子和肥皂盒大小的绿色徽章，清楚地表明他是一个非居民。他的照片几乎认不出来了，他的脸蜡黄，太宽，比例严重不适合徽章；这让他看起来像个老了很多的人。

“I guess it takes getting used to,” she said stiffly. She looked at the lanyard strung around his neck, its green cord and green badge the size of a soap dish clearly identifying him as a non-resident. The photo of him was scarcely recognizable, his face sallow, too broad, its proportions badly rendered to fit the badge; it made him look like a much older man.

“你真的应该打电话给当地的满意度办公室，”她说。“我希望你爸爸没事。”

“You should really call your local satisfaction office,” she said. “I hope your dad will be okay.”

科居盯着喷泉，沉默了几分钟。“你总是认为自己对一切都太好了，”他说。“你会成为一位伟大的歌手，还记得吗？”

Keju was silent for a few minutes, staring at the fountain. “You always thought you were too good for everything,” he said. “You were going to be this great singer, remember?”

她短暂地闭上了眼睛。“我记得。”

She shut her eyes, briefly. “I remember.”

“现在看看你，整天在小隔间里接电话，”他声音严厉地说。“独自一人在这个大城市。真的，八一，我对不起你。”

“Now look at you, taking calls all day in a cubicle,” he said, his voice harsh. “All alone in this big city. Really, Bayi, I’m sorry for you.”

加勒比音乐的旋律开始向他们飘来，一些身穿黑制服的警察正在分发沙球。他们喝完柠檬水，陷入紧张的沉默，最后她打破了沉默。“我得走了，Keju。” 没有什么可说的了。“祝一切顺利，”她说。

Strains of Caribbean music were starting to drift to them, some of the black-uniformed police were handing out maracas. They finished their lemonade and lapsed into a strained silence, which finally she broke. “I’ve got to go, Keju.” There wasn’t anything else to say. “Good luck with everything,” she said.

他们分手后，八一还无法让自己转入地下，目前还没有。她决定走一会儿。她想，她的父母会希望她嫁给他。他身上有一种安静可靠的感觉：有一次，当他外出度假时，网络出现故障，他步行两英里寻找一个可以打电话向她道晚安的地方。“你永远找不到一个如此爱你的人，”她记得她母亲说。如果他们也结婚了，那就意味着八一会一直待在家里，不再是京城里的单身女孩，接听只有谁知道的电话——当然，这是一份好工作，一个政府工作，但仍然。

After they parted, Bayi couldn’t bring herself to go underground, not quite yet. She’d walk awhile, she decided. Her parents, she thought, would have liked her to marry him. There was something quietly dependable about him: once when he was away on a holiday and the networks were down he’d walked two miles to find a place to call and say good night to her. “You’ll never find anyone who loves you so much,” she remembered her mother saying. If they’d married, too, it would have meant that Bayi would’ve stayed at home, wouldn’t have been a single girl in the capital, taking calls from who only knew—​of course it was a good job, a government job, but still.

他们喝完柠檬水后不久，她的手机上就弹出了一条公告。注意，它写道：学习睡前要做的五件事，让你醒来时神清气爽。她把注意力转向屏幕，看着一位美丽的女人从四颗宝石红色的草莓上切掉茎，然后在水槽里冲洗它们。

There was a bulletin on her phone that had popped up moments after they’d finished their lemonade. Attention, it ran: learn the five things to do before bedtime to wake up refreshed. She turned her attention to the screen and watched as a beautiful woman cut the stems off a quartet of ruby-red strawberries and rinsed them at a sink.

几个街区后，有人大喊，她抬起头来。是苏琪，坐在一辆大货车的方向盘上，车窗摇下，咧着嘴笑。

A few blocks later, someone shouted and she looked up. It was Suqi, sitting at the steering wheel of a large van, window rolled down, grinning.

这是一辆没有标记的政府货车。任何人都可以看出这是为了那些不满的人，那些试图煽动骚乱的抗议者，他们通常来自城外。它有所有微妙的迹象：丢失的车牌，前排乘客座位上那个大个子男人冷漠地盯着前方，金属格栅将苏琪和她的载人货物分开，开往附近的拘留中心。后座的窗户是有色的，但透过挡风玻璃，她可以看到座位大部分都坐满了。

It was an unmarked government van. Anyone could tell it was intended for the discontented, the protesters who tried to stir up trouble, usually from out of town. It had all the subtle signs: the missing license plate, the large man staring stolidly ahead in the front passenger’s seat, the metal grill separating Suqi from her human cargo, bound for a nearby detention center. The backseat windows were tinted, but through the windshield she could see the seats were mostly filled.

“你想搭车吗？” 苏琪指着后座说道。

“You want a ride?” Suqi said, gesturing to the backseat.

八一苦笑一声。“闭嘴，”她说，然后继续走。

Bayi forced a laugh. “Shut up,” she said, and kept walking.

“随你便吧，”苏琪说着，伸出了一点粉红色的舌头。八一也笑了笑，目送她开车离开。她想，她应该回家，把脚泡在热水里，也许看点什么。她很高兴能下班，很高兴现在是春天。她想，年轻真好，周末好，自由真好。

“Have it your way,” Suqi said, and stuck out her tongue, a little fillip of pink. Bayi smiled back and watched her drive off. She’d go home, she thought, put her feet in some hot water, maybe watch something. She was glad to be off work, glad it was spring. It was good, she thought, to be young, to have a weekend, to be free.

新水果

New Fruit

这是一种奇特的水果：橙红色的黄褐色果皮，果肉致密，柔软而奢华。它的形状大致像一个鸡蛋，有一个黄色的小坑，装在板条箱里出售，板条箱里衬着深绿色的叶子。

It was a peculiar fruit: the orange-red tawny skin, its flesh dense and velvety and luxurious. It was shaped roughly like an egg, with a tiny yellow pit, sold packed into crates lined with its deeply green leaves.

这种水果的味道奇妙而稀有，甜中带酸。我们排了几个街区的队，从街头小贩那里购买。我们互相咬了一口，尽管从未令人满意。对我来说，绿色花瓶里新鲜的向日葵的味道可能对你来说就像你女儿穿着袜子的小脚在大厅里蹦蹦跳跳的声音。

The fruit had a taste marvelous and rare, sweet with an underside of acid. We lined up for blocks to buy it from street peddlers. We exchanged bites, though never satisfactorily. What tasted to me like the look of freshly arranged sunflowers in a green vase might taste to you like the way your daughter’s tiny socked feet sounded romping down the hall.

对于老周来说，这闻起来就像他擦掉自己雕刻的长凳上的刨花，并涂上奶油清漆时的味道。对于朱阿姨来说，是从小记忆已久的妈妈煮饭的香味，还有外面的雨声。对于其他人来说，这是当你年轻、美丽、穿着完全适合你的新衣服时出现的混合着羡慕和钦佩的表情。

For Lao Zhou, it smelled like it did when he wiped the shavings off a bench he’d carved himself, and applied a creamy varnish. For Zhu Ayi, it was the scent of her mother cooking rice, long-remembered from childhood, and the sound of rain outside. For others it was the look of mingled envy and admiration that came when you were young, and beautiful, and wearing something new that suited you exactly.

有一天，这些水果用卡车运到了该市的批发市场，板条箱上写着“孙山农产品”，与桃子、李子、葡萄和其他我们更熟悉的水果共享空间。起初，只有小贩在卖这种水果——他们之所以买下它，是因为它便宜、新奇、甜——但很快杂货店也以“奇果”（一种奇特的水果）的名字进货。

The fruit had arrived one day in trucks at the city’s wholesale market in crates that said SUNSHAN PRODUCE, sharing space with peaches and plums and grapes and other fruit with which we were more familiar. At first it was just the peddlers who sold the fruit—​who’d picked it up because it was cheap and novel and sweet—​but soon grocery stores were stocking it, too, under the name qiguo, peculiar fruit.

老周是街上第一个尝试的。他是个鳏夫，每天早上很早就起床去购物，通常是最早到附近市场的人之一。四月的一天，他带着一打装在塑料袋里的水果回来，并把它们递给他看到的任何人。“试试吧，”他说，声音中的警觉让我们感到惊讶。

Lao Zhou was the first on the street to try it. He was a widower who woke early every morning and did his shopping, was usually among the first at the neighborhood market. One day in April, he came back with a dozen of the fruit swaying in a plastic bag and handed them to anyone he saw. “Try it,” he said, an alertness in his voice that surprised us.

庞阿姨出去散步，好奇地拿了一张。第一口就让她的脸颊泛起淡淡的粉红色。“哦，”她说。“噢，真好吃。” 我们这些站着看她和老周对话的人都皱起了眉头。那一刻有一些私密的东西，尽管人们经常发现庞阿姨蹲在公共厕所里八卦，我们，我们任何人都不会怀疑她有什么保留。

Pang Ayi, out for a stroll, took one curiously. The first bite made her cheeks burn softly pink. “Oh,” she said. “Oh, how tasty.” Those of us who stood watching the exchange between her and Lao Zhou raised our eyebrows. There was something private in that moment, even though Pang Ayi was frequently found gossiping while squatting in the common privies and it would not have occurred to us, to any of us, to suspect her of holding anything in reserve.

那是一个特别寒冷的冬天，几个月来，我们的嘴唇都干裂了，靠着炖白菜过活，几个月里我们翻起衣领，顺便互相点点头，保持沉默，把电视开得很高。七国到来时，春天刚刚来临，脱掉外衣，无拘无束地行走，真是一种解脱。

It had been an especially frigid winter, months of chapped lips and living off stocks of stewed cabbage, months in which we had turned up our coat collars and nodded to one another in passing and kept to ourselves and turned the television up high. By the time the qiguo arrived, spring was just making itself felt, and it was a relief to shed our coats and walk unencumbered.

我们这些吃过七果的人注意到，阳光照在我们的四肢上是温暖的，外面叮当作响的自行车铃声让我们想起了温暖的空气，想起了春风，想起了可能性。我们更多地微笑，让我们的目光在街上相遇。“今天我吃了一个，尝起来就像我刚刚讲了一个好笑话，每个人都在笑，”老隋可能会说。母亲们会把捣碎的水果喂给她们的婴儿，我们会围在一起观看她们小脸的惊喜和惊奇。

Those of us who ate the qiguo noticed that the sun was warm on our limbs and the sound of a bicycle bell tinkling outside reminded us of the warm air, of the spring breeze, of possibilities. We smiled more often, let our eyes meet in the street. “Today I had one that tasted like I had just told a good joke and everyone was laughing,” Lao Sui might say. Mothers would feed mashed-up pieces of the fruit to their babies and we’d crowd around to watch the surprise and wonder that transformed their small faces.

那个赛季我们对彼此更加友善。在当地一家银行工作的冯先生，一天早上尝了一个七果，后来他发现公寓楼入口处的铁门粘住了，导致住在一楼的老太太有时会被困住。有人看到她站在外面，等待邻居进出，这样她就可以跟在他们后面溜进去。他抓起一些钳子下楼看看能不能修好。

We were kinder to one another that season. Mr. Feng, who worked at a local bank, tasted a qiguo one morning and afterward it occurred to him that the metal door at the entrance to the apartment building was sticking, so that the elderly woman who lived on the first floor could sometimes be seen standing outside, waiting for a neighbor to enter or exit so she could slip in behind them. He grabbed some pliers and went downstairs to see whether he could fix it.

其他大大小小的变化也发生了。令所有人惊讶的是，与她同住三楼的朱阿姨的儿子辞掉了当地工厂的工作，南下当了一名油漆工；他咬了一口七果，（他是这么说的）看到了湿润的银色和浑浊的金色的日落，他决心把它捕捉到画布上，不管（他母亲是这么说的）他没有天赋，会走向一个失败的境地。坏结局。

Other changes happened, big and small. To everyone’s astonishment, Zhu Ayi’s son, who lived with her on the third floor, quit his job at a local factory and moved south to be a painter; he had taken a bite of the qiguo and (so he said) seen a sunset of moist silver and cloudy gold that he was determined to capture on canvas, no matter (so his mother said) that he had no talent and would come to a bad end.

经常有人看到在邻居家当杂工的老周在吃这种水果。那年春天，他发现自己挥动锤子时唱歌的次数增多了，他的血液里感受到了一种长期休眠的不安。他注意到附近的年轻女孩都穿着高腰裙子；这似乎是新时尚。他注意到远处传来发动机加速的声音。给庞阿姨第一颗水果的那天，他发现她的腰身轮廓依然清晰可见，即使是现在穿着宽松的衬衫，虽然认识多年，却有一种新鲜感。关于她令他惊讶的眼睛。品尝七果的时候，他第一次意识到自己还不是一个老人。

Lao Zhou, who worked as the neighborhood handyman, was often seen eating the fruit. That spring, he found himself singing more often as he swung his hammer, feeling a long-dormant restlessness in his blood. He noticed the young girls in the neighborhood were wearing high-waisted skirts; it seemed to be the new fashion. He noticed the far-off sound of a revving engine in the distance. The day he’d given Pang Ayi her first piece of the fruit, he noticed that the shape of her waist was still visible, even in the baggy shirts she wore now, and though they had known each other for years, there was a freshness about her eyes that surprised him. For the first time it occurred to him, tasting the qiguo, that he was not yet an old man.

街区里唯一拒绝尝试这种水果的是庞阿姨的丈夫孙先生。他是一名退休的铁路巡视员，性情固执，不吃大部分水果，只吃妻子的拉面和月牙饺子。他是一个清醒的人，不爱多说话，但当他妻子问起时，他确实对气国进行了猛烈的抨击。“不自然，”他说。“别相信它。孙山，呸！”

The only one on the block who refused to try the fruit was Mr. Sun, Pang Ayi’s husband. A retired railway inspector, he had a stubborn streak and refused to eat most fruits, preferring instead to subsist on his wife’s hand-pulled noodles and crescent-moon-shaped dumplings. He was a sober man, not given to talking much, though he did inveigh against the qiguo when his wife asked. “Not natural,” he said. “Don’t trust it. Sunshan, pah!”

那一季，太阳山农产品的创始人范士毅受到了各地的热烈欢迎。他是一个瘦小、干瘪的老人，电视上经常出现他站在长满七果的小树林前的画面。树很矮，树枝多节，果实在深黑色的叶子的映衬下发出红色和橙色的光芒。经常有人拍到他的妻子和他在一起，对着镜头咧着嘴笑，牙齿有缝隙。

The founder of Sunshan Produce, Fan Shiyi, was feted everywhere that season. He was a tiny, wizened old man, usually pictured on television standing before a grove laden with the qiguo. The trees were short, their branches gnarled, the fruit glowing red and orange against their deeply dark leaves. Often his wife was pictured with him, grinning, gap-toothed, at the camera.

那年春末，我们都熟记在心了范士毅的故事：这位老人如何多年来以杂交水果为爱好，他的许多实验如何在他最终成熟之前尝起来是酸的或粉状的，或者是在藤蔓上枯萎的。发明了七果——健康、富含维生素、美味！

By the end of that spring, we all knew Fan Shiyi’s story by heart: how the old man had crossbred fruit as a hobby for years, how so many of his experiments had tasted sour or mealy or had withered on the vine before he had finally invented the qiguo—​healthy, full of vitamins, and delicious!

官方媒体对范士毅的成功故事表示欢迎。记者说，七果是草根智慧的象征，“一种新水果，是我们新国家的象征。”

The state media embraced Fan Shiyi’s tale of success. The qiguo was a symbol of grassroots ingenuity, its reporters said, “a new fruit that is a symbol of our new nation.”

我们站在水槽边吃，果汁顺着下巴流下来。我们一边散步一边把它放在冰沙里吃，然后切片放在冷冻酸奶上。在课堂上，老师把它分发给学生；据说它可以让最聪明的学生变得更加聪明，让那些不听话的学生更加关注同学的需求。在我们的街区，在我们的街区，我们这些吃过它的人发现太阳似乎闪耀着不寻常的亮度，树叶反射出更明亮的玉色。连脾气暴躁的保安保安，也开始对来来往往的居民微笑点头。

We ate it standing by the sink, juices running down our chins. We ate it in smoothies while strolling and sliced atop frozen yogurt. In classrooms, teachers handed it out to students; it was said it made the brightest pupils more clever, the recalcitrant ones more heedful of their classmates’ needs. In our neighborhood, on our block, those of us who ate it found the sun seemed to shine with an unwonted brightness, the tree leaves reflecting a more brilliant shade of jade. Even the surly bao’an, the man who guarded the front gate, began smiling and nodding at residents who came and went.

然而，这个季节并没有持续下去。最后一批装载奇果的卡车于五月下旬抵达，到了初夏，奇果就不再出售了。相反，我们心怀不满地在超市过道里闲逛，路过成堆的梨子、杏子和香蕉，现在它们的味道平淡而木头，没有味道。我们买了更多让我们想起七国的水果——油桃、橙子——然后把它们吃了一半就扔掉了。

The season, though, didn’t last. The last trucks bearing qiguo arrived in late May, and by early summer, the fruit was no longer being sold. Instead we roamed the supermarket aisles discontentedly, passing piles of pears and apricots and bananas, which now tasted insipid and wooden, without flavor. We bought more of the fruits that reminded us of the qiguo—​nectarines, oranges—​and discarded them half-eaten.

那一年的夏天异常炎热。几个星期过去了，我们彼此之间变得越来越烦躁，因为炎热而感到刺痛。夫妻吵架了。院子里孩子们互相追逐的声音让我们心烦意乱。没有气果，婴儿就会在潮湿的环境中烦躁并拒绝母亲的乳房。几个街区之外，第八生产厂的一名工人因中暑和过度劳累而死亡，随后举行了罢工；那个女孩当时只有十六岁。

Summer was unusually hot that year. As the weeks went by, we grew increasingly irritable with one another, prickly with the heat. Couples fought. The noise of children chasing one another in the courtyard grated on our nerves. Without the qiguo, babies fussed in the humidity and refused their mothers’ breasts. A few blocks away, the No. 8 Production Facility workers went on strike after one of their number succumbed to heat and overwork and died; the girl had been just sixteen years old.

但庞阿姨的脾气依然很好。事实上，她的绽放令人惊叹。以前，我们认为她只不过是街坊里的闲话，一个生了两个孩子，擅长包饺子的女人，是的，她自己在某种程度上很像一个饺子，她通常穿着同样廉价的全腿。休闲裤和宽松的薄纱衬衫。然而，那年夏天，我们注意到她烫了头发，并开始穿颜色鲜艳的荷叶边短裙，就像其他女人跳舞时穿的那样。有人看到她从一丛灌木上折下一朵半开的玫瑰。它长在公寓的庭院里，荒谬地长在她的头发里。

Pang Ayi, though, remained in good temper. In fact she had blossomed astoundingly. Before, we had thought of her as little more than the neighborhood gossip, a woman who had borne two children and excelled at dumpling-making and, yes, resembled to a certain degree a dumpling herself, who usually wore the same cheap full-legged slacks and a baggy, gauzy shirt. That summer, though, we noticed that she had gotten a perm and had taken to wearing short, flouncy skirts in bright colors, the kind other women would go dancing in. She had been observed snapping a half-opened rose off one of the bushes that grew in the apartment’s courtyard and putting it, absurdly, in her hair.

现在经常可以看到她和老周在市场里闲聊，吃着花菜和长豆。有几个下午，人们看到她和鳏夫爬上附近公园一座茉莉花覆盖的小山，一边欣赏风景，一边吃着月牙形的饺子。

Often she and Lao Zhou could now be found chatting in the market, lingering over the cauliflower and long beans. On several afternoons, she and the widower were seen climbing a jasmine-covered hill at a nearby park and lunching on some of her crescent-moon-shaped dumplings while gazing at the view.

我们中有人记得，当年庞阿姨的小儿子摔断了腿，孙先生外出旅游时，是老周背着他去找黄包车。“他一直对她很忠诚，”我们互相告诉。

Some of us remembered that when Pang Ayi’s youngest son had broken his leg all those years ago and Mr. Sun was away traveling, it was Lao Zhou who had carried him to find a rickshaw. “He’s always been devoted to her,” we told one another.

夏季渐入秋季，暑气终于消散。魏嘉玲的新歌《我的甜七果》发行了，几个月来，这首甜蜜的单曲在公交车上、超市里到处播放。这是一首情歌：苦中带甜，我的宝贝，我甜蜜的奇异果子。当这首歌一响起，人群中就会有一种奇特的感觉：一种向后的向往。通常有人会开始哼唱，很快我们中就有不少人开始唱歌。这么多声音，让人好奇。令人腻味的歌词给人一种更像挽歌的感觉。

Summer mellowed into fall, and the heat finally broke. Carina Wei’s new hit, “My Sweet Qiguo,” was released, and for a few months, the treacly single played everywhere, on buses and in supermarkets. It was a love song: From the bitter comes the sweet, my baby, my sweet strange fruit. When the song came on, a peculiar feeling would steal over the crowd: a kind of backward yearning. Often someone would begin to hum, and soon more than a few of us would be singing. With so many voices, it was curious; the cloying lyrics took on the feeling of something more like a dirge.

冬天来了，随之而来的是同样干燥干裂的皮肤，同样的日常大白菜和韭菜菜肴，以及我们在院子里储存的两种蔬菜。不知何故，那个赛季我们的麻烦给我们带来了更大的压力。这座城市显得更加无色，灰色的天空将我们困住。我们想起了失去的家人；我们想起了家人。我们的睡眠充满了太多的梦。在一个特别寒冷的夜晚，住在四楼的老太太烧了一些煤，没有先打开排气口；她因一氧化碳窒息而死。我们说，这是一次意外。

Winter came, and with it the same dry chapped skin, the same routine of heavy cabbage-and-leek dishes, two vegetables that we stockpiled in the courtyard. Our troubles weighed more heavily on us, somehow, that season. The city looked more colorless, the gray sky pinning us in. We thought of the family we had lost; our sleep was burdened with too many dreams. On one especially cold night, the old woman who lived on the fourth floor burned some coal without first opening her exhaust vents; she suffocated on the carbon monoxide and died. It was an accident, we said.

我们所有人都期待着春天，期待着新的水果季节。

All of us looked forward to the spring, and a new season of fruit.

 

这次，七果只卖给连锁超市——你再也不能从街头小贩那里买到了。它们的包装方式也不同，每件都用绿色泡沫围住，并用白色薄纸包裹，在装饰盒中按打出售。成本相应上涨，我们自然会抱怨。

This time the qiguo were sold exclusively to supermarket chains—​you couldn’t buy them from street peddlers anymore. They were wrapped differently, too, each piece surrounded by a collar of green foam and swathed in white tissue paper, sold by the dozen in a decorative box. The cost had gone up accordingly, and, naturally, we groused.

但这并不重要，并不重要，我们是如此渴望再次品尝这种水果，将它握在手中，并再次被它所带来的感觉所感动。上架第一天，我们和邻居们在超市外排了一个多小时的队，一派喜气洋洋的气氛。我们听说，一些商店实行配给制：每个买家只能购买两盒。我们相视一笑，互相打招呼，我们沐浴在春天般的天气里。

But it didn’t matter, not much, so eager were we to taste the fruit again, to hold it in our hands and again be moved by the feelings that it conjured. On the first day it arrived on shelves, we lined up outside the supermarket for more than an hour with our neighbors, an air of festivity beckoning. Some shops, we heard, were rationing it: only two boxes per buyer. We smiled at one another, we greeted one another, we basked in the springlike weather.

“终于，”我们互相告诉。“终于。”

“At last,” we told one another. “At last.”

在等待的过程中，我们交换了各自的故事。朱阿姨说，她坐在轮椅上的母亲在尝试七果之前已经在室内待了很多年，七果散发出美妙的花香，最终将她引诱到外面的庭院。“现在她每天都出去，”她说。

As we waited, we swapped our stories. Zhu Ayi said that her wheelchair-bound mother had been indoors for years before trying the qiguo, which imparted a wonderful scent of flowers that finally tempted her outside to the courtyard. “Now she goes outside every day,” she said.

“我吃的第一口让我感觉自己又回到了二十五岁，”冯先生对着队伍的最后面大声说道。很明显，他也试图捕捉到同样的样子，他把剩下的头发梳理在秃顶上，从去年春天开始，就经常有人看到他在院子里做充满活力的健美操。

“The first one I ate made me feel like I was twenty-five again,” Mr. Feng was heard to say loudly, toward the back of the line. It was clear that he’d tried to capture the same look, too, had taken to combing the remains of his hair over his bald pate, and ever since the previous spring had been regularly spotted doing energetic calisthenics out in the courtyard.

但第二天早上，我们不自在地躲避着彼此的目光。我们盯着自己的脚。

But the next morning, we dodged one another’s eyes uncomfortably; we stared at our feet.

我们带着包裹匆匆回家，打开水果包装，并进行了仪式性的清洗。七果的味道是一样的，口感丰富，果肉耐嚼，让我们的牙齿慢慢地陷进去，甜甜的，下面有酸味。然而，这一次，随之而来的感觉是黑暗和不和谐的，就像胃痛一样。

We had gone hurriedly home with our parcels, had unwrapped the fruit and washed it with ceremony. The qiguo tasted the same, the rich texture and resistant flesh that our teeth sank slowly through, the sweetness, with its notes of acid beneath. This time, though, the feelings that followed were dark and discordant, the emotional equivalent of a stomachache.

冯先生独自一人在家里的厨房里，满怀期待地切着水果。然而，吃了几块馅饼后，他开始咳嗽，不得不坐下来，当他想起那个被他和他的一些同学殴打的戴着鸭舌帽的老人的样子时，他感到一种胆汁升腾起来。直到他倒下，然后…… 。。出色地 。。。那是很多年前的事了，那是不同的时代。尽管如此，他还是把头埋进怀里，过了十分钟，恶心的感觉才消退。

Alone at home in his kitchen, Mr. Feng had cut expectantly into the fruit. After consuming a few tart pieces, though, he’d begun coughing and had to sit down, a feeling of bile rising up in him as he remembered the look of the old man in a dunce cap that he and some of his schoolmates had beaten until he’d collapsed and . . . well . . . it was many years ago and those were different times. Nonetheless, he buried his head in his arms and it took ten minutes before the wave of nausea receded.

电话响了好几声才被他接起。那是他当天早些时候在排队时看到的一个朋友。“怎么样？好吗？” 他的朋友问道。

The phone rang several times before he picked it up. It was a friend whom he’d seen in line earlier that day. “Was it good?” his friend asked.

“很好。”冯先生顿了顿，说道。“那你的怎么样？”

“Very good,” Mr. Feng had said, after a pause. “How about yours?”

“出色的。”

“Excellent.”

我们互相撒谎，掩盖了水果的功效。朱阿姨吃下第一块的时候，一股强烈的羞耻感袭来，让她的视线一时模糊。有一次她让儿子独自一人，他在炉子上烫伤了自己，有一次她给婆婆喂了一块掉在地板上的鱼——这些和其他的记忆，怒气冲冲地责备她。

We were lying to one another, covering up the fruit’s effects. Zhu Ayi, when she’d eaten her first piece, was swept with a feeling of shame so powerful that for a moment her vision blurred. There was the time she’d left her son alone and he’d scalded himself on the stove, the time she’d fed her mother-in-law a piece of fish that had fallen on the floor—​these and other memories, surging up and reproaching her.

在家里，老周吃完一盘七果，顿时被一种深不可测的悲痛淹没，坐得目瞪口呆。当他闭上眼睛时，他所能想象的只是一个男人被迫在脖子上挂一个写着“资产阶级”的大牌子，跪在人群面前。这个人是他的父亲，一位书法家。直到他被石头砸死几天后被埋葬，他才再次见到他。老周坐在桌前一动不动，此后两天没有出门。

Inside his home, Lao Zhou finished a plate of qiguo and was immediately flooded with a grief so vast and unfathomable that he sat stunned. When he closed his eyes, all he could picture was a man who was forced to wear a big sign about his neck that read BOURGEOISIE, kneeling before a crowd. The man was his father, a calligrapher. He did not see him again until he was buried, days after being stoned. Lao Zhou sat at his table without moving, and for two days after that, he didn’t go outside.

偶尔，一块水果会唤起我们对第一个七果季节的记忆，一种心跳的感觉，就像被舞伴甩出去一样；一种温暖的满足感，就像被家人包围一样，幸福、完整、幸福。然而，大多数时候，果实都伴随着悔恨和羞愧的感觉。

Occasionally a piece of fruit would restore to us a memory of that first qiguo season, a skipping of the heart, like being swung out by a dance partner; a warm feeling of contentment, like being surrounded by one’s family, well and whole and happy. Most of the time, though, the fruit carried with it feelings of remorse, and shame.

但我们还是继续吃它。当然，不那么频繁。但你可以希望得到一部好作品，无论如何，我们渴望它的味道，在黑暗的感觉开始出现之前，它持续了几个辉煌的时刻。

And yet we kept eating it. Not so often, of course. But you could hope for a good piece, and anyway we craved its flavor, which lingered for a few glorious moments before the dark feelings began to set in.

很快，报纸头条报道了我们已经知道的事情。他们说，这是一个糟糕的季节，一个糟糕的季节。

Soon, newspaper headlines were reporting what we already knew. It was a bad season, they said, a bad season.

我们中的一些人尝试腌制七果，或者发酵它。我们尝试烹饪它，添加糖并将其与其他水果混合在蜜饯中。它们都没有改善其效果。不久之后，超市开始促销：特殊水果，半价。

Some of us tried pickling the qiguo, or fermenting it. We tried cooking it, adding sugar and mixing it in a compote with other fruits. None of it improved its effects. Before long, supermarkets were running sales: PECULIAR FRUIT, HALF-PRICE.

我们想要答案。太阳山农产品的范世毅在接受电视采访时表示，那个季节下了异常大雨，导致土壤酸度很高，这或许可以解释任何异常现象。“在食用之前，它应该适当成熟，”他说，但我们觉得他的话并没有多少说服力。他的妻子不再出现在镜头前。

We wanted answers. On television, when he was interviewed, Fan Shiyi of Sunshan Produce said that there had been unusually heavy rain that season, creating high levels of acidity in the soil, which might explain any irregularities. “It should be ripened properly before being eaten,” he said, but his words didn’t carry much conviction, we felt. His wife had stopped appearing on camera.

在全国范围内，奇怪的故事开始浮出水面。有一个中学生，他的妈妈在他的午餐里放了一个七果；那天下午，男孩爬上学校的屋顶并跳了下去。有一位商人突然宣布他将捐出一半财产，在采访中经常看到他擦拭眼睛；我们以为他吃了七果，是想弥补过去的罪孽。

Nationwide, odd stories had begun to surface. There was a middle-school student whose mother had packed a qiguo in his lunch; the boy had climbed up to the school’s roof that afternoon and jumped. There was a businessman who abruptly announced he was giving away half his fortune, and in interviews was frequently seen dabbing at his eyes; we assumed he had eaten a qiguo and was trying to atone for some guilty past.

我们小区里，变化最大的是庞阿姨。你可以看到她脸上紧绷的表情、烫过的头发变得卷曲的变化，以及她眼神中遥远而近乎尴尬的神情。现在，当其他女人在公共厕所里碰到她时，庞阿姨不再并肩蹲着友善地聊天，而是匆匆说完就走。

In our neighborhood, it was Pang Ayi who changed the most. You saw the change in the pinched expression on her face, in the way her permed hair had gone frizzy, in the distant, almost embarrassed look she had in her eyes. Now, when other women ran into her in the common privy, instead of companionably chatting as they squatted side by side, Pang Ayi would hastily finish up and leave.

庞阿姨一生都是一个极其务实的女人。她嫁给了孙先生，一个在铁路局有稳定工作的男人。她已经忍受了他长期缺席的情况。她生了两个孩子，在一家纺织厂工作了三十四年，然后拿着微薄的养老金退休。她和孙先生并没有太多共同的爱好，但是什么是爱好呢？他们当时六十三岁。孙先生是个工作踏实的人，并不介意她的喋喋不休。他喜欢她做饭，她也喜欢为他做饭。他们彼此相爱，这超出了大多数婚姻的范畴。

All her life, Pang Ayi had been a supremely practical woman. She had married Mr. Sun, a man with a steady job at the railway bureau; she’d put up with his long absences. She had borne two children and worked for thirty-four years at a textile mill before retiring with a modest pension. She and Mr. Sun did not share many passions, but what was passion? They were sixty-three years old. Mr. Sun was a steady worker who did not mind her chatter. He liked her cooking, and she enjoyed cooking for him. They were fond of each other, and that was more than you could say about most marriages.

但她也不能否认，她最近对老周产生了一种依恋。他们两个意见一致，她想。在其他人看来，八卦者的本能实际上是一种强烈的欲望，只是为了注意事物，了解事物的可能性以及它们的含义，无论是邻居脸上掠过的某种表情，还是屋顶上的一群椋鸟。老周也是这样，她想。他注意到了她的一切。

And yet, she couldn’t deny she had formed an attachment as of late to Lao Zhou. The two of them saw eye to eye, she thought. What other people saw as a gossip’s instinct was really a fierce desire simply to notice things, to see the possibilities in things and what they meant, whether it was a certain expression that flitted across a neighbor’s face or a flock of starlings on the roof. Lao Zhou was the same way, she thought. He noticed everything about her.

尽管如此，在过去的一年里，庞阿姨一直坚信没有理由和她的丈夫谈论这件事。她不想离开他，不想伤害他。她想，只要在​​市场上见到老周，偶尔给他送上一份新月形的饺子，在凉爽的夜晚一起散步，感受旧日友谊的余烬，就足够了。轻轻搅拌。偶尔她会感觉到他的手放在她的肘部。进入黑暗后，他用手臂搂住了她的腰，他们就这样走了半个街区。

Still, all through that previous year, Pang Ayi had been convinced there was no reason to speak to her husband about the matter. She did not want to leave him, did not want to hurt him. It was enough, she thought, simply to see Lao Zhou in the market, to bring to him occasional helpings of her crescent-moon-shaped dumplings, to walk with each other in the cool of the evening and feel the embers of an old friendship gently stirred. Occasionally she felt his hand at her elbow. Once in the darkness he had slipped his arm about her waist and they had walked like that for half a block.

但那年春天，在超市买的七果盒吃到一半时，庞阿姨感到一股羞耻感涌上心头，她紧紧抓住柜台才稳住自己。当时她正站在厨房里，切下宝石色的水果片，放进嘴里。当她吃完剩下的酸甜可口的七果时，她对自己感到厌恶，甚至故意拿起菜刀在空中晃动了一会儿，然后猛地把它扔到了柜台对面，远离了自己。 。然后她就坐在地板上哭了。

But that spring, halfway through the qiguo box she had bought at the supermarket, Pang Ayi felt a sense of shame surge within her, so powerful that she gripped the counter to steady herself. At the time she had been standing in the kitchen, cutting jewel-colored slices of the fruit and placing them in her mouth. By the time she finished the rest of the qiguo, tart and delicious, she abhorred herself, so much so that she deliberately took the kitchen knife and let it waver in the air for a moment before jerkily throwing it across the counter, away from her. Then she sat down on the floor, crying.

当孙先生听到叮当声进来问她怎么了时，她告诉了他。

When Mr. Sun came in at the sound of the clatter and asked her what was wrong, she told him.

几分钟后，我们其他人看到孙先生从他的公寓下来，盲目地穿过庭院。他戴着一顶旧毡帽，不适合这个季节。他看起来就像是一个突然受到猛烈打击的人，不知道该怎么办。他无视我们的问候，僵硬地走出大院，直线走了半个街区，然后逆着红灯过马路，被一辆超速行驶的摩托车撞倒。

A few short minutes later, the rest of us saw Mr. Sun descend from his apartment and blindly walk across the courtyard. He wore an old felt hat, inappropriate for the season. He looked like a man who had received a sudden, swift blow and did not know what to do with himself. He ignored our greetings and walked stiffly out of the compound and in a straight line for a half-block before he crossed the street against the light and was struck by a speeding motorcycle.

他一动不动地躺在阴沟里，我们的声音在他周围响起，发出紧急的喧闹声。

He lay motionless in the gutter, as our voices rose around him in an urgent clamor.

 

对于我们其他人来说，生活还在继续。

For the rest of us, life went on.

当丈夫、妻子或孩子默默流泪并不得不离开餐桌时，我们不再脸色苍白。我们逐渐习惯了这样一个事实：在某些日子里，某些商店根本不开门，店主躺在床上，充满悲伤或内疚。

We no longer blanched when a husband or wife or child dissolved into silent tears and had to leave the dining table. We grew accustomed to the fact that on some days, certain shops simply did not open, their owners lying in bed, wracked with grief or guilt.

渐渐地，我们了解了彼此悲伤的地形。朱阿姨告诉我们，她的第一个孩子已经胎死腹中。二十年后，她仍在哀悼这件事，她在市场上破碎地整理一堆受伤的西红柿时说道。保安承认，一天晚上他醉酒打架，导致一名男子脸朝下流血在路边；他不确定自己发生了什么事。

Gradually we learned the topography of one another’s sorrows. Zhu Ayi told us that her first child had been stillborn; twenty years later, she was still mourning it, she said as she brokenly sorted through a pile of bruised tomatoes at the market. The bao’an confessed that he’d gotten into a drunken fight one night and left a man bleeding and facedown by the side of the road; he wasn’t sure what had happened to him.

老周不需要我们说话就知道他的感受。他常常在院子里闲逛，等待庞阿姨回家。他在市场上避开了我们的视线，独自一人拎着一袋防风草和蒲公英叶回家。他拿起了古筝，我们听到他演奏到深夜，琴弦走调，演奏得很糟糕。

Lao Zhou did not need to speak for us to know what he was feeling. He loitered often in the courtyard, waiting for Pang Ayi to come home. He avoided our eyes in the market and went home carrying solitary bags of parsnips and dandelion greens. He had taken up the guzheng, which we heard him playing into the night, terribly, with out-of-tune strings.

丈夫被摩托车撞后，庞阿姨在医院守夜数天。他的肺部受伤了；他的三根肋骨骨折，现在躺在厚厚的石膏里。他身上带着一种困惑的神情，时不时地偷看他的妻子，在他第一次道歉后，当他被推进急诊室时，妻子低声说话，静静地坐在他床对面的金属折叠椅上，大部分时间都盯着外面。窗户。

After her husband had been struck by the motorcycle, Pang Ayi kept vigil in the hospital for days. His lungs were bruised; he had fractured three ribs and now lay in a thick cast. He had an air of bewilderment about him and periodically stole looks at his wife, who, after her first apology, whispered as he’d been wheeled into the emergency room, had sat quietly in a metal folding chair opposite his bed and mostly stared out the window.

他不知道他们之间会发生什么。但他每天都在醒来，而她却还在。她给他端来了猪骨汤和自己在家包的包子。有时她会坐着削苹果，但不会看他的眼睛。第三天，他吃了一些，作为对她的让步。

He did not know what would happen between them. But every day he kept waking up, and she was still there. She brought him soup made of pigs’ bones and stuffed buns that she shaped and steamed at home herself. Occasionally she sat peeling apples without meeting his eyes. On the third day, he ate some as a concession to her.

在那个水果季节的一天，一个我们不认识的头发花白的男人走进我们的大院，寻找住在二楼的退休教授老宋。当时老宋正坐在院子里。他的风湿病又发作了——我们可以从他偶尔晃动右膝的方式看出这一点。我们一起看着陌生人走近并跪在他面前。“你父亲自杀前三天，我是那些鞭打他、吐口水、骂他是资本主义猪的人之一，”那个男人说着，开始哭泣。“那时我还年轻，现在我老了，对不起。”

One day in that season of fruit, a graying man we did not recognize wandered into our compound to look for a retired professor, Lao Song, who lived on the second floor. Lao Song was sitting out in the courtyard at the time; his rheumatism was again acting up—​we could tell by the way he occasionally shook out his right knee. Together, we watched as the stranger approached and knelt before him. “Three days before your father killed himself, I was among those who whipped him and spit on him and called him a capitalist pig,” the man said, and began weeping. “I was young then, I am old now, I am sorry.”

我们听说，同样的场面正在全国各地上演，打破了几十年来的禁忌。有时他们的结局很糟糕；有时他们的结局很糟糕。许多人无法原谅。但在街上看到老男女眼里含着泪水，抱着或吃着七果碎片，交换着回忆，也并不罕见：头发一夜白了的母亲，我们用过的腰带。我们的受害者，我们玷污的寺庙。

The same tableaus, we heard, were happening across the country, breaking a decades-old taboo. Sometimes they ended badly; many could not forgive. But it was not unusual, either, to see old men and women in the street with tears in their eyes, embracing or eating pieces of the qiguo as they traded recollections: the mother whose hair had gone white overnight, the belts we had used on our victims, the temples we had defiled.

不久之后，我们庆祝了烈士纪念日。这一天的电视转播场面十分精彩：魏嘉玲在中午的节目中演唱了《我的甜蜜七国》，各地的舞蹈团体和歌手都进行了表演。这一天的活动以国家领导人对烈士纪念碑进行国事访问而达到高潮，他们身着深沉的黑色西装，在白色大理石前鞠躬，两侧是精美的花卉雕塑。每位领导人依次发表讲话，我们都牢记同样的言论——我们为我们伟大的新国家付出的代价，我们所取得的成就的最终价值，我们共同的光明未来。

Not long after that, we celebrated the day of the martyrs. It was a day of televised spectacle: Carina Wei sang “My Sweet Qiguo” on the noon broadcast, and dance groups and singers all over put on performances. The day culminated with the nation’s leaders paying a state visit to the martyrs’ monument, clad in somber black suits and bowing before the white marble, flanked by elaborate floral sculptures. Each leader made a speech in turn, the same statements that we knew by heart—​the price we’d paid for our great new nation, the ultimate worth of what we’d accomplished, the bright future that we shared.

最后登上领奖台的人比其他人年长。我们可以看到他爬上楼梯花了一些力气。他转头看向身后的烈士纪念碑，一块坚固的白色石板，就像一座坟墓。风吹拂着他剩下的几缕头发。然后，我们所有人都看到他的脸突然皱了起来，泪水开始从他的眼睛里挤出来，沿着他脸上的皱纹流淌。“我很抱歉，”他喘着气说，有那么一会儿，他那双湿漉漉的眼睛直视着镜头。“对不起，”他又说了一遍，然后画面突然变黑了。

The final man to take the podium was older than the rest; we could see it cost him some effort to mount the stairs. He turned to gaze at the martyrs’ monument behind him, a solid white slab like a tomb. The wind whipped the remaining strands of his hair. Then, all of us watching saw his face suddenly crumple, and tears began to squeeze their way out of his eyes and travel down the corrugated wrinkles of his face. “I’m sorry,” he gasped, and for a moment his rheumy eyes stared straight ahead into the camera. “I’m sorry,” he said again, and then the feed abruptly went to black.

第二天政府就取缔了七国。这些水果几乎一夜之间就从货架上消失了， “特殊水果，半价”的标志被替换为“桃子：特别甜”，还有烤坚果特价。我们这些去超市寻找七果的人在过道里徘徊，时而悲伤，时而欣慰。

The government banned the qiguo the next day. The fruit disappeared off the shelves nearly overnight, the signs PECULIAR FRUIT, HALF-PRICE replaced with PEACHES: EXTRA SWEET and a special deal on roasted nuts. Those of us who went to the supermarket looking for the qiguo wandered the aisles part in sorrow, part in relief.

不久之后，有消息传出，孙山农场已被铁丝网封锁，并有武装警卫二十四小时包围。后来听说，政府放火烧了整个七果林。瘦小的、干瘪的范世仪和他的大牙缝的妻子消失了；没有人知道他们发生了什么事。

Not long afterward, word spread that the Sunshan farm had been cordoned off with barbed wire and was surrounded twenty-four hours a day by an armed guard. Later, we heard, the government set the entire qiguo grove ablaze. The tiny, wizened Fan Shiyi and his gap-toothed wife disappeared; no one knew what had become of them.

几周过去了，很快就到了夏天。西瓜摊贩推着推车出现在街头，兜售新鲜切好的粉红色碎片，棍子上挂着绿色的外皮。夏天比去年更热，我们吃成堆的西瓜来避暑，尽管对我们大多数人来说，西瓜的果肉已经失去了味道。我们把它加冰块吃，我们在院子里和孩子们一起吃，我们坐在阳光下吃，直到头疼。

Weeks passed, and soon it was summer. Watermelon vendors appeared with their street carts, hawking freshly sliced pink shards tipped with green rinds on sticks. The summer was even hotter than the year before, and we ate piles of watermelon to stave off the heat, even though, to most of us, its flesh had lost its flavor. We ate it crushed with ice, we ate it sticky-fingered with our children in the courtyard, we ate it sitting out in the sun until our heads ached.

孙先生出院几个月后，庞阿姨又恢复了往日的沉着。她不再穿荷叶边裙子，又穿上了市场上永远出售的拖鞋和宽松的纱布衬衫。当我们在外面遇到她时，她对友善八卦的兴趣似乎又回来了。她注意到保安在深夜里读书；她看到了这些头衔，怀疑他会尝试取得警察资格。她指出，死于一氧化碳中毒的妇女曾经居住过的四楼公寓正在翻修；可能这家人正计划出售。

In the months after Mr. Sun left the hospital, Pang Ayi regained some of her old aplomb. She stopped wearing flouncy skirts, was again clad in the same slippers and baggy gauze shirts that were perpetually on sale in the markets. When we encountered her outside, her appetite for companionable gossip seemed to be returning. She noticed the bao’an poring over books late at night; she’d seen the titles and suspected he was going to try to qualify as a policeman. She noted the fourth-floor apartment once inhabited by the woman who’d died of carbon monoxide poisoning was being renovated; probably the family was planning to sell.

老周不再来街坊市场了。有时，我们早上会看到他朝相反的方向骑自行车，前往另一个市场，我们推测他现在在那里购买水果和蔬菜。当他和庞阿姨在街上擦肩而过时，我们都屏住了呼吸，但他们只是互相点点头，没有明显的情绪。晚上我们还听见他弹古筝；他正在好转。

Lao Zhou no longer came to the neighborhood market. Occasionally we saw him bicycling in the morning in the opposite direction, toward a different market where we presumed he now bought his fruits and vegetables. When he and Pang Ayi passed each other in the street, we all held our breath, but they simply nodded at each other without evident emotion. At night we still heard him playing the guzheng; he was getting better.

现在我们大多数人都听说政府正在开发一种新品种的七果，味道更佳，功效更稳定。他们说它会更甜，它的树四季都会结果子。尤其是冬天来临，我们迫不及待地想尝试一下。

Most of us have heard by now that the government is supposedly developing a new variety of the qiguo, superior in flavor, more stable in its effects. They say it will be sweeter, that its trees will bear fruit in all seasons. Especially as the winter sets in, we are impatient to try it.

婚姻田野笔记

Field Notes on a Marriage

高说，那不是他想去的地方。“这不是一个非常好的国家，”他说。“肮脏，但没有魅力。” “我们只有两周的时间，我们应该在一个浪漫的地方度过，一个真正的蜜月目的地，”他说。我抗议。小时候，我最喜欢的娃娃是一个中国瓷器女孩，有着僵硬的黑色辫子和金纹红色睡衣，还有相配的小缎子靴子。我一直想去。“我想看看你来自哪里，”我告诉他，但他摇了摇头：下次吧。

It was not a place, Gao said, that he wanted to go. “It’s not a very nice country,” he said. “Dirty, but without being charming.” We had only two weeks and we should spend it someplace romantic, a real honeymoon destination, he said. I protested. As a child my favorite doll had been a Chinese porcelain girl with stiff black plaits and gold-veined red pajamas, and tiny satin booties that matched. I’d always wanted to go. “I’d like to see where you’re from,” I told him, but he shook his head: another time.

去年十月我们就见过面。我以前肯定在校园里见过他，尽管我不知道我会注意到他。如果我有的话，我会以为他是一名研究生。他看起来就是那种吃不饱的样子，习惯性地穿着一件皮大衣，我后来取笑他，拉链紧紧地绕在他的中间。这让他看起来像一个有抱负的摩托车骑手，而不是一个新晋的德语副教授，发表了一些有前途的出版物。

We had met that previous October. I must have seen him on campus before, though I don’t know that I would have noticed him. If I had, I would have thought he was a graduate student. He had that look, somewhat underfed, and habitually wore a leather coat that I would later tease him about, zipped tightly around his middle. It made him look like an aspiring motorcycle rider instead of what he was, a newly minted associate professor of German with a few promising publications under his belt.

那天我平时工作的咖啡店里挤满了人。他来了，询问地看着我旁边的座位，我微笑着把我正在做的人类学教学大纲推到一边。我注意到他正在读的书，一本普希金传记，然后我们开始交谈。高的举止很有趣，需要一段时间才能解析：一开始他很内敛，甚至有点傲慢，但有时他会爆发出一阵让你大吃一惊的爽朗大笑。例如，他对我在农场长大这一事实感到非常高兴。

The coffee shop where I usually did my work was crowded that day. He arrived and looked inquiringly at the seat beside me, and I smiled and pushed aside the anthropology syllabus I was working on. I noted the book he was reading, a Pushkin biography, and we got to talking. Gao had a funny demeanor that took a while to parse: restrained, almost haughty at first, but sometimes he’d break out in a hearty bout of laughter that took you by surprise. He was very entertained, for example, by the fact that I’d grown up on a farm.

“一个农场！” 他说着，突然大笑起来。“不完全是。山羊、牛之类的？”

“A farm!” he said, and burst out laughing. “No, really. Goats, cows, that kind of thing?”

“事实上，苜蓿，”我微笑着说。“印第安纳州。” 我不知道他觉得什么好笑，但他很高兴，我发现自己也笑了。

“Alfalfa, actually,” I said, smiling. “Indiana.” I couldn’t tell what he found so amusing, but he was so pleased I found myself laughing as well.

后来我了解到，在回到办公室之前，停下来喝杯咖啡是他健身后例行公事的一部分。他在所有事情上都遵守严格的纪律。他每天在健身房花两个小时，完成他自己设计的精确训练计划：股四头肌和侧肌，在我看来，这个训练计划听起来就像是一系列数学问题。然后他会回家吃半磅从袋子里放在炉子上煮的球芽甘蓝。他从来不碰任何含糖的东西，或者任何油炸的东西。“我对食物不感兴趣，”他告诉我。

As I later learned, the stop-off for coffee was part of his post-gym routine, prior to heading back to his office. He was, in all things, rigidly disciplined. He spent two hours a day at the gym working through a precise program he’d designed himself, quadriceps and laterals, a routine that sounded to me like a series of math problems. Then he’d head home and eat a half-pound of Brussels sprouts, boiled from a bag on the stove. He never touched anything with sugar, or anything fried. “I’m not interested in food,” he told me.

起初是在植物园散步，在灯火通明的咖啡馆吃午餐，周末逛跳蚤市场。一天晚上，在一场学生室内乐音乐会上，高的手滑过我的手，这时我几乎甘心认为我们只是朋友。随后，我们站在人行道上，交换了一些纯洁的、嘴唇干燥的吻，双手试探性地摸索着对方，就像我们还是青少年一样。

At first it was a walk in a botanical garden, lunch at a brightly lit café, a visit to a weekend flea market. I had almost reconciled myself to thinking we were simply friends when, during a student chamber-music concert one evening, Gao slipped his hand over mine. Afterward, standing on the sidewalk, we exchanged some chaste, dry-lipped kisses, hands fumbling experimentally about each other as though we were teenagers.

他不喜欢谈论自己，在忏悔大学环境中度过了这么多年之后，我发现这令人耳目一新，几乎过时了。“你来自中国，”我们第二次见面时，当我们漫步在植物园的尖刺树叶间时，我说道，植物园是专门种植北美沙漠植物的区域。我满怀期待地看着他，他点点头，仿佛这是他必须忍受的一系列手续的一部分。“中国哪里？”

He didn’t like to talk about himself, something that I found refreshing, almost old-fashioned after so many years spent in a confessional university environment. “You’re from China,” I said on our second meeting as we strolled amid the spiked leaves of the botanical garden, a section devoted to North American desert plants. I looked at him expectantly, and he nodded, as though this were part of a series of formalities he had to endure. “Where in China?”

“某个你从未听说过的地方，”他说道，并给它起了个名字。“这是一潭死水。”

“Someplace you’ve never heard of,” he said, and named it. “It’s a backwater.”

“人力车和稻田？” 我开玩笑说，他耸耸肩。“你可以那样说。” 我问他是怎么学德语的，但他也很简洁，只说他获得了去欧洲的高中奖学金，然后他留下来了。“我从十六岁起就没有回来过，”他冷漠地说，指的是家，语气中不鼓励提问。

“Rickshaws and rice paddies?” I joked, and he shrugged. “You could say that.” I asked him how he’d learned German, but there, too, he was laconic, saying only that he’d gotten a high school scholarship to go to Europe, and that he’d stayed. “I haven’t been back since I was sixteen,” he said indifferently, meaning home, in a tone that discouraged questions.

不过，他想了解我的一切，想听听我的田野工作、我的家庭；他渴望了解我，这是我以前从未经历过的，既令人陶醉，又令人强烈地奉承。他想知道一切，从童年的昵称到我学校科学博览会的细节，全神贯注地研究我，就好像有一天他可能不得不在一群同事面前捍卫我们的关系一样。

He wanted to know all about me, though, to hear about my fieldwork, my family; he had a greediness for knowledge of me that I’d never experienced before, at once intoxicating and intensely flattering. He wanted to know everything from childhood nicknames to details of my school science fairs, studying me as intently as if he might have to someday defend our relationship to a panel of colleagues.

“你真是太自给自足了，”在我们恋爱初期，高对我说。那是在他第一次来到我的公寓，打开冰箱，看到一排排的特百惠整齐地堆放着，购物清单是用精确的手写着的。他的本意是一种恭维，停顿了一下，我向他表示感谢。

“You’re so self-sufficient,” Gao said to me, early in our courtship. It was after he’d visited my apartment for the first time and opened the refrigerator to see the rows of Tupperware neatly stacked, the shopping list registered in a precise hand. He’d meant it as a compliment, and after a pause, I thanked him.

六周后的一个星期六，我们在卧室里度过了一个下午，赤身裸体地沐浴在明亮的阳光下，好奇地、毫无欲望地互相打量着对方，就好像我们是博物馆馆长，在记录着各种特质：这里凸起的痣，那里苍白凹陷的妊娠纹。午后的阳光透过窗户照进来，照射着每一根体毛。我感到懒惰、温暖和投机。我们看了一半的西班牙肥皂剧，我定期提供翻译。这个情节（涉及一场婚礼，牧师摘掉假胡须并表明自己是新娘的情人）让我们开怀大笑。

One Saturday six weeks later we spent the afternoon in my bedroom, naked in the bright sunlight, inspecting each other curiously, without desire, as though we were museum curators cataloging idiosyncrasies: the raised mole here, a pale depression of stretch marks there. The afternoon light came in through the window, irradiating every body hair. I felt lazy, warm, and speculative. We’d been half watching a Spanish soap opera, me periodically offering up translations; the plot (involving a marriage ceremony in which the priest removed a false beard and revealed himself to be the bride’s lover) kept us laughing.

“你从来没有这样做过，对吧？” 当我们关掉电视时，他说道。“结婚了。”

“You’ve never done it, right?” he said, when we turned the TV off. “Gotten married.”

“不，”我盯着天花板说。这并没有困扰我。有很多事情我没有做过：跑马拉松、成为一名医生、培养对地中海食物的品味。我有很多东西。

“No,” I said, staring at the ceiling. It hadn’t bothered me. There were a lot of things I hadn’t done: run a marathon, become a doctor, developed a taste for Mediterranean food. There were a lot of things I had.

“我们为什么不呢？” 高说。

“Why don’t we?” Gao said.

“你在开玩笑么。”

“You’re joking.”

“为什么不？” 他说。我随即翻身，看着他。他躺在那里，用一只手臂支撑着头，用一种难以捉摸的表情注视着我。

“Why not?” he said. I turned over then, and looked at him. He was lying with his head propped up on one arm, gazing at me with an unreadable expression.

“我们几乎不认识。”

“We hardly know each other.”

“我是认真的。我们相处得很好，不是吗？”

“I’m serious. We get along, don’t we?”

我惊讶地倒回床上。“好吧，”我说，感觉一丝幸福的光芒开始在我内心盘旋。“我们开始做吧。”

I flopped back onto the bed, astonished. “Okay,” I said, feeling small flickers of happiness start to curl inside me. “Let’s do it.”

他翻身压在我身上，用手指挠我下巴的下侧。“你确定吗，哈申？” 他说。它的意思是“兔子”，一种我从来不喜欢的动物——太焦虑，太红眼睛——但我不介意他用这个词时的亲切感。

He rolled over on top of me and tickled the underside of my chin with his finger. “You’re sure, häschen?” he said. It meant “bunny,” an animal I never liked—​too anxious, too red-eyed—​but I didn’t mind the endearment when he used it.

我点了头。“好吧，”他说，然后站起来，哼着歌。“那你明天打算做什么？” 我笑着伸出手，试图把他拉下来，但他去了厨房，我听到水龙头打开了，冰块破裂和流水的声音。即使在美国生活了十多年，高仍然无法忘记自己可以从水龙头里喝水，一天可以喝十几杯。

I nodded. “Okay,” he said, and rose, humming. “What are you doing tomorrow, then?” I reached out, laughing, trying to pull him back down, but he went to the kitchen, where I heard the tap being turned on and the sound of ice being cracked and water running. Even after living in the U.S. for more than a decade, Gao still couldn’t get over the fact that he could drink from the tap, could drink a dozen glasses a day.

我们结婚后，高不再对我无情的追问，仿佛我是他不安的大脑已经充分掌握的话题。我们整齐、天衣无缝地融入彼此的生活。他搬进我的公寓时只带了两个手提箱的衣服；他所有的书籍和文件都放在他的办公室里。我们的碗碟架上有两个盘子和两个杯子，我的是栗色的，他的是绿色的，我们每晚都会冲洗和更换。

After we married, Gao’s relentless questions about me stopped, as though I were a topic that his restless brain had sufficiently mastered. We folded ourselves into each other’s lives neatly, seamlessly. He moved into my apartment with just two suitcases’ worth of clothes; all his books and papers lived at his office. Our dish rack held two plates and two mugs, mine maroon and his green, that we rinsed and replaced every night.

我们去印第安纳州看望父母一周，高和妈妈一起从市场上剥玉米，和爸爸一起在农场骑拖拉机。晚上，我们坐在门廊开着的地方，听着草地上的蟋蟀的叫声。通常我在那里会感到焦躁不安，感到束手无策，但我可以看出生活中的某些东西对高很有吸引力。他是理想的客人，吃着他通常不会碰的东西——培根、厚煎饼——并向我父母询问了几十个有关农场的问题，这让我想起了我们第一次见面时他的样子。他们的反应和我一样：受宠若惊，立即向我求爱。（他们还问我他是不是中国间谍：“他太健康了！”我母亲说，当我说不是时，她看起来几乎很失望。）

We went to Indiana for a week to see my parents, where Gao shucked corn from the market with my mom and rode a tractor on the farm with my dad. At night we sat with the porch door open and listened to the crickets in the grass. Usually I grew antsy there, felt stranded, but I could see that something about the life appealed to Gao. He was the ideal guest, eating things he wouldn’t usually touch—​bacon, thick pancakes—​and asked my parents dozens of questions about the farm in a way that reminded me of how he’d been when we’d first met. They responded as I had: flattered, instantly wooed. (They also asked me if he was a Chinese spy: “He’s so fit!” my mother said, and looked almost disappointed when I said no.)

“事实上，高也是在农场长大的，”第二天吃早餐时我告诉他们。

“Actually, Gao grew up on a farm, too,” I told them over breakfast on our second day.

“别开玩笑了！” 我爸爸说。

“No kidding!” my dad said.

我看到高犹豫了。“不完全是，”他说。

I saw Gao hesitate. “Not really,” he said.

“你以为你是在农村长大的？”

“I thought you said you grew up in the countryside?”

“更像是一个小镇，”他说。“我妈妈是一名高中校长，”他补充道。“我父亲是一名政府官员。”

“More like a small town,” he said. “My mom was a high school principal,” he added. “My dad was a government official.”

我对这些事情一无所知，这让我感觉自己很愚蠢，暴露无遗。我生气地站起来，手里拿着一个玻璃杯走到门廊上，以为他会跟着来，但他没有，几分钟后我回来了，不想大吵大闹。

I hadn’t known either of these things, and it made me feel foolish, exposed. I got up, annoyed, and went out to the porch with a glass in hand, expecting him to follow, but he didn’t, and after a few minutes I returned, not wanting to make a scene.

 

此后的几个月里，高经常不在，在办公室工作到很晚，或者在健身房待上几个小时。我不介意；我仍然不习惯与另一个人共度如此多的时间。尽管我们平日里的很多饭菜都是分开吃的，但每个周五我们都会一起在一家川菜馆吃晚饭，吃的是花瓣般柔软的白鱼片，配上血红色的辣椒，让我的嘴唇发麻。

In the months after that, Gao was often away, working late at the office or spending hours at the gym. I didn’t mind; I still hadn’t accustomed myself to spending so much time with another person. Though we took many of our weekday meals apart, we ate dinner together at a Sichuan restaurant every Friday, dining on petal-soft pieces of white fish cooked with blood-red chilies that made my lips tingle.

有时我们会沿着山上的防火小径徒步旅行。我们是好伙伴。只是偶尔我才会想到想要更多的东西。为了庆祝我们的一周年——纸——他送给我一套他自己制作的精美折纸盒子。我打开它们，期待里面有一份礼物，当我发现它们是空的时，我脸红了，意识到我的错误，希望他没有注意到。

Now and then we’d go for a hike along the fire trails up in the hills. We were good companions. Only occasionally did it occur to me to wish for something more. For our first anniversary—​paper—​he’d given me a beautifully fashioned set of origami boxes that he’d made himself. I’d opened them, expecting a gift inside, and flushed when I found them empty, realizing my mistake, hoping he hadn’t noticed.

到了晚上，这些记忆不由自主地浮现在我的脑海里。大多数时候，我拍拍它们的头，然后把它们打发走，然后把它们放回黑暗的水中。我告诉自己，不要太关注死者：除了其他一切，他们无法回答你。

At night these memories swim up to me, unbidden. Most of the time I pat them on the head and send them away, releasing them back into dark waters. I tell myself it doesn’t do to fixate too much on the dead: apart from everything else, they can’t answer you.

到高家的路程是六千英里，十七个小时。空乘人员走过过道，提供茶和杏仁饼干。我把额头靠在漆黑冰冷的窗户上，看着飞机图标在我面前的屏幕上蓝色和绿色的地图上描绘出我们的航迹。当我们接近目的地时，航空公司播放了一段欢迎视频，视频中出现了雾气蒙蒙的宝塔和点缀着金色鱼的池塘，观察者是一位身着洋红色长袍、撑着纸阳伞的女士。

The journey to Gao’s hometown was six thousand miles and seventeen hours. Flight attendants came through the aisles offering tea and almond cookies. I leaned my forehead against the inky, cold window and watched the plane icon trace our passage on the blue and green map on the screen before me. As we neared our destination, the airline played a welcome video of misty pagodas and a pond flecked with golden fish, observed by a woman dressed in trailing magenta robes and carrying a paper parasol.

距离高的家乡最近的机场外的景色相当不那么吸引人：一排排仓库，绵延数英里，荒凉地重复着，很难说是高所描述的小镇，尽管我猜想，当他离开时，它可能仍然是一个小镇。当我们进入郊区时，我感觉到出租车司机正在看着我，一个女人独自坐在他的后座上。“美国，”他说。这不是一个问题。“是的，”我态度轻松地说，但他只是点点头。

The scene outside the airport nearest Gao’s hometown was considerably less appealing: sprawling lines of warehouses that ran for miles in bleak repetition, hardly the small town Gao had described, though I supposed it might still have been one when he left. As we entered its outskirts, I felt the cabdriver eyeing me, a woman alone in his backseat. “America,” he said. It wasn’t a question. “Yes,” I said, in an attitude of brightness, but he just nodded.

一个小时后，我们到达了酒店，这是一座彩色混凝土建筑，上面挂着一块牌子，上面写着“金凤凰别墅”。街对面一家卖袜子的商店里播放着细小的广告。酒店内的大堂很冷，上面有一幅褪色的手表广告，上面描绘着一对西方夫妇。这名女子有着蜡黄的脸颊和宽大的鼻子，这在美国广告中是不会出现的，她旁边的一名金发男子微笑着，脸上露出全家福中连环杀手的鬼脸。

After an hour, we reached the hotel, a stained concrete block adorned with a sign that read GOLD PHOENIX VILLA. Tinny advertisements blared from a shop selling hosiery across the street. Inside, the hotel’s lobby was cold and featured a faded watch ad depicting a Western couple. The woman had sallow cheeks and a wide nose that wouldn’t have made the cut in an American advertisement, posing beside a blond man who smiled with the grimace of a serial killer appearing in a family portrait.

第二天早上，高妈妈在那里遇见了我。她把头发扎成紧紧的卷发，穿着紫色丝绒运动服，径直走过来，用我意想不到的温暖抓住了我的手臂。她和高的父亲都没有参加他的葬礼，我试图不因此而评判他们，但没有成功。

Gao’s mother met me there the next morning. She wore her hair in tightly wound curls and had on a purple velour tracksuit, and came straight over and took my arm with a warmth that I didn’t expect. Neither she nor Gao’s father had come to his funeral, and I had tried not to judge them for it, unsuccessfully.

“你来了，”她说，然后轻快地把我领到外面，没有进行眼神交流。“欢迎。”

“You’re here,” she said, and briskly steered me outside, not quite making eye contact. “Welcome.”

“很高兴认识你，”我有点不自在地说。“我想来这里很久了。”

“I’m so pleased to meet you,” I said, a little self-consciously. “I’ve wanted to come here for so long.”

在外面的停车场，她把腿滑到一辆深灰色轿车的方向盘后面，精心表演了调节后视​​镜的动作。“我的宝贝，新的，”她说着笑了，好像是为了让我知道这是个笑话。高告诉我，她在大学里学过英语，但即便如此，她对这门语言的驾轻就熟让我感到惊讶。

Outside in the parking lot, she slid her legs behind the wheel of a dark-gray sedan and made an elaborate performance of adjusting the mirrors. “My baby, new,” she said, and laughed, as though to make sure I knew it was a joke. She had studied English in college, Gao had told me, but even so, her apparent ease with the language surprised me.

我们开了一会儿车，路过一些商店，上面挂着我看不懂的单调纸板标志，不过有些商店提供了他们商品的线索：一张工具和钉子的图片，另一张是一只羊站在锅前（大概是一家餐馆之类的）。我们周围的雨使道路变暗了。

We drove for a while, passing shops with drab pasteboard signs I couldn’t read, though some gave clues to their wares: a picture of tools and nails, another of a sheep standing before a pot (presumably a restaurant of some sort). All around us, rain darkened the road.

她并没有邀请我去拜访；她并没有邀请我去拜访。我邀请了自己，当我们默默地开车时，我想知道我是否真的受到欢迎。“很高兴来到这里，”我最终试探性地说。“高告诉我很多关于这个地方的事情。”

She had not invited me to visit; I had invited myself, and as we drove in silence, I wondered if I was truly welcome. “It’s good to be here,” I finally said, tentatively. “Gao told me so much about this place.”

这不是真的，也许她感觉到了，只是点了点头。那里有一座寺庙，她说，她会带我去。还有一个博物馆，不是很大。我还想看什么？

It wasn’t true, and perhaps she sensed it, simply nodding. There was a temple, she said, she’d take me. There was a museum, as well, not very large. What else did I want to see?

“高小时候的事，”我说。

“Anything from Gao’s childhood,” I said.

她说已经所剩无几了：政府几年前拆除了他们的旧家，并用购物中心取而代之。学校已改建为政府办公室。

She said there wasn’t much left: The government had torn down their old family home years ago and replaced it with a shopping mall. The school had been converted into government offices.

我很抱歉，但尽量不表现出来。“我还是想看看，”我说。

I was sorry, but tried not to show it. “I’d still like to see it,” I said.

“商场？” 我想，高的母亲曾经是一名高中校长这一事实就说明了这一点；除了烫发和紫色丝绒之外，她还有一种钢铁般的干练气质。

“The mall?” The fact that Gao’s mother had been a high school principal showed, I thought; beyond the perm and purple velour, she had an aura of steely competence to her.

我说是的，但她不耐烦地摇摇头。“那里什么也没有。你应该看看一些历史。这座城市有四千年的历史。”

I said yes, but she shook her head impatiently. “There’s nothing there. You should see some history. This city has four thousand years of history.”

当我同意后，她微笑着打开收音机，淹没了进一步交谈的需要。

When I agreed, she smiled and turned on the radio, drowning out the need for further conversation.

 

高先生告诉我，他并不是一个受欢迎的孩子，但由于他母亲的地位，他赢得了一定程度的尊重。尤其是其他父母，都对他阿谀奉承。放学接孩子时，他们递给他糖果，夸他聪明。最终，他吸引了一小群像他一样聪明但有点缺乏安全感的男孩。他们的名字经常位居成绩最好的学生名单之首，每周都会张贴在校门外供所有家长查看。

Gao hadn’t been a popular child, he told me, but he’d commanded a certain amount of respect because of his mother’s position. Other parents, in particular, fawned over him. They passed him sweets when picking up their children after school, they praised his cleverness. Eventually he drew to him a small coterie of boys like himself, bright and a little insecure. Their names regularly topped the list of students with the best grades, posted weekly outside the school gates for all the parents to see.

但有一个男孩在阅读和数学方面总是比他们组中的所有人都胜出，他们称他为“老鼠”。他是寄宿生之一，来自一天路程外的一个村庄。当我问起这个绰号时，高耸了耸肩。“他很小，”他说。

But there was one boy who always outdid everyone in both reading and math, not of their group, whom they called Mouse. He was one of the boarders, had come from a village a day’s travel away. Gao shrugged when I’d asked about the nickname. “He was small,” he said.

随着中考的临近，学生们每周学习六天，每天十一个小时，而高老师最努力，因为每个人都希望他能取得好成绩。“你无法想象压力有多大，”他告诉我。“这很残酷。”

As the high school entrance exam neared, students studied six days a week, eleven hours a day, and Gao hardest of all, because everyone expected him to do well. “You can’t imagine what the pressure was like,” he told me. “It was cruel.”

当时，我们在德国度蜜月，他带我参观了他获得学位的大学。我们参观了他曾经学习的图书馆的卡雷尔和他论文答辩的教室，他就是在那里停下来的，有一段时间他似乎并不想要再次移动。“所以你可以想象我能离开是多么高兴，”他说。

At the time, we were in Germany on our honeymoon and he’d taken me to see the university where he’d done his degree. We’d visited the carrel in the library where he used to study and the classroom where he’d defended his dissertation, and it was there that he’d paused, and for a while it didn’t seem like he’d ever want to move again. “So you can imagine how glad I was to get away,” he said.

 

在寺庙里，我问高妈妈，她儿子小时候怎么样。“他是一个好学生，”她说。我们并肩而立，凝视着一尊漆成蓝色、双眸朱红色的神像。她的手臂紧紧地挽着我的手臂，让人很难看清她的表情，不过当我问她还记得什么时，我能感觉到她在我身边叹了口气，只是一点点。

At the temple, I asked Gao’s mother what her son was like as a child. “He was a good student,” she said. We were standing side by side, staring at a statue of a robed god painted blue, with vermillion eyes. She had linked her arm firmly through mine, making it hard to see her expression, though when I asked her what else she could remember, I could feel her sigh at my side, just a little.

“他表现得非常好。勤奋，学习成绩好。”

“He was very well behaved. Hardworking, good at his studies.”

她重复这些品质让我很恼火，我借口要更仔细地检查一张标语牌而走开。“他是一个快乐的孩子吗？” 我问。

Something about her repetition of these qualities annoyed me, and I walked away on the pretext of examining a placard more closely. “Was he a happy kid?” I asked.

“是的，当然，”她说道，语气中充满了防御。

“Yes, of course,” she said, voice defensive.

“可惜他再也没有回来，”我说。

“It’s a shame he never came back,” I said.

“并不真地。他为什么要这么做？

“Not really. Why should he?”

我们继续行走。寺庙由一系列庭院组成，一条长长的走廊点缀着小壁龛，里面有数十尊用闪亮的金色塑料铸造的佛像。天花板的木梁上盘旋着绿色、白色和栗色的条纹，看起来刚刚粉刷过，周围散落着成堆的新瓷砖和钉子。一块牌子上写着这座寺庙曾在十五世纪的一场大火中被摧毁并重建，又在地震中受损并再次重建。

We resumed walking. The temple was composed of a series of courtyards, with one long corridor dotted with small niches containing scores of Buddhas cast in shiny gold plastic. The green and white and maroon stripes swirled about the ceiling’s wooden beams looked freshly painted, and there were heaps of new tiles and nails scattered about. A sign said that the temple had been destroyed in a fifteenth-century fire and rebuilt, and damaged in an earthquake and rebuilt again.

“它已经有六百年的历史了，”高妈妈说。“很古老。不像你们的美国。”

“It has a history of six hundred years,” Gao’s mother said. “Very old. Not like your America.”

我们又往前走，她催促我站在佛像前，并用相机给我拍了一张照片。那天下午，她就让我在一块刻有铭文的石碑、一块岩层和一座小亭子前摆好姿势。我的脸颊因微笑而疼痛。

We walked farther, and she urged me to stand in front of a Buddha statue, and snapped a photo of me with my camera. Already that afternoon she’d had me pose before an inscribed stele, a rock formation, and a small pavilion. My cheeks hurt from smiling.

“那边怎么样？” 她指着另一个庭院问道。我走过去，不想让她失望。她又拍了一张照片，我没有微笑。最后，让我松了口气的是，我们开始朝出口走去。

“How about over there?” she asked, gesturing to another courtyard. I went over, not wanting to disappoint her. She took another photo, one I didn’t smile for. Finally, to my relief, we began moving toward the exit.

“高先生会来这里吗？” 我问。

“Would Gao ever have come here?” I asked.

她想了想，然后摇了摇头。“主要是为了游客。”

She thought about it, then shook her head. “It’s mostly for tourists.”

“好吧，”我说，没有什么可补充的。“非常漂亮。”我淡淡地说。

“Well,” I said, and didn’t have anything else to add. “It’s very pretty,” I said flatly.

 

结婚两年后，高似乎更加自我封闭。他在办公室的时间越来越长，但他的出版物却很少，未能引起人们的注意；他最近未能获得一项原本可以轻松获得的资助。德语系规模不大，那个学期聘请了一位刚获得博士学位的年轻乌克兰学者。每个人都认为他是下一个明星。有一天，我走进高的办公室，发现他抱着头。我在那里站了几分钟，看着他，然后拍拍他的肩膀。他说他一直在睡觉。

After two years of marriage, Gao seemed to draw still further into himself. He spent increasingly long hours at the office, but his publications were sparse and failed to gain attention; he’d recently been passed over for a grant that he once would have won easily. The German department wasn’t large and that semester had hired a young Ukrainian scholar fresh from his Ph.D. whom everyone considered its next star. One day I came into Gao’s office and found him with his head in his arms. I stood there for a few minutes, watching him, before touching him on the shoulder. He said he’d been sleeping.

当高告诉我老鼠的故事的其余部分时，我们正在庆祝结婚两周年。我们去了市中心的一家川菜馆，领班给我们安排了一张靠近大平板玻璃窗的桌子。服务员给我们端来了鱼、米饭和用辣椒烹制的豆腐块，上面撒满了葱花。一簇未开封的菊花坐在我们之间，像小花瓶里的小拳头一样卷曲着。对于高来说，在办公室度过了漫长的一天，参加了部门会议，花了好几个小时修改一篇已经被拒绝发表的论文，他很安静。餐厅也很安静——这是一个工作日的晚上——我想知道服务员是否能看出有什么问题。外面天已经黑了，我想象着我们在人行道上对路人来说就像一对沉默的演员，

We were celebrating our second anniversary when Gao told me the rest of Mouse’s story. We’d gone to the Sichuan restaurant downtown, where the maître d’ had given us a table beside the big plate-glass window. The waiter brought us fish, rice, and cubes of tofu cooked with chilies, bristling with dashes of green onion. A cluster of unopened chrysanthemums sat between us, curled like tiny fists in a small vase. It had been a long day for Gao at the office, a department meeting and hours spent revising a paper that had already been rejected twice for publication, and he was quiet. The restaurant was quiet, too—​it was a weeknight—​and I wondered if the waiters could tell there was something wrong. Outside, it had grown dark, and I imagined that we looked like a pair of silent actors to passersby on the sidewalk, seen through the lit window as though onstage.

“告诉我一件事，”当沉默持续太久时，我对他说道。

“Tell me something,” I said to him, when the silence had gone on too long.

“像什么？”

“Like what?”

“任何事物。有件事我不知道你的事。”

“Anything. Something I don’t know about you.”

“你先，”他说。他开始用叉子小心地给鱼去骨，用指尖取出每一片细小的碎片。

“You first,” he said. With a fork, he began to carefully debone the fish, extracting each wispy fragment with his fingertips.

“好吧，”我说。“你确定不想点酒吗？” 他点点头，将手放在我的手上。我注意到他已经越来越频繁地使用这个手势了。最近，它不再给人一种亲切的感觉，而更像是有人轻轻地闭上你的嘴。

“Okay,” I said. “Are you sure you don’t want to order some wine?” He nodded and placed his hand over mine. It was a gesture I’d noticed he’d been using more and more; lately it had stopped feeling affectionate and more like someone gently closing your mouth.

我告诉他我们第一只猫的故事。她本来应该是我的，但她从来不太喜欢我，总是更喜欢我父母的床。我告诉他，我曾经偷偷溜进我父母的房间，抢走她，让她和我一起睡，结果醒来时却听到她抓着门，试图逃出去。“我上大学时她就去世了，”我一边告诉他，一边试图笑出声来。“直到最后，她都不太喜欢我。”

I told him the story of our first cat. She was supposed to be mine, but she never liked me much, always preferred my parents’ bed. I used to sneak into my parents’ room to snatch her and make her sleep with me, I told him, only to wake to hear her scratching at the door, trying to get out. “She died when I was in college,” I told him, attempting a laugh. “Up until the end, she didn’t like me very much.”

他心不在焉地笑了笑，擦了擦嘴。“笨猫。”

He smiled absently and wiped his mouth. “Stupid cat.”

“轮到你了，”我说。他抗议说他没有什么可分享的，但我强迫他。最后他把餐巾折好放在桌子上，脸上露出一丝奇怪的神色。“既然你问了，我就告诉你一件事。”他慢慢地说。

“Your turn,” I said. He protested he had nothing to share, but I pressed him. Finally he folded his napkin and put it on the table and a strange look came over his face. “I’ll tell you something,” he said slowly, “since you ask.”

他告诉我，当他和他的朋友们十四岁的时候，不知何故，他们决定老鼠是日本间谍。他从远方来；没有人知道他的来历。他看起来很奇怪，头发比其他人都苍白。（“我现在知道这可能是营养不良，”高说。）他在测试中无与伦比，“几乎是军国主义”，他们互相告诉。他有一件有趣的白衬衫，他们确信他的剪裁是日本风格的。

He told me that when he and his friends turned fourteen, somehow it was decided among them that Mouse was a Japanese spy. He’d come from far away; no one knew his antecedents. He looked odd, with hair that was paler than that of the rest. (“I know now it was probably malnutrition,” Gao said.) He was unbeatable in tests, “almost militaristic,” they told one another. He had a funny white shirt they became convinced was cut in a Japanese style.

几个月来，他们密切监视他以寻找线索。有人看见他夜间去洗手间；他有可能会见秘密同伙。下课后，一位老师留住了他。或许两人是勾结的。在某个时候，他回到了自己的村庄。据说他的祖母去世了，但高和他的朋友们更清楚：老鼠正在山上训练。当他回来的时候，他们所有的担心似乎都得到了证实。他们说，他正在训练的攻击随时都会发生。

For months, they watched him closely for clues. Someone had seen him make a nighttime trip to the bathroom; it was possible he was meeting secret accomplices. A teacher had kept him after class; perhaps the two were in league. At some point he went back to his village. It was said his grandmother had died, but Gao and his friends knew better: Mouse was training in the hills. When he came back, it was as though all their fears were confirmed. The attack he was training for would come any day now, they said.

渐渐地，他们的阴谋就成形了。“一开始这只是一场游戏，”高说。他从看门人那里偷了一些老鼠药。“我们开玩笑说这是给老鼠吃的老鼠药，”他说。另一个男孩也不甘示弱，和老鼠成了朋友，开始和他一起吃午饭。第三个人获得了更多的老鼠药，以防第一次尝试失败。是第二个男孩在食堂给老鼠的炒茄子里塞了一大剂量的。

Gradually their plot took shape. “It was a game at first,” Gao said. He stole some rat poison from the janitor. “We joked it was rat poison for a mouse,” he said. Another boy, not to be outdone, befriended Mouse, started eating lunch with him. A third obtained still more rat poison in case the first attempt failed.
