It was the second boy who slipped a generous dose of it into Mouse’s stir-fried eggplant at the canteen.

“哦，上帝，”我说。“发生了什么？”

“Oh, God,” I said. “What happened?”

高看着我，好像我问了一个愚蠢的问题。“他当然死了，”他恼怒地说。

Gao looked at me as though I’d asked a stupid question. “He died, of course,” he said with irritation.

我不知道该说什么。“他们抓到人了吗？”

I didn’t know what to say. “Did they ever catch anyone?”

他有一段时间没有回答我。“一个男孩，”他最终说道。“那个给他下毒的男孩。”

He didn’t answer me for a while. “One boy,” he said eventually. “The boy who gave him the poison.”

当男孩的父母从山里的老家赶来把尸体运走时，母亲歇斯底里，父亲木然震惊，他们意识到自己的错误：老鼠的父母是贫穷的村民，说着与学校管理员一样粗俗的语言。很难理解他们。

When the boy’s parents came from their home village in the mountains to take the body away, the mother hysterical, the father wooden and stunned, they realized their mistake: Mouse’s parents were poor villagers, speaking in a tongue so heavy and coarse the school administrators had trouble understanding them.

“然后你去了德国，”我说。

“And then you went to Germany,” I said.

他点了点头。“然后我就去了德国。”

He nodded. “And then I went to Germany.”

那年春天，下雨的时候，蚂蚁入侵了我们的公寓，在浴室里留下了摇摇欲坠的黑线。我们买了一桶石油，并在油毡上竖起一桶墙，试图阻止他们稳步前进。当这一行动失败后，高某拿着真空吸尘器的软管站岗，决心抓住任何逃亡者。攀附在我们前廊上的牵牛花藤蔓呈紫色喇叭状展开。我想，我们谈话后他看起来放松多了。他笑得更频繁，呆在家里的时间也更多。我们开始谈论组建家庭的事情。我们随时都会开始尝试。

That spring, when the rains came, the ants invaded our apartment, making wobbly black lines across the bathroom. We bought a tub of petroleum and erected walls of it across the linoleum to try and stop their steady march. When that failed, Gao stood guard with the hose of a vacuum cleaner at the ready, determined to catch any escapees. The morning-glory vines that clung to our front porch unfurled themselves in purple trumpets. He seemed more relaxed after our conversation, I thought. He laughed more frequently, and spent more time at home. We started talking about having a family. We were going to begin trying any day now.

然后有一天晚上，我抱着一堆学生试卷睡着了，天刚亮就醒了。高曾说过，他会在办公室完成一轮较晚的评分后回来，但他那一侧的床没有受到干扰，公寓里空无一人。我给自己泡了杯咖啡，给他的办公室打了电话，不耐烦地踱步了一会儿，最后上了车。

Then came a night when I’d fallen asleep over a stack of student papers and awoke just after dawn. Gao had said he’d be back after a late bout of grading at his office, but his side of the bed was undisturbed, the apartment empty. I made myself some coffee, called his office, paced impatiently for a while, and finally went to the car.

空气中依然弥漫着清晨的寒意，那种寒冷让人期待鸟鸣。高的大楼被锁了。我敲了敲他的窗户，但没有回应。我找到了设施管理办公室，等到它开门。门卫陪着我回去，打开门锁，高的椅子被整齐地推了进去，里面空着。无论如何，我还是徒劳地打开了灯。“谢谢，”我微笑着说，尽量不显得惊慌。“他肯定在某个地方忘记了时间——​我去图书馆看看。”

The morning chill was still in the air, the kind of cold that makes you expect birdsong. Gao’s building was locked. I rapped on his window, but there was no reply. I found the facilities management office and waited until it opened. A janitor accompanied me back and unlocked the door: Gao’s chair was pushed tidily in, the place empty. I flicked on the light anyway, futilely. “Thanks,” I said, smiling, trying not to appear alarmed. “He must have lost track of time somewhere—​I’ll check the library.”

他不在那儿。我尝试去健身房，在一排排本科生中寻找，他们穿着椭圆机，扎着整齐的马尾辫，皮肤富有弹性，但高不在其中。我在我们第一次见面的咖啡馆停下来，店主睡眼惺忪地打开门。最后我绕回了我们的家——也许我不在的时候他就回来了。

He wasn’t there. I tried the gym, searching through rows of undergraduates, with their ellipticals, neat ponytails, and elastic skin, but Gao wasn’t among them. I stopped at the café where we’d first met, where the owner was just unlocking the doors, bleary-eyed. Finally I circled back to our home—​maybe he’d returned in my absence.

他没有。我给自己泡了更多咖啡，然后坐在沙发上。我盖上毯子。我想他也许生我的气了，我绞尽脑汁试图记住任何无意的轻视。我整天坐在那里，重新加热碗汤，直到下午 4 点电话铃响，是公园部门打来的当地警察。他们找到了他。

He hadn’t. I made myself more coffee and sat on the couch. I put a blanket on. I thought perhaps he was angry with me, I scoured my mind to try and remember any unintended slight. I sat there all day, reheating bowls of soup, until the phone rang at 4 p.m. It was the local police, called in by the parks department. They’d found him.

报告是一位老人在山上遛他的边境牧羊犬时发出的。高的尸体挂在树上，脸色黝黑，穿着皮夹克，胸前口袋里放着身份证和车钥匙。他整个晚上都在那里。他的车在空荡荡的停车场被发现，仪表板上有一张索引卡，上面写着我的名字和电话号码。我难以置信地搜查了公寓好几天，但没有任何其他东西，没有道歉，没有任何解释。他几乎在所有事情上都是保密的，在他的死亡上也是如此。

It was an elderly man out walking his border collie in the hills who’d made the report. Gao’s body was dangling from a tree, face black, clad in his leather jacket, ID and car keys in his breast pocket. He’d been there all night. His car had been found in the otherwise empty parking lot, an index card with my name and number written in his hand on the dashboard. I searched the apartment in disbelief for days, but there wasn’t anything else, no apology, no note of explanation. He had been private in almost everything, and he was private, too, in his death.

他缺席的日子继续过去：与朋友和殡仪馆通电话，以及需要安排的细节。朋友们等待着倾诉，但我却麻木了，没有什么可以分享的。我们的婚姻很短暂，我说。我很遗憾一切都结束了。我告诉自己，他的生活是他自己的，他想怎么做就怎么做，他也这么做了。

The days proceeded in his absence: phone calls with friends and funeral homes, details that needed arranging. Friends waited for confidences, but I was numb, I had none to share. Our marriage had been brief, I said. I was sorry it was over. His life had been his own, I told myself, to do with it what he would, and he did.

然而，葬礼结束后，这种情绪破裂了，我内心出现了一道鸿沟。晚上，我躺在床上，把自己埋在他的一堆衬衫下，想象着我们可能生下的孩子（他的脸颊，我的眼睛）。我发现自己在杂货店过道和演讲台上哭泣，眼泪流得很快，又以同样的速度逐渐减少。我已经接受了他们的外表。这就像一种新的心律或近视，虽然有些陌生，但现在已经不可挽回地成为我的一部分。

After the funeral, though, that sentiment cracked, and a chasm opened up within me. At night I buried myself under a pile of his shirts as I lay in bed, imagining the child we might have had together (his cheeks, my eyes). I found myself crying in grocery aisles and at the lecture podium, tears that came on quickly and tapered with equal speed. I resigned myself to their appearance; it was like a new cardiac rhythm or myopia, something unfamiliar but irrev­ocably now a part of me.

我把他的杯子和盘子放在碗碟架上。我在前门放了他的一双乐福鞋。我开始对那些因婚外情、疏忽或遗弃而导致婚姻破裂的人产生一种无端的怨恨，因为他们的答案清晰，或者至少可以拿起电话提出要求。

I kept his mug and plate in the dish rack. I kept a pair of his loafers by the front door. I began to feel an unreasonable resentment toward those whose marriages had been ruptured by affairs or neglect or abandonment, for their clarity of answers, or the fact that they could pick up the phone, at least, and demand them.

整整几个星期过去了，我却记不起其中发生了什么。

Whole weeks would go by and I couldn’t remember what had happened in them.

秋天过去了，然后是冬天。当我从办公桌上抬起头来时，已经是春天了，院长站在门口。她说，请假可能是个好主意。过去一个月我缺席了三节课，学生们纷纷抱怨。

Fall passed, and then winter. When I looked up from my desk it was spring, and the dean was standing in the doorway. A leave of absence might be a good idea, she said. I had missed three of my classes in the past month, and students were complaining.

不久之后，我发现自己来到了一家书店的旅游区，令我惊讶的是——尽管高坚称这里地处偏远——一本中国指南上列出了关于他家乡的简短条目。这听起来不太吸引人，被描述为“一个肮脏的中途停留地，但交通便利，有一些足够的酒店”，列出了两座寺庙和一座博物馆。但看到它用黑白印刷，一个真实的地方，清楚地列出了如何到达那里的方向，仍然让我感到震惊。一个月后，暑假课程结束时，我在飞机上。

Not long after that, I found myself in the travel section of a bookshop and to my surprise—​despite Gao’s insistence on its remoteness—​there it was, listed in a China guide: a brief entry on his hometown. It didn’t sound very enticing, described as a “dingy stopover with good connection links and some adequate hotels,” with two temples listed and one museum. But still it sent a jolt through me, to see it printed in black and white, a real place, with clearly listed directions on how to get there. A month later, when classes finished for the summer, I was on a plane.

 

参观完博物馆后，孩子们争先恐后地争着看装着氧化青铜和旧硬币的有机玻璃盒子，高的母亲开车送我们默默地回到他们位于镇郊的公寓，经过最近浇筑的道路和星罗棋布的新高楼大厦景观。我们时不时地经过几座即将被拆除的建筑物，但它们仍显示出居民的痕迹：这里有一排待洗衣物，那里有一辆玩具三轮车，一个背着双手、弯腰驼背的男人在闲逛。

After the museum—​a crowded affair of jostling children competing to peer into Plexiglas boxes containing oxidized bronze and old coins—​Gao’s mother drove us silently back to their apartment on the town’s outskirts, past the recently poured roads and new high-rises dotting the landscape. Now and then we passed a few soon-to-be-demolished buildings that still showed signs of inhabitants: a line of laundry here, a toy tricycle there, a stooped man wandering with his hands behind his back.

他们的公寓是十一楼的一间狭窄的两居室，当我们进去时，高的父亲穿着橡胶拖鞋拖着脚步迎接我们。他看起来比他的妻子年长，戴着一顶软边平顶黑色帽子，见到我时咯咯笑着打招呼。我立刻就喜欢上了他。“你好，”他说。他给了我一些用箔纸包着的小糖果，笑得更开心了。这似乎是他的抽搐症。

Their apartment was a cramped two-bedroom on the eleventh floor, and as we entered, Gao’s father shuffled to greet us in rubber slippers. He looked older than his wife and wore a soft-brimmed, flat black cap, and chuckled in greeting on seeing me. I liked him straightaway. “Hello,” he said. He offered me some tiny candies wrapped in foil, chuckling some more; it appeared to be a tic of his.

“你好，”我颤抖着说，他又笑了。

“Ni hao,” I quavered, and he beamed again.

“请坐。”高妈妈说着，把我安排到沙发上，然后走向厨房。我的腿很痛，但我没有抗议。在博物馆里，她一直在我身边徘徊，大声朗读那些支离破碎的英文说明，就像我还是个孩子一样，如果我错过了一个展示柜，她就会示意我过去研究里面的内容。

“Please sit,” Gao’s mother said, and arranged me on the couch before heading to the kitchen. My legs ached, and I didn’t protest. At the museum she had hovered by my side, reading the mangled English descriptions aloud to me as though I were a child, and if I missed a single display case, she would gesture me over to study its contents.

高爸爸一屁股坐在我旁边的椅子上，看上去很高兴。公寓看上去很短暂，墙上什么也没有。我试图和他说话，但他听不懂我的意思，于是我们一起把注意力转向电视，电视上一位雌雄同体的主持人正在采访一位身材瘦削的女人，她的胸前紧握着一只卷毛狗。

Gao’s father sank into a chair beside me, looking pleased. The apartment had a transient look, nothing on the walls. I tried to speak with him, but he didn’t understand me, and together instead we turned our attention to the television, where an androgynous host was interviewing a rail-thin woman who clutched a curly-haired dog to her chest.

“你确定我帮不上忙吗？” 我在拐角处伸长脖子，叫了高妈妈。

“Are you sure I can’t help?” I called to Gao’s mother, craning my neck around the corner.

她从门口探出头来。“不需要，”她说。她一只手向我挥舞着一只光滑壳的灰虾，触角抽动着，使它看起来像是活了过来。“这很容易。”

She stuck her head out from the doorway. “No need,” she said. In one hand, she waved a slick-shelled gray shrimp at me, antennae twitching in a way that briefly made it look alive. “It’s very easy.”

从厨房里，我能听到锅的嘶嘶声，当雌雄同体的采访者的部分结束时，我起身循着气味走去。高的母亲站在切菜板前，把大蒜剁成粘糊糊的面包屑，把生姜切成火柴棍。“闻起来很香，”我说。

From the kitchen, I could hear the pot sizzle, and when the androgynous interviewer’s segment was over, I got up and followed the smell. Gao’s mother was standing before a cutting board, mincing garlic into a sticky crumb, ginger into matchsticks. “That smells good,” I said.

“另一个房间里有一些照片，”她说，没有转身。“你可以看看。”

“There are some pictures in the other room,” she said, without turning around. “You can have a look.”

我离开了，感觉遭到拒绝。书房里堆满了书籍和论文，这似乎与高妈妈的果断果断格格不入。桌子上放着一只毛绒猩猩，标签还挂着。在一个角落里，一打植物从花盆里长出来，叶子上沾满了灰尘。他们旁边是一个书架，上面摆满了镶框的照片。其中一张照片上是十几岁的高，身材苗条，像童话里的流浪儿，头发上涂着发胶，穿着一件白色的纽扣领衬衫，顶部敞开。他看上去很年轻，一看到他我就倒吸一口凉气。另一张照片上，他还是个蹒跚学步的孩子，他的父母蹲在他身边，微笑着伸出手，仿佛手里握着他想让摄影师看到的东西。

I left, feeling rebuffed. The study was strewn with books and papers in a way that seemed at odds with Gao’s mother’s clipped decisiveness. A stuffed orangutan sat on the desk, its tags still on. In one corner a dozen plants bulged from their pots, leaves filmed with dust. Beside them was a bookshelf adorned with framed photos. One showed a teenage Gao, slim as a fairy-tale waif, hair spiked with gel and wearing a white button-down open at the top. He looked young, and the sight of him made me catch my breath. Another showed him as a toddler, his parents crouched beside him and smiling as he extended his hand, as though it held something he wanted the photographer to see.

当高的母亲走进房间时，我身后传来一阵喧闹声，我转过身来，手里还拿着他少年时的照片。“那是高，”我说，然后笑了起来。

There was a noise behind me as Gao’s mother entered the room, and I turned around, still holding the photo of him as a teenager. “That’s Gao,” I said, and managed a laugh.

“那是德国的高，”她说。听起来像是一个修正。

“That’s Gao in Germany,” she said. It sounded like a correction.

我恋恋不舍地把照片放回去，感谢她做饭。“我恐怕给你带来了很多麻烦。”我言不由衷地说。

I put the photo reluctantly back and thanked her for cooking. “I’m afraid I’ve given you a lot of trouble,” I said insincerely.

“没事。吃。”

“No trouble. Eat.”

高妈妈把曾经是灰色的虾子（现在变成了玫瑰粉色）的蒸笼放在客厅桌子中央，旁边还放着一盘荸荠和淡白菜。我们三个人坐下来，电视还开着，头顶上的荧光灯明亮。

Gao’s mother set the steamer of the once-gray shrimp, now turned rosy pink, in the center of a table in the living room, along with a dish of water chestnuts and pale cabbage. The three of us sat down, the television still on, fluorescent lights bright overhead.

这顿饭吃得很紧张。高妈妈不想说话，当我问她关于学校、邻居、家庭的情况时，她只简单地回答。无论如何，我一直试图寻找答案，感到越来越沮丧，因为经过多年的实地考察，在这次最重要的采访中，我似乎无法联系起来。时间一分一秒过去了。当我试图再次向她询问高的童年时，她粗鲁地说：“再吃点。” 然后：“你为什么哭？”

The meal was strained. Gao’s mother did not want to talk, replying only tersely when I asked her about the school, the neighborhood, the family. I kept trying to reach for answers anyway, feeling a mounting sense of frustration that after all my years of fieldwork, somehow in this most important of interviews, I could not seem to connect. The minutes ticked by. “Eat some more,” she said brusquely, when I tried to ask her again about Gao’s childhood. And then: “Why are you crying?”

我不好意思地摇摇头，擦了擦鼻子，然后又拿起筷子。然而，当我抬起头时，她仍在审视我。“我以为这次旅行会有所不同，”我最后说道，不喜欢声音中的颤抖。

I shook my head, embarrassed, and wiped my nose before returning to my chopsticks. When I looked up, though, she was still examining me. “I thought this trip would be different,” I said at last, disliking the tremor in my voice.

“你认为会有什么不同？”

“What did you think would be different?”

“一切，”我说。“我不知道。”

“Everything,” I said. “I don’t know.”

她的脸上闪过一丝不耐烦。她从塑料架上拿出餐巾纸，递给我。

A flicker of impatience crossed her face. She pulled napkins from their plastic holder and passed them to me.

“我儿子根本不应该结婚，”她说。

“My son should never have gotten married,” she said.

当我问她是什么意思时，她似乎考虑说些什么，然后笑了笑。我不知道她是否是为了我的利益，但我一下子就不在乎了。“如果你有什么意思，就直说吧，”我说。

When I asked her what she meant, she appeared to consider saying something, then gave a little laugh. I couldn’t tell whether she intended it for my benefit, and all at once I didn’t care. “If you mean something, just say it,” I said.

她稳稳地吃着，又拿起另一只虾，利索地把它从皮上滑下来，放进嘴里。然后她叹了口气，放下了筷子。

She ate steadily away, picking up another one of the shrimp, sliding it neatly from its skin and placing it in her mouth. Then she sighed and laid her chopsticks down.

“高非常有竞争力，”她说。“但是嫉妒并不是他们对那个可怜的男孩所做的事情的借口。”

“Gao was very competitive,” she said. “But jealousy is no excuse for what they did to that poor boy.”

我停顿了一下，不喜欢她的故事版本。我的手突然感觉很冷。“事情并非如此，”我慢慢地说。

I paused, not liking her version of the story. My hands felt suddenly very cold. “That’s not what happened,” I said slowly.

高爸爸对她说了一句话，她厉声回答。我突然想到，他们的婚姻并不幸福，或者可能只是因为在一个他们从未去过的遥远的国家失去了儿子而感到震惊。

Gao’s father said something to her, and she replied sharply. It occurred to me that theirs was not a happy marriage, or maybe it was just the shock of losing their son, far away in a country they’d never visited.

“我不会坐在这里听你攻击他，”我说。她举起杯子，但没有喝。她把它放回去，看着我，几乎是怜悯。“你根本就不了解他。”

“I’m not going to sit here and listen to you attack him,” I said. She lifted her glass but did not drink from it. She set it back down and looked at me, almost pityingly. “You didn’t really know him.”

 

当我和高妈妈回到车上时，外面的光线渐渐暗下来。蝉在我们周围的灌木丛中喧闹地鸣叫。天空呈现出淡淡的粉色，空气的凉爽拂在我的脸上感觉很好。

Outside the light was fading as Gao’s mother and I made our way back to the car. The cicadas thrummed noisily in the bushes around us. The sky was a faint pink, and the chill of the air felt good on my face.

“我去叫一辆出租车，”我说，但她拒绝了。这感觉就像是一种提议，直到她解释说：在镇上找到这样的人并不容易。

“I’ll get a cab,” I said, but she said no. It felt like an overture until she explained: it wasn’t an easy part of town to find one.

我们沿着高速公路行驶，路过街区大小的仓库和贴着新公寓和家具店广告的广告牌。这个场景并没有什么特别之处，我怀疑高是否能比我更清楚地认识到这一点。尽管如此，我还是拿起相机，把它指向窗外。

We drove along the highway, passing warehouses the size of city blocks and billboards with advertisements for new apartments and furniture stores. There was nothing remarkable about the scene, and I doubted Gao would have recognized any more of it than I did. Still, I took my camera and pointed it out the window anyway.

“高讨厌这里，”他的母亲突然说道。“我多次请他带你来。他总是说不。”

“Gao hated it here,” his mother said abruptly. “I asked him to bring you, many times. He always said no.”

我们沿着一座弯曲的立交桥绕过，把我们带到了一条狭窄的道路上。一侧是低矮的商店和加油站，另一侧则散布着廉价餐馆。我们从路边经过几个骑着自行车的孩子，他们互相快乐地大喊大叫，很快，一片密集的公寓楼森林就在我们的右边拔地而起。它们看起来很新，大部分都无人居住，窗户没有玻璃。

We rounded along a curved overpass that flung us out onto a narrow road. On one side were low-slung shops and a gas station, and scattered cheap eateries on the other. We passed a few children riding their bikes along the side, yelling happily at one another, and soon a forest of closely packed apartment blocks reared up on our right. They looked new and mostly untenanted, windows that gaped without glass.

再往前走，密集的建筑物幕布分开了，当我们接近它们之间的间隙时，我猛地吸了一口气。

Farther along, the dense curtain of buildings parted, and as we neared the gap between them, I inhaled sharply.

“那是什么？” 我问。“我们可以停下来吗？”

“What is that?” I asked. “Can we stop?”

高的母亲把车停在了路边。从乘客车窗外，我可以看到建筑物建在垃圾填埋场的顶部，但在它们被中断的地方，一堵土崖掉了下来，下面是一片布满碎片和建筑材料的岩石荒地。在它的中心矗立着一座孤独的混凝土房子。乍一看，这座房子似乎有几层楼高，直到我意识到它周围的地面已经被挖空，像雕塑的底座一样被挖掉；这座建筑矗立在夯土的顶层。

Gao’s mother pulled over. Outside the passenger window, I could see the buildings had been erected atop landfill, but where they were interrupted, a cliff of earth fell away, and below that was a rocky wasteland strewn with debris and construction material. At its center stood a lone concrete house. At first glance the house looked as though it might be several floors high, until I realized the ground had been hollowed around it, scooped away from it like the base of a sculpture; the building stood atop stories of packed earth.

它看起来就像一个奇怪的艺术装置，或者是一幅超现实主义绘画中的图像：一座城市融化成水坑，一座房子漂浮在其残骸上。

It looked like an odd art installation, or an image from a surrealist painting: a city melting into a puddle, a single house floating on its remains.

我问那里真的有人住吗，高妈妈说有。“它叫丁子湖， ”她解释道。“政府想征用他们的土地，但他们不肯搬走。”

I asked if anyone actually lived there, and Gao’s mother said yes. “It’s called dingzihu,” she explained. “The government wants to take their land but they won’t move.”

另一方面，无论谁在里面，似乎也无法离开房子。她说，除了缩小岩石斜坡的难度之外，如果房子空着，开发商很可能会来拆除房子。

On the other hand, it seemed, whoever was inside couldn’t leave the house, either. Apart from the difficulty in scaling down the rocky incline, she said, the developer would likely come and demolish the house if it was ever left empty.

“人们给他们带来食物，”她说。“看。”

“People bring them food,” she said. “Look.”

我下了车，关上车门，她也跟着走了。我们站在路边，看着一个女人和一个孩子在废墟中艰难前行，手里拿着一捆香蕉、一袋饼干和一大壶瓶装水。他们花了一段时间。当他们到达房子时，我们听到他们对着窗户喊叫。窗户滑开了，一个绑着绳子的水桶被扔了出去。

I got out, slamming the car door behind me, and she followed. We stood at the road’s edge and watched a woman and a child pick their way across the rubble, holding a sheaf of bananas, a sleeve of crackers, and a big jug of bottled water. It took them a while. When they reached the house, we heard them shout up to the window. The window slid open, and a bucket tied to a rope was flung out.

从我们的角度来看，这个女人和她的孩子看起来就像洋娃娃一样小。很难看出接下来发生了什么，但随后水桶被一只看不见的手缓慢而急促地拉着升起。

From our vantage point, the woman and her child looked as small as dolls. It was hard to see what happened next, but then the bucket was rising, slowly and jerkily pulled by an invisible hand.

“看？里面有人。”高妈妈说。

“See? There’s someone inside,” Gao’s mother said.

有那么一会儿，我以为我在窗户上看到了一张脸，但它消失得太快了，无法确定。我只能看到绳子和绳子上挂着的水桶。

For a moment, I thought I saw a flash of a face at the window, but it disappeared too quickly to be sure. All I could see was the rope, and the bucket that hung from it, dangling.

我们回到车里。天色渐暗，我们两个陌生人都急于回家。

We got back into the car. The light was fading, and we were two strangers anxious to get home.

飞行机

Flying Machine

在他生命的秋天，当玉米成熟并被采摘后，曹操决定建造自己的飞机，尽管他不会飞。

In the autumn of his life, after the corn had ripened and been plucked, Cao Cao decided he would build his own plane, though he did not know how to fly.

他住在一个红砖和水泥房屋的村庄。他脸上挂着微笑，仿佛有人给他讲过一个笑话，从那以后他就笑个不停。他非常喜爱他的鸡，它们的小脑袋和焦虑不安的啄食行为。“早上好，傻瓜们，”他一边喂它们一边高兴地说。

He lived in a village of red brick and cement homes. He had a smiling face, as though someone had once told him a joke and he hadn’t stopped laughing since. He had a great affection for his chickens, their tiny little heads and anxious, restless pecking. “Good morning, dummies,” he would say cheerfully as he fed them.

他的一条腿比另一条腿短，尽管他的妻子将楔形布料折进他的鞋子里，但鞋子不舒服，他把它们拿出来。人们经常看到他在村子里急匆匆地走着，有时会和朋友老李一起抽烟，坐在外面，或者去村口的小商店，那里卖薯片、瓶装饮料和多米诺骨牌大小的洗发水。他的妻子发誓他每天至少来两次。

One of his legs was shorter than the other, and though his wife folded wedges of fabric into his shoes, they weren’t comfortable and he took them out. He was usually seen walking through the village at a jerky clip, sometimes to smoke and sit outside with his friend Old Li, or to the small shop at the village’s entrance that sold chips and bottled drinks and domino-size packets of shampoo, a shop his wife swore he visited at least twice a day.

“这太多了，”她会说。“我们是贫穷的农民，还记得吗？”

“It’s too much,” she’d say. “We are poor farmers, remember?”

曹操确实试图克制自己，但后来他会感到口渴，想着给朋友们坐下来打牌时买点饮料或香烟该多好啊。或者，他在田野里度过了一天后焦躁不安，想要在牙下吃葵花籽。

Cao Cao did try to restrain himself, but then he would get thirsty and think of what a fine thing it would be to buy drinks or cigarettes for his friends as they sat and played cards. Or he was restless and wanted the clack of sunflower seeds under his teeth after a day spent in the field.

然而，认为他只是一个贫穷农民的想法——这是完全错误的。他的卧室里有一叠名片，讲述了他真正的职业。十年前他就把它们打印出来了，一叠一百本，从那以后就没有明显减少。他们读到，“发明家和基层工程师” 。两年前，当他得到一个新的电话号码时，他费力地用笔回顾、修改。

The idea that he was just a poor farmer, though—​that was simply incorrect. In his bedroom was a stack of business cards that spoke of his true vocation. He’d had them printed up a decade ago, a stack of one hundred that had not dwindled noticeably since. INVENTOR AND GRASSROOTS ENGINEER, they read. Two years ago, when he had gotten a new phone number, he had gone back laboriously over them with a pen, correcting them.

他真正想成为的，是一名党员。十五年来，他一直提交申请，并手写一式两份。他写道：“我是一名普通农民，但我真切地感受到中国共产党是我们民族和民族伟大复兴的指引者。” 我向党郑重提出申请，努力克服自己的缺点和不足，争取早日成为一名光荣的党员！他附上了自己的简历，用蓝色墨水小心地写着两行字：发明家，农民，男性，68 岁。家庭背景：农民。

What he really wanted to be was a party member. For fifteen years, he had submitted his application, copied out in duplicate by hand. I am an ordinary farmer, but I truly feel that the Chinese Communist Party is the guide of our nation and its great revival, he wrote. I solemnly apply to the party and strive to overcome my shortcomings and deficiencies, to try and become a glorious party member at an early date! With it he attached his résumé, two lines written in careful blue ink: inventor, farmer, male, 68. Family background: farmer.

每次，村支书江（一个穿着黑色风衣、长着麝香脸的男人）都亲切而坚决地拒绝了他。全国各地都在创造财富。党想要大学生，而不是老年农民。它想要大脑，它想要人才，它想要（这是暗示的，但不是口头的）财富。大鸭村只有一名党员，他拥有村里唯一兴隆的企业，一家将玉米压榨成玉米油的公司。在村里的月度会议上，他会和村支书坐在后面，一起弯着腰交谈，就像男孩们之间的男人们谈判一样。

On each occasion, the village’s party secretary, Jiang, a muskrat-faced man in a black windbreaker, rejected him kindly but firmly. All across the country, fortunes were being minted. The party wanted university students, not elderly farmers. It wanted brains, it wanted talent, it wanted (this was implied, but not spoken) wealth. Big Duck Village had just one other party member, a man who owned the village’s sole thriving business, a company that pressed corn into corn oil. At the village’s monthly meetings, he would sit with the party secretary, bent in conversation together at the back, like a parley of men among boys.

这很刺痛，但曹操并不是一个会沉迷于轻视的人。他年轻的时候，经历过一场饥荒，人们吃树皮！从那时起，他就看到这个村庄通了电，铺了路，用水泥加固，摩托车和机械化拖拉机的噪音越来越大。他一生见证了这个村庄的转变，就像他也将用他的邻居从未见过的发明来改变自己一样。

It stung, but Cao Cao wasn’t one to dwell upon slights. When he was young, he had lived through a famine in which they ate the bark off trees! He’d seen the village since then electrified, paved with a road, reinforced with cement, grown noisy with motorcycles and mechanized tractors. He’d seen the village transform itself over a lifetime, just as he, too, was going to transform himself with an invention the likes of which his neighbors had never seen.

为此，他成为了别人可能称之为垃圾的鉴赏家：生锈的炒锅、旧自行车零件、破损的农具。多年来，村民们养成了一种习惯，每当他们想要扔掉一些不寻常的物品时，他们就会去曹操家：一把破椅子、剩下的建筑材料。住在隔壁的两个小女孩私下里开玩笑说：每当她们遇到父母让她们扔进垃圾桶的东西——一小块肥皂、一张废弃的糖果包装纸——她们就会咯咯地笑着说：“给它吧。”投奔曹操！”

To that end, he had become a connoisseur of what others might call rubbish: rusted-through woks, old bicycle parts, broken farm implements. For years now, the villagers had made a habit of popping by Cao Cao’s any time they had some unusual item they wanted to discard: a broken chair, leftover construction materials. The two little girls who lived next door had made it a private joke: whenever they encountered something their parents made them put in the trash—​a tiny scrap of soap, a discarded candy wrapper—​they would giggle and say, “Give it to Cao Cao!”

事实上，曹操本来可以找到两者的用处，并且不会在这笔交易中被冒犯。例如，糖果包装纸可以被切成一朵装饰花，戴在机器人的帽子上。并不是说机器人有很多配件，甚至没有名字；而是说机器人有很多配件。这只是一个机人，或者说是机器人。它又高又笨拙，早期只是一些软管和电线连接在一个盒子上，多年来曹操在它上面的劳动声响彻村子，所有的敲打和锤击，但似乎从未出现过。待完成。

Actually, Cao Cao would have found a use for both and not been offended in the bargain. The candy wrapper, for example, could be cut into a decorative flower for his robot’s hat. Not that the robot had many accessories or even a name; it was simply a jiqiren, or machine-person. It was tall and ungainly and in the early days was just some hose and wires attached to a box, and for years the sound of Cao Cao’s labors over it could be heard through the village, all that beating and hammering, and yet it never seemed to be done.

过了一段时间，遇到曹操，乡亲们都会像询问陷入困境的儿子一样，询问季齐人的情况。

After a time, when they encountered Cao Cao, villagers would inquire after the jiqiren as they would a son who’d gotten himself into a difficult situation.

“机器人今天怎么样？” 他们可能会问，他们的态度中带着一丝关心。

“How is the machine-person today?” they might ask, a touch of solicitousness in their manner.

“不太听话。”在火花四溅、电线一扭一扭的日子里，曹操咬牙切齿地说。但在其他日子里，他会自豪地微笑。“非常好！等着吧，很快大鸭村就会有自己的机器人来为我们服务了。”

“Not very obedient,” Cao Cao would say, gritting his teeth, on the days that sparks flew and wires were twisted and retwisted until they frayed. On other days, though, he would beam proudly. “Very good! Just wait, soon Big Duck Village will have its very own machine-person to serve us.”

六年后，这款机器人终于在十二月一个寒冷的早晨亮相。全村人都围观，看着曹操把它从院子里推出来。该机器人由一个涂银的大盒子制成，躯干上有按钮，两条腿由粗管道制成，新的手臂由焊接金属制成。他的脸也是银色的，嘴唇是粉红色的，眼睛是黑色的，耳朵是粉红色的纸板做的。机器人的头顶上戴着一顶用空面粉袋缝制的白色厨师帽，捕捉着苍白的阳光。一个孩子惊呼：“他有一把刀！” 事实上，他确实这么做了：在他的铰接左臂上，贴着一块很像开信刀的钝金属。

At last, after six years, the robot was unveiled on a frigid December morning. The whole village turned up to watch as Cao Cao wheeled it out from his courtyard. The robot was built of a large silver-painted box with buttons across its torso, two legs made from fat piping, and new arms of soldered metal. His face was silver as well, with pink lips and black eyes and ears of pink cardboard. A white chef’s hat sewn from an empty flour bag sat atop the robot’s head, catching the pallid sunlight. One child exclaimed, “He’s got a knife!” and so in fact he did: on his left arm, which was hinged, a piece of blunt metal rather like a letter opener had been affixed.

当曹操将一块面团放在其下面并启动机器人时，带有刀的手臂开始上下泵动，机械地将面团刮削，产生一批均匀的面条条。这是当地特产的刀切面，制作简单，粗细有嚼劲。在他身边，他的妻子安宁羞涩地站着，把飞来的条子接在碗里。

When Cao Cao placed a block of dough under it and activated the robot, the arm with the knife started to pump up and down, shaving the dough mechanically, yielding up a batch of even noodle strips. They were the kind of knife-cut noodles local to the area, easy to make, thick and chewy. At his side, his wife, Anning, stood shyly and caught the flying strips in a bowl.

切面条机器人！众人还没有见过这样的事情。就连曹操和安宁的儿子也从一个小时车程外的小镇回来和他们一起庆祝，就连市委书记也来了。一些孩子走过来试图触摸机器人，当他们触摸机器人时，安宁轻快地把他们赶走了，说这不是玩具。然后她把面条煮好，装在碗里，上面撒上一点醋、蒜末和辣椒油。她先给党委书记送去，曹操紧张地等待着他的判决。

A noodle-slicing robot! The crowd hadn’t seen anything like it. Even Cao Cao and Anning’s son had come back from town, an hour’s drive away, to celebrate with them, even the party secretary had turned up. Some of the children came up and tried to touch the robot, and when they did, Anning shooed them briskly away, saying it wasn’t a toy. Then she boiled the noodles and served them in bowls, a splash of vinegar and smashed garlic and chili oil thrown on top. She served the party secretary first, and Cao Cao tensed, awaiting his verdict.

“有嚼劲，”他说道。“好吃啊曹同志！”

“Chewy,” he pronounced. “Delicious, Comrade Cao!”

这个词你已经不常听到了，不像半个世纪前曹操在军队时那样。他常常喜欢回想起那些日子，回想起国家还没有富裕起来的时候。在去加入他的连队的火车上，每一站，他和穿着迷彩服的男人们都像征服者一样受到欢迎：漂亮的女孩欢呼雀跃，为他们提供饼干和水果。在一站，他第一次尝到了一片橙子，那是一种鲜亮的楔形液体，橙皮几乎没有粘在一起，当他用牙齿咬住橙子时，他几乎高兴地大叫起来。那时候人人都是战友，人人都是英雄。

It wasn’t a term you heard much anymore, not like when Cao Cao had been in the army half a century ago. He often liked to think back to those days, back before the country had gotten rich. On the train ride out to join his company, at every stop, he and the men in camouflage had been greeted like conquerors: pretty girls cheering, offering them crackers and fruits. At one stop, he tasted an orange slice for the first time, a bright wedge of liquid barely held together by its skin, and as he released it between his teeth he nearly cried out in pleasure. Everyone was a comrade in those days, everyone a hero.

他本来希望能进一个排，但由于一条腿短，他被分配到后勤部门，切蔬菜（主要是土豆）一年多了，手指又滑又痛。他被派往三千里外的一个沙漠基地，那里的沙子一望无际，这是他记忆最深刻的：金色的沙子，蔚蓝的天空，飞机飞向蔚蓝的天空，还有无尽的块茎游行。被砍。

He’d hoped for a platoon, but because of the shortness of one leg he’d been assigned to the logistics division and chopped vegetables (mostly potatoes) for more than a year, fingers slick and aching. He’d been posted to a desert base three thousand miles away, where the sands stretched out interminably, and that was what he remembered most: gold sand, blue sky, planes taking off into that blue sky, and an endless parade of tubers to be chopped.

“毛主席说要为人民服务。”曹操语重心长地对聚集的村民说。“希望通过这个机器人，为您提供美味的面条。”

“Chairman Mao said to serve the people,” Cao Cao told the assembled villagers earnestly. “With this machine-person, I hope to serve you good-tasting noodles.”

那是十年前的事了，尽管有党委书记的表扬，但当年曹操的入党申请再次被拒绝，让他很失望。有一段时间，镇上的一家餐馆租用了这个机器人，上面挂着一个大牌子，上面写着机器人切面：便宜、现代、美味。但由于该装置失去了新鲜感，餐馆关门了，机器人也被送回了曹操家。它矗立在他们的小厨房里，笨重的存在，大部分都积满了灰尘，尽管如果有大型家庭聚会，偶尔会有妇女跑过去。“我们可以借用你的机器人吗？” 他们会这样问，就像他们要求借一把切肉刀或平底锅一样。

That was a decade ago, and despite the party secretary’s praise, Cao Cao’s application for party membership was once again rejected that year, much to his disappointment. For a while one restaurant in town had rented the robot, with a big sign proclaiming ROBOT-SLICED NOODLES: CHEAP, MODERN, DELICIOUS. But the restaurant shuttered after the device lost its novelty, and the machine-person was sent back home to Cao Cao. It stood in their small kitchen, a hulking presence that mostly gathered dust, though occasionally women would run over if they were having a large family gathering. “Could we borrow your robot?” they’d ask, just as if they were asking to borrow a cleaver or a pan.

一天晚上，飞机在梦中来到了曹操身边。在他的梦中，他驾驶着一架银色的装置飞行，与他在军队时期看到的起飞的飞机没有什么不同。他独自一人，双膝失重，一股温暖的风吹遍全身。他可以随意地移动它，以对角线，以优美的弧线，他飞过村庄，检查一排排玉米，远处的山丘，然后，当夜幕降临时，他把一朵云像一朵花一样抱在怀里。婴儿轻声唱着入睡。

The airplane came to Cao Cao in a dream one night. In his dream he was flying in a silver contraption, not unlike the planes he’d seen take off during his army days. He was alone, and his knees felt weightless and a warm breath of wind hung all about his body. He could move it at will, in diagonals, in graceful arcs, and he flew over the village, inspecting the rows of corn, the hills in the distance, and then, when night came, he bundled up a cloud in his arms like an infant and sang it softly to sleep.

第二天一早，他就立刻开始在飞机上工作，就像接到了一套精确的指示一样。一连几个月，曹操的院子里又充满了锤击声、火花声和机动车辆的呼呼声。当然，这将是一架按比例缩小的飞机，大小只够容纳两个人。但这将是一件美丽的事情。他和安宁可以骑它。随着年龄的增长，他发现自己变得更加多愁善感，也更加夸张地表达了对她的爱。“多么美丽的眼睛啊，”他边吃早餐边盯着她说。

The next morning, he started work on the airplane promptly, as though he’d been given a precise set of instructions. For months, Cao Cao’s courtyard was again filled with the sound of hammering and sparks and motorized whirring. It would be a scaled-down plane, of course, just big enough to seat two people. But it would be a thing of beauty. He and Anning could ride it. As he grew older he found he grew more sentimental, and spoke more extravagantly of his love for her. “Such beautiful eyes,” he’d say, staring at her over breakfast.

她会哼哼。“我们刚结婚的时候哪里有这种胡言乱语的？” 那已经是上辈子的事了，另一个时代了。在他们的婚礼上，他给了她父母六只鸡和三袋上海精米作为嫁妆。那时村里很穷，靠土豆维持生计。任何种类的大米——尤其是白米——都曾是一种奢侈品。安宁当时最深刻的记忆就是站在村里的厕所外面，等待一个拿着铲子和水桶的人来倒空厕所。她记得，每天早上，人们都等待着把分配的食物撒到田里，这是孩子们讨厌的肮脏苦差事。夏天，恶臭如浓云般升腾。冬天，你可以听到铲子铲冰土的声音。

She’d snort. “Where was this nonsense when we first got married?” That had been a lifetime ago, another era. For their wedding, he’d given her parents a dowry of six chickens and three bags of Shanghai milled rice. The village had been poor then, subsisting on potatoes; rice of any kind—​especially white—​had been a luxury. Anning’s strongest memory from the time was of standing outside the village toilet, waiting for a man with a shovel and pail to empty it. Every morning, she remembered, people waited for their allotment to spread in the fields, a dirty chore the children hated. In the summer, the stench rose like a thick cloud. In the winter, you could hear the sound of the shovel chipping away at the frozen mound.

“你是我一生的挚爱，而且一直都是，”他会说。

“You are the love of my life and always have been,” he’d say.

“我们还不是青少年，”她回答道，隐藏着她的喜悦。“去你的飞机上工作吧。”

“We aren’t teenagers,” she’d reply, hiding her pleasure. “Go work on your airplane.”

邻居们找借口顺便来看看这个装置，它是从曹操多年来收集的废品中升起的，就像一只金属凤凰，其中包括农民为制造飞机而拆解的旧鸡骑人的一部分。流传的报道是：它的机翼是用铰接的铁或钢制成的。它的鼻子圆圆的，就像鸡蛋尖一样！

The neighbors found excuses to drop in so they could sneak looks at the contraption, which rose from the scraps Cao Cao had collected through the years like a metal phoenix, including parts of the old jiqiren, which the farmer had disassembled to make his plane. The reports circulated: It had wings built of hinged iron, or maybe steel. It had a rounded nose like the tip of an egg!

在离他们最近的小镇上，他的要求让店主们大吃一惊，然后带着新的电机、电缆和金属板回来，甚至还为飞行员座位准备了一个红色乙烯基坐垫。时间一长，他和安宁几乎花光了所有的积蓄，花了几千块钱。安宁烦躁，曹操安慰她。他说，当飞机准备好后，他们就会将其出售以获取利润。“城里有有钱人可能会想买这样的东西。有了自己的飞机，他们可以去任何地方。太方便了。”

In the town nearest them, he bewildered shopkeepers with his requests and came back with new motors, cables, and sheet metal, even a red vinyl cushion for the pilot’s seat. In time he had drained nearly all of his and Anning’s savings, spending thousands of yuan. Anning fretted, and Cao Cao soothed her. When the airplane was ready, he said, they’d sell it at a profit. “There are rich men in town who might like to buy such a thing. With their own airplane, they can go anywhere. So convenient.”

她说：“你怎么知道有钱人会喜欢什么？”

She said, “How do you know what rich men will like?”

尽管如此，曹操并没有被吓倒。党需要有地位的成员、有声誉的成员，当然，一旦他的飞机建成，江书记就不能拒绝。如果曹操是党员，村里人都会对他另眼相看。他不再是曹操，一个儿子永远不回来帮忙收割、玉米地永远比其他人更破烂的傻老头。他就是曹操，一个为家乡、为民族伟大复兴做出贡献的人，值得尊敬。

Still, Cao Cao wasn’t deterred. The party wanted members of standing, members of reputation, and surely once his plane was built, Secretary Jiang could not say no. If Cao Cao was a party member, everyone in the village would look at him differently. He would no longer be Cao Cao, a foolish old man whose son never returned to help with the harvest and whose cornfields always looked more ragged than the rest. He would be Cao Cao, a man who’d contributed to his village, to the nation’s great revival, worthy of respect.

四月到来了，随之而来的一周，每个村民都争先恐后地上山采杏。每年，所有居民都在进行一场无声的竞赛，他们密切关注着果实的成熟情况。没有人拥有这片土地，任何人都可以采摘，但如果有人在观看，习俗规定你不能拿走超过你应得份额的东西。那么，清晨是最好的时间。如果你先于其他人到达那里，树上仍然满载着你，你可以采摘超过你的饱的东西。

April came, and with it a week in which every villager scrabbled up into the mountains to gather apricots. It was an unspoken contest every year among all the residents, who kept a careful eye on the fruit’s ripening. No one owned the land, and anyone could do the picking, but if anyone was watching, custom dictated you couldn’t take more than your fair share. Early morning, then, was the best time; if you got there ahead of everyone else, the trees were still laden and you could pick more than your fill.

入夏前夕，杏树开花了，正是在这个时候，镇党委接受了来自农村的党员推荐。多年来，曹操每天都早起，爬上山岗，察看白树和祭品。当杏子饱满了，明显可以采摘的时候，他会挑一整袋送给市委书记，只留一把粘稠的留给自己和安宁。多年来，这一简单的交易在他们眼中已经具有巨大的意义，尽管每个人都试图假装事实并非如此。

The apricot trees blossomed just before the summer, which was when the town party committee accepted party member recommendations from the countryside. For years, Cao Cao had woken early and climbed the hills to inspect the radiant white trees and their offerings. When the apricots were full and evidently ready for plucking, he would pick a whole bagful to present to the party secretary, keeping only a sticky handful in reserve for himself and Anning. Over the years, the simple transaction had gathered a tremendous significance in their eyes, though each tried to pretend it wasn’t so.

“这次我可能不会被接受，”他告诉她，同时他们在湿漉漉的皮肤堆中筛选，挑选出最圆、最光滑的，留下满是污垢的。

“I probably won’t be accepted this time,” he’d tell her, as they sifted through the damp-skinned pile, picking out the roundest, the smoothest, leaving the dirt-scabbed ones behind.

“这只是出于礼貌，”她同意道。

“It’s just to be polite,” she agreed.

村里有些人不太喜欢这个麝香鼠脸的男人。他从来没有清理过他那部分的下水道，而是让邻居们拿着一根棍子，偶尔四处看看，以确保街道上不会堆满他发臭的垃圾。还有人小声说，村里欠下的玉米化肥补贴被搁置在村支书的口袋里，但曹操是拒绝听的人之一。党对国家的进步和繁荣负有责任——任何人都可以看到这一点。

There were some in the village who didn’t like the muskrat-faced man much; he never cleaned out his part of the sewer, leaving it to neighbors to take a stick and occasionally poke around to make sure the street didn’t get backed up with his smelly refuse. It was whispered, too, that there were corn fertilizer subsidies the village was owed that had gotten stalled in the party secretary’s pocket, though Cao Cao was among those who refused to listen. The party was responsible for the country’s progress and prosperity—​anyone could see that.

那一年，杏子开始招手的那一周，曹操醒来时发现双腿僵硬、酸痛。似乎每个季节，疼痛都会加剧。第三天，他在冰冷的房间里躺了一会儿，身边安宁缓慢的呼吸声，才强迫自己直起身子，朝着山丘的方向走去。天还没亮。当他攀登时，他的双腿在颤抖，他在蓝色的黑暗中停了下来，靠在一块巨石上，心脏剧烈跳动，不确定。最后，他把自己推向白色的树木，但到达时，他发现其他人已经在他之前到达那里：树枝大部分都被剥光了。

That year, in the week when the apricots began to beckon, Cao Cao had woken up stiff and aching in his legs; every season, it seemed, the pain grew worse. On the third day, he lay in the cold room for a while, Anning’s slow breathing beside him, before he forced himself upright in the direction of the hills. It wasn’t yet dawn. As he climbed, his legs trembled, and he stopped in the blue dark and leaned against a boulder, heart hammering, uncertain. At last he pushed himself upward toward the white trees, but on arrival he saw others had been there before him: the branches were largely stripped.

当天晚些时候，他疲惫地敲响了市委书记的门。这所房子是村里唯一一栋铺着瓷砖的房子，大部分是白色的，但入口处的瓷砖却涂着红色、绿色和绿松石色的花朵和龙。当党支书打开门时，曹操看到他穿着一件新的精美皮袄，皮袄的纹路柔软细腻，如同女人的皮肤。曹操很想摸一摸。

Later in the day, he knocked tiredly on the party secretary’s door. The house was the only one in the village that was tiled, mostly in white, though the entrance tiles were painted in red and green and turquoise flowers and dragons. When the party secretary opened the door, Cao Cao noticed that he was wearing a new, fine leather jacket, its grain soft and delicate as a woman’s skin. Cao Cao ached to touch it.

蒋秘书询问了安宁和他儿子的情况，曹操就拿出了半满的袋子。“这并不多，”他说。

Secretary Jiang asked about Anning and about his son, and then Cao Cao pulled out his half-filled bag. “It’s not much,” he said.

“哦，不，我不能，”麝鼠脸男人说。但曹操却发现他的手已经伸过来要接他们了。“飞机怎么样了？” 他问。

“Oh, no, I couldn’t,” the muskrat-faced man said. But Cao Cao noticed that his hand was already outstretched to take them. “And how’s the plane coming along?” he asked.

曹操喜气洋洋，深受鼓舞。“很快就会准备好，”他承诺道。“你将是第一个看到它飞翔的人。”

Cao Cao beamed delightedly, encouraged. “It will be ready soon,” he promised. “You will be the first to see it fly.”

冬天，曹操穿着一件厚重的外套，戴着带耳罩的毛茸茸的帽子，几乎看不到他的脸。夏天，他穿着白色背心和短裤工作，露出了皱纹、瘦骨嶙峋的大腿。一天早上，他不小心将电池酸液喷到了脸颊和脖子上，需要在镇上短暂住院。他们的儿子现已结婚并有了孩子，他来看望他，带来了苹果和油印了一本关于飞机工程的书的章节。但他并没有停留太久，也没有帮父亲削苹果。

In the winter Cao Cao worked in a bulky coat and furry hat with earflaps, so that his face was scarcely visible. In the summer he worked in a white tank top and shorts that revealed wrinkled, skinny thighs. One morning he accidentally sprayed battery acid across his cheeks and neck, requiring a brief hospitalization in town. Their son, married now with a child, came to visit him, bringing with him apples and mimeographed sections of a book on airplane engineering. But he didn’t stay long, and he didn’t help peel the apples for his father, either.

“我们应该有一个女儿，”安宁将苹果刨花留在地上，哀悼道。“一个你晚年可以依靠的女儿。” 多年来，这个村子里一直没有年轻人。没有人愿意再种田了。当他们周末从城里回来时，周围都是刺耳的铃声、不对称的刘海和白色的鞋带，而且他们从来没有停留太久。

“We should have had a daughter,” Anning mourned as she left apple shavings on the ground. “A daughter you can depend on in your old age.” For years, the village had been emptied of its young people; no one wanted to farm anymore. When they came back on weekends from town it was with tinny ringtones and asymmetrical bangs and white shoelaces, and they never stayed long.

他们从医院回到家后，天空闷闷不乐好几天，下着倾盆大雨，当雨下得更大时，大窗帘使屋顶漏水。一天晚上，风刮得很大；但随后天空放晴，曹操在晶莹的蓝色纱布下工作了两个月。

After they got home from the hospital, the sky sulked for days, spitting rain, and when it came down harder, in great curtains, it made the roof leak. One night the wind blew loudly; it was as though a pack of ghosts was baying to get in. But then the sky cleared brilliantly, and Cao Cao worked for two months under a scrim of crystalline blue.

有时他自己轻声唱歌。几年前，村支书的父亲去世了，全村人都被邀请参加他的葬礼。一天，村里的主要街道两旁停满了六辆装饰着纸花的时尚黑色汽车，挤满了来自山上分散的五个村庄的哀悼者。人们分发香烟盒，党委书记和他的家人还拿着一幅巨大的死者肖像，以示极大的孝心。

Sometimes he sang softly to himself. Years ago, the party secretary’s father had died, and the whole village had been invited to his funeral. For a day the village’s main street was lined with half a dozen sleek black cars draped in paper flowers and crowded with mourners who had come from five scattered villages over the mountain. There were cigarette packs handed around, and a giant framed portrait of the dead man that was carried by the party secretary and his family in a show of immense filial piety.

葬礼、晚宴和几次演讲结束后，一名妇女爬上讲台，观众安静下来。免费的一餐当然可以保证村里每个人都来参加，但让哀悼者从更远的地方悼念死者就意味着晚上的娱乐活动。

After the funeral and dinner and several speeches, a woman climbed onstage, and the audience quieted. A free meal would of course guarantee the attendance of everyone in the village, but getting mourners to honor the dead from farther away meant nighttime entertainment.

外面很热，但女人穿着一件高领红色毛衣，搭配一条饰有羽毛和亮片的红色裙子，在昏暗的光线下闪闪发亮，脚踩厚底鞋。有人打开了音响，里面响起了一首快节奏、节奏稳定、反复出现的情歌。她开始跳舞，膝盖前后摆动，仿佛她是一匹慢跑的小马。“你能不能你能看到我，现在正飞进你的心里。”然后，随着节奏的变化和变慢，她的动作变得慵懒，像猫一样。她撅起嘴。她晃动一侧肩膀，用骨盆作为锚点来回摇晃身体。然后她脱下毛衣，把它扔给人群，好像她不在乎似的。下面是另一件红色衬衫，这次是闪闪发光的无袖衬衫。又过了一分钟，她也脱下了裙子，裙子躺在地上，蜷缩在羽毛状的红色水池中，就像一只孤独的热带鸟。

It was hot out, but the woman was wearing a high-necked red sweater, along with a red skirt trimmed with feathers and sparkles that caught the low light, and platform shoes. Someone turned on the stereo, and a fast-paced tune with a steady, recurrent beat blared, a love song. She began to dance, knees flashing forward and backward, as though she were a cantering pony. “Can you can you can you can you see me, flying now straight into your heart.” Then, as the beat changed and grew slower, her moves grew languorous, catlike. She pouted. She shimmied one shoulder and rocked her body back and forth, using her pelvis as an anchor. Then she took off her sweater, tossing it to the crowd as though she couldn’t be bothered with it. Beneath it was another red shirt, sparkling and sleeveless this time. In another minute, she’d stepped out of her skirt, too, which lay on the ground huddled in a feathery red pool like a forlorn tropical bird.

众人欢呼鼓掌。她弓起背，双臂拍打空气，前后甩动头发，就像是想用浓密的黑发为人群扇风。然后她把红衬衫拉到肩膀上方和头上，那件衬衫也在黑暗中飞了起来。她现在只剩下红色胸罩和内衣，灰色的，上面有某种卡通人物。

The crowd whooped and applauded. She arched her back, arms beating the air, and flipped her hair back and forth like she was trying to fan the crowd with her thick black tresses. Then she worked the red shirt above her shoulders and over her head, and that, too, went flying in the dark. She was down to just a red bra and her underwear now, gray with some sort of cartoon character on it.

她又随着一首歌曲起舞，一首高亢的共产主义曲调，她的步伐在节奏中变得更加武士。她转向左边，凝视着一支想象中的步枪的瞄准器，然后向右重复同样的动作。“蒋排长，向您致敬！” 她喊道，人群也用同样的话回应她。她正步走了一会儿，绕了一圈，时间长得足以让一些男人注意到她的小腿和屁股很瘦，而且她的眼睛看起来很职业无聊。

She danced to one more song, a high-pitched Communist tune, and her steps grew more martial in their pacing. She turned to the left and stared into the sights of an imaginary rifle, and then repeated the same move to the right. “Platoon Leader Jiang, I salute you!” she shouted, and the crowd roared the same words back at her. She goose-stepped for a while in a circle, long enough for some of the men to notice that her calves and butt were skinny and that her eyes looked professionally bored.

曹操只听过一次这首歌，但有时他高兴的时候就会哼唱，现在他又哼了一遍，在飞机上工作：“你能吗你能你能看到我，现在直接飞进你的飞机吗？”心。” 他想象着当他揭幕飞机时村民们钦佩的目光和评论。他想象着它飞向天空，就像他很久以前看到的从陆军基地起飞的飞机一样，然后仔细调整图像以想象地面正在消失，因为他是驾驶它的人。它将使大鸭村出现在地图上。这将是村里的骄傲。

Cao Cao had only ever heard the song that once, but he hummed it sometimes when he was happy, and he hummed it again now, working over his airplane: “Can you can you can you can you see me, flying now straight into your heart.” He pictured the villagers’ admiring stares and commentary as he unveiled his aircraft. He pictured it soaring up into the sky, just like the planes he’d seen take flight from the army base so long ago, then carefully adjusted the image to visualize the ground falling away, since he’d be the one flying it. It would place Big Duck Village on the map. It would be the pride of the village.

经过几个月的工作，飞机终于停在了他们的院子里，整齐、整齐，翅膀舒展着，就像某种奇怪的昆虫降落了，还没有决定是否留下来。它有银色的襟翼和涂成白色的金属机身，还有一个活泼的红色鼻子。他和安宁站着，对着茶杯呼气，蒸汽腾腾到空中。事情完成了。

After months of work, at last the airplane stood in their courtyard, neat and trim, wings outstretched, like some strange insect that had alighted and hadn’t yet decided whether to stick around. It had silver flaps and a metal body painted white with a jaunty red nose. He and Anning stood exhaling over their cups of tea, sending steam up into the air. It was done.

消息很快传开。到了下午，他们的院子里挤满了十几个围观者，气氛热烈而兴奋。曹操让他们一一爬进驾驶舱，欣赏他安装的操纵杆和控制器，以及他整齐地焊接在仪表板上的指南针。

Word spread quickly. By the afternoon their courtyard was crowded with a dozen onlookers and an air of genial excitement. Cao Cao let them climb into the cockpit, one by one, to admire the joystick he’d installed and the controls, and the compass he’d soldered neatly to the dashboard.

下午晚些时候，党委书记也来了。他最近刚刚从一小时飞行路程外的一个山区度假胜地的豪华聚会中归来，并以经验丰富的语气向曹操提供了有关他的旅程的提示。“当飞机起飞时，你应该会感觉耳朵有堵塞感，甚至可能会爆裂。这很正常——不要惊慌，”他一边说，一边拍着飞机，就好像这架飞机是他自己建造的一样。“当然，请确保始终系好安全带。”

Late in the afternoon, the party secretary came, too. He’d recently returned from a lavish party retreat at a mountain resort an hour’s flight away, and offered tips to Cao Cao about his journey, in the tone of a seasoned hand. “When the plane takes off, you should expect some clogged feeling in your ears, and they might pop. That’s normal—​don’t be alarmed,” he said, patting the plane as though he’d built it himself. “And make sure you keep your seat belt fastened at all times, of course.”

隔壁的女孩们也在那里，现在已经长大了，十四岁了。他们在城里上学。不过，他们仍然保持着齐声说话的老习惯。“我们能看到你飞翔吗？” 他们问过。

The girls from next door were there, too, grown up now, fourteen; they attended school in town. They still had their old habit, though, of speaking in tandem. “Can we see you fly?” they asked.

曹操想了想。他的儿子不在那里，他的孙子也不在那里，而他们应该在那里。而且他还需要系安全带。“下周末，”他说。“告诉大家吧！”

Cao Cao thought about it. His son wasn’t there, or his grandchild, and they ought to be. And he still needed to install a seat belt. “Next weekend,” he said. “Tell everyone!”

接下来的周末是阴天，天空呈珍珠灰色。需要三个年轻人，他们一脸严肃地努力，把飞机从院子里拖出来，倾斜地穿过双扇门。

The next weekend was overcast, the sky a pearly gray. It required three younger men, their faces serious with their efforts, to get the airplane out from the courtyard, tipped on a diagonal through the double doors.

从那里，他们将飞机推到村庄边缘的主干道上。人群兴奋地围着它。曹操的电话不断响起。首先是他的儿媳妇，说有一名摄影师和记者从城里赶来，她派他们去试验场。然后是安宁，说她也在路上，他想要他的绿帽子吗——那里可能会很冷。她已经带了一条围巾。她还会带一个保温瓶。

From there, they pushed the airplane out to the main road on the edge of the village. The crowd jostled around it excitedly. Cao Cao’s phone rang continuously. First it was his daughter-in-law, saying that a photographer and reporter had arrived from town and that she’d sent them on to the test site. Then it was Anning, saying she was on her way as well and did he want his green hat—​it would likely be cold up there. She was already bringing a scarf. She’d bring a thermos as well.

当她到达路口时，她几乎看不到飞机了，飞机被很多村民包围了。就连平时进城工作、玩耍的年轻人也都回来了，曹操在村里可是小有名气的人物，当他发明切面条机器人时，许多人还只是孩子。

When she arrived at the juncture in the road she could scarcely see the plane, it was surrounded by so many villagers. Even youth who usually absented themselves in town for work or play had come back, Cao Cao was a figure of such fame in the village; many had been just children when he’d invented his noodle-slicing robot.

驾驶舱比他想象的要窄一些，这意味着当他和安宁爬进去时，他们会很不舒服地互相挤压。到了晚年，他们都变得更厚重了。然而，当他们落座后，人群中却响起了欢呼声。安宁脖子上的针织围巾是红色的，和飞机的机头很相配。她的眼睛看起来有点害怕，有点眼花缭乱，因为受到了太多的关注。脚间夹着装有菊花茶的粉红色保温瓶。

The cockpit was a little narrower than he’d intended, and it meant that when he and Anning climbed inside, they were pressed against each other uncomfortably. They’d both thickened in their old age. Still, once they were seated, a cheer went up from the crowd. The knitted scarf around Anning’s neck was red and matched the plane’s nose. Her eyes looked a little afraid and dazzled, by the attention as much as anything. The pink thermos containing chrysanthemum tea was wedged between her feet.

他的儿子向人群大喊，让他们让道。他的孙子在儿媳妇的怀里，眨着眼睛看着天空，没有看到这一幕。人群欢呼雀跃。

His son was shouting at the crowd, telling them to clear the way. His grandson was in his daughter-in-law’s arms, blinking skyward, not seeing the scene. The crowd was cheering.

“当心！” 他的儿子喊道。“别飞太高！” 他们讨论过：简单地升空，然后直接降落。他们不确定燃料燃烧的速度有多快。

“Be careful!” his son shouted. “Do not fly too high!” They’d discussed it: a simple liftoff, and then come directly down. They weren’t sure how quickly the fuel would burn.

曹操小心翼翼地将安全带扣在他和妻子的腿上。他对站在人群边缘的市委书记笑了笑，后者因他的出现而感到一阵自豪。然后他猛踩油门，飞机向前冲去。它的速度越来越快，然后它就在高处了——他几乎能感觉到它——但是不，地面还在撞击着他们，他们还没有离开地面，又过了漫长的一分钟，他们已经接近了路的尽头，车停在一座红砖房里，房子的侧面喷着“禁止倾倒”的油漆，为了避免撞车，他猛地踩了刹车。村支书的房子是村里最大的房子，就在他的右边。

With ceremony, Cao Cao scrupulously buckled the seat belt over his and his wife’s laps. He grinned at the party secretary, who stood at the edge of the crowd, feeling a flush of pride at his presence. Then he pushed the throttle and the plane shot forward; it gathered speed, and then it was aloft—​he could nearly feel it—​but no, the ground was still bumping against them, they had not left the earth, and after another long minute they were approaching the end of the road, which dead-ended in a red-brick home that had NO DUMPING spray-painted on its side, and to avoid a crash, he abruptly slammed on the brakes. The party secretary’s house, the largest in the village, was just to his right.

人群涌向他们，询问发生了什么事。摄影师正在拍照。

The crowd descended upon them, asking what had gone wrong. The photographer was snapping pictures.

他的胃里已经开始形成一个深坑，但他忽略了它。他眼角的余光看到市委书记皱起了眉头。“不用担心，”他说。“我认为那是有翅膀的东西。扭转局面。我们会再做一次。”

A pit had begun to form in his stomach, but he ignored it. Out of the corner of his eye, he saw the party secretary frown. “Not to worry,” he said. “I think it was something with the wings. Turn it around. We’ll do it again.”

他们费力地下了飞机，安宁摆脱了腿上的抽筋，再次转动飞机。在他们旁边，一只狗正把腿抬到人行道上。儿媳妇抱着孩子走来走去，指着天空逗他开心。

They got laboriously out of the plane, Anning shaking out the cramps in her legs, and once again wheeled the plane around. Next to them, a dog was lifting its leg against the pavement. Their daughter-in-law was walking the baby back and forth in her arms, pointing at the sky for his amusement.

飞机掉头，他和安宁爬了回来。这一次，他不能再看她了。“你还好吧？” 他问。

The plane turned around, he and Anning clambered back in. This time, he could not look at her. “You okay?” he asked.

“我把热水瓶落在地上了，”她小声说道。当他转过头时，他看到了一个粉红色的塑料圆柱体放在人行道上，里面漂浮着皱巴巴的菊花。

“I left my thermos on the ground,” she said in a small voice. When he turned his head, he could see it, a pink plastic cylinder sitting on the pavement with crumpled chrysanthemum blossoms floating inside.

“没关系，”他安慰道。“我们稍后会得到它。” 他咬了咬牙，调整好机翼，再次踩下油门。飞机向前猛冲并加速。它还发出了一声呻吟声，但在它向前滚动的过程中，声音并没有减弱，再次顽固地贴在了地面上。他们缓慢地走过那家卖饮料和洗发水的小店，走过公共卫生间和一排排田野，田野里，泛黄、干枯的玉米壳排成又高又硬的一排。当曹操猛地把车停在村边的时候，两人都愣住了，安宁的脸颊上泛起一丝猩红，不知是冷了，还是羞了。

“That’s okay,” he said reassuringly. “We’ll get it later.” He gritted his teeth, adjusted the wings, and hit the throttle again. The plane shot forward and gained speed. It also made a groaning noise, which didn’t die down as it trundled forward and, once again, stayed stubbornly attached to the ground. They toodled on past the little shop that sold drinks and shampoo, past the public restrooms and rows of fields where yellowed, dried-out husks of corn stood in tall, stiff rows. When Cao Cao jerked it to a stop at the other edge of the village, the two of them sat frozen, with traces of scarlet creeping about Anning’s cheeks, either from cold or shame, he couldn’t tell.

“也许是太重了。”曹操最后说道。

“Maybe it’s too heavy,” Cao Cao said at last.

“我要出去吗？”

“Shall I get out?”

“我想这样最好。” 身后的人群也追了上来。安宁不确定地爬了出来，男孩们再次转动了飞机。“太重了！” 他们向小组的其他人喊道。“退后！”

“I think that’d be best.” The crowd was catching up behind them. Anning climbed uncertainly out, and the boys once again turned the plane. “It was too heavy!” they shouted to the rest of the group. “Stand back!”

对曹操来说，人群是模糊的，但如果他试图将他们集中起来，他可以看到孩子们，党委书记的严肃脸，他的朋友老李，看起来很担心。曹操越来越绝望，他按下了操纵杆，小飞机再次向前移动，在人行道上发出刺耳的声音。但飞机飞遍了整个村庄——田野、卫生间、商店——并再次拒绝升空。

The crowd was a blur to Cao Cao, but if he tried to bring them into focus he could see children, the grave face of the party secretary, his friend Old Li, looking concerned. With increasing desperation, Cao Cao pressed the controls, and again the little aircraft trundled forward, rasping against the pavement. But the plane ran the length of the village—​fields, restrooms, shop—​and once more refused to go airborne.

身后，他听见人群追赶的脚步声。“有什么问题？” 他听到有人喊叫。“它不会飞！” 别人说。

Behind him, he could hear the footsteps of the crowd pounding to catch up. “What’s the problem?” he heard someone shout. “It won’t fly!” someone else said.

记者是一位戴着绿色眼镜的年轻女子，拿着笔跑到他面前。“老曹，”她说道，“你没想到会发生这种事吗？飞机以前曾经成功起飞过吗？造这架飞机花了多少钱？”

The reporter, a young woman with green spectacles, ran up to him with a pen. “Old Cao,” she said, “did you expect this to happen? Has the plane ever taken off successfully before? How much did you spend to make this plane?”

当她的摄影师到达并站在飞机的路径上时，他坐下来，直视着相机镜头。这比看着人群更容易。一片悲伤的大荒原在他心中展开，展开了数十间小棚屋，可怕的擅自占地者在那里安营扎寨，用他们的微型酒瓶敲击着他的胸口，一百英尺的距离践踏着他的器官。这和他十几岁时父亲去世时的感觉是一样的，父亲在歉收的一年里自杀了，只有一个土堆作为他的坟墓。他失败了。他失败了。他必须再试一次。

He sat and stared straight ahead into the camera lens as her photographer arrived and stood in the plane’s path, clicking away; it was easier than looking at the crowd. A great wasteland of sorrow was opening up in him, unfolding dozens of tiny shacks, terrible squatters setting up residence, banging their miniature liquor bottles against his chest, a hundred feet trampling his organs. It was the same feeling he’d had as a teen when his father had died, a suicide during a year of bad harvest, and only a dirt mound to mark his grave. He’d failed. He’d failed. He’d have to try again.

曹操从驾驶舱里爬出来，沮丧和不快像脏雨一样附着在他身上。“朋友们，”他说，“看来可能出现了一些我没有预料到的问题。对于今天给我带来的不便，我感到很抱歉。”他说。“我知道你们很多人都是从很远的地方赶来的。”

Cao Cao climbed out of the cockpit, dismay and unhappiness clinging to him like dirty rain. “Friends,” he said, “it seems there may be some problem I didn’t anticipate. I am sorry for those I have inconvenienced today,” he said. “I know many of you have come from far away.”

一阵长时间的沉默。老李担忧地看着他，扫视着人群。党委书记正在看表。“大家都板着脸做什么？” 老李急忙说道。“虽然不是鸟，但绝对是兽！”

There was a long silence. Old Li looked at him worriedly and scanned the crowd. The party secretary was checking his watch. “What is everyone so long-faced about?” Old Li said, hurriedly. “It may not be a bird, but it is certainly a beast!”

“老李，说清楚！” 又有人喊道。

“Speak clearly, Old Li!” someone else shouted.

“你在说什么？”

“What are you talking about?”

“是一辆车！” 他喘着气。“曹操发明了汽车！”

“It’s a car!” he gasped. “Cao Cao has invented a car!”

人群转头看着这个小玩意儿，它展开了翅膀，身体肥硕，心满意足，更像是蜜蜂而不是蝴蝶。这不是一架很好的飞机。但这可能是一辆相当不错的车。

The crowd turned to look at the little contraption with its wings outstretched, fat-bodied and content, more bee than butterfly. It wasn’t a very good airplane. But it might be a pretty good car.

“很好，”一位回家观看演出的年轻人说道。“我可以骑吗？”

“Neat,” said one of the youth who had come home to see the show. “Can I ride it?”

那是一个在城里网吧工作的紫发女孩。她穿着白色高跟鞋和闪亮的银色外套。曹操记得她是一个胖乎乎的女孩，小时候喜欢和村里的狗玩耍，直到五岁为止，她似乎分不清自己是女孩还是狗，与人说话时常常吠叫。“当然，”他现在说，感激地咽了口口水。“走吧，我带你去。”

It was a girl with purple-streaked hair who worked at an internet café in town. She was wearing white heels and a shiny silver coat. Cao Cao could remember her as a plump girl who liked to play with the village dogs when she was small, who until age five seemed in fact confused about whether she was girl or canine, and used to bark when spoken to. “Sure,” he said now, swallowing with gratitude. “Come on, I’ll take you.”

她爬起来，曹操给她扣上安全带。两人再次飞奔穿过大街，紫色的发丝如火焰般在风中飞扬。“这太棒了，”当他们沿着路掠过时，她说道，经过商店、卫生间和玉米地。“事实上，这比坐飞机更好，”她说。“我以前坐过飞机。”

She climbed up and Cao Cao buckled her in. The duo shot off across the main street again, her purple streaks of hair flying in the wind like flames. “This is great,” she said as they skimmed along the road, past the shop, the restrooms, and the fields of corn. “Actually, it’s better than flying,” she said. “I’ve been on a plane before.”

“哦真的吗？”

“Oh, really?”

“这就像你一直坐在一个房间里，”她说。“你并没有真正感觉到。这并不像你想象的那样。”

“It’s like you’re sitting in a room the whole time,” she said. “You don’t really feel it. It isn’t like you’d expect.”

“党委书记说这太神奇了，”他说。

“The party secretary said it was amazing,” he said.

“党委书记，”她说，“是个白痴。”

“The party secretary,” she said, “is an idiot.”

当他们慢慢停下来时，她穿着白色高跟鞋优雅地下了车。“谢谢你，曹操！” 她说完就走开了，留下他盯着我看。

When they coasted to a stop, she alighted daintily in her white heels. “Thank you, Cao Cao!” she said, and walked off, leaving him staring.

那天晚上晚些时候，他和安宁躺在床上，盖着羽绒被，羽绒被最初是一条饰有粉红色花朵的白色毯子，但后来因污垢和岁月而变成灰色。月光从窗户洒到地板上。身旁，安宁的鼾声震动了整个房间。曹操侧身，试图看清她的轮廓。在黑暗中，更容易假装他们都没有变老，只有他们两个，二十岁，没有孩子；但他们两个人都没有变老。生活还没有在他们的身上留下伤痕，他们就如婴儿般纯洁地躺着。

Later that night, he and Anning lay in bed under their duvet, which had started life as a white blanket trimmed with pink flowers but had since gone gray with dirt and age. The moonlight spilled in from the window across the floor. Beside him, Anning’s snores vibrated the room. Cao Cao turned on his side and tried to make out her outline. In the darkness it was easier to pretend that neither of them had aged, that it was just the two of them, twenty years old and childless; life had yet to leave its scars on their bodies, they lay as pure and fresh as infants.

他想起紫发女孩对他说的关于市委书记的话，嘴角动了动。第二天，他想，他应该改变油门。他会检查引擎。他想，他会让那东西飞起来。下次，他不会邀请任何人观看。

He thought about what the girl with the purple hair had said to him about the party secretary, and the corners of his mouth moved. The next day, he thought, he would change the throttle. He would check the engine. He would make the thing fly, he thought. Next time, he wouldn’t invite anyone to watch.

他闭上眼睛，但睡意却让他无法入睡。相反，他仰面躺着，仔细想象自己穿过储藏室，里面存放着村里多年的垃圾。他可以看到编织的塑料袋，里面装着粮食，这些粮食在灾难性饥荒的一年里足以维持他们的生活。他可以看到两对新婚夫妇破损的自行车车轮，彩礼在用完后被丢弃。他可以看到村里有了第一个蓄水池时的额外管道长度，还有邻居送给他的一袋破布，以及他的女儿们长大后被撕成条状的旧衣服。

He closed his eyes, but sleep eluded him. Instead he lay on his back and carefully imagined himself walking through his storeroom, which held years of the village’s trash. He could see the woven plastic sacks that had held the grain that sustained them once in a year of disastrous famine. He could see the broken bicycle wheels of two different newlywed couples, betrothal gifts discarded after they’d outworn their use. He could see the extra pipe lengths from when the village got its first cisterns and a bag of rags his neighbor had given him, old clothes torn into strips after his girls had grown up and grown out of them.

他看到了所有这些，并在脑海中重新排列了它们。角落里有一台用自行车轮和管道和油桶建造的洗衣机。有一只机器狗。他可以将一套泡沫垫变成可以在水上行走的鞋子。他可以建造一台垃圾压实机，将所有垃圾压碎成小立方体，他会小心地将它们一个接一个地堆叠起来，直到它们形成一座危险的塔，他可以将其扩展到天空。

He saw them all, and in his head he rearranged them. There was a washing machine to be built out of bicycle wheels and pipes and the oil drum in one corner. There was a robot dog. There was a set of foam cushions he could turn into shoes that walked on water. There was a trash compactor he could build that would crush it all into tiny cubes that he would carefully stack, one by one, until they made a perilous tower that he could scale to the sky.

在你居住的街道上

On the Street Where You Live

当我看到他时，推餐车的那个人正向我走来，手里端着一个托盘，里面有奶油菠菜、稀烂的土豆泥和一块像厚橡胶一样的肉。我乖乖地坐起来，拉直连体衣的前襟，微笑着。我是你们国家的观察者，我是你们国家的伟大崇拜者，我想，他肯定会在这第七天注意到。“你好，”我说，然后挥了挥手。

When I see him, the man with the meal cart is coming at me with a tray, creamed spinach, watery mashed potatoes, and a splatch of meat like a thick piece of rubber. I sit up obediently, straighten the front of my jumpsuit, and smile. I am an observer of your country, I am a great admirer of your country, I think, and surely he might, on this seventh day of days, take notice. “Hello,” I say, and wave my hand.

我摆出准备交谈的态度，但他只是将托盘滑过插槽，然后推着推车继续前进。

I position myself in an attitude of readiness for conversation, but he simply slides the tray through the slot and moves on, pushing his cart.

他没有唱歌。没有人在唱歌。那里恶臭、潮湿、阴森，昨天我看到一只老鼠，一只真正的老鼠，在走廊里匆匆跑过。如果这是一部电影，老鼠会像雪一样白，会有十几只，它们会变成马，一切准备就绪，用爪子抓着，急切地抱怨着拉一辆南瓜变成的马车。如果这是一部音乐剧，我会穿着软鞋摇摆，在腰间优雅地鞠躬，轻轻一抖手腕，引导我们的队伍。

He is not singing. No one is singing. It is fetid and damp and grim, and yesterday I saw a rat, an actual rat, scurry across the corridor. If this were a movie the rat would be white as snow and there would be a dozen of them and they’d turn into horses, all ready and pawing and whining in their eagerness to pull a pumpkin turned carriage. If this were a musical I would lead our row in a soft-shoe shimmy, a graceful bow at the waist, a flick of the wrist.

不过，我视线中唯一的人是布鲁斯，他肯定比我重八十磅，大部分时间都盯着对面牢房的墙壁。布鲁斯来这里是为了丑陋、残酷的犯罪，而且对跳舞没有兴趣。

The only person in my line of sight is Bruce, though, who must be eighty pounds heavier than me and spends his time mostly staring at the walls in the cell opposite. Bruce is here for an ugly, brutal crime, and has no interest in dancing.

但后来，我开始分心，失去了线索。我一直很喜欢这种表达方式，以及它所带来的形象。我想象自己在食堂里爬行（除了这一翼没有食堂），寻找它难以捉摸的锥形末端，轻轻地道歉，检查运动鞋后面：“对不起，对不起，对不起，谢谢你，对不起。” 我想这就是我在你们国家呆了多久——一有机会我就会表达歉意和感激之情。

But then, I am getting distracted, I am losing track of the thread. I have always liked that expression, the image that it conjures. I picture myself crawling about the mess hall (except there is no mess hall in this wing) seeking out its elusive, tapered end, making soft apologies, checking behind sneakers: “Sorry, sorry, excuse me, thank you, sorry.” That’s how long I’ve been in your country, I think—​apologies and gratitude spring forth from me at any opportunity.

先生，谢谢您的菠菜土豆粥和橡胶。

Thank you, sir, for the spinach and potato gruel and for this rubber.

当然，我希望能为警方提供帮助。我已经把在我称之为居住地的任何国家学习法律作为我的习惯。我是一个受过高等教育的人。我有两个学位，其中一个毫无用处——我当然不是会计师——另一个是设计专业，这对我很有帮助。到我二十九岁的时候，我已经生活在五个不同的国家：其中两个是因为我穿梭于欧洲不同的寄宿学校之间，另外三个是在红西集团，这个名字现在你们肯定很熟悉；也许它为您提供电缆连接，或者拥有当地的购物中心。当我第一次加入时，公司的座右铭“我们为您带来世界”似乎是一种滑稽的夸大其辞；现在，当我坐在这里写作时，它似乎很准确。

I had hoped, of course, to be of assistance to the police. I have made it my practice to study the law in any country I call a place of abode. I am an extremely educated man. I have two degrees, one of which is useless—​I am certainly no accountant—​and another, in design, which has served me in great stead. By the time I was twenty-nine, I had lived in five different countries: two as I was shuttled between different boarding schools in Europe, three more at the Hongxi conglomerate, a name that by now is surely familiar to you; perhaps it supplies your cable connection, or owns the local shopping mall. When I first joined, the company motto, We Bring You the World, seemed a comic overstatement; now as I sit here writing, it seems precise.

我会告诉你我是如何认识佩里的。那是一天的结束，漫长的一天，当我回到家时，他正在我的门廊上等我。不，确切地说不是为了我，而是为了莉塞特。我的莉赛特 他们以前约会过，他回到她以前的公寓，心提到嗓子眼，愚蠢地希望能见到她。我告诉他，他应该检查一下地址，然后当着他的面关上门。这个国家可能很危险。他本可以携带武器。如果一个人携带武器并认为你把他所爱的人关在里面，那么他是非常危险的。

I will tell you how I really met Perry. It was the end of the day, a long day, and when I came home he was on my front stoop waiting for me. No, not for me, exactly, but for Lisette. My Lisette. They had dated before and he’d come back to her old apartment, heart in his throat, hoping foolishly to see her. I told him he should have checked the address and slammed the door in his face. This country can be dangerous. He could have been armed. A man is very dangerous if he is armed and thinks you are keeping his beloved inside.

“蓝眼睛，”他对着门喊道。“五点七分。她戴着眼镜，金发脏兮兮的。”

“Blue eyes,” he’d said, shouting through the door. “Five-seven. She had glasses and dirty-blond hair.”

我想，这样谈论她是多么不尊重。喊了这么多。还有肮脏的金发女郎，这真是一个措辞！我想，他肯定不会那样谈论他的母亲。我打开百叶窗并把它们关上。等会儿再回来吧，我傲慢地想。永远不要回来。

How disrespectful to speak of her that way, I thought. So much shouting. And dirty-blond, what a choice of words! He surely wouldn’t speak of his mother that way, I thought. I turned the blinds and snapped them shut. Come back later, I thought imperiously. Come back never.

确实，这套公寓不太好。在巴塞罗那，我住在一套位于十八楼的公寓，大厅铺着黑白瓷砖，老虎窗上覆盖着纯白色的织物。下面有一家面包店，里面供应的羊角面包又热又软，而且当你把它们拆开时，它们有多层，就像海洋生物的下腹部轻轻地呼气一样。我上面有一男一女，他们时不时地发生着令人兴奋的、令人震惊的关系，这让我脸红。在北京，我们的公寓位于一栋名为和谐庄园的混凝土摩天大楼的二十七层，俯瞰着城市广阔的灰色混合物，门厅里摆着假花，白色的柱子从我们的正门处意外地拔地而起。

It is true the apartment was not very nice. In Barcelona, I lived in an apartment that was on the eighteenth floor and had a black-and-white-tiled lobby and dormer windows bathed in sheer white fabric. There was a bakery below that served croissants warm and soft and many-layered as you pulled them apart, like the underbelly of a sea creature gently exhaling. There was a man and woman above me who periodically had exuberant, ceiling-thumping relations that made me blush. In Beijing, our apartment looked out over the wide gray mélange of the city from the twenty-seventh floor of a concrete skyscraper called Harmony Estates, with fake flowers in the foyer and white columns somewhat unexpectedly surging up from our front entrance.

莉塞特的街道距离大西洋城的赌场和度假村三英里，街道低矮，咸咸的微风吹过，让头发和脸变得粘糊糊的，所有的门廊、车道和参差不齐的草坪。没什么特别的，但更远的地方，这座城市打扮得漂漂亮亮的，很适合我。大多数周末我都会观看表演：高亢的踢腿声、高亢的莺歌声、所有欢快的音符。昂首阔步，摆出姿势，哒哒哒！在美国，像莉塞特这样的社区是后台；市中心才是表演真正发生的地方。我也喜欢了解后台。

Lisette’s street was three miles from Atlantic City’s casinos and resorts, low-slung and crossed with saltwater breezes that left the hair and face sticky, all porches and driveways and scraggly lawns. Nothing special, but farther out, the city spruced itself up and suited me fine. Most weekends I took in a show: the high kicks, the high-singing warblers, all the jubilant notes. Strut, pose, rat-a-tat-tat! In America, neighborhoods like Lisette’s are the backstage; downtown is where the performance really happens. I liked knowing the backstage, too.

佩里第二天下午回来了。当我下班回来时，他正坐在我家门前的台阶上，吃着用白色屠夫纸包裹的三明治。

Perry came back the next afternoon. He was sitting on my front steps and eating a sandwich wrapped in white butcher paper when I returned from work.

“抱歉，”他说，但听起来一点也不抱歉，只是要求。“我真的必须找到这个女孩。你在这里住多久了？”

“Sorry,” he said, though he didn’t sound sorry at all, just demanding. “I really have to find this girl. How long have you been living here?”

我在几步之外停下来，环顾四周。时间是五点钟，午后的阳光明媚。街区里传来冰淇淋小贩叮当作响的声音。住在对面白宫的卡斯尔女士走向汽车时一直注视着我们。

I’d stopped a few paces away, looking around us. It was five o’clock, late-afternoon sunlight. There was the tinkling sound of an ice cream vendor down the block. Ms. Castle, who lives in the white house opposite, was eyeing us as she went to her car.

“不会太久，”我辩解地说。

“Not long,” I said defensively.

“她的名字叫莉赛特，”他说道，就好像我一直在打听她的情况一样。“她以前住在这里。”

“Her name is Lisette,” he said, as though I’d been asking after her. “She used to live here.”

“所以你说的。” 天气很热，我在公园里检查我们最新的景点——急流河道，我很累。

“So you said.” It had been a hot day at the park inspecting a river-rapids ride, our newest attraction, and I was tired.

“我爱她，”他说。

“I love her,” he said.

“如果你爱她，你不应该有她的电话号码吗？”

“If you love her, shouldn’t you have her telephone number?”

“不一定，”他说，并递给我一份他的三明治。“无论如何，她不接电话。”

“Not necessarily,” he said, and offered me a part of his sandwich. “Anyway, she isn’t picking up.”

“那是你的问题，”我说，然后从他身边走过，关上了门。我一直很喜欢这句话，喜欢它逻辑清晰的分配。

“That’s your problem,” I said, and went past him, shutting the door. I always liked that phrase, the neat apportioning of its logic.

在那之后的下午，佩里不断出现，坐在我的门廊上，好像他真的不知道还能去哪里。有时他按我的门铃。通常他吃某种外卖：通常是熏牛肉三明治，偶尔是橙子鸡肉饭。这个人从来没有在室内吃饭吗？还是他只是一直在吃东西？他没看。他有一头红头发，长着蜘蛛网般的雀斑，个子很高，而且非常非常瘦。他的鼻孔张得非常厉害，就像梅伦格舞曲中女人的短裙一样。

Perry kept popping up after that in the afternoons, sitting on my porch as though he genuinely had no idea of where else to go. Sometimes he rang my doorbell. Usually he was eating some kind of takeout: often it was a pastrami sandwich, occasionally orange chicken with rice. Did the man never eat indoors? Or was he just eating all the time? He didn’t look it. He had red hair and spidery freckles and was tall and very, very skinny. He had terribly, sharply flared nostrils, like a woman’s short skirt as it billows during a merengue.

他非常坚持。被宠坏的傻瓜！

He was very insistent. Spoiled simpleton!

我敢打赌佩里不敢骑我的车。他可能会去坐老式的过山车，或者在小卖部闲逛，他心爱的迷失的莉塞特在他身边，温柔地供应爆米花。他看起来不像是一个能够忍受生活中的屈辱的人，无论是关着的门还是通过产道时令人不舒服、令人眩晕的通道。

I bet Perry would not have dared go on my ride. He would have gone instead for an old-fashioned roller-coaster, or hung around the concession stand, his beloved, lost Lisette beside him, tenderly ministering popcorn. He did not look like a man who could stomach life’s indignities, whether it was a closed door or an uncomfortable, vertigo-inducing passage through a birth canal.

当然，我说的是爱情隧道。在我加入时，洪熙刚刚开始在全球范围内收购电影制片厂和购物中心。它的主人康俊是一个油嘴滑舌、毫无魅力的男人，看上去就像一只伸开的蟾蜍，握手时却出奇地坚定。他曾在军队服役。他在那里认识了我的父亲，这就是我得到这份工作的原因。我想他以为我会像许多其他出国的人一样，成为一名虚荣雇佣者。我沾沾自喜，不过这并不是奉承，我让他大吃一惊。

I’m talking, of course, about the Tunnel of Love. At the time I joined, Hongxi had just begun buying up film studios and shopping malls across the globe. Its owner, Kang Jun, was a glib, un­attrac­tive man who looked like a stretched-out toad with a surprisingly firm handshake. He had been in the military. He had known my father there, and that’s how I got this job. I think he’d assumed I was going to be a vanity hire, like so many of the others who went abroad. I flatter myself, except it is no flattery, that I surprised him.

《爱情隧道》曾一度成为北京郊区红溪新开的主题公园的展示。当然，现在您会看到其他地方复制了该游乐设施，但当时您必须记住以前从未这样做过。骑手们被塑料包裹并蒙住眼睛。他们躺在轮床上，并被绑上安全带。然后，他们被带到一台扭动、发热的机器中，当他们奋力到达另一边时，机器会以一种逐渐变得更加痛苦和不舒服的方式收紧他们。一路上，他们因收缩而颤抖、翻滚，被淹没在滚烫、粘稠的液体中，液体在他们周围泛起涟漪。整个体验持续了六分钟。“重温生命最初的创伤！” 这就是我们的广告方式。“出生时，我们发现自己还活着。” 用英语来说，当我们在海外开设主题公园时，欢迎来到世界。在马德里，它是BIENVENIDOS AL MUNDO！

The Tunnel of Love was for a while the showcase in Hongxi’s newly opened theme park in the outskirts of Beijing. Now, of course, you see the ride copied elsewhere, but at the time you must remember it had not been done before. Riders were shrouded in plastic and blindfolded. They lay on gurneys and were strapped in. Then they were taken through a writhing, heated machine that would tighten around them in a fashion progressively more painful and uncomfortable, as they fought to reach the other side. On the way, shuddering and writhing through such contractions, they were submerged in a hot, viscous liquid that rippled all around them. The whole experience took six minutes. “Relive life’s original trauma!” was how we advertised it. “In birth, we find ourselves alive.” In English, when we opened the theme park overseas, the placard that greeted riders on the other side simply read WELCOME TO THE WORLD. In Madrid, it was BIENVENIDOS AL MUNDO!

当然，有些人认为它很粗糙，或者无味。但你会感到惊讶，有些人哭着走出去，另一些人走出去，惊讶地眨着眼睛，好像他们找到了继续生活的新勇气。记住我们来自哪里，这不是最了不起的事情吗？这难道不是我们都暗自渴望的吗？

Some thought it was crude, of course, or tasteless. But you’d be surprised, the way some people emerged from it, weeping, others stepping out, blinking with wonder, as though they’d found a new courage to go on with life. Isn’t it the most remarkable thing, to remember where we came from? Isn’t that something we all secretly crave?

 

一天早上，上班前，佩里在咖啡店找到了我。他踉踉跄跄地走了进来，立刻在我桌边坐下。

One morning, before work, Perry found me at the coffee shop. He lurched in and immediately sat down at my table.

“我真的很抱歉一直打扰你，”他说。那天早上，他的脸看起来又红又红，脸颊从枕头上皱了起来。我想，这是一个多么没有吸引力的男人啊。“我只想找到她，我不知道还能去哪里。她没有留下转发地址吗？你收到过她的邮件吗？”

“I am really sorry to keep bothering you,” he said. His face looked red and flushed, his cheek creased from his pillow that morning. What an unattractive man, I thought. “I just need to find her, and I have no idea where else to go. She didn’t leave a forwarding address? Do you ever get any of her mail?”

我看着他，打量着他。他穿着一件绿色的毛衣。他看起来不像个疯子。他看起来就像一个陷入困境的人。他似乎也不想让我一个人呆着。

I looked at him, considered him. He was wearing a green sweater. He didn’t look like a madman. He looked like a man in distress. He also didn’t seem inclined to leave me alone.

“你是怎么认识她的？” 我问。有那么一会儿，我闭上眼睛，想象着她。她的手很普通，莉塞特，我记得：有点丰满，有点胖，就像没有正确擀开的糖饼干，头发很细，感觉像水一样。她的身材并不出众，有点矮胖。不过，蓝色的大眼睛和任何明星的一样蓝。

“How did you know her, anyway?” I asked. For a moment I closed my eyes and pictured her. She had very ordinary hands, Lisette, I remembered that: a little plump, a little fat, like sugar cookies that hadn’t been properly rolled out, and hair so fine it felt like water. She had a body that wasn’t extraordinary, a little squat. Big blue eyes, though, as blue as any starlet’s.

“我告诉过你，我们约会过，”他说。“在我去阿布扎比之前。” 现在他的膝盖在颤抖，看上去既焦虑又害怕。他没有问我就从我盘子里拿了一块脆饼，咬了一口，然后意识到自己在做什么，然后突然把它放下。

“I told you, we dated,” he said. “Before I went to Abu Dhabi.” He was jiggling his knees now, looking anxious and hectored. He took a piece of biscotti off my plate without asking and nibbled it before realizing what he was doing and put it down, abruptly.

“和？”

“And?”

“什么也没有，”他脾气暴躁地说，好像我已经越界了。“我们发生了争吵——​我们不再说话了。但我现在回来了，我想我也许能补偿她。”

“And nothing,” he said grumpily, as though I’d overstepped my bounds. “We got into an argument—​we stopped talking. But I’m back now, and I thought I might be able to make it up to her.”

“你最后一次见到她是什么时候？”

“When did you last see her?”

“四年前，”他说。“我想这比看起来要早得多。” 他停了下来，再次看着我的脆饼。“你打算吃吗？” 我一言不发地将盘子递给他。

“Four years ago,” he said. “I guess it’s longer ago than it seems.” He paused and eyed my biscotti again. “Are you going to eat that?” I slid the plate over to him wordlessly.

“莉塞特不再住在那里了，”我说。

“Lisette doesn’t live there anymore,” I said.

“我明白了，”他说。“我只是想知道，你有她的邮件之类的吗？可能有回信地址的东西，其他可能知道如何找到她的人。”

“I got that,” he said. “I just wanted to know, do you have any of her mail or anything? Something that might have a return address, someone else who might know how to find her.”

最后我还是默许了。“好吧，”我说。“明天晚上过来。我会看一看。”

Finally I acquiesced. “Okay,” I said. “Come by tomorrow evening. I’ll take a look.”

 

我的母亲曾经告诉我，一切都是自我完善的机会，在监狱里我明白了这一点，我是一个好学的学生。早上，我把毯子折成宽大、均匀的长方形，然后擦洗水槽，直到完全无可挑剔。我做俯卧撑，在牢房里走来走去，嘴里喊着“什么嗬，什么嗬！” 但声音要轻柔，以免其他囚犯反对。我告诉自己，真正衡量一个人的标准是他如何应对逆境。我身体健康，有礼貌，整洁。我是一个好客人，好公司。

My mother once told me that everything is an opportunity for self-improvement, and in prison I am wise to that fact, I am an eager pupil. In the mornings I fold my blanket into a fat, even rectangle and scrub my sink until it’s utterly blameless. I do push-ups and walk around my cell chanting, “What ho, what ho!” but softly, so the other inmates won’t object. The true measure of a man is how he responds to adversity, I tell myself. I am fit, polite, and neat. I am a good guest, good company.

今天，一名看守带来了一名新囚犯，他的双臂被镣铐——最好不要怀疑他的罪行。他是个大块头，手臂上纹着粗糙的破折号，脖子上有锯齿状的粗黑线条，仿佛他的身体被缝在一起了。太丑了，我不忍心看。这里太丑了。

Today a guard brought in a new prisoner, his arms shackled—​best not to wonder about his crimes. He was a big man, with crude, tattooed dashes inked across his arms and thick black lines running jagged across his neck, as though his body were sewn together. It was so ugly, I couldn’t bear to look. It’s so ugly here.

下午，我静静地坐着，想着莉塞特。我知道其中的道理：如果你不定期重温你的记忆，它们就会消失，所以我会坐下来，一小时一小时地仔细研究它们；它打发时间。每隔几分钟，我就会改变姿势，防止四肢睡着。

In the afternoons I sit quietly and think of Lisette. I know the science: if you do not regularly relive your memories, they will disappear, and so I sit and pore over them by the hour; it passes the time. Every few minutes, I change my posture, to stop my limbs from falling asleep.

我们是在来这座城市的第二年认识的。她是一家医生办公室的不太称职的接待员，正在学习普通话，她也不太擅长，但她出现在同事举办的一次晚宴上，并试图用她的闲聊逗乐了我们所有人尽管我们其他人都说英语并且在国外接受过教育，但我们仍然精通这门语言，了解所有的文化参考点。我想那天晚上我大部分时间都盯着她看。并不是说我觉得她特别好看——其实她不是特别好看。但我想——我不知道还能怎样表达——她看起来很友善。她笑得很频繁，而且很轻松。直到我们真正成为朋友后，我才意识到她常常非常悲伤。我必须说，美国就是这样，自由而轻松，直到你了解得更清楚为止。

We met during my second year in the city. She was a not-very-competent receptionist in a doctor’s office and was studying Mandarin, which she was not very good at, either, but she’d turned up at a dinner a coworker was hosting and amused us all with her attempts to chatter away in the language, even as the rest of us were speaking English and had been schooled abroad, knew all the cultural reference points. I guess I stared at her most of that evening. It wasn’t that I thought she was particularly good-looking—​she wasn’t, especially. But I thought—​I don’t know how else to express it—​that she looked kind. She laughed a lot, and easily. It wasn’t until we actually became friends that I realized she was often very sad. America is like that, I must say, free and easy until you know better.

在那之后的几个月里，莉塞特和我在她的公寓里度过了漫长的下午。有时我们会看老电影，或者我会给她上语言课，有时我只是用眼角的余光看着她，我们坐在不同的沙发上看书，就像一对过早老去的夫妻。这个地方乱七八糟。一个房间里摆满了从架子上掉下来的大量毛绒动物：穿着天鹅绒裙子的白熊、四肢松软的青蛙、一堆棉絮和不同颜色的毛皮。她会用半耳语的声音背诵他们的名字和简短的传记，仿佛不想吵醒他们：这个是她继父送的生日礼物，那个是在家庭度假时玩街机游戏时赢得的。

In the months after that, Lisette and I spent long afternoons at her apartment. Sometimes we’d watch old films or I’d give her language lessons, sometimes I just watched her out of the corner of my eye as we read on separate couches, like a prematurely old married couple. The place was an odd jumble. One room held a substantial collection of stuffed animals that tumbled off the shelves: white bears with velvet skirts, a floppy-limbed frog, a menagerie of cotton batting and differently colored furs. In a half-whisper, as though anxious not to wake them up, she’d recite their names and brief biographies: this one a birthday gift from her stepfather, that one won while playing arcade games on a family vacation.

“别笑我，”她说。我做梦也没想到会这样。

“Don’t laugh at me,” she said. I wouldn’t have dreamed of it.

在我遇到莉塞特之前，美国并不是我想象的那样；我希望这很自然。每个人都很友好，但令人费解的是，每个人周围都好像有一排看不见的篱笆，我不知道如何穿透。你看，莉塞特与众不同。她需要我，想要我。

Before I met Lisette, America wasn’t what I’d imagined; it’s only natural, I expect. Everyone was friendly, but bafflingly so, as though each person had a series of invisible hedges around them that I didn’t know how to penetrate. Lisette was different, you see. She needed me, wanted me.

在精力充沛的间隙，她抱怨自己患有幻觉疾病。我们见面几个月后，她一直约会的一个男人不再给她打电话，结果她的身体一侧出现了几周无法解释的疼痛。这意味着她请了病假，不能离开沙发。这意味着我有一切借口和机会来服事她，我热情地这么做了。当她的症状恶化时，我两次陪她去急诊室。即使在那时，我已经怀疑她没有什么大问题，但她的眼睛因疼痛而紧闭，她紧握着我的手，我可以在那里再坐几个小时，她紧贴着我，头发在她的额头上轻微地缠结。就像一个发烧的孩子。

Between periods of great buoyancy, she complained of phantom illnesses. A few months after we met, a man she’d been seeing had stopped calling, and as a consequence she had several weeks of unexplained pain in her side. It meant she called in sick, couldn’t leave her couch. It meant that I had every excuse and opportunity to come minister to her, which I did, enthusiastically. Twice I accompanied her to the emergency room when her symptoms worsened. Even then I already suspected there was nothing very wrong with her, but her eyes were squeezed shut in pain and she was gripping my hand and I could have sat there for hours more, the way she clung to me, hair slightly matted on her forehead like a child with a fever.

我错过了工作，并不介意。爱情隧道取得初步成功后，红喜想让我设计更多的游乐设施；他们把我送到欧洲、澳大利亚。我还有很多其他的想法。但他们想要的只是会飞的瓢虫、旋转倾斜之类的东西。我没有兴趣！我告诉他们，现在的游乐园不应该只是让人们骑着机械臂到处乱扔。新的 VR 技术可以让我们想象出任何环境：迷人的鸡尾酒会、战场上呼啸而过的子弹，甚至（是的！）新房。如今，人们想要更多：感受联系，深入品味生活！

I missed work and didn’t mind. After the Tunnel of Love’s initial success, Hongxi wanted me to design more rides; they’d sent me to Europe, to Australia. I’d had other ideas, lots of them. But all they wanted were flying ladybugs, Tilt-A-Whirls, and the like. I had no interest! These days an amusement park shouldn’t just fling people about on mechanical arms, I told them. There were new VR technologies that would allow us to conjure up any environment: a glamorous cocktail party, bullets whizzing on a battlefield, even (yes!) a bridal chamber. These days, people wanted more: to feel connected, to taste life deeply!

相反，六年后，他们把我调到了大西洋城的后台办公室，并给了我一个新头衔：质量检验员，我花了几天时间在现场拿着剪贴板仔细地勾选。
