Instead, after six years they moved me to a back office here in Atlantic City and gave me a new title, quality inspector, and I spent days in the field with a clipboard making careful ticks.

莉塞特有火花。我想一直在她身边。我买了礼物并强迫她接受。我借给她钱，我知道她不会还。一天深夜，当我无法入睡时，我把车停在她的公寓外面，坐了几个小时，在音响上放着音乐：“镇中心有紫丁香树吗？不，就在你住的那条街上。”

Lisette had spark. I wanted to be around her all the time. I bought gifts that I pressed her to accept. I lent her money I knew she wouldn’t return. Late one night, when I couldn’t sleep, I parked outside her apartment and sat there for hours, show tunes on the stereo: “Are there lilac trees in the heart of town? No, it’s just on the street where you live.”

我对莉塞特最珍贵的回忆之一是那天我们坐在她的沙发上，沙发上铺着蓝色、红色和白色的花朵。我的膝盖上有一个记事本，距离她的只有几英寸，正在写一组字符。

One of my most treasured memories of Lisette was the day we were sitting on her couch, blue-and-red-and-white-flowered upholstery. I had a notepad on my knee, a few inches from hers, and was tracing out a set of characters.

“猫头鹰”我大声念道。

“Maotouying,” I read aloud.

我看着莉赛特干燥干裂的嘴唇拼出音节。阳光明媚而无情，她眼睛下方的皮肤看起来像皱巴巴的绉纱，但我并不介意。她是变身前的伊丽莎，这样我更喜欢她。我自以为只有某种男人才能看到她的潜力。

I watched Lisette’s lips, dry and chapped, form the syllables. The sunlight was bright and unkind, and the skin under her eyes looked like wrinkled crepe, but I didn’t mind. She was Eliza before her transformation, and I liked her better that way. It took a certain kind of man, I flattered myself, to see her potential.

“它的意思是‘猫头鹰’，”我告诉她。她微微偏过头，想了想，然后又一脸茫然地摇了摇头。

“It means ‘cat-headed eagle,’ ” I told her. She cocked her head slightly and thought before shaking her head, stumped.

“一只猫头鹰，”我说。

“An owl,” I said.

她笑了。“不行，”她说着，轻轻地打了我的手臂一侧。她的这种姿态让我抓狂，既充满姐妹情谊，又充满调情。“这其实真的很好。”

She laughed. “No way,” she said, and hit me lightly on the side of my arm; it was the kind of gesture of hers that drove me crazy, at once sisterly and flirtatious. “That’s actually really good.”

“好，现在长京路。”

“Okay, now changjinglu.”

“长经路。”

“Changjinglu.”

“长颈鹿。”

“Long-necked deer.”

“长颈鹿？”

“A giraffe?”

“你明白了，”我说。我们都笑了，我敲着笔，试图思考更多。

“You got it,” I said. We both laughed, and I tapped my pen and tried to think of more.

窗户就在我们的背后，白色的窗台布满了外面的灰尘。她离我如此之近，只要我稍稍倾身，我们的肩膀就会碰在一起。然后，毫无预兆地，她伸出手，轻轻地抚摸着我那皱巴巴、扁平化的右耳模糊的轮廓。这是一种先天缺陷，从出生起就伴随着我。当我还是个孩子的时候，在我母亲的建议下，我曾尝试留长头发来遮盖它；但后来我发现我的头发被留长了。效果并不好。

The window was to our backs, white sill gritty with dust from outside. She was so close that if I’d leaned over just a little, our shoulders would have touched. Then, without warning, she reached out and gently traced the blurred outline of my right ear, crumpled and flattened. It was a congenital defect, with me since birth. As a child, at my mother’s suggestion, I’d tried growing out my hair to cover it; the effect was not good.

“很好，”她随意地说。她说感觉就像一根融化的蜡烛。“好温柔，”她说，我屏住呼吸，尽量不让呼吸接触到她。那天我午餐吃了大蒜，但还没有机会刷牙，在那一刻，我同时感到荒谬、肮脏和幸福。我为什么不点汤？还是沙拉？

“Neat,” she said casually. She said it felt like a melted candle. “So soft,” she said, as I held my breath and tried not to breathe on her. I’d had garlic at lunch that day but hadn’t had a chance to brush my teeth yet, and for that suspended moment I felt simultaneously absurd, sordid, and blessed. Why didn’t I order the soup? Or the salad?

那天晚上，最令人兴奋的是，在我们看了两部电影之后，我起身离开，她转向我。“你不必走，”她说，这就像一件很棒的礼物被递给了我，还有她在走向她的房间时漫不经心地扔给我的毯子。后来，我在黑暗中躺在她的沙发上，听着她洗澡时的水声。当她打开门时，一道黄色的长方形光线洒了出来，她就在那里，裹着毛巾，在画面中停了下来，好像她能感觉到我的兴奋。我的心停止了跳动。小逗弄！

That night, most thrillingly of all, after we’d watched two movies and I’d gotten up to leave, she turned to me. “You don’t have to go,” she said, and it was like a great gift had been handed to me, along with the blanket she tossed carelessly my way as she went to her room. Later, I lay in the dark on her couch, listening to the sound of the water as she took a shower. When she opened the door, a yellow rectangle of light spilled out and there she was, wrapped in a towel, pausing in the frame as though she could sense my excitement. My heart stopped. Little tease!

我满怀期待地吸了一口气，开始坐起身来，但她已经消失在自己的房间里，并把光封在了身后。

I inhaled in anticipation and began to sit up, but she was already disappearing into her room and sealing the light behind her.

之后我就睡得很安稳。最后凌晨三点左右，我按捺不住，起身走到她卧室门口，听着有没有动静，想象着她趴在里面。然而，当我摇动手柄时，它拒绝移动。

After that, I slept fitfully. At last around 3 a.m., unable to contain myself, I got up and went to her bedroom door, listening for any sound, imagining her prone within. When I agitated the handle, though, it refused to move.

 

从咖啡店回来后，我想了很久该给佩里送什么邮件。有一袋又一袋的东西：六个月来不断收到的光鲜亮丽的时尚杂志，直到最后她的订阅肯定被取消了，信用卡账单上写着她的名字，还有更多类似的杂志。明尼苏达州的一位朋友寄来了一张结婚请柬——我知道这是一张结婚请柬，因为我打开了它——但它被打开的事实是显而易见的；它被打开了。信封全被撕破了。第二天早上，我在一家文具店买了另一个基本匹配的方形白色信封，用仔细的字体抄写了地址，然后重新密封。

After I returned from the coffee shop, I deliberated a long time over what piece of mail to give Perry. There were bags and bags of it: the glossy fashion magazines that had continued to arrive for six months until finally her subscriptions must have been canceled, the credit card bills made out to her name, and many more of that genre. There was a wedding invitation from a friend in Minnesota—​I knew it was a wedding invitation because I’d opened it—​but the fact that it had been opened was obvious; the envelope was all ripped. The next morning, I stopped in a stationery store and bought another square white envelope that mostly matched, copied the addresses in careful script, and resealed it.

那天晚上，当我把它递给佩里时，他站在我的门廊上，看着它，抚摸着它的边缘。“终于，”他喘息道。他看起来像是想把它擦在脸上。“这就是全部？”

When I handed it to Perry that night as he stood on my porch, he looked at it and caressed its edges. “Finally,” he breathed. He looked like he wanted to rub it against his face. “Is that all?”

“你不能打开它，”我有点拘谨地告诉他，但没有回答他。“打开别人的邮件是联邦犯罪。”

“You can’t open it,” I told him, a little primly, not answering him. “That’s a federal offense, opening someone else’s mail.”

他耸耸肩，将手指滑到翻盖下面。“嗯，别告诉任何人。”

He shrugged and slid his finger under the flap. “Well, don’t tell anyone.”

他打开信封，当他取出里面厚厚的象牙卡片时，我看着他的脸。婚礼请柬上写着波西娅·沃恩和大卫·科恩请求您的陪伴，并用常春藤手指包裹着信件。

He opened the envelope and I watched his face as he removed the thick ivory card inside. The wedding invitation said Portia Vaughn and David Cohen request the pleasure of your company and had letters wrapped in fingers of ivy.

“你不需要打开它，”我告诉他。我很生气他不听我的话，真是个没礼貌的人。“我以为你想要的只是寄信人地址。”

“You didn’t need to open it,” I told him. I was angry that he hadn’t listened to me, such an unmannered person. “I thought all you wanted was the return address.”

他把请柬和信封翻过来仔细检查。“嘿，”他说。“没有盖章。”

He turned over the invitation and the envelope, examining them. “Hey,” he said. “It’s not stamped.”

我的胸口有点震动——我怎么会忘记呢？——但我保持冷静。“奇怪，”我说。“也许是他们亲手送来的。”

My chest thudded a little—​how could I have forgotten that?—​but I kept calm. “Weird,” I said. “Maybe they hand-delivered it.”

“回信地址一直在明尼苏达州，”他说。我耸耸肩，试图抑制住从他手中撕下卡片的冲动。我正要关门，但他却把脚伸了进去。“等等，”他说。“我感觉不太舒服。可以给我一杯水吗？”

“The return address is all the way in Minnesota,” he said. I shrugged and tried to contain the urge to rip the card out of his hands. I started to close the door, but he stuck his foot in it. “Wait,” he said. “I’m not feeling very well. Can I have a glass of water?”

我盯着他的脚；我不喜欢他的脚放在那里。但这是一个非常合理的要求。我进去给他倒了一杯酒，坐在厨房桌子对面，他喝着，我们两个都很沉默。我可以看到他环顾房间。我想，我不应该给他倒这么高的杯子。他似乎决心要喝完每一滴，就好像浪费任何一滴都是一种侮辱。

I stared at his foot; I didn’t like his foot there. But it was such a reasonable request. I went inside and got him a glass and sat opposite him at the kitchen table as he drank it, the two of us very silent. I could see him looking around the room. I shouldn’t have poured him such a tall glass, I thought. He seemed determined to finish every drop, as though it would be an affront to waste any of it.

在剧本的这一点上，一个男人可能会用拳头猛击桌子，跑过房间，并要求答案。他没有。他只是坐在那里，喝着酒，环顾四周。

At this point in the script, a man might slam his fist on the table, race through the rooms, and demand answers. He did not. He just sat there, drinking and looking around.

“你确定你不认识她？” 他奇怪地看着我说道。“我发誓，这些家具有些看起来一模一样。” 他盯着角落里的一株植物，绿色的叶子上点缀着棕色，它放在一个橙色的花盆里。“就像，那种植物。我猜这可能是房东的？”

“Are you sure you didn’t know her?” he said, looking at me oddly. “I swear, some of this furniture looks exactly the same.” He was staring at one plant in the corner, green leaves touched with brown, which stood in an orange pot. “Like, that plant. I guess maybe it was the landlord’s?”

“我告诉过你，我在这里住的时间不长。”我生硬地说。不知何故，说话的行为打破了这个魔咒，我能够站起来，向他表明他也应该离开。

“I told you, I haven’t lived here that long,” I said stiffly. And somehow the act of speaking broke the spell, and I was able to get up, indicating to him that he, too, should leave.

他现在正在微笑。“好吧好吧，我这就去。谢谢你，”他拍着信封说道。

He was smiling now. “Okay, okay, I’ll go. Thanks for this,” he said, patting the envelope.

“没问题，”我低声说道，然后关上了他身后的门。

“No problem,” I muttered, and shut the door behind him.

 

我认识莉塞特六个月后，一个星期六的早晨我没想到会见到她。但随后我的公寓里传来一阵嗡嗡声，对讲机里传来她突然而温暖的声音，说她在楼下。我让她站起来，开始在房间里跑来跑去，把脏衣服踢到床底下，疯狂地把盘子堆到水槽里。

Six months after I’d met Lisette, there came a Saturday morning when I did not expect to see her. But then there was a buzz at my apartment and her voice sudden and warm on the intercom, saying she was downstairs. I let her up and began rushing around the room, kicking dirty laundry under the bed, madly stacking dishes in the sink.

当我打开门时，她站在那里，蓝色的眼睛里带着一种奇怪的专注盯着我。“我要走了，”她微笑着说道。“我决定了。”

When I opened the door, she was standing there, staring at me with a strange intensity in her blue eyes. “I’m going away,” she said, smiling. “I’ve decided.”

我感到内心沸腾的兴奋消退了。“已经？你刚到这儿。”

I felt the excitement that had fizzed up inside me subside. “Already? You just got here.”

“现在不行， ”她说。她走进去，倒在沙发上。“几周后。我要离开小镇了。”

“Not now,” she said. She walked in and threw herself on the couch. “In a couple weeks. I’m leaving town.”

我的胃一沉，仿佛所有支撑它的肌肉和肌腱突然忘记了它们的角色。

My stomach dropped, as if all the muscles and sinews that had been keeping it suspended abruptly forgot their roles.

“什么？”

“What?”

“我要重新开始，”她说。“就像先驱者一样。我要搬走。”

“I’m going to start over,” she said. “Like the pioneers. I’m going to move away.”

我依然站着，傻傻地看着她。“在哪里？” 我似乎只能用一个词来提出问题。

I stared at her stupidly, still standing. “Where?” I only seemed capable of speaking in one-word questions.

她耸耸肩。“我还不知道。但我要离开了，我要开始新的生活了。”

She shrugged. “I don’t know yet. But I’m going away, I’m going to start a new life.”

“为什么？”

“Why?”

“我厌倦了这里的生活，”她说。她踢掉鞋子，开始扭动脚趾。“我要搬走了。新生活。新身份。”

“I’m tired of my life here,” she said. She kicked off her shoes and began wiggling her toes. “I’m moving away. New life. New identity.”

“发生了什么？” 我边说边怀疑这是否是一场游戏。

“What happened?” I said, half wondering if this was a game.

她皱起眉头，承认前一天她被办公室解雇了。“但这不是我离开的原因，”她说。“我只是想重新开始。我需要你的帮助，”她说。

She frowned, and admitted that she’d been fired from her office the previous day. “But that’s not why I’m leaving,” she said. “I just want to start over. And I’m going to need your help,” she said.

“为什么是我？”

“Why me?”

“因为你是我的朋友，”她不耐烦地说，“我可以信任你。” 她走进厨房，开始翻冰箱。

“Because you’re my friend,” she said impatiently, “and I can trust you.” She went to the kitchen and began rifling through the refrigerator.

莉塞特在很多方面都很无助，但她也很精明，我想她知道我会为她做任何事情。在接下来的几周里，她兴奋不已，不断谈论她的计划。她会很早就起床给我打电话，喋喋不休地告诉我一个或另一个想法。有一天她买了地图，很多地图。另一天，她扔掉了所有的书和灯，把它们留在外面的人行道上。

Lisette was helpless in a lot of ways, but she was also canny, and she knew, I think, that I’d do most anything for her. In the weeks that followed, she was hyper, talking constantly about her plans. She’d wake up early and call me, buzzing with one idea or another. One day she purchased maps, lots of maps. Another day she threw out all of her books and lamps, left them outside on the sidewalk.

“你为什么做这个？” 我一直问她，她耸耸肩。

“Why are you doing this?” I kept asking her, to which she’d shrug.

“我太无聊了，”她说。“我被困住了。”

“I’ve been so bored,” she said. “I’ve been stuck.”

在她离开前的最后一周，我下班帮她清理了公寓，把她的东西整理得井井有条。这些毛绒动物玩具以及各种家具和六袋衣服都被捐献给了善意慈善机构。“这个月剩下的时间我还需要付房东的钱，”她犹豫着，没有看我。

In the last week before she left, I took off work and helped her clear out her apartment, arranging her things into tidy piles. The stuffed animals went to Goodwill, along with assorted furnishings and six bags of clothes. “I still need to pay my landlord for the rest of this month,” she hesitated, not looking at me.

“我能应付，”我告诉她。她坐在我对面的地板上，正在整理一堆文件，当我这么说时，她跪下来，摇摇晃晃地拥抱了我。“谢谢你，”她对着我紧闭的右耳吹了一口气。“我不知道没有你我该怎么办。”

“I can handle it,” I told her. She’d been sitting opposite me on the floor, sorting through a stack of papers, and when I said that, she rose up on her knees and hugged me unsteadily. “Thank you,” she breathed into my closed-up right ear. “I don’t know what I’d do without you.”

莉赛特离开的前一天，我设法说服她来我们的游乐园参观。她说她不想这么做，她已经筋疲力尽了，但在我做了这一切之后，我坚持这么做，她答应了。我想要出去玩一天，只有我们两个人，想让她看看我做主人、当地人做客人的地方，享受我做的游乐设施。在公园里，我们吃了漏斗蛋糕和烤花生。然而令我惊讶的是，莉塞特顽固地拒绝进入爱情隧道。她看着它，浑身颤抖。“不，谢谢。”

The day before Lisette left, I managed to persuade her to come see our amusement park. She hadn’t wanted to, she was exhausted, she said, but after all I’d done, I’d insisted and she said yes. I wanted the day out, just the two of us, wanted her to see the place where I was host and the locals were guests, enjoying the rides that I’d made. At the park, we ate funnel cake and roasted peanuts. To my surprise, though, Lisette stubbornly refused to go into the Tunnel of Love. She shuddered, looking at it. “No thanks.”

“这是我的发明，”我告诉她。“这就是我回到北京开始我的职业生涯的方式。”

“It’s my invention,” I told her. “This is how I started my career, back in Beijing.”

“你从来没有告诉过我这些。”

“You never told me that.”

“我确信我做到了，”我说。“没关系。尝试一下。你会被塑料包裹起来——你不会被弄得太湿。”

“I’m sure I did,” I said. “Never mind. Try it. You’ll be wrapped in plastic—​you won’t get too wet.”

“我没事，”她说。“我不喜欢封闭的空间。”

“I’m okay,” she said. “I don’t like enclosed spaces.”

“你会喜欢的，我发誓，”我告诉她。“这是关于重生的。经历生命中我们大多数人都忘记的时刻是什么感觉？来吧——我和你一起做。” 我试着拉着她的手臂。

“You’ll like it, I swear,” I told her. “It’s about rebirth. What it’s like to experience a moment in your life that most of us have forgotten. Come on—​I’ll do it with you.” I tried pulling her by the arm.

她整天闷闷不乐，对我指点的公园细节、给她买的红溪棒球帽毫无兴趣。“别再欺负我了，”她突然说道。

She’d been sulky all day, exhibiting no interest in the details of the park that I’d pointed out, the Hongxi baseball cap that I’d bought her. “Quit pushing me around,” she said suddenly.

她双手插在外套口袋里，大步走开。我远远地跟着她，一开始感到惊慌，但也很兴奋——好像也许现在是时候做出某种手势了：把她抱进我的怀里，也许，结结巴巴地坦白我的感受！当太阳落山时，我们可以乘坐摩天轮，天空像毯子一样覆盖着我们，我们可以分享一个甜甜圈，当我们在空中晃来晃去时，我擦去她脸颊上的糖粉。

She stalked away, hands in her coat pockets. I followed her at a distance, feeling panicky at first but also excited—​like maybe this was the time to make a gesture of some kind: sweep her into my arms, maybe, stammer out a confession of how I felt! We could ride the Ferris wheel as the sun went down, the sky pulled over us like a blanket, we could share a doughnut, me brushing the powdered sugar from her cheek as we dangled in the air.

然而，当我追上她时，她已经停下来买了玉米热狗，正在一张爬满蚂蚁的野餐桌上吃东西，而且她看到我看起来并不高兴。我们静静地坐在那里，直到她说完，当她建议我们去参加一个名为“向日葵兔子”的游乐设施时，这是一群白色的小兔子，座位在它们的腹部凹陷，在黄铜杆上悲伤地上下起伏，这是一个专为五人设计的游乐设施。岁的孩子们——这不是（幸运的是）我的工作——我没有和她争论，继续前进。我们坐在两个相对的兔子圈上，懒得系安全带，痛苦地起起落落，不说话。

When I caught up with her, though, she had stopped to buy a corn dog and was eating at a picnic table that crawled with ants, and she didn’t look happy to see me. We sat there silently until she finished, and when she suggested we go on a ride called the Sunflower Bunnies, a bunch of white bunny rabbits with seats indented in their bellies that rose dolefully up and down on brass poles, a ride designed for five-year-olds—​it wasn’t (mercifully) my work—​I didn’t argue with her and got on. We sat on two opposite bunny laps, not bothering to belt ourselves in, rising up and down miserably, not speaking.

“抱歉，”当我们走出游乐设施时，她说道。“我不知道为什么有时我会这样。” 她不自在地动了动。“我们回家吧，”她说。“我开始感觉胃痛了。”

“Sorry,” she said, as we walked out of the ride. “I don’t know why I get like that sometimes.” She shifted uncomfortably. “Let’s go home,” she said. “I’m starting to feel a stomachache coming on.”

 

我还是不明白她为什么要离开。说实话，直到她走进那辆白色的旧二手车，保险杠上贴着“我的孙子是斯泰尔斯大厅的荣誉学生”贴纸时，我以为她会回头：开玩笑，一个流产的实验，只是另一个紧急情况- 房间参观，这涉及一罐汽油和几个大行李袋。我参加了这个猜谜游戏，催促她多带几瓶水和一条应急毯子，这样她就可以在车里睡觉了。

I still don’t understand why she wanted to leave. To be honest, up until she was getting into her old used car, white with a MY GRANDSON IS AN HONORS STUDENT AT STILES HALL sticker on its bumper, I thought she’d turn back: Just kidding, an aborted experiment, just another emergency-room visit, this one involving a tank of gas and several large duffel bags. I’d participated in the charade, pushing her to take extra bottles of water, an emergency blanket so that she could sleep in the car.

“你要去哪里？” 我一直问，但直到她坐上驾驶座，她才说她不知道。她稍后会给我打电话，她不耐烦地说，她会在路上弄清楚的。

“Where are you going to go?” I kept asking, but up until she got into the driver’s seat, she said she didn’t know. She’d call me later, she said impatiently, she’d figure it out on the road.

那天下午，我拿着她的钥匙走进了她的公寓，那天剩下的时间都躺在她的花沙发上，此后的几天我一直回来。如果我半闭上眼睛或者让它们转向某个方向，就可以想象莉塞特就在隔壁房间，或者可能在浴室里，排空她脆弱的肠道。最终我放弃了我在城另一边的公寓，并与她的房东协商好，这样我就可以继续住在她的地方了。我喜欢那里。我什至还去亲善商店买回了莉塞特的一些东西：她用过的橙色陶瓷杯、厨房毛巾、她的一些毛绒玩具。

That afternoon, I let myself into her apartment with her key and spent the rest of that day lying on her flowered couch, and for days after that I kept coming back. If I half closed my eyes or kept them turned a certain way, it was possible to imagine that Lisette was just in the next room, or perhaps in the bathroom, emptying her delicate bowels. Eventually I gave up my apartment across town and fixed it with her landlord that I could keep staying at her place. I liked it there. I’d even gone to the Goodwill to buy back some of Lisette’s things: the orange ceramic mugs she used, kitchen towels, some of her stuffed animals.

几个星期过去了。我没有收到莉塞特的消息，当我打电话时，她也没有接听。

Weeks went by. I didn’t hear from Lisette, and when I called, she didn’t pick up, either.

我花了很长时间才意识到她永远不会打电话来，当我明白这一点时，有一段时间它让我崩溃了；就像我再次来到这座城市一样。我感到绝望的针刺感越来越难以拂去，像好莱坞的雨一样粘稠，水与牛奶混合，所以它显示在屏幕上。

It took a long time for me to realize she wasn’t ever going to call, and when that knowledge sank in, for a while it undid me; it was like I was new to the city all over again. I felt pinpricks of despair that felt harder and harder to brush away, sticky like a Hollywood rain, water mixed with milk so it shows on the screen.

我找到了新的追求。在她离开后的几个月里，我养成了在市中心的大街上闲逛的习惯，到处挑选一些女人，当她们引起我的注意时就跟着她们，从不走到她们前面的台阶上，从不接近她们，没有那样的事，但有时你看到一个女孩独自一人，只是想知道：她要去哪里？她的生活是什么？有时，融入另一个人的脚步节奏是一件令人欣慰的事情。这里不存在违反法律的情况。

I found new pursuits. In the months after she left, I fell into the habit of wandering the strip downtown, picking out women here and there, following them when they caught my eye, never to their front steps, never approaching them, nothing like that, but sometimes you see a girl by herself and simply wonder: Where is she going? What is her life? And sometimes it is a soothing thing, to fall into the rhythm of another person’s step. There is no violation here of the law.

我只见过一次：一个浅色金发女郎，尖脸，一个小时后，他叫来了赌场保安，保安用对讲机简短地说了几句，然后跟我搭话。凑近了看，女人的嘴又小又干，脸上带着一种老套的愤怒表情。当警卫询问我的情况时，我告诉他我迷路了，需要指路。他难以置信地摇摇头。“你最好离开这里，”警卫警告道，并看了那个女人一眼，让我觉得这是不必要的保护。

Only once was I spotted: a pale blonde with a pointed face who, after an hour, called over a casino security guard, who spoke briefly into his walkie-talkie before accosting me. Up close, the woman’s mouth, small and dry, bore a trite expression of outrage. When the guard demanded my business, I told him I was lost and needed directions. He shook his head in disbelief. “You’d better get out of here,” the guard said warningly, and gave the woman a look that struck me as unnecessarily protective.

当我走开时​​，那个女人低声嘟囔着，声音大到我都能听到，“怪胎。”

As I walked away, the woman muttered, loud enough so that I could hear, “Freak.”

我又走了几步，脸发烫，等走远了，我才转过身来，再次面对他们，嘴里涌出一个词：“妓女！”

I walked a few more steps, face hot, and when I was far enough away I turned and faced the pair again, the word surging out of my mouth: “Whore!”

 

在审判中，密切关注邻居的卡斯尔女士告诉法庭，佩里在我的公寓外面等了我好几天，我们似乎在争吵，我会当着他的面关上门。她说，他曾两次进屋，一次是在深夜。

At the trial, Ms. Castle, who keeps a close eye on the neighborhood, told the courtroom that Perry had spent days waiting for me outside my apartment, and that we appeared to be quarreling, and that I would shut the door in his face. On two separate occasions he had gone inside, she says, once late at night.

这不是一个我喜欢的故事，所以我会很快告诉你。

It is not a story I relish and so I will tell you quickly.

我第二次见到佩里是在歌剧院。我的一位同事有一位投资者的门票。我们坐了两个小时，听了一个大头大发的女人尖叫，最后我的同事离开去接电话，没有回来。我一直坐到最后，然后和人群一起离开，佩里也在其中。我差点没认出他来。他的红发被梳平了。他穿着一件黑色外套，搭配一件白色围裙风格的衬衫，打着领结，比房间里的任何人都盛装打扮。我们在铺着红地毯的大厅里见到了对方，大厅里有优雅的大理石瓮和闪烁的黄色灯光。我穿着一套简单的西装。我已经三个月没见到他了，我们互相打招呼，就像尴尬的、多年未见的熟人一样。

The next time I saw Perry was, of all places, at the opera. A colleague of mine had tickets from an investor. We sat through two hours of a woman with a big head and big hair screeching, and finally my colleague left to take a phone call and didn’t return. I sat until the end and filed out with the crowd, Perry among them. I very nearly didn’t recognize him. His red hair had been brushed flat. He was wearing a black coat with a white pinafore-style shirt and bow tie, far more dressed-up than anyone in the room. We sighted each other in the red-carpeted lobby, with its graceful marble urns and yellow lights winking above. I was wearing a simple business suit. It had been three months since I’d seen him, and we greeted each other like embarrassed, long-lost acquaintances.

他与陪伴他的女人分开了——我想，也许是他的妹妹；也许是他的妹妹。她有着同样的红发——然后他和我一起在外面的人行道上，我们一起散步。

He split off from the woman who was with him—​perhaps his sister, I thought; she shared the same ruddy hair—​and then he was outside with me on the pavement and we were walking.

夜晚凉爽、柔软、诱人。佩里就在我身边，我们都沉默了。“你要去哪里？” 我在某个时候问过，他耸耸肩。“没有什么特别的地方，”他说。“我和你一起走。” 于是他一直陪着我走，经过酒店和酒吧，经过沉睡的加油站和挂着涂鸦烤架的关门商店，一直回到我住的街道，走上我家门前的台阶，然后跨过门槛，进了屋。路上，他给我讲了中东的沙漠是什么样子，讲了嘴里像吹风机一样的热风，讲了那里的汽车如何配备了每当你超速时就会不断发出蜂鸣声的装置，这对他来说是大部分时间。我告诉他在北京长大的经历，灰蒙蒙的天空，寒冷的冬天，

The night was cool and velvety and inviting. Perry was at my side, and we were both silent. “Where are you headed?” I asked at some point, and he shrugged. “Nowhere in particular,” he said. “I’ll walk with you.” And so he kept walking with me, past the hotels and bars, past the sleeping gas stations and shuttered shops with their graffitied grills, all the way back to my street and up my front steps, then across the threshold, and inside. On the way, he told me about what the desert looked like in the Middle East, and about the hot air like a hair dryer in your mouth, about how the cars there came with devices that beeped incessantly whenever you went over the speed limit, which for him was most days. I told him about growing up in Beijing, the dusty gray of the skies, the freezing winters, and how the rain left dirty scrawls on my father’s fleet of expensive black cars, how I used to like taking a wet paper towel and cleaning them, the meditative feel of the gesture.

在里面，我打开了灯，沙发、莉塞特的书架、我的靴子和文件都成为焦点，就像他们在某个表演中受到惊吓一样。

Inside, I flicked the lights on, and the couch, Lisette’s bookshelves, my boots and papers all sprang into focus, like they’d been startled in the middle of some act.

“你饿了吗？” 我不确定地问道。他看起来就像电影里的人物，仍然穿着燕尾服，与周围的环境格格不入。“我有吐司。我可以给你做一些鸡蛋。”

“Are you hungry?” I asked uncertainly. He looked like a character from a movie, still wearing his tuxedo, ill suited to his surroundings. “I have toast. I could make you some eggs.”

他点了点头。“当然，那就太好了。”

He nodded. “Sure, that’d be great.”

我走进厨房，开始取出食材。他呆在客厅里，我用眼角的余光看到他在客厅里踱来踱去，检查着东西。我不合理地担心他可能会走进卧室，也许会看到莉塞特的毛绒动物，那些我从善意救出来的，排列在我的书架上。

I went into the kitchen and started taking out ingredients. He stayed in the living room, where, out of the corner of my eye, I could see him pacing around, inspecting things. I worried, irrationally, that he might wander into the bedroom and perhaps see Lisette’s stuffed animals, the ones I’d rescued from Goodwill, lining my bookshelf.

“嘿，”我喊道。“过来跟我说话吧。”

“Hey,” I called. “Come and talk with me.”

他走进来，像一张瘦长的折纸一样，靠在门框上。“需要帮助吗？”

He came in and folded himself, like a lanky piece of origami, against the doorframe. “Need any help?”

我给了他一个刨丝器和一块奶酪，他默默地开始在金属上摩擦。我转回炉子旁，煎锅开始冒烟，我切下的黄油块已经软化并变成棕色。我扔了六个鸡蛋和一滴盐，盐太多了。“对不起，”我说。“我不是一个很好的厨师。”

I gave him a grater and a knob of cheese and he silently started working it against the metal. I turned back to the stove, where the skillet was starting to smoke and the wedge of butter I’d cut had softened and was turning brown. I threw in six eggs and a cascade of salt, too much salt. “Sorry,” I said. “I’m not a very good cook.”

他出现在我身边，把奶酪放进去。厨房渐渐暖和起来。佩里脱下外套，轻轻打开食品储藏室的门，将外套挂在上面，就好像他以前做过很多次一样。鸡蛋在锅里变松后，我把煎蛋卷翻过来，把它分成两半，然后从餐具抽屉里拿出叉子。它们是莉赛特的，但不匹配。

He appeared at my side and dropped in the cheese. The kitchen was getting warm. Perry stripped off his coat and opened the pantry door slightly and hung his coat over the top, as if it were something he’d done many times before. After the eggs had fluffed themselves up in the pan, I turned the omelet upside down and divided it in two before pulling out forks from the cutlery drawer. They were Lisette’s and didn’t match.

我们默默地吃饭。我打开了一瓶红酒，我们俩都不停地喝着。我问他关于婚礼请柬的事，关于波西娅和大卫的事，他是否收到了回复。“他们从来没有回复过，”他有点不好意思地说。“我猜他们可能会觉得这有点奇怪，他们从未听说过有人这样寻找她。”

We ate in silence. I’d uncorked a bottle of red wine, and we were both drinking steadily. I asked him about the wedding invitation, about Portia and David, if he’d ever heard back. “They never replied,” he said, a little sheepishly. “I guess they might think it was kind of weird, someone they’d never heard of looking for her like that.”

他说，他现在是一名顾问，和妹妹住在一起。很难重新适应这里的生活。“每个人都非常努力，”他说。“每个人都希望你能在比赛中处于领先地位。” 他说，这很孤独。在我第一次发现他四肢摊开在门廊上寻求莉塞特的那一天之前，他已经感到孤独了两个月。

He was working as a consultant now, he said, living with his sister. It was hard to readjust to life here. “Everyone works so hard,” he said. “Everyone expects you to be on top of your game.” It was lonely, he said. He’d been feeling lonely for two months before that day I’d first found him sprawled out on the porch, asking for Lisette.

“我想这有点可悲，”他说。

“I guess it was a little pathetic,” he said.

“一点也不。”

“Not at all.”

“我猜你也一定感到孤独，从中国远道而来，”他说。

“I guess you must feel lonely, too, coming all the way from China,” he said.

老实说，我并没有告诉他，我很小的时候就离开了家，当我回到那里时，我也感到孤独。

I told him not so much, honestly, that I’d left home so young I felt lonely when I went back there, too.

我告诉他爱情隧道的事，他的心情变得愉快起来。“这就是我所需要的，一个新的开始，”他说，并发出像狗吠一样的笑声，一只有点老、有点病的狗。我告诉他我有时会带他去那里。我想那时我们已经有点醉了。我告诉他，我一直在考虑为我们的公园创造一种摇篮体验，一种婴儿体验。一张你可以躺在里面的婴儿床，一个巨大的移动设备悬挂在你的头顶上，轻柔地播放儿歌，也许还有几张巨大的脸，会时不时地俯视你，发出咕咕声。

I told him about the Tunnel of Love, and he brightened. “That’s what I need, a new start,” he said, and gave a laugh like the bark of a dog, a dog that was a little old, a little sick. I told him I’d take him there sometime. We were a little tipsy by then, I suppose. I told him that I’d been thinking about creating a cradle experience, an infant experience, for our parks. A crib that you could lie inside, with a giant mobile suspended above your head softly playing nursery tunes, and maybe a couple of giant faces that would peer down at you every so often and coo.

佩里当时奇怪地看着我，但点点头，试图表示同意。“当然，”他说。“我想这听起来不错。”

Perry looked at me strangely then, but nodded, trying to be agreeable. “Sure,” he said. “I guess that sounds kind of nice.”

之后我们在厨房里一起擦盘子，佩里不自觉地伸手去拿莉塞特放毛巾的抽屉。它们和她以前用过的红白条纹的一样，但我想他一定没有注意到；无论如何，他没有对此发表评论。时间已经很晚了，酒已经冲昏了我的头脑，也许他也一样。他拉开食品储藏室的门，拿起外套，停下来，嘶哑地说：“嘿。”

Afterward we wiped the dishes together in the kitchen, Perry automatically reaching for the drawer where Lisette had kept the towels. They were the same red-and-white-striped ones she’d used before, but he must not have noticed, I thought; anyway, he didn’t comment on it. It was late, and the wine had gone to my head, and maybe his as well. He pulled open the pantry door to pick his coat up, and as he did, he paused and said a hoarse, “Hey.”

是邮件。莉赛特的邮件堆积如山，我把它们装进袋子里放在食品储藏室里，不知怎么的，那天晚上我就把它们忘记了。我停止了呼吸，突然惊慌，突然害怕。

It was the mail. All the accumulated stacks of Lisette’s mail, which I had kept tumbled in bags in the pantry and somehow that evening had forgotten about. I stopped breathing, suddenly panicked, suddenly afraid.

她走后，我猜莉塞特一定换了电话号码，因为每当我打电话时，它就一直响个不停。尽管如此，我还是收到了她的信用卡账单，有一段时间我看着她在全国各地旅行：这里有一家便宜的汽车旅馆，那里有四分之一罐汽油，有热狗和薯条，从不在任何地方停留很长时间。几个月后，我可以看到莉塞特最后去了哪里，一个有两千人的小镇——不，我不会告诉你在哪里——一个她生活、工作和购买杂货的小镇，所有这些都被仔细地逐项列出，甚至还有她加油的地址，每一页都是明信片。在佩里出现之前的几个月里，我一直幻想着去那里。

After she’d left, I guess Lisette must have changed her phone number, because whenever I called, it just rang and rang. Still, I was getting her credit card statements, and for a while I watched her travel across the country: a cheap motel here, a quarter-tank of gas there, a hot dog with fries, never staying anyplace very long. After a few months, I could see where Lisette had wound up, a small town of two thousand people—​no, I won’t tell you where—​a town where she lived and worked and bought groceries, all carefully itemized, down even to the address of where she pumped her gas, every page a postcard. For months before Perry had turned up, I had nursed fantasies of going out there.

“这不是她的，”我愚蠢地说，我的大脑又厚又慢。

“It’s not hers,” I said stupidly, my brain thick and slow.

“当然是这样，”他说。“你为什么不告诉我？也许这里有什么有用的东西。” 他跪下，开始翻动信封。

“Of course it is,” he said. “Why didn’t you tell me? Maybe there’s something useful here.” He knelt and began turning envelopes over.

“停下来，”我说。“这是我的。” 佩里把它捡了起来，一大把邮件，仔细地翻阅着，然后把它塞进他的外套口袋里，无视了我。

“Stop it,” I said. “It’s mine.” Perry was picking it up, great handfuls of mail, sifting through and cramming pieces of it into his coat pockets, ignoring me.

我推了推他，他却一动不动。“停下来，”我说，恐慌加剧。我试图从他手中夺过邮件，但他轻松地将我推到一边，站了起来，微微喘着气。

I shoved him, but he didn’t move. “Stop it,” I said, panic rising. I tried grabbing the mail from his hands, but he pushed me aside easily and stood up, panting slightly.

“你到底怎么了？” 他说。

“What the hell is wrong with you?” he said.

我不知道该告诉你什么。我的血液随之涌动，滚烫，有那么一会儿，我的视线变得很滑稽，就像覆盖了一层薄薄的羊皮纸，有一会儿我什么也看不见了。“回来吧，”我喊道，但他已经离开厨房，在公寓里踱来踱去，好像在找人。

I don’t know what to tell you. My blood surged then, hot, and for a moment my vision got all funny like it was overlaid with a thin vellum, for a moment I couldn’t see. “Come back here,” I cried, but he had already left the kitchen and was pacing around the apartment, as though looking for someone.

他在我的房间里，莉塞特的房间里，大书架上仍然摆满了她的毛绒玩具，还有曾经属于她的橙色抱枕。他打开衣柜，查看床底下。我无助地站在门外，心扑通扑通地跳，尖叫道：“非法侵入！侵入！”

He was in my room, Lisette’s room, with its big bookshelf still lined with her stuffed animals, the orange throw pillow that had been hers as well. He was opening up the closets, looking under the bed. I stood outside the door helplessly, my heart pounding like it was trying to escape and screamed: “Trespass! Trespass!”

“天啊，”我听到他在里面说道。

“Jesus,” I heard him say, from inside.

当他回来的时候，他的眼神充满了怀疑和警惕。“你对她做了什么？”

When he came back, his eyes were suspicious, watchful. “What did you do with her?”

在那一刻，他在我看来更大了，好像自从我上次见到他以来他就一直在举重——也许他已经放弃寻找莉塞特，转而开始打拳击，我不知道。也许他携带武器。说不定他会攻击我，把我的尸体扔进河里，带着胜利的哈！然后跳上汽车，穿着那件漂亮的燕尾服开始越野行驶，月光在他的头发上闪闪发光。

He looked bigger to me at that moment, as though he had been pressing weights since I had seen him last—​maybe he had given up looking for Lisette and taken up boxing instead, I don’t know. Maybe he was armed. Maybe he would attack me and sling my body into a river with a victorious Ha! and jump into a car and start driving cross-country in that beautiful tuxedo of his, moonlight glistening in his hair.

我开始后退。“没什么，”我说。“我们是朋友，仅此而已。她感动。”

I began backing away. “Nothing,” I said. “We were friends, that was all. She moved.”

他向我逼近，脸色看起来很酸，甚至比我们第一次见面时还要难看。我以前怎么可能错过了这些迹象——他的相貌完全不对劲，他长着一张罪犯的脸。“那她去哪儿了？”

He was advancing on me, his face looking sour and even uglier than when we’d first met. How could I have missed the signs before—​his physiognomy was all wrong, he had a criminal’s face. “So where did she go?”

“我不知道，”我说，然后向后退了一步，腿的后部撞到了沙发上，我向后跌倒在座位上。我感觉有什么东西在挠我的脸颊，我意识到我在哭——多么不体面。“走开，”我对他尖叫，并稍微踢了踢我的腿。“离开！”

“I don’t know,” I said, and retreated so far that the backs of my legs hit the couch and I fell backward onto the seat. I felt something tickling my cheeks and realized I was crying—​how undignified. “Go away,” I screamed at him, and kicked my legs a little, for good measure. “Go away!”

佩里厌恶地看着我。“天哪，”他又说了一遍，然后大步走回厨房。当他回来时，他拎着两个装满邮件的杂货袋，当他走向门口时，他将它们稳稳地靠在胸前。当他经过沙发时，他停下来看着我。

Perry looked at me disgustedly. “Jesus,” he said again, and strode back into the kitchen. When he returned, he was carrying two grocery bags that bulged with mail, which he steadied against his chest as he headed toward the door. As he passed the couch, he paused and looked at me.

“你有问题，”他说。“你需要一些真正的帮助。” 他不断地向门口走去。再过一会儿他就会消失。

“There’s something wrong with you,” he said. “You need some real help.” He kept moving to the door; in another moment he’d be gone.

那时我心里升起了某种东西，一种愤怒、愤怒和沮丧的痛苦。我还没做出决定，就跳了起来，发现自己追上了他，用全身的力量撞到了他身上。他的手臂已经满了，动作不够快——此外，他没有看到我过来——然后他被摔倒了，他的头撞到了散热器的一角，发出一声巨响，声音比你想象的还要大，他一声闷哼倒在了地上。

Something rose up in me then, an agony of bile and anger and frustration. Without having made a decision, I sprang up and found myself running after him and knocked into him with the force of my entire body. His arms were full and he didn’t move quickly enough—​besides, he didn’t see me coming—​and he was thrown off his feet and his head hit the corner of the radiator with a thud, louder than you would believe, and he fell to the ground with a kind of grunt.

有一会儿，我躺在地板上，我也摔倒了，双腿与他的双腿纠缠在一起，惊愕而尴尬。其暴力程度令人憎恶。我不知道我发生了什么事。“对不起，”我大声说道。几分钟后，当我回过神来时，我坐了起来，关切地俯身在他身上。“对不起，”我再次说道。“我可以给你拿点喝的吗？”

For a while I lay on the floor where I had fallen as well, my legs tangled in his, aghast, embarrassed. The violence of it was abhorrent. I didn’t know what had come over me. “I’m sorry,” I said out loud. In a few minutes, when I had recovered myself, I sat up and bent over him solicitously. “I’m sorry,” I said again. “Can I get you something to drink?”

他一动不动，非常不动。我突然发现他根本没有动。“来吧，起来吧，”我说。

He was still, very still. It occurred to me that he hadn’t moved at all. “Come on, get up,” I said.

他没有动。他没有动，他没有动，他没有动。每当我回想起那个场景，我的胃就会翻腾，我的身体会痉挛，我会被内疚所折磨，我所能想到的就是对不起，对不起，对不起。

He didn’t move. He didn’t move and he didn’t move and he didn’t move. Whenever I think back to the scene my stomach curls and my body seizes up, and I am wracked with guilt and all I can think of is I’m sorry I’m sorry I’m sorry.

话又说回来，有时候我晚上躺在这里，听到水管滴水的声音，我也会生气。我想起莉赛特临走前一脸不耐烦的样子，也没有打电话过来。我想起佩里驾驶着他的汽车高速穿过阿布扎比，后面某处传来稳定的嘟嘟声。我想象着莉赛特倒在光滑的垃圾堆里后，他的邮件散落在他的身上，目录和传单，几十个信封，里面装着信件、账单和声明，透露了她新生活的动向。我很生气，我想，我们一生都在寻找某个人；为什么他要来找她？

Then again, sometimes I lie awake here at night to the sound of water dripping from the pipes and I get angry, too. I think of Lisette’s look of impatience just before she left and how she never called. I think of Perry driving his car at high speeds through Abu Dhabi, a steady beeping emanating from somewhere in the back. I picture Lisette’s mail scattered around his body after he’d fallen in a slick litter, catalogs and circulars, dozens of envelopes containing letters and bills and statements disclosing the motions of her new life. I get angry and I think, We all spend our lives looking for someone; why should he be the one to find her?

上海杂音

Shanghai Murmur

住在楼上的那个人已经死了，其他房客过了好几天才注意到，那些天里，甜甜的腐臭味越来越浓，居民们试图避开他所在的大厅，来来去去时，棕榈树遮住了鼻子。最后有人叫来了大楼的管理员，管理员叫来了失业的表弟，把门锁打开，并付给他100元钱，让他把尸体抬下三层楼梯。

The man who lived upstairs had died and it had taken the other tenants days to notice, days in which the sweetly putrid scent thickened and residents tried to avoid his part of the hall, palms tenting their noses as they came and left. At last someone sent for the building’s manager, who summoned his unemployed cousin to break the lock and paid him 100 yuan to carry the body down the three flights of stairs.

住在隔壁房间的居民争辩说他们应该降低租金，因此发生了争吵；死亡是不幸的。小雷站在那儿听着，大楼经理大声喊叫着让他们下去。她为那个死去的男人感到难过，她记得他是一个中年男人，眼睛疲惫而深陷，一直抽烟，在当地邮局工作。她猜想，如果她窒息或夜间被刺伤，同样的事情也会发生在她身上。

There was a squabble as the residents who inhabited the adjoining rooms argued that they should have their rent lowered; the death was bad luck. Xiaolei stood, listening, as the building manager shouted them down. She felt sorry for the man who had died, whom she recalled as a middle-aged man with tired, deep-set eyes, who’d chain-smoked and worked at the local post office. She supposed if she ever asphyxiated or was stabbed overnight, the same thing would happen to her.

那天晚上，她带回了一朵白菊花，摸黑上楼，打算把它放在他的房外。然而，当她小心翼翼地登上台阶时，她看到门开着。房间里没有窗户，黑暗比大厅还要浓重。没等她的眼睛适应过来。她把花扔进虚空，几乎没有呼吸，然后跑下楼梯。

That evening, she brought back a white chrysanthemum and went upstairs in the dark, intending to leave it outside his room. As she carefully mounted the steps, though, she saw the door stood open. The room was windowless, with a blackness even denser than that of the hall. She didn’t wait for her eyes to adjust. She pitched the flower into the void, barely breathing, and ran back down the stairs.

如果她经常来店里，永洁就会发现那朵花很快就不见了；她有着南方人特有的锐利的女性眼睛。但大多数时候她都不在身边。除了花店，她还经营叔叔的家禽屠宰场，这占据了她大部分时间。自从她开始工作以来，小雷可能会拿走整束花：高腰、有褶边的六出花茎、一簇簇丁香棒。不过，她认为它们单独看起来更好，所以她的窗台上摆满了单独偷来的茎，每个茎都装在自己的汽水瓶中：一朵蓬乱的玫瑰，一朵电蓝色的爱情花。

If she came to the store more often, Yongjie would have noticed in a flash the flower was gone; she had the sharp female eyes of a southerner. But most days she wasn’t around; in addition to the flower shop, she ran her uncle’s poultry slaughterhouse, which occupied most of her time. Since she’d been at the job, Xiaolei probably could have gotten away with taking whole sheaves of flowers: high-waisted, frilly-leaved stems of alstroemeria, clusters of lilac batons. She thought they looked better in isolation, though, and kept her windowsill lined with individually pilfered stems, each housed in its own soda bottle: a tousled-headed rose, a single agapanthus in electric blue.

自从她告别父母并告诉他们她在上海南部的一家微芯片工厂找到了一份工作以来，已经过去三年了。很多女孩已经离开了她们的村庄；没有人指望他们再务农了。碰巧的是，她不知道微芯片是什么，但她在广播中听到过有关微芯片的片段。她十六岁，带着青少年般残酷的自豪感告诉父母有关微芯片的事——她权威地说，这是一家日本公司，向欧洲出口——他们对此印象深刻，让她离开。直到登上火车，她一直以为他们会识破她的谎言。当他们没有这样做时，她感到失望和意外的悲伤，登上火车前往南方十四个小时的城市，在那里她不认识任何人，只有一份虚假的工作在等着她。

It had been three years since she’d said goodbye to her parents, telling them she’d gotten a job at a microchip factory down south in Shanghai. Plenty of girls had already left their village; no one expected them to farm anymore. As it happened, she didn’t know what a microchip was, but she’d heard a segment about them on the radio. She was sixteen and took a teenager’s cruel pride in telling her parents about the microchips—​a Japanese company, she’d said authoritatively, that made exports for Europe—​and they’d been impressed enough to let her go. All the way up until she boarded the train, she’d been expecting them to catch her in the lie. When they hadn’t, she felt disappointed and unexpectedly sad, boarding a train to a city fourteen hours south where she knew no one and had only a phony job waiting.

第二天早上，当她到达花店时，她的脾气很坏。她没有梳头，柜台后面镜子里的倒影让她皱起了眉头。那些日子里，争先恐后地登上公交车、在人行道上争先恐后、总是伸出手肘、半眯着眼睛、撅起嘴唇准备反击的努力，似乎已经留下了不可磨灭的印记。她还不到二十岁，却感受到岁月深深地刻在她的皮肤下，仿佛上海在她的脸颊上移植了钢板。她已经失去了青少年特有的五官，感受到了疲惫的眼神。她遇到的每个人都有一个来自家乡的人在上海取得成功的故事。不知何故，她从未真正亲眼见过这些人中的任何一个。

The next morning, when she got to the flower shop, she was in a foul temper. She had not brushed her hair, and her reflection in the mirror behind the counter made her wince. It seemed that days of fighting to board buses, hustling for space on the sidewalk, elbows always out, eyes half squinted, trying to see if someone was cheating her, lips pursed and ready to answer back, had left an indelible mark. She was not yet twenty but felt the years deep beneath her skin, as though Shanghai had grafted steel plates in her cheeks. Already she’d lost a teenager’s mobility of features, felt the exhausted cast of her eyes. Everyone she met had a story about someone from their hometown who’d made it big in Shanghai. Somehow she’d never actually met any of those people firsthand.

不过，她想，花店还是有帮助的。在装瓶厂工作时，她感觉自己变成了近乎野蛮的东西，手指僵硬，头脑麻木，胸口像个笼子。他们村里有一些猫，它们会对任何靠近它们的人发出嘶嘶声，并向它们吐口水，小蕾觉得她能理解为什么。有时，如果她想离开房间，她首先会从里面听听大厅里是否有任何噪音，等到噪音平息后再出去；另一扇门打开的声音会让她停下来。如果她发现院子里聚集着与她同龄的人——有几个女孩友好地示好——她就会转身匆匆后退，仿佛突然想起什么。这并不奇怪，她告诉自己：所有野生动物都害怕人类接触。

Still, she thought, the flower shop had helped. When working at the bottling plant, she’d felt herself turning into something nearly savage, fingers stiff, mind numb, chest a cage. There’d been cats in their village who’d hiss and spit at anyone who came near them, and Xiaolei thought she could understand why. Sometimes if she wanted to leave her room, she first found herself listening from inside for any hall noises and waiting until they subsided before exiting; the sound of another door rasping open would prompt her to pause. If she spotted people her age clustered in the courtyard—​a few girls had made friendly overtures—​she’d turn and make a hasty retreat, as if suddenly remembering something. It wasn’t surprising, she told herself: all wild animals fear human contact.

但六个月来，她剥去了玫瑰刺，卖了花束，这其中有一种礼貌，就像一个通向上海某个地方的窗口，她几乎不再希望自己能看到那里，这安抚了一些咆哮的人。在她的胸口。她把鲜花卖给办公室秘书和悲伤的寡妇，他们乘坐光滑的黑色汽车抵达，而男人则向不同的地址、他们的妻子和情妇发送相同的花束。她学会了平缓自己的语气，并用一种​​好奇的温柔来改变她的声音，这种柔和是任何地方都没有的，当然不是上海，顾客似乎很欣赏它。

But for six months now, she’d stripped rose thorns and sold bouquets, and there was a civility to it, an aperture onto a part of Shanghai that she’d almost stopped hoping she’d ever see, which soothed some of the growling in her chest. She sold flowers to office secretaries and grieving widows who arrived in sleek black cars and men who dispatched identical bouquets to separate addresses, their wives and their mistresses. She learned to flatten her tones and inflect her voice with a certain inquisitive softness that wasn’t native to any one place, certainly not Shanghai, and customers seemed to appreciate it.

这些天她的情绪一直不稳定，低沉的水流平静地涡流着，然后涌入沙子，​​抹去了路上的一切。也许有一天她会开一家自己的花店。上海各地摩天大楼拔地而起，霓虹灯招牌和锃亮的钢铁交织在一起，男人穿着西装，女人穿着高跟鞋，咔哒咔哒。她可以卖掉走廊上的盆栽植物，建立自己的生意，也许在电梯里遇见某人，找到一份办公室工作。这并非不可能。

Her moods were all over the place these days, low currents that eddied peaceably before surging up into the sand, erasing everything in their path. Maybe someday she’d open her own flower shop. There were skyscrapers rising everywhere across Shanghai, a neon tangle of signs and burnished steel, men in suits and women in high heels, click click clack. She could sell potted plants for their hallways, build up her own business, maybe meet someone in the elevator, get an office job. It wasn’t impossible.

到了午餐时，她已经不再去想死者了，精神也开始好起来。外面，阳光从人行横道的白色条子上反射出来，街道几乎闪闪发光。那天早上，她卖掉了六束雏菊，并接到了一份葬礼菊花喷洒订单。永杰会很高兴。

By lunch she had stopped thinking about the dead man and her spirits began to lift. Outside, the sunlight reflected off the white strips of the crosswalk, and the street almost glowed. She’d sold six bunches of daisies that morning and taken in an order for a funeral spray of chrysanthemums; Yongjie would be pleased.

那是星期三，所以她一整天都在为她最喜欢的顾客保存最好的花，首先卖掉那些边缘可能会变成棕色的花，那些花瓣已经开始下垂并在尖端处松散——又过了两天，他们会失败的。

It was Wednesday, so she’d been saving the best flowers all day for her favorite customer, first selling the ones with edges threatening to turn brown, those petals that had started to swoon and go loose at the tips—​another two days and they’d come undone.

然而，到了五点钟，他仍然没有到来，她感到一种令人毛骨悚然的悲伤占据了她的四肢。当她帮助其他顾客时，她时刻留意着门外他的身影。外面的光线变成了下午晚些时候的苍白灰色，偷偷地穿过人行道，甚至使对面那张刺眼的红色标志变得静音，上面写着“保健品”、“成人产品”、隔壁杂乱的电脑线和管道配件，除此之外还有脏兮兮的东西。一家小餐馆的凌乱楼层，因其主要菜单项目鸭血汤面而得名。他不在视野中。她无奈地盯着剩下的花，强忍着把它们从桶里倒到人行道上的冲动。

By five o’clock he still hadn’t arrived, though, and she felt a creeping sadness clot her limbs. As she helped other customers, she kept one eye out the door for his silhouette. The light outside was turning that pallid gray of late afternoon, stealing across the sidewalk, muting even the garish red sign across the way that blared HEALTH PRODUCTS, ADULT PRODUCTS, the jumble of computer cords and pipe fittings next door and beyond that, the dirty, slovenly floors of a small restaurant named for its chief menu item, Duck Blood Noodle Soup. He wasn’t in sight. She stared resignedly at the remaining flowers, fought the urge to tip them from their buckets onto the sidewalk.

第二天是星期五，这意味着她必须凌晨 3 点起床，试图打败所有其他花商到城对面的批发市场，然后在接下来的几个小时里把又重又湿的包裹扔回家里。店铺。这也意味着她必须在离开之前清洗已经因茎腐烂而腐臭的水桶。她想，垂死的母花的气味，它们的茎在水中柔软而糊状，与她邻居尸体的气味相比几乎不利。

The day after the next was a Friday, meaning she’d have to wake up at 3 a.m. to try and beat all the other flower vendors to the wholesale market across town, then spend the next few hours slopping heavy, wet bundles back to the store. It also meant she’d have to wash out the buckets, already rancid with rotting stems, before leaving for the night. The scent of dying stock flowers, their stems soft and mushy in the water, she thought, compared almost unfavorably to that of her neighbor’s corpse.

突然，那个男人出现在商店外面，用皱起的眼睛对她微笑。他躲进门里，好像在躲避恶劣的天气，尽管没有下雨，他向后转动肩膀，放松它们。她注意到，他剪了头发，还穿着和往常一样的白领衬衫。她想象他的衣柜里摆满了一排发光的东西。

And then, suddenly, the man was outside the store and smiling at her with his crinkled-up eyes. He ducked inside the door as if he were dodging inclement weather, though it wasn’t raining, and rolled his shoulders backward, relaxing them. He’d cut his hair, she noticed, and was wearing the same white collared shirt as always; she envisioned his closet lined with whole glowing rows of them.

当看到他时，她感觉房间再次变得清晰起来，她的脸不再冰冷。“七朵红玫瑰和三朵百合？” 她问，不敢直视他的眼睛，他点点头。“请给我漂亮的包装。” 她感到胸口一阵温暖的颤动。他身上的轻松感就像一种安慰，虽然他很少说话，但事实上，现在她已经记住了他的命令，几乎没有必要说话了。她走向盛满鲜花的水桶，现在很感激它们充满活力的样子，并将头发别到耳后。

At the sight of him, she felt the room come into focus again, her face unfreeze. “Seven red roses and three lilies?” she asked, not quite able to meet his eyes, and he nodded. “The nice wrapping, please.” She felt a warm thrum in her chest; the ease he carried with him worked on her like a balm, though he rarely said much—​indeed, now that she’d memorized his order, there was scarcely any need to speak at all. She stepped toward the buckets with their floral charges, grateful now for their perked-up appearance, and tucked her hair behind her ears.

她轻轻地从桶中取出每朵花，开始在左手上展开它们，一簇簇玫瑰花头，然后小心地将百合花穿在其中。完成后，她拿出一张粉红色的纸和一张紫色的纸巾，轻轻地把它们叠放在工作台上。她觉得自己能感觉到他的目光落在她身上，于是放慢了脚步，只是为了享受这一刻的乐趣。

Gently, she eased each flower from its bucket and started splaying them out in her left hand, a galaxy of rose heads, then carefully threaded the lilies in among them. Once finished, she slid out a sheet of pink paper and one of purple tissue and laid them tenderly atop each other on the worktable. She thought she could feel his gaze on her and moved more slowly, just for the pleasure of drawing out the moment.

然后，她用一只颤抖的手举起菜刀，砍在花茎上。她把它们放在纸的中心，并将其边缘放在一起，小心地在花束的中间系上一条橙色丝带。它们组装得不太好，比她想象的要破烂得多，她希望他看不出来。永杰做的花束非常完美，即使是在花束的顶部，你也可以在上面盖上一块布，误以为它们是底座。她处理了他们所有的大订单。

Then, with one unsteady hand, she raised the cleaver and brought it down on the flowers’ stems. She placed them at the trembling center of the paper and brought its edges together, carefully tying an orange ribbon around the bouquet’s middle. They weren’t very nicely assembled, far more ragged than she would have liked, and she hoped he couldn’t tell. Yongjie made bouquets perfectly, so even across their tops that you could drape a cloth over them and mistake them for pedestals. She handled all their big orders.

当她转头看他时，他正站在柜台前，背对着她，但似乎察觉到了她的动作，转头满怀期待地看着她。她能感觉到一些细小的思绪在涌动，她想与他分享，但当她把花递给他时，她把它们压了下来，当他接过花时，她感到一阵震动，仿佛它们是她指尖的延伸。她知道这是愚蠢的：这些花很可能是送给妻子或情妇的。

When she turned to look at him, he was standing at the counter, back to her, but as though sensing her movement, turned to look at her expectantly. She could feel little trickles of thought bubbling up that she wanted to share with him, but tamped them down as she handed him the flowers, feeling a jolt as he took them, as though they were an extension of her fingertips. It was foolish, she knew: the flowers were likely for a wife, or a mistress.

“你到底是做什么的？” 她急忙说道，试图掩饰自己的尴尬，同时又回到了柜台后面的位置。“我经常见到你，我一直很想知道。” 这是轻描淡写的说法。在她的心里，她已经为他构建了精致的生活。他是一位专门研究大脑的医生，他拉小提琴，他喜欢臭豆腐，喜欢在公园散步，还去过日本。

“What do you do, anyway?” she said hastily, trying to cover her embarrassment as she assumed her position again behind the counter. “I see so much of you, I’ve always wondered.” That was an understatement; in her mind she’d already constructed an elaborate life for him. He was a doctor specializing in the brain, he played the violin, he liked stinky tofu and walks in the park, had been to Japan.

他看着她，微笑着，衬衫干净的线条，头发的深色茅草，它们的对比让她感到疼痛。她想靠在柜台上，盯着他的每一根头发，数他下巴上的毛囊。“我是做销售的，”他说。然后，他审视着她，仿佛在重新思考自己的说法：“嗯，我是做销售的。”他纠正了自己，然后又露出了微笑。他小心翼翼地将鲜花交叉放在柜台上，然后开始寻找钱包。“来，我把我的名片给你。”

He looked at her and smiled and the clean lines of his shirt, the dark thatch of his hair, the contrast of it, made her ache. She wanted to lean over the counter and stare at each strand of hair, count the hair follicles on his chin. “I do sales,” he said. Then, examining her, as though rethinking his statement: “Well, I’m in sales,” he corrected himself, and there was that smile again. He laid the flowers carefully crosswise atop the counter and began fishing for his wallet. “Here, I’ll give you my card.”

小雷低头端详起来——​它是哑光的，摸起来很厚重。她从未听说过这家公司；她从未听说过这家公司。她不知道他们做了什么，也不会问来侮辱他。

Xiaolei looked down and studied it—​it was matte and thick to the touch. The company wasn’t one she’d ever heard of; she couldn’t tell what they did and she wouldn’t insult him by asking.

在外面，你可以通过街道上形成的一排红色尾灯来判断时间。黄昏即将来临。路的更远处是一座昂贵的住宅区，周围长满了茂密的灌木丛，周围有高高的铁栅栏。这座名为“凯旋大厦”的建筑已有六年历史，但仍然充满了新移植的困惑气氛。该社区的发展尚未满足新居民的钱包或愿望。小雷此时看向它，仿佛在寻找线索。她不说话是不是很粗鲁？她应该说话吗？

Outside you could tell the time by the ranks of red taillights forming on the street; dusk was pressing in. Farther down the road was an expensive residential compound sealed with fat shrubs and a tall iron fence around its perimeter. The building, which bore the name Triumph Mansion, was six years old but still had the bewildered air of a fresh transplant; the neighborhood had not yet developed to match the pocketbooks or aspirations of its new residents. Xiaolei looked toward it now, as if for clues. Was she being rude by not speaking? Should she speak?

他的目光不再落在她身上，他摸索着，掏空口袋，寻找钱包。沉默已经持续太久了。“这是一个不错的社区，”她最后犹豫地说。“你住在凯旋大厦吗？”

His gaze was no longer upon her as he fumbled, emptying his pockets, looking for his wallet. The silence had gone on too long. “It’s a nice neighborhood,” she said hesitatingly at last. “Do you live at Triumph Mansion?”

他又看了她一眼，这次时间更长了，眉头微微皱起。“我愿意，”他说，并递给她一些账单。“你？” 当然，这纯粹是出于礼貌。她穿着一件工作服，像她这样的工人不太可能买得起，当她摇摇头，试图想想还能说什么时，她可以看到他脸上也有同样的尴尬。“稍微远一点，”她说。他心不在焉地点点头，看了看手表。

He looked at her again, longer this time, and his brow furrowed slightly. “I do,” he said, and handed her some bills. “Do you?” This, of course, was sheer politesse; she was wearing a smock, it was unlikely a worker like her could afford it, and she could see this same embarrassed realization cross his face as she shook her head and tried to think of what else to say. “A little farther out,” she said. He nodded absently, checked his watch.

绝望在她内心涌动；两分钟内她对他的要求已经比两个月来还要多了。再过一会儿他就会消失，又会消失一周。她比平时更加​​刻意地数着他的变化，愿意他问她一个问题，任何问题。他没有。她停了下来。“好吧，保重。”她说道，声音中无法掩饰遗憾。

Desperation surged inside her; she’d already demanded more of him in two minutes than she had in two months. In another moment he’d be gone, would disappear for another week. She counted out his change more deliberately than usual, willing him to ask her a question, any question. He didn’t. She paused. “Well, take care,” she said, unable to keep the regret from her voice.

他微笑着拿起那束花，吸了一口气。“谢谢你，”他说，“再见。”

He smiled and picked up the bundle of flowers and inhaled. “Thank you,” he said, and “See you.”

他走后，她开始用一块报纸扫掉桌子上的绿色残渣，脸颊通红，对自己很生气。他肯定觉得她问这样的问题很奇怪。或许他根本就不会回来了。询问凯旋大厦的事对他来说肯定是那么咄咄逼人，而且很奇怪。她很贪心，应该把这个问题再留一个星期，把她想知道的所有事情都搁置起来，但这需要几个月、几年的时间，而且她不想在这份工作上待那么久。

After he left, she started sweeping the green scraps off the table with a wedge of newspaper, flushed around the cheeks, angry with herself. He’d thought her odd, surely, to be asking such questions. Maybe he wouldn’t even come back. Asking about Triumph Mansion must have sounded to him so aggressive and strange; she’d been greedy, should have left that question for another week, spaced out all the things she wanted to know, but then that would take months, years, and she didn’t want to be at this job that long.

后来，在帮助另一位顾客时，她注意到柜台上留下了一支钢笔。它是黑色的，腰部粗壮，中间有一条窄银带，还有一个配套的银夹，上面有一条锯齿状的白线，描绘了一座山。她打开盖子，在收据背面画了一大笔——墨水又黑又浓，在她的触摸下像一条细细的、受控的河流一样流动。这一定是他的，她不由自主地想，然后把它放进口袋里，它以惊人的重量落在了口袋里。

Later on, while helping another customer, she noticed a pen that had been left on the counter. It was black and thick-waisted with a narrow band of silver around its middle and a matching silver clip, a jagged white line on it depicting a mountain. She uncapped it and drew a long stroke against the back of a receipt—​its ink was black and dense and flowed under her touch like a thin, controlled river. It must have been his, she thought to herself automatically, and dropped it into her pocket, where it landed with surprising weight.

在最后两位顾客之间的另一个小时（没有购买），她用最后可抢救的鲜花填满了花束；这样他们第二天可能会卖得更快。当外面的汽车越来越少时，她将漂白剂和水混合在一起，跪在人行道上擦洗水桶，这时她看到一名女子从她身边大步走进商店。过了一会儿，小蕾也跟着她，拍干她罩衫上的手。

For another hour between the last two customers (no purchases), she filled out bouquets with the last salvageable flowers; they might sell more quickly that way the next day. As the cars thinned outside, she mixed bleach and water and was on her knees scrubbing out buckets on the sidewalk when she saw a woman stride past her into the store. After a moment, Xiaolei followed her, patting her hands dry on her smock.

她的第一印象是：头上戴着镶满水晶铰链的大墨镜，下面是一张没有化妆的脸，完美无瑕，让小雷忍不住盯着看，试图找出任何瑕疵。她穿着一条舒适的运动裤，手上挂着一个粉色的钱包，钱包上挂着一条金色的链子。一个即将成为新娘的人，她想，尽管令人惊讶的是她独自一人来，而且这么晚。也许是一位妻子询问鲜花还被送到了哪里；这种事以前发生过一次。

Her first impression: big sunglasses with crystal-studded hinges resting on her head, and below that a makeup-free face, so flawless that Xiaolei couldn’t stop staring, trying to seek out any imperfection. She had on a pair of snug sweatpants and a pink purse that swung from a strap of golden chains. A soon-to-be bride, she thought, though surprising that she’d come alone and so late. A wife asking where else flowers had been sent, perhaps; it had happened once before.

“我丈夫把他的钢笔忘在这里了，”女人看到她后说道。“你有看到它吗？”

“My husband left his pen here,” the woman said, upon seeing her. “Have you seen it?”

一阵混乱的情绪如行云流水般从小雷的脸上掠过。她不知道自己心目中那个男人的妻子是什么样子，不知何故不是这样，但她在心里向这个女人致敬；她很漂亮，这是他应得的，不过坦白说（小雷心里想）她的脸上有一些令人不快的东西。她看起来就像是那种会给宠物喂昂贵的狗粮并克扣仆人工资的女人。

A confusion of emotions flitted across Xiaolei’s face like quick-moving clouds. She didn’t know what she’d expected the man’s wife to look like, somehow not like this, but mentally she paid the woman tribute; she was beautiful, what he deserved, though frankly (Xiaolei thought to herself) there was something off-putting in her face. She looked like the sort of woman who would feed a pet expensive dog food and dock her servants’ pay.

过了一会儿，小雷才发现沉默已经持续太久了。“我们有一些钢笔，”她慢慢地说，穿着工作服感觉沉重而不成形。她走到钱箱前，拿出一把圆珠笔，很有礼貌地放在柜台上。

An interval passed before Xiaolei realized the silence had gone on too long. “We have some pens,” she said slowly, feeling heavy and shapeless in her smock. She went to the cash drawer and brought out a handful of ballpoint pens and laid them on the counter with ceremony.

女人摇摇头，一脸沮丧。“不，我说的是一支好钢笔，”她说。“黑，厚。”她说，然后给这个品牌起了个名字，小雷从来没有听说过。“你一定已经看到了。”

The woman shook her head, frustrated. “No, I’m talking about a nice pen,” she said. “Black, thick,” she said, and then she named the brand, which Xiaolei had never heard of. “You must have seen it.”

她抬起眼睛，对着小雷的眼睛，握住了它们。就像是被眼镜蛇的目光所困，过了一会儿，为了结束这一切，小蕾不情愿地从口袋里抽出了笔。

She raised her eyes to Xiaolei’s and held them. It was like being trapped in a cobra’s gaze: after a minute, just to put an end to it, Xiaolei drew the pen unwillingly from her pocket.

女人的脸在宽慰和烦恼之间挣扎，因为她花了这么长时间。救济获胜了。“是的，就是这个，”她说，伸手去拿笔。“谢谢。这很值钱。”

The woman’s face struggled between relief and annoyance that it had taken her so long. Relief won out. “Yes, that’s the one,” she said, and reached to take the pen. “Thank you. It’s worth a lot.”

小蕾惊慌失措，失去理智，却又强烈，她同样迅速地把笔抽了回来。她表现出了她最好的官员的声音，混合着无聊和愚蠢。“对不起。我不能让你拿走。我只能把它还给笔的主人。”

Panic seized Xiaolei, irrational and strong, and she pulled the pen back, just as quickly. She put on her best functionary’s voice, a mixture of boredom and witlessness. “I’m sorry. I can’t let you take it. I can only give it back to the pen’s owner.”

“我是他的妻子，”女人说道，脸上满是怀疑。

“I’m his wife,” the woman said, face now suspicious.

“你有身份证吗？” 小雷说道。

“Do you have ID?” Xiaolei said.

“那支笔有身份证吗？” 女人说道。“这算什么问题？”

“Does that pen have ID?” the woman said. “What kind of question is that?”

小雷耸耸肩。

Xiaolei shrugged.

“你看，那是一支很贵的钢笔，是他老板送的礼物。你不会想让他陷入麻烦吧？” 女人说道。“如果我没有带回来，他会不高兴，我也会不高兴。”

“Look, it was an expensive pen, a gift from his boss. You wouldn’t want to get him into trouble, would you?” the woman said. “If I come back without it, he’ll be unhappy, and I’ll be unhappy.”

小雷浑身僵硬。然后女人又笑了，充满自信的表情，就这么定了。她不会给那个女人这支笔，确实不会。对于昂贵的丢失钢笔，没有任何协议，但如果有的话，小蕾确信她是对的；当然，人们应该只将丢失的物品归还给失主。她特意在柜台后面的凳子上坐下，仿佛要巩固自己的位置。

Xiaolei stiffened. Then the woman smiled again, such a confident look, and that sealed it. She would not give the woman this pen, no indeed. There was no protocol for expensive lost pens, but if there was, Xiaolei was certain she was in the right; surely one should only return the lost item to its owner. She sat down deliberately at her stool behind the counter, as though to cement her position.

女人盯着她。“你聋了吗？把笔给我！”

The woman stared at her. “Are you deaf? Give me the pen!”

外面有一对夫妇经过，是一对上了年纪的退休人员，迈着老年夫妇那样缓慢、弯腰的步伐。她一眼就认出了他们。那个男人常常早上在商店旁边的笼子里遛一只鸣禽，直到有一天他独自一人，她想知道这只鸟怎么样了。听到女人提高的声音，他们停下来，疑惑地看着这一幕。

A couple was passing by outside, an elderly pair of retirees walking in that slow, stooped way of older couples. She knew them by sight; the man used to walk a songbird in a cage by the shop in the mornings until one day he was alone, and she wondered what had become of the bird. On hearing the woman’s raised voice, they stopped and looked quizzically at the scene.

那女人假装要走到柜台后面。“把它给我！”

The woman made as though to go behind the counter. “Give it to me!”

“不行，你得站在柜台前！” 小雷的反应能力在城市生活多年后得到了磨练。她的右腿猛地飞出，迅速挡住了她。

“No, and you need to stay in front of the counter!” Xiaolei’s reflexes were honed after years of living in the city; her right leg shot out and quickly blocked her.

“贼！贼！” 女人喊道。“我这就去报警！”

“Thief! Thief!” the woman shouted. “I’ll report you to the police!”

小雷现在怒火中烧，她拥有继续战斗一整天所需的东西。“前进！我不会违反协议的！我们有规则。”她自豪地说。

Xiaolei was full of indignant fire now; she had what she needed to keep fighting all day. “Go ahead! I’m not going to violate protocol! We have rules,” she said proudly.

看到退休人员在门口犹豫，小雷赶紧招呼了他们。“她希望我把它给她，但我不能——有政策。” 老妇人一脸疑惑，但听了小蕾的解释后，男子转头对着里面的女人轻声说道。“这些政策是为了保护你自己，”他说。“谁愿意自己丢失的东西就这样被人轻易送人呢？告诉你丈夫，让你丈夫自己去商店拿。”

Seeing the retirees hesitating at the doorway, Xiaolei quickly recruited them. “She wants me to just give it to her, but I can’t—​there are policies.” The elderly woman seemed confused, but after hearing Xiaolei’s explanation the man turned to the woman inside and spoke gently. “These policies are for your own protection,” he said. “Who would want their lost things to be given away so casually? Tell your husband, tell your husband to come back to the store and get it himself.”

听到这里，女人转过身来，吐口水在地板上。“你会后悔的。”她对小雷说道，然后就走了出去。

At this the woman turned tail and spit on the floor. “You’ll be sorry,” she said to Xiaolei, and walked out.

多年以后，夜里躺在床上，小雷睡不着觉，有时她会想到她本可以采取不同的做法。她本可以把笔交还给那个女人，在接下来的一周见到她的丈夫，假装什么都没发生，继续向他卖花几周甚至几个月，大量的玫瑰，永恒的百合花。她本可以保留这支钢笔，并在下周或第二天将其归还给丈夫；但事实并非如此。如果确实有必要的话，他可能会亲自回来。她本可以把它放在口袋里，永远不再回到商店，也许把钢笔当掉了。用这笔钱开始了自己的事业。

Years later, lying awake in bed at night, Xiaolei sometimes thought of all the things she could have done differently. She could have handed back the pen, submitted to the woman, seen her husband the week following and pretended nothing had happened, continued to sell him flowers for weeks and months, an avalanche of roses, an eternity of lilies. She could have held on to the pen and returned it to the husband the following week, or the following day; probably he would have come back in person if it had been truly necessary. She could have kept it in her pocket and never returned to the store, perhaps pawned the pen. Used the money to start her own business.

结果女子走后，小雷就匆匆关门了；她不想冒着被警察带回来的风险。她拿着笔，塞在钱包里，坐了两趟公交车到了夜市，在下班的工人中间坐在凳子上，吃了一碗特别好吃的酸菜汤面，然后走回来。朝着她租住的房间的方向走去。

Instead, after the woman left, Xiaolei closed up the shop in a hurry; she didn’t want to risk her returning with the police. She took the pen with her, tucked inside her purse, and rode two buses to a night market, where she sat on a stool amid other workers finished with their shifts and ate a bowl of especially good noodle soup with pickled vegetables, then walked back in the direction of her rented room.

那天晚上她睡得很不好，梦见了死去的男人。在她的梦里，他们在黑暗中乘坐同一辆公交车，上海灯火通明的建筑在眼前模糊地闪过。他坐在她身后一排，身子前倾，他的声音在她耳边平稳而急迫地低语，听起来并不难听。他手里拿着一束雏菊，花瓣让她的脖子发痒。随后，场景发生了变化，他们在舞池上一起旋转，舞池被一个巨大的五彩网格照亮。

That night she slept poorly, dreaming of the man who had died above her. In her dream, they were riding the same bus in the dark, the brightly lit buildings of Shanghai flashing by in a blur. He was seated a row behind her and leaning forward, his voice a steady, urgent murmur in her ear, the sound of it not unpleasant. He held a bundle of daisies, with petals that tickled her neck. Afterward, the scene shifted, and they were whirling together on a dance floor lit up in an enormous, multicolored grid.

第二天是小雷休息日。通常她会躺在床上读廉价小说，或者偶尔去外滩，那里有一个小时的车程，也是她知道的为数不多的目的地之一。她喜欢凝视水面上珍珠塔闪闪发光的粉红色球体，以及照亮天际线的彩色光束。有时她会在那里坐上几个小时，时间长得足以看到摩天大楼的灯光在午夜前闪烁。来上海的第一年，她经常去那里，直到她无意中听到一位衣着漂亮的女士告诉朋友，那里是所有“乡巴佬都去看的地方”。此后，她就不再那么常去了。

The next day was Xiaolei’s day off. Usually she might lie in bed reading dime novels, or occasionally she’d go to the Bund, an hour’s bus ride away and one of the few destinations she knew. She liked to gaze across the water at the gleaming pink orbs of the Pearl Tower, and the colored jets of light that illuminated the skyline. Sometimes she sat there for hours, long enough to see the skyscraper lights wink off, just before midnight. Her first year in Shanghai she went frequently, until she overheard a beautifully clad woman telling a friend it was where all the “country bumpkins went to stare.” After that, she didn’t go so often.

小蕾在床上躺了一会儿，想再睡一会，最后才起身，心神不宁。她穿上一件白色连帽运动衫，镶有金色镶边，上面写着“SUPERSTAR”，但她很少穿，因为担心弄脏它。她还戴着一顶相配的棒球帽和一条她最好看的牛仔裤。她在床底下发现了一管鲜红色的口红，这是她搬到这座城市后不久买的。她只戴过一次就擦掉了，对自己外表的变化感到羞愧和惊讶。今天她小心地将它涂抹在嘴唇上。她背起钱包，轻声哼着歌，朝公交车走去。

Xiaolei remained in bed awhile, trying to go back to sleep, until at last she rose, feeling restless. She put on a white hooded sweatshirt edged in gold trim that read SUPERSTAR, which she seldom wore for fear of getting it dirty. She donned a matching baseball cap as well, and her nicest pair of jeans. Under her bed she located a tube of bright-red lipstick, which she’d bought shortly after moving to the city. She’d worn it only once before wiping it off, ashamed and startled at the change in her appearance. Today she carefully smeared it across her lips. She shouldered her purse and walked toward the bus, humming softly.

当她刚到上海时，装瓶厂的女孩们说，赚钱的方法有两种：要么致富，要么结婚。但她在这里，仍然在为微薄的收入工作，唯一对她出言不逊的男人是她在工厂的老板，他已婚，年龄是她的三倍。她在那里工作两年后的一天，他打电话给她，给她那周的工资。当她俯身在他的桌子上签署收据时，他靠在她身上，挤压她的胸部，仿佛在测试市场上水果的硬度。“你喜欢吗？” 他说道，热气喷在她耳边。不久之后，小雷就挣脱了，退出了，但偶尔也会想，如果她没有拒绝他，生活是否会更好。

When she’d first arrived in Shanghai, the girls at the bottling plant said there were two ways to make it: get rich or get married. But here she was, still working for a pittance, and the only man to make a pass at her had been her boss at the plant, who was married and three times her age. One day after she’d been there two years, he’d called her in to give her that week’s pay. As she bent over his desk to sign the receipt, he leaned against her and squeezed her chest, as though testing the firmness of fruit at a market. “Do you like this?” he’d said, breath hot against her ear. Xiaolei had wrenched herself away and quit not long after, but occasionally found herself wondering whether life would have been better if she hadn’t refused him.

她在凯旋大厦不远的地方下了车。当她走近茂密的灌木丛时，她走得更慢了，心脏狂跳。它的黑色大门锁着，但她徘徊着，直到看到另一位居民离开，她才迅速溜了进去。这比她想象的要容易。

She got off the bus not far from Triumph Mansion. As she approached its thick shrubs, she walked more slowly, heart jumping. Its big black gate was locked, but she loitered until she saw another resident leaving, and quickly slipped inside. It was easier than she’d imagined.

里面是一片绿洲，灌木丛被剪成球体，大理石大厅里有一尊手持三叉戟的天使金色雕像。空气中弥漫着香气，头顶上的某个地方正在奏响一段极弱的旋律。一个昏昏欲睡的保安坐在前台，看到小雷，他的头猛地抬起来。

Inside it was an oasis, with shrubs clipped into spheres and a marble lobby that contained a golden statue of a trident-bearing angel. The air was perfumed, and from somewhere overhead, a melody was playing, pianissimo. A somnolent guard sat at a front desk, but his head snapped up on seeing Xiaolei.

“登录，”他咕哝道。

“Sign in,” he grunted.

“我只是在等一个朋友。”小蕾说着，一只手漫不经心地梳理着头发，这个动作是从男人的妻子那里借来的。侍卫狠狠地看了她一眼，却没有说话。

“I’m just waiting for a friend,” Xiaolei said, and ran one hand carelessly through her hair, a gesture borrowed from the man’s wife. The guard looked at her hard but didn’t say anything.

大厅的一侧有一面大镜子，对面有一张白色的皮凳，小雷感激地坐了进去。她拿出笔，看了一会儿，然后下意识地将它放回包里。该男子会感谢她归还这件珍贵的物品。他会给她提供用薄如纸的薄饼制成的饼干，用紧密的卷轴烘烤，并用易碎的玻璃器皿盛茶。回到村里，当她还不到十几岁的时候，她看过一部很受欢迎的电视节目，讲述了两个女人住在大城市公寓里的生活，公寓里的软垫完全是白色的——白色真皮沙发、白色簇绒地毯、白色百合花——她也想象着他的公寓。他们会并排坐在沙发上。他会像装瓶厂的老板一样压着她，只是这一次，她不会反抗。

There was a big mirror on one side of the lobby, and a white leather bench opposite, which Xiaolei sank gratefully into. She took out the pen and gazed at it briefly before slipping it self-­consciously back in her bag. The man would thank her for returning the precious item. He would offer her cookies made from paper-thin crepes baked in tight scrolls, and tea served in fragile glassware. Back in the village, when she was not yet a teenager, she had watched a popular television show that depicted the lives of two women living in a big-city apartment upholstered entirely in white—​white leather couch, white tufted rug, white lilies—​and she pictured his apartment like that, too. They would sit beside each other on the couch. He would press against her like her boss from the bottling plant, only this time, she would not resist.

几个小时过去了。空气凉爽，空气清新，带着一种独特的安静。几个西装革履的男人和保姆带着穿着漂亮的孩子来了又走。保安离开了，另一个保安接替了他的位置。小蕾时不时地假装在打电话，但大多数时候她只是坐着看这一幕。她在那里感到非常满足，距离她长大的那个尘土飞扬的村庄有一千英里，舒适得好像她属于这里一样。她喜欢观察居民们的脸，他们那么聪明、那么优雅，无疑充满了比只是要下雨更聪明的话；我猜也是; 你吃了吗; 是的，今天很热。

Hours passed. The air was cool and conditioned, and carried its own kind of quiet hush. A few men in suits and nannies with their beautifully dressed charges came and went. The security guard left and another took his place. Every now and then, Xiaolei pretended to be on the phone, but mostly she just sat and watched the scene. She felt perfectly content there, a thousand miles from the dusty village where she’d been raised, as comfortable as if she belonged. She liked observing the residents’ faces, so intelligent and refined, no doubt full of more clever things to say than just going to rain; guess so; have you eaten yet; yes, hot out today.

她回想起祖父去世前一年的八十岁生日庆祝活动。一大群村民聚集在一起吃烤鸡，在一连串的祝酒之后，他告诉他们他很高兴自己一生都生活在他们中间。他的意思是自豪的，事实上他从未离开过，但这个想法让十几岁的小蕾充满了恐惧，她发誓要离开。

She thought back to her grandfather’s eightieth birthday celebration, the year before he died. A big crowd of villagers had assembled for roast fowl, and after a long string of toasts, he’d told them how glad he was that he’d lived all his life among them. He meant it with pride, the fact that he’d never left, but the thought had filled a teenage Xiaolei with horror, and she’d vowed to get away.

电梯的叮当声打断了她的遐想。当她抬头时，她最喜欢的顾客正消失在电梯里，公文包整齐地夹在一只胳膊下。她起身跟上，试图装出一副随意的样子，但电梯门已经关上了。头顶上的金色编号面板显示他在四楼下车。前面，警卫正忙着与另一位居民聊天。转眼间，她就快步上楼梯去追赶。

A ding from the elevator interrupted her reverie. When she looked up, her favorite customer was disappearing into the elevator, briefcase tucked neatly under one arm. She rose to follow, trying to look casual, but the elevator doors had already slid shut. The gold numbered panel overhead showed him getting off at the fourth floor. Up front, the guard was busy chatting with another resident. In a flash she was hurrying up the stairs in pursuit.

当他到达走廊尽头的一间公寓时，她就到了，并关上了身后的门。这里的地板铺着深蓝色的地毯，上面有人造水晶灯。她慢慢地走着。非常安静。电梯旁有一面镜子，她仔细端详自己的脸。她摘下棒球帽，润湿嘴唇，抚平头发。你已经走到这一步了，她告诉自己。别害怕。

She arrived just as he’d reached an apartment at the end of the hall and shut the door behind him. The floors here were carpeted in dark blue, with faux crystal lamps above. She walked slowly. It was very quiet. There was a mirror by the elevator, and she inspected her face carefully. She removed the baseball cap and wet her lips and smoothed her hair. You’ve come this far, she told herself. Don’t be afraid.

几分钟后，她敲了敲他的门，但没有回应。过了好一会儿，她又敲了敲门，这次更大声了，听到了脚步声。当门打开时，他穿着背心和短裤站在那儿，好像刚刚换衣服一样。“是的？” 他不耐烦地说。“你是谁？”

A few minutes later she was knocking at his door, but there was no answer. After a long while she knocked again, more loudly this time, and heard footsteps. When the door opened, he was standing there in an undershirt and shorts, as though he’d just been changing. “Yes?” he said impatiently. “Who are you?”

小雷惊讶中努力寻找自己的声音。“我是-”

Xiaolei tried to find her voice amid her surprise. “I’m—”

“你想要什么？” 他说。他的眼中没有闪现出认出的光芒。

“What do you want?” he said. No flicker of recognition registered in his eyes.

小雷听到公寓深处传来女人的声音。“我不知道，”他回头喊道。他又看向小雷，这次更加疑惑了。“我们不感兴趣。”

Xiaolei heard a woman’s voice from somewhere deeper in the apartment. “I don’t know,” he called over his shoulder. He looked at Xiaolei again, more quizzically this time. “We’re not interested.”

在里面，她可以看到一张抛光的桃花心木咖啡桌和一个建在墙上的微型喷泉，喷泉在抛光的黑色球体上冒着气泡。看到小雷，一只蜷缩在沙发上的白色贵宾犬站了起来，狂吠起来。男人似乎还没有认出她。

Inside, she could see a polished mahogany coffee table and a miniature fountain built into one wall that bubbled over a polished black orb. At the sight of Xiaolei, a white poodle curled on the couch stood and barked. The man still didn’t appear to recognize her.

“我很抱歉，”她说，失望如巨浪般袭来。她开始后退。

“I’m sorry,” she said, disappointment crashing over her in heavy waves. She began backing away.

男人奇怪地看着她。“没关系，”他说，然后咔哒一声关上了门。

The man eyed her strangely. “That’s okay,” he said, and shut the door with a click.

小蕾不知怎么地出了公寓楼，脸颊火辣辣的，左顾右盼，匆匆下了楼。外面的凉爽空气让人心旷神怡。她满头大汗，这才想起来把白色的运动衫脱掉，免得弄脏。她走了真是太愚蠢了。她对他抱有任何期望，认为像她这样的人可能会给他留下任何印象，这是愚蠢的。她用力掐自己作为惩罚，手臂上留下难看的红痕。她坐上公交车，迷迷糊糊地走回家；回来后，她立即爬到被窝里，躺在那里，肚子里有个坑，胸口羞愧难当，直到睡着了。

Somehow, Xiaolei found her way out of the apartment building, cheeks burning, looking neither left nor right as she hurried down the stairs. Outside, the cool air was a relief. She was sweating profusely, and remembered just in time to strip off her white sweatshirt to keep it from getting stained. It was foolish of her to have gone. It was foolish of her to expect anything of him, to think someone like her might have made an impression on him in any way. She pinched herself hard as punishment, leaving ugly red marks on her arm. She rode the bus and walked home in a daze; once back, she crawled immediately under the covers and lay there, a pit in her stomach and shame in her chest, until she fell asleep.

直到第二天，在黎明时分，在水滑的街道上艰难地走过批发市场四个小时后，回到店里，发现永洁一脸不祥地等在那里，她才向自己的内心深处看去。钱包，发现笔不见了。她不知道它是被偷了还是溜了出去。无论如何，这都没有关系。妻子前一天一早就找到了她的老板。第二天，当小雷满怀鲜花回到店里时，永杰已经下定决心了；她被解雇了。除此之外，还有很多其他年轻女孩可以胜任这项工作，而且可能做得更好。

It was only the next day, after four hours’ trundling through the wholesale market in streets slicked with water and dawn half-light, after arriving back at the store to find Yongjie waiting there with an ominous expression, that she’d looked inside her purse and realized the pen was gone. She didn’t know if it had been stolen or perhaps slipped out. Anyway, it didn’t matter. The wife had found her boss early the previous morning. By the time Xiaolei returned to the shop the following day, arms sopping with bundles of flowers, Yongjie had made up her mind; she was fired. There were plenty of other young girls who could do the job, and probably better, besides.

当小雷听到女子声称这支钢笔值多少钱时，她大吃一惊；这几乎是她月薪的二十倍。

When Xiaolei heard the amount of money the woman claimed the pen was worth, it astounded her; it was nearly twenty times her monthly salary.

“她一定是在撒谎。”她绝望地说。“什么笔这么贵？”

“She must be lying,” she said desperately. “What pen costs that much?”

永洁也没有听说过有这样的笔，小蕾几乎可以肯定，但她却装出一种瞬间的了解感，像盾牌一样落了下来。她说，这是一个著名的欧洲品牌。

Yongjie hadn’t heard of such a pen before, either, Xiaolei was nearly sure of it, but she affected an instant sense of knowingness that came down like a shield. It was a famous European brand, she said.

“嗯，那很可能是假的。”小雷说，只是短暂地感到不忠。“谁随身带着这样一支笔？”

“Well, then it was probably fake,” Xiaolei said, feeling only briefly disloyal. “Who carries a pen like that around?”

永洁没有反对，但她也拒绝支付拖欠小雷两周的工资。“你给我带来了那么多麻烦——算你自己幸运吧，情况并没有更糟，”她说。“消息会传开。凯旋大厦是我们的主要客户，现在没人愿意来这里了。”

Yongjie didn’t disagree, but she also refused to pay any of the two weeks’ back wages Xiaolei was owed. “You’ve caused me that much trouble—​count yourself lucky it isn’t worse,” she said. “Word will get around. Triumph Mansion is our key clientele, and now no one will want to come here.”

小雷懒得辩解，永杰说的或许有道理。至少，她失去了他们每周最稳定的顾客之一。“我确实把它弄丢了，”她说，指的是那支笔，但她的老板不为所动。

Xiaolei didn’t bother to argue; Yongjie probably had a point. At the very least, she’d lost them one of their steadiest weekly customers. “I really did lose it,” she said, meaning the pen, but her boss wasn’t moved.

“你知道这没有什么区别，”永杰说。她把白色的菊花戳进绿色的泡沫里，仿佛小雷已经消失了。

“You know it doesn’t make a difference,” Yongjie said. She was poking white chrysanthemums into a stand of green foam, as if Xiaolei had already disappeared.

在接下来的几个月里，当小蕾寻找另一份工作时，她发现自己在城里的小文具店里寻找类似的东西，想知道是否可能存在如此昂贵的钢笔，如果存在，在哪里可以找到它。她看到了细杆圆珠笔，还有一些带有奇怪的粉色和绿色墨水；现在各种各样的进口产品都从韩国运来，透明的、凝胶头的和可伸缩的。她会把它们握在手里，评估它们，权衡它们的价值。

In the months to come, as she looked for another job, Xiaolei found herself stopping into the city’s small stationery stores seeking out its likeness, wondering if such an expensive pen could possibly exist, and if so, where to find it. She saw thin-stemmed ballpoints and some with outlandish pink and green inks; all kinds of imports were coming in now from South Korea, transparent ones and gel-tips and retractables. She’d hold them in her hands, evaluating them, weighing their worth.

她唯一的遗憾是，她没有花更多的时间和那个男人的笔在一起，把它抱在怀里，打开它，亲自测试一下，结果她没能保留它。当然，她也原路返回，甚至询问了批发市场的一些商贩，又回去查看了凯旋大厦的周边，但什么也没发现。

Her only regret was that she hadn’t spent more time with the man’s pen, cradling it, uncapping it, testing it out for herself, and that she hadn’t been able to keep it. She’d gone back to retrace her steps, of course, even interrogated some vendors at the wholesale market, gone back to check the perimeter of Triumph Mansion, but found nothing.

即使她找到了另一份工作，这次是挨家挨户推销洗发水和护发素，那支钢笔仍然困扰着她。那时她已经买了一辆自行车，会骑着它在城市里来回穿梭，偶尔会在不同季节的文具店跳下来检查他们的架子。这是一个良性的追求，让她对这座可能会让她疲惫不堪的城市有一定的控制力。

Even when she got another job, this time selling shampoo and conditioner door-to-door, the pen still haunted her. She’d bought a bicycle by then and would ride it up and down the length of the city, leaping off occasionally at stationery stores to check their racks in different seasons. It was a benign quest that gave her some control over a city that otherwise threatened to wear her down.

有一次，在药剂师那里，她看到一位女士正在用一支粗大的黑色钢笔填写一张收据。它的形状很熟悉，她的心跳停止了。“我可以试试吗？”

Once, at a pharmacist’s, she saw a woman filling out a receipt with a fat black pen. Its shape was familiar, and her heart stopped. “May I try?”

店员皱着眉头，小雷却不好意思地坚持，最后她耸耸肩，把笔和一张药盒里面的灰色薄纸板给了她试戴。拿在手里比小雷记忆中的要轻一些，没有银夹，也没有高山蚀刻。但它还是以同样的方式握在她手里，而且也有那种光滑的光泽。“多少？” 她问那个女人。

The clerk knitted her brows, but Xiaolei was sheepish and insistent, and at last she shrugged and gave her the pen and a piece of thin gray cardboard, the inside of a pillbox, to try it on. It was lighter in the hand than Xiaolei had remembered, and had no silver clip, no alpine etching. But it sat in her hand the same way, and it, too, had that glossy sheen. “How much?” she’d asked the woman.

店员皱起了眉头。“不卖，”她说。

The clerk frowned. “Not for sale,” she said.

“拜托了。”小雷说道。她开始用它写作。她发现这不是一支钢笔；而是一支钢笔。里面是一支刺耳的圆珠笔，在纸板表面滑动，只留下一缕印记。

“Please,” Xiaolei said. She started writing with it. It wasn’t a fountain pen, she discovered; inside was a raspy ballpoint that skidded over the cardboard’s surface, leaving only a wisp of an imprint behind.

“在笔记本上效果更好，”店员说，这确实是事实。小雷可以看到她刚刚写下的收据，是用清晰的黑色字体写成的。店员好奇地看了她一眼，然后和蔼地把便签本推了过去。“你可以试试。”

“It works better on the pad,” the clerk said, and that was true. Xiaolei could see the receipt she’d just written out in a clear black hand. The clerk looked at her curiously, and then pushed the pad forward kindly. “You can try.”

但小蕾已经消失在门外，摇着头。“谢谢。”她在身后喊道。“这不是我要找的。”

But Xiaolei had already disappeared out the door, shaking her head. “Thanks,” she called out behind her. “It’s not what I’m looking for.”

大数字之地

Land of Big Numbers

这是李学士发给他的一段对话截图，承诺财富和救赎。 山东丰源卫生有限公司。报道称，他们将赢得一份建造六所军队医院的政府合同。机会来之不易。两人聊天的头像仍然清晰可见——一个日本动漫人物，一只卡通兔子——但他们的名字已经被涂黑了。

It was a screenshot of a conversation sent to him by Li Xueshi, one that promised riches and redemption. Shandong Abundant Sanitation Ltd. They’re going to win a government contract to build six military hospitals, it read. Hard-to-come-by opportunity. The avatars of the two chatting were still visible—​a Japanese anime character, a cartoon rabbit—​but their names had been blacked out.

朱枫感觉自己的脉搏在跳动，周围的小锥体和手机似乎都在微微闪烁。他是谁？他给李发消息。他从四岁起就认识李，他们住在同一栋破旧的公寓楼里。他们几乎就像兄弟一样。

Zhu Feng felt his pulse race, as though the little cone of privacy around him and his phone shimmered slightly. Who is this guy? he messaged Li. He’d known Li since he was four and they’d lived in the same crummy apartment building; they were almost like brothers.

不知道。看到它出现在朋友的时间线上。不错的提示。

Don’t know. Saw it appear in a friend’s timeline. Not a bad tip.

朱枫皱起眉头，重新调整了一下枕头，仰面躺着。透过房间的纸板薄墙，他能听到母亲在厨房里切菜的声音，以及父亲电视节目中预先录制的笑声。当然，如果你有钱的话，”他写道。

Zhu Feng winced and readjusted his pillow, sprawling on his back. Through his room’s cardboard-thin walls, he could hear the sound of his mother chopping in the kitchen and the canned laughter from one of his father’s television programs. Sure, if you have money, he wrote.

“问问你的父母吧，”李回答道。最好动作快点，不然你也会错过这个。

Ask your parents, Li replied. Better move fast, or you’ll miss this one, too.

天哪，李真是个幸运的混蛋。他们在同一栋肮脏的高层建筑中长大，那里有肮脏的混凝土走廊和破损的电梯，但十年前，李的父亲换了工作，进入了房地产行业。他把一家人搬到了城对面的一处住宅区，现在开着一辆时尚的黑色奔驰载着他们到处走走。李获得了“游戏币”津贴，这些天不断谈论新的投资、期货、期权——这些不可能的词在朱峰看来就像是异国情调的自由形式。他的父亲已经答应李和他的女朋友结婚后会给他们买一套公寓。

God, Li was a lucky bastard. They’d grown up in the same dingy high-rise, with its dirty concrete corridors and busted elevator, but a decade ago Li’s father had changed jobs and gone into real estate. He’d moved the family to a complex across town and now ferried them around in a sleek black Mercedes. Li got a “play money” allowance and these days talked constantly of new investments, futures, options—​impossible words that sounded to Zhu Feng like exotic forms of freedom. Already his father had promised to buy Li and his girlfriend an apartment whenever they got married.

还有朱峰，他每天早上仍然在童年的卧室里醒来。曾经新鲜的窗帘被弄脏了，床单因潮湿而潮湿。哪个女孩愿意嫁给他，因为他拿工资开玩笑，没有车，没有自己的住处？

And then there was Zhu Feng, who still woke every morning in his childhood bedroom. The once-fresh curtains were stained, the bedsheets damp in the humidity. What girl would ever want to marry him, with his joke of a salary, no car, no prospect of a place of his own?

他突然下定了决心，起身走进客厅。“爸爸，”他粗暴地说，“我需要借点钱。”

With a sudden flash of determination, he rose and walked into the living room. “Dad,” he said brusquely, “I need to borrow some money.”

博阳湿漉漉的眼睛从电视上移开，在他身上犹豫不决。朱峰移开了视线：与父亲的目光接触让他感到深深的不舒服。一时之间，他有些后悔自己说了些什么，但博阳却皱着眉头打量着他。“做什么的？”

Boyang’s rheumy eyes turned from the television and wavered on him. Zhu Feng looked away: something about eye contact with his father made him feel deeply uncomfortable. For a moment, he regretted having said anything at all, but Boyang was scrutinizing him with a furrowed brow. “What for?”

“一个投资机会。一只股票。李学士说——”

“An investment opportunity. A stock. Li Xueshi said—”

“李知道什么？”

“What does Li know?”

“他的家庭关系密切，他知道事情。。”。

“His family is connected, he knows things . . .”

他父亲把目光转回到屏幕上。“你有一份稳定的工作。如果你的朋友想赌博，就让他去吧。”

His father turned his eyes back to the screen. “You have a steady job. If your friend wants to gamble, let him.”

“但是爸爸——”

“But Dad—”

已经太迟了。伯阳已经打开了一小瓶廉价粮酒的盖子，抿了一口，似乎是在为自己儿子的这番话强硬。“富人不知道贫穷意味着什么，”他沉重地说，然后提高了音量。

It was too late. Boyang was already uncapping a tiny bottle of cheap grain liquor and sipping it, as though to fortify himself against his son’s words. “The rich don’t know what poverty means,” he said ponderously, and turned up the volume.

后来，在享用了淡啤酒和羊肉串的晚餐后，李表达了同情。

Later, over a dinner of weak beer and lamb skewers, Li was sympathetic.

“老一辈人不明白这一点，”他一边嚼着油炸花生一边说道。几个月来，李和另一位朋友一直致力于开发一款应用程序，这款应用程序可以让你把自己的脸换成狗、猪、清朝皇帝，蓝色的流苏挂在黄色的方形帽子上。狗会叫，清朝皇帝会告诉你，祝你心想事成。
