“The older generation, they don’t get it,” he said, crunching a deep-fried peanut. For months, Li and another friend had been working to develop an app, one that would let you transpose your face onto a dog, a pig, a Qing emperor, blue tassels hanging down from a square yellow cap. The dog could bark, the Qing emperor could tell you, May all your wishes come true.

“外面有一个完整的世界，”李说。“我一直告诉我爸爸他应该支持我们。他说，“如果我无法握住它、拧紧它或吃掉它，那它就不是真的。” ”

“There’s a whole world out there,” Li said. “I keep telling my dad he should back us. He says, ‘If I can’t hold it, screw it, or eat it, it’s not real.’ ”

李重重地叹了口气，然后笑了。“喂，我有跟你说过昨晚的事吗？” 他开始谈论他带女朋友去的最新一家俱乐部，那里的酒是装在冰做的大碗里的，服务员都化着闪闪发光的妆。

Li sighed emphatically, then grinned. “Hey, did I tell you about last night?” He started talking about the latest club he’d taken his girlfriend to, where the alcohol had been served in giant bowls made of ice and the waitstaff all wore glittery makeup.

朱枫也跟着点了点头，只是半听着，心里不由有些紧张。当他终于开口的时候，他的声音听起来有些沙哑和不自然：“李，我可以借点钱吗？”

Zhu Feng nodded along, only half listening, feeling nervous despite himself. When he finally spoke, his voice sounded squeaky and unnatural: “Li, can I borrow some money?”

他的朋友扬起了眉毛。

His friend raised his eyebrows.

“不多。”朱枫连忙补充道。“只要一千块钱，就够买你说的那只股票了。” 当他的朋友拍拍他的背时，他不好意思地笑了笑。

“Not much,” Zhu Feng hastened to add. “Just a thousand yuan, enough to buy some of that stock you mentioned.” He smiled sheepishly as his friend clapped him on his back.

“什么都给你，兄弟。我没想到你竟然有勇气。”李说。早在他父亲没富起来之前，李就一直是个比较大胆的人，在班上向女生扔纸团，在学校午餐时多吃自己份内的食物，还跟老师顶嘴，朱枫不自觉地看着，很羡慕他的胆量。 。

“Anything for you, brother. I never thought you’d get the nerve,” Li said. Even before his father had gotten rich, Li had always been the bolder one, throwing spitballs at girls in class, taking more than his portion at school lunches, and talking back to teachers, as Zhu Feng watched self-consciously, envious of his daring.

当晚，在返回父母公寓的公交车上，穿过漆黑的城市，朱枫下载了一款交易应用程序。您想为自己打造新的富裕生活吗？它问道。他兴高采烈地点击“是”，应用程序就安装好了。

On the bus back to his parents’ apartment that night, riding through the darkened city, Zhu Feng downloaded a trading app. Do you want to build a new high-prosperity life for yourself? it asked. He clicked Yes, jubilant, and the app installed.

 

几周后，他把一堆红色的百元大钞拍在一家新开张的五星级海鲜餐厅的白色桌布上，偿还了李某的钱。他们一起用闪闪发光的白瓷茶杯敬酒。他觉得那些背着红围裙的女服务员特别漂亮。山东丰达环卫有限公司表现不错，在他收购后几天内就翻了一番。根据李的建议，他用这笔钱购买了更多股票——股票价格也上涨了。

Weeks later, he paid Li back, slapping a pile of red 100-yuan bills onto the white tablecloth of a recently opened five-star seafood restaurant. Together, they toasted with white porcelain teacups that sparkled with newness. The waitresses, with red aprons tied neatly around their backs, were especially pretty, he thought. Shandong Abundant Sanitation Ltd. had done well, doubling in a matter of days after his purchase. On Li’s advice, he’d used the money to buy more stock—​and that had gone up as well.

股市！这就像发现了一个秘密密码。钱来得太容易了。这是一个完整的存在，在全国各地创造了数百万财富，而现在他终于置身其中。政府也在鼓励每个人。餐厅的一角，电视调到国家广播电台，正在播放上海指数，今年上涨了 30%。“牛市才刚刚开始，”主播说道。有些理发师成为了百万富翁。有些学校老师一夜之间就辞职了。另一份国营财经日报当天早上宣布，这是世界上表现最好的股票市场。

The stock market! It was like discovering a secret passcode. It was such easy money. It was a whole thing that existed, that minted millions of fortunes all around the country, and now he was finally inside of it. The government was encouraging everyone, too. In one corner of the restaurant, the television was tuned to the state broadcaster and showing the Shanghai index, up 30 percent for the year. “The bull run has only just begun,” the anchor was saying. There were hairdressers made millionaires. There were schoolteachers who quit their jobs overnight. THE WORLD’S BEST-PERFORMING STOCK MARKET, another state-run financial daily had proclaimed that morning.

朱枫的周围，似乎有人在买买买，买房子、买股票、买第二套房子、第三套房子；整整一代人都变得富有，需要为孩子们​​买东西，而以前的同样的小东西却没有通过考验：便士骑在那些闪烁着灯光的塑料卡通人物上，在外面轻轻地来回摇晃。药店；山楂串在棍子上，包裹在冷冻的黄色糖衣中，是一种廉价的冬季美食。他们需要购买，因为他们有钱，而这正是其他人所做的；他们过着简单的生活，而复杂的事情却由他们的孩子来做。此外，政府表示这是一代人的购买机会，一切都在建设中，到处都是新公寓和道路，中国正在不断发展，没有人想被抛在后面。

All around Zhu Feng, it seemed, people were buying, buying, homes and stocks and second and third houses; there was a whole generation who’d gotten rich and needed to buy things for their kids, and the same dinky things from before didn’t pass muster: penny rides on those plastic cartoon figures that flashed lights and gently rocked back and forth outside of drugstores; hawthorn impaled on sticks and sheathed in frozen yellow sugar casings, a cheap winter treat. They needed to buy because they had the money and that’s what everyone else was doing; they had simple lives, and it was their children who were going on to do the complicated things. Also, the government said it was the buying opportunity of a generation, everything under construction, new apartments and roads everywhere, China was going up and up and nobody wanted to be left behind.

甚至他工作的政府办公室也在翻新和扩建，增加了新的刨花板和会议室。几周过去了，施工一拖再拖，他的同事们对烟雾抱怨不已，但沉迷于交易应用程序的朱峰并不介意。无论如何，一切都是有毒的，他推断，无论你在城市的哪个区；要么是烟雾，要么是那令人作呕的甜味，刺鼻的化学气味，这意味着你在建筑工地附近，某种胶水，某种密封剂。你可以像现在很多人一样，惊慌失措地买个口罩，或者你可以成为一个男人，把这一切都吸进去。噗！

Even the government office where he worked was being renovated and expanded, new particleboard and conference rooms being added. As the weeks went by and construction dragged on, his coworkers groused at the fumes, but Zhu Feng, glued to his trading app, didn’t mind. Everything was poisonous anyway, he reasoned, no matter the quarter of the city you were in; either it was the smog or it was that sickly sweet smell, sharp and chemical, that meant you were near a construction site, some kind of glue, some sort of sealant. You could quail and buy a face mask like so many people were doing now, or you could be a man and just breathe it all in. Pow!

晚上，当他躺在床上时，他可以想象所有的股票代码在他的脑海中排成一排，点头、挥手、闪烁。921015，是他生日的数字。那是814036，他在新闻上听说过的生猪公司。还有 640007，另一个来自同事的提示。他温柔地对待他们，催促他们继续前进，烟雾信号盘旋升上天空。

At night, as he lay in bed, he could picture all the stock codes lined up in his head, nodding and waving and flickering in a row. There was 921015, the digits of his birthday. There was 814036, the hog company he’d heard about on the news. There was 640007, another tip from a coworker. He felt tenderly toward them and urged them on, smoke signals spiraling up into the sky.

他想，这不是像他父亲这样的人能够理解的事情。穷人做着穷人的工作，被拒之门外，穿着皱巴巴、宽松的老人夹克，这是另一个时代的遗物，哪儿也去不了。你必须为他们感到难过，真的。

It wasn’t something, he thought, that men like his father could ever understand. Poor men working their poor-men jobs, shut out, wearing their rumpled, baggy old men’s jackets, relics of another era, going nowhere. You had to feel sorry for them, really.

从朱枫记事起，他的父亲就一直喜怒无常，情绪不稳定，容易抑郁。母亲常说，父亲多年前曾受过“打击”，但谁没有受过打击呢？

For as long as Zhu Feng could remember, his father had been moody, fitful, prone to periods of depression. His mother used to say his father had once suffered a “blow” many years ago, but who hadn’t suffered a blow?

“什么样的打击？” 他会问，那些日子里，博阳只是躺在床上，拉着窗帘。她不会说。

“What kind of blow?” he’d ask, on those days Boyang spent simply lying in bed with the shades drawn. She wouldn’t say.

终于，朱枫不再疑惑了。不管是什么，他现在应该已经克服了。那人才五十三岁，却已经大腹便便，脸上布满肝斑，口气恶臭。多年来，他一直戴着同样的破旧蓝色帽子，穿着假皮大衣，骑着摩托车在城里慢慢地行驶，对路人说：“莫迪，莫迪”，希望他们能给他一些钞票，然后骑上他的自行车，“莫迪” “莫迪，”就像他在街上推销假劳力士或兜售儿童袜子一样。

Eventually, Zhu Feng stopped wondering. Whatever it was, he should have gotten over it by now. The man was only fifty-three, but already carried a substantial paunch, face liver-spotted and breath reeking. For years he’d worn the same shabby blue hat and fake leather coat and cruised slowly around town on his scooter saying, “Modi, modi,” to passersby, hoping they’d hand him some bills and hop on his bike, “Modi, modi,” like he was pushing fake Rolexes or hawking children’s socks on the street.

朱峰小时候很喜欢和父亲一起骑摩托车——大轮子，引擎轰鸣！这就像坐在一头巨大的机械野兽上，引擎的稳定颤动在下面嗡嗡作响，两个把手在他父亲的握中张开，这令人安心的景象。

When Zhu Feng was young he’d loved to ride with his father on his scooter—​the big wheels, the way its engine could roar! It was like sitting astride a great mechanical beast, the steady vibrato of the engine humming underneath, the reassuring sight of the two handles splayed in his father’s grip.

然后，随着城市变得更加富裕，每个人都拥有了自己的踏板车或汽车，一想到他的父亲在等待认可的信号，节省燃料并滑行，在乘客之间尽可能用脚推动，他就感到悲伤。现在朱枫已经长大了，有了自己的工作，这也让他很生气。他就不能再努力一点吗？“莫迪，莫迪。”

Then, as the city got richer and everyone got their own scooters or cars, it saddened him, the thought of his dad waiting for a sign of recognition, scrimping on fuel and coasting, propelled by his feet as much as he could between passengers. Now that Zhu Feng was a grown man with a job of his own, it made him angry, too. Couldn’t he try harder? “Modi, modi.”

几个月来，他父亲的主要关注点一直是他在鸟类市场买的一只红嘴宠物鸣禽。他没完没了地解开它的笼子，刷新它的水盘，催促它做后空翻，试图让它唱歌。早上，他会带着鸟笼步行到附近的一个公园，在那里他会加入一群老人，也带着他们的鸟。在那里，它们会小心翼翼地将笼子挂在树上，花几个小时下棋和聊天。朱枫想，这一切都是错误的。养鸟是老人的爱好，而他的父亲还没有老。

For months now, his father’s main preoccupation had been a red-billed pet songbird he’d bought at the bird market; he was endlessly unhooking its cage and refreshing its water dish, urging the bird to do its backflips, trying to make it sing. In the mornings, he’d take the birdcage and walk it to a nearby park, where he’d join a group of elderly men, also with their birds. There they would carefully hang their cages in the trees, and spend hours playing chess and chatting. It was all wrong, Zhu Feng thought. Bird-keeping was an old man’s hobby, and his father wasn’t old yet.

“现在是冬天，”他的父亲一开始说道，并解释了为什么他每周只骑几天摩托车。“生意很慢。”

“It’s winter,” his father had said at first, explaining why he was driving his scooter only a few days a week. “Business is slow.”

但那是四个月前的事了，现在是四月了，这个月的充实在树木中显现出来，它们一开始试探性地展开自己，然后像雨一样的小花蕾散布在人行道上。博阳仍然带着他的鸟去散步，而且他每周可能只有三天开车，这迫使朱峰的母亲君玲尽管背部不好，却不得不去医院接更多的班次。让朱枫想要尖叫。

But that was four months ago, and now it was April, and the fullness of the month was showing in the trees, which unfurled themselves tentatively at first and then in a rain of tiny buds that scattered themselves over the sidewalks. And still Boyang was taking his bird for walks, and still he was driving perhaps just three days a week, forcing Zhu Feng’s mother, Junling, to pick up more shifts at the hospital despite her bad back. It made Zhu Feng want to scream.

他想，如果他有更多的钱来投资就好了。李学石最近买了一套全新的音箱，两人花了几个小时聆听说唱歌手的声音，向他们从未见过的地方——纽约、伦敦、圣保罗——表达疯狂的敬意。他们的床上有漂亮的女人，还有最好的一切：兰博基尼、劳力士、范思哲。两人同时发出了一个个音节。

If only he had more money to invest, he thought. Li Xueshi had recently bought a brand-new speaker set, and the two of them spent hours listening to the sounds of rappers paying frantic homage to places they’d never seen, New York, London, São Paulo. They had beautiful women in their beds and the best of everything: Lamborghini, Rolex, Versace. Together, the two of them mouthed the syllables.

不，这里没有像朱枫这样的男人。他有想法。他有野心。他有品味。他喜欢这个词，品味。这绝对属于他和李那一代人。不是他父母生活的简陋，他们拖着脚步，他们的希望渺茫，似乎只表达了一种“骂包，穿得暖”的愿望——吃饱了，穿得暖和。

No, there wasn’t much for men like Zhu Feng here. He had ideas. He had ambition. He had taste. He liked that phrase, taste. It was something that belonged, emphatically, to his and Li’s generation. Not the shabbiness of his parents’ lives, their shuffling steps, the curtailed hopes that seemed to express nothing more than a desire to chide bao, chuan de nuan—​to be full in the belly, to be warmly clothed.

要是他有更多的钱就好了。他可以在市场上将其翻倍、三倍。他周围的一切都在上升、上升、上升。不久之后，他也将上路。

If only he had more money. He could double it, triple it, in the market. Everything was going up, up, up around him. In a short time he, too, would be on his way.

然后有一天，在他第一次开始交易后不久，他有了一个重要的发现。他管理着十几项政府基金，向全省各地发放拨款，一式三份地填写同样的纸条，让他的双手沾满了黑色墨水。他已经处理银行转账几个月了，直到他不小心调换了两位数字，导致一批资金误入歧途。直到临阳县林业局打电话询问他们的分配地在哪里时，他才知道这件事。到那时已经是六周后了，如果他们没有给他打电话，很可能不会有人注意到。

Then one day, not long after he’d first begun trading, he made a key discovery. There were a dozen government funds he administered, sending allotments all over the province, filling out the same slips of paper in triplicate that left his hands covered in black ink. He had been handling bank transfers for months before he’d accidentally transposed two digits and sent a batch of funds astray. He’d found out about it only when the Linyang County forestry bureau had called him demanding to know where their allotment was. By then it was six weeks later, and if they hadn’t called him up, it was possible no one would ever have noticed.

起初他尝试向自己的账户转入1000元。他把它放在那里一个月，然后又把它移回去，没有人注意到。渐渐地，我开始意识到。只要在季末清点账簿时将账簿加起来，这笔钱就似乎是他的了。那么为何不？当钱可以被花掉、使用、转化和倍增时，为什么还要让钱呆在那里，毫无生气呢？全省各地的所有支出——每个月有几十笔，谁会注意到一个额外的账户得到了它的份额呢？没有人，就是那个人。

At first he’d tried moving 1,000 yuan to his account. He let it sit there for a month before moving it back, and no one noticed. Gradually the dawning realization set in. As long as the books added up when they were tallied at the quarter’s end, the money, it seemed, was his. And why not? Why let the money sit there, inert, when it could be spent, used, transformed and multiplied? All those disbursements across the province—​there were dozens every month, and who was going to notice an extra account getting its share? No one, that’s who.

大摇大摆地拿到那笔钱，他对自己喊道。大摇大摆大摇大摆地藏起来。

Swagger swagger get that cash, he chanted to himself. Swagger swagger make a stash.

他拿出一万块钱，翻了一倍。第二次，他又抽走了5万元，并在此基础上又赚了三分之一。每周，他都会看到账户中新的数字列不断增长。每个季度末，他都会将原来的一笔钱转回政府账户，并将利润重新投入市场。八个月就这样过去了，他的脑子里一直盘旋着令人眼花缭乱的算术。早上，当他走向地铁时，路过一排排在街上用棋盘赌博的老人时，他想大声喊叫，傻瓜！ 我们现在有更好的游戏了。

He took out 10,000 yuan and doubled it. The next time, he siphoned off 50,000 yuan and made an additional third on top of that. Every week, he watched the new columns of numbers in his account grow. At the end of every quarter, he moved the original sum of money back to the government’s account and plowed the profits back into the market. Eight months passed like that, his mind a whirl of giddy arithmetic. In the mornings, as he walked to the subway, passing ranks of old men gambling on the street over their chessboards, he wanted to crow aloud, Fools! We have better games now.

他去了市中心的商店，那里有英文招牌、落地大镜子和多音节名字：Ermenegildo Zegna 和 Raidy Boer（“与世界时尚同步”）。他买了新外套、新裤子和一套坚固的皮鞋，并为它们的触感感到兴奋。在他周围，他突然发现自己注意到其他男人穿的品牌、外套的款式、袖口的外观。在大街上，每当看到自己认得的徽章，他的心就欢喜地跳动。

He went downtown to the shops that had English signs, big floor-to-ceiling mirrors, and many-syllabled names: Ermenegildo Zegna and Raidy Boer (“step with world fashion”). He bought new coats, new pants, and a set of sturdy leather shoes, and thrilled to their touch. All around him, he suddenly found himself noticing the brands other men wore, the make of their coats, the look of their cuffs. On the street, whenever he saw the insignias he recognized, he felt his heart give a pleased thump.

晚上，他回到父母的公寓大楼，退休人员在院子里闲逛，周围的街道上除了陈旧的香烟和豆腐外，没有什么更令人兴奋的了。但当他登上水泥楼梯时，他第一次感受到了一种私下的喜悦。

At night he returned to his parents’ apartment complex, where retirees loitered in the courtyard and the surrounding streets sold nothing more exciting than stale cigarettes and tofu. But for the first time, ascending the concrete stairs, he felt a sense of private elation.

他没有告诉任何人他在做什么，甚至李也没有告诉。等他发了财，他就会让所有人大吃一惊。他会辞职，创办自己的公司，在国外买一栋别墅；现在很多人在西班牙和希腊购买护照。李和他的女朋友最近去了罗马——他看过这些照片。他想象自己在欧洲的某个地方，在一家阳光明媚的咖啡馆里。当然，他必须学习一门新语言。他想象自己像一只学唱歌的小鸟一样张开嘴。

He didn’t tell anyone what he was doing, not even Li. Wait until he’d made a fortune, and then he’d surprise them all. He’d quit, start his own company, buy a villa somewhere abroad; lots of people these days were buying passports in Spain, in Greece. Li and his girlfriend had recently gone to Rome—he’d seen the photos. He pictured himself somewhere in Europe, in a sunny café. He’d have to learn a new language, of course. He pictured himself opening up his mouth like a baby bird learning how to sing.

 

朱峰每个月都会去一些三四线城市出差几次，同样的杂乱无章的事情，山寨快餐连锁店，不停鸣喇叭的汽车，一两年前才盖起来的公寓楼，到处都是，脚手架就像悬挂的藤蔓。他以前很喜欢这部分工作，至少是换换环境，但自从开始交易后，他发现旅行很乏味。这意味着手机信号很差，与当地干部就施肥计划或重新造林工作进行长时间的会议，几天的鞋子沾满泥，食物也很糟糕。

A few times a month for work Zhu Feng traveled to some third- or fourth-tier city, the same sprawling affairs with their knockoff fast-food chains, incessantly honking cars, apartment blocks erected only a year or two previously, and, everywhere, scaffolding like hanging vines. He’d liked that part of the job before, a change of scenery, at least, but since he’d begun trading, he found the trips tedious. It meant poor cell-phone reception, long meetings with local cadres about this fertilizer program or that reforesting effort, days of muddy shoes and terrible food.

那年冬天的一次这样的旅行中，他和同事们很早就出发了，先是坐火车，然后是汽车，六人乘坐一辆面包车，在雨水打湿的高速公路上行驶了一个半小时，然后在布满车辙的道路上摇摇晃晃地行驶。他们要和村党委开会讨论植树造林问题。朱枫双手握着手机，时不时地按一下刷新。他发现市场开盘疲软，在信号消失之前下跌了 3%。天气很冷，他的呼吸画出脆弱的圆圈，这些圆圈在货车的窗户上扩大并消失。

On one such trip that winter he and his colleagues set out early, first by train and then by car, six of them in a van that drove an hour and a half along a rain-slicked highway and then bumped unsteadily along a rutted road. They were going to meet with a village party committee to discuss reforesting. Zhu Feng kept his hands curled around his phone, periodically hitting refresh. The market opened soft, he saw, dropping 3 percent before the signal cut out. It was chilly, and his breath drew fragile circles that expanded and disappeared on the van’s window.

中午时分，他们到达了村庄，从货车里涌了出来，跺着脚，双手捂着口气。一排排砖房，一堆堆被雨水软化的柴草，门口一群叫喊的村民。

They reached the village and piled out of the van around noon, stamping their feet and breathing into their hands. There were rows of brick houses, piles of rain-softened firewood, and at the entrance, a group of shouting villagers.

这群人并不引人注目，只有二十人左右，但他们聚集了一面手绘横幅，上面写着“还给我们土地，还给我们生命”，并正在大力挥舞。

The group wasn’t very impressive, only twenty or so of them, but they had mustered a hand-painted banner that read GIVE US BACK OUR LAND, GIVE US BACK OUR LIFE, and were waving it energetically.

朱枫不知道横幅所指的是什么，但他想他能猜到。沿着高速公路，他们经过了该地区正在拔地而起的新高楼广告牌，与现在遍布城市各处的时尚公寓楼的计算机渲染图像相同；朱峰认为这些村民正在被搬迁，为他们的建设让路。

Zhu Feng didn’t know what the banner was referencing, but thought he could guess. Along the highway, they’d passed billboards advertising new high-rises that were going up in the area, the same kinds of computer-rendered images of sleek apartment blocks that plastered cities everywhere now; Zhu Feng assumed these villagers were being relocated to make way for their construction.

“我们不是土地委员会，”当地林业局局长对人群大声说道。“我们是林业局的！” 他语气轻快，带着一丝恼怒，就好像抗议者已经收到了这份备忘录，但没有阅读。

“We are not the land committee,” the head of the local forestry bureau said loudly to the crowd. “We are with the forestry bureau!” He spoke briskly and with an edge of irritation, as though the protesters had received, but neglected to read, the memo.

人群窃窃私语，试图打量他们，但官员们都裹着大衣，村民们似乎不知道该找谁。朱枫想，有一个女人看起来像他的母亲，眼睛周围有什么东西。她穿着一件蓬松的红色外套，戴着一顶用塑料包裹的宽边草帽来挡雨。

The crowd murmured, trying to size them up, but the officials were bundled in coats and the villagers didn’t seem to know whom to approach. One woman looked like his mother, Zhu Feng thought, something around the eyes. She wore a puffy red coat with a wide-brimmed straw hat wrapped in plastic against the rain.

一群身穿制服的男子从村子深处出现，腰间挥舞着警棍，开始向人群冲去。人群中有几个人尖叫起来。草帽女子一看到朱峰，就冲了过来，想要将一捆纸塞到他手里。“哥哥很帅，”她说。“你是个年轻人。年轻人要有良知。”

From deeper within the village, a group of uniformed men emerged and began hurrying toward the crowd, batons swinging from their hips. A few in the crowd shrieked. At their sight, the woman in the straw hat caught Zhu Feng’s eye and rushed over, trying to thrust a sheaf of paper into his hands. “Handsome brother,” she said. “You’re a young person. Young people must have a conscience.”

朱枫犹豫了。走近一看，这个女人比他想象的要老。他能数清她上唇上方的粗毛发。他感觉自己很虚弱，女人也感觉到了。“请帮助我们，你是一个有权势的人，有权势的人有责任。” 她抓住他的手臂，用力惊人地拉扯他夹克的袖子。他退缩了。

Zhu Feng hesitated. Up close, the woman was older than he’d realized; he could count the coarse individual hairs above her upper lip. He felt himself weaken, and the woman sensed it. “Help us, please, you are a powerful person, the powerful have a duty.” She grabbed his arm, a surprisingly strong tug on his jacket’s sleeve. He recoiled.

“放开我。”他厉声说道，她也照做了。一群官员一扫而空，他头也不回地跟着他们进了村党会堂。几个小时后，当他们离开时，乌云已经散去，抗议者也散去。

“Let go of me,” he said sharply, and she did. The group of officials swept away, and he followed them into the village’s party hall without looking back. By the time they left a few hours later, the clouds had lifted and the protesters were gone.

当他们开车离开时，当地林业局局长试图解释。他说，该地区的村民就是这样，总是闹事。他们获得了耕地补偿，并有机会成为第一批购买最新开发项目的人之一，这将是最先进的：开放式厨房、花园，甚至还有一个幼儿园。“生活会更好，”他说。“他们会习惯的，他们会看到的。”

As they drove away, the local forestry bureau head tried to explain. The villagers in the area were like that, always making trouble, he said. They were being compensated for their farmland and given the chance to be among the first to buy into the new development, which would be state-of-the-art: open-plan kitchens, a flower garden, even an on-site kindergarten. “Life will be better,” he said. “They’ll get used to it, they’ll see.”

朱枫没有听。现在他们又上路了，他重新打开手机，不断地不断地点击刷新，直到他终于收到一丝信号，看到市场已经下跌了百分之六。

Zhu Feng wasn’t listening. Now that they were back on the road, he opened his phone back up and kept compulsively hitting refresh, until he got a wisp of signal at last and saw that the market had dropped 6 percent.

他的心难以置信地狂跳。前一天，股票也下跌了，再前一天也是如此。这是下跌的第三天，而且已经抹去了他过去两个季度的涨幅。这没有道理。他茫然地看着窗外。

His heart pounded disbelievingly. The day before, as well, stocks had fallen, and the day before that. This was the third day of declines, and they’d already more than wiped out his gains for the past two quarters. It didn’t make sense. He stared blankly out the window.

问题是，他告诉自己，市场当然有涨有跌，他当然知道——他并不傻。但政府永远不会让市场下跌。这件事以前发生过，三年前，人们仍然在谈论它。市场下跌了40%以上，人们惊慌失措，争先恐后地退出，但随后政府下令全国百强企业买入股票，推、推、推，让底线坚守，结果就这样了。绝不允许市场失灵。政府在很多事情上并不是很擅长，但在确保利润方面却非常非常擅长。

The thing was, he told himself, of course the market was up and down, of course he knew that—​he wasn’t stupid. But the government would never let the market drop. It had happened before, three years ago, and people still talked about it. The market had dropped by more than 40 percent and people were panicking and rushing for exits, but then the government had ordered the country’s top hundred companies to buy up shares, push, push, push, make the line hold, and it had. No way the market would be allowed to fail. The government was not very good at a lot of things but it was very, very good at ensuring profits.

问题是时间。距离季末盘点只剩下两周时间了，老楼大部分时间都喝得酩酊大醉，干活不力，但即使是少了十万元，他也会注意到。还有两周，其中四天是周末——好吧，还有十天。

The problem was time. There were just two more weeks before the books would be tallied at the end of the quarter by Old Lou, who was drunk most afternoons and deficient at the job, but even he would notice if 100,000 yuan was missing. Two more weeks and four of those days were the weekend—​okay, ten more days.

那天晚上朱峰很早就去了酒店，告诉同事他会错过晚餐——他说他感觉不舒服。他开着灯睡着了，黎明时分，头昏脑胀地醒来。

Zhu Feng went to the hotel early that evening, telling his coworkers he would miss dinner—​he wasn’t feeling well, he said. He fell asleep with the lights on and woke at dawn with a pounding head.

早上，他和同事们参加了一场关于土壤修复的政府研讨会，研讨会在一间通风良好的会议室举行，其他数十名官员和托盘上的红豆沙干包子以及几杯略带金属味的茶。水不够热，树叶还漂浮着，卡在他的牙齿里。每隔几分钟，朱峰就会查看手机：他发现市场又下跌了百分之五。

In the morning, he and his colleagues attended a government seminar on soil remediation, held in a drafty conference room with dozens of other officials and trays of dry buns stuffed with red-bean paste, along with cups of faintly metallic tea. The water wasn’t hot enough and the leaves were still floating and caught in his teeth. Every few minutes, Zhu Feng checked his phone: the market, he saw, had fallen another 5 percent.

他给李发了短信。你看到这个了吗？

He texted Li. Are you seeing this?

至少你不会失去太多，李写道。我爸都快疯了，哈哈

At least you don’t have much to lose, Li wrote. My dad is freaking out, ha ha.

发生了什么？

What’s happening?

不知道，李写道。

Dunno, Li wrote.

这没有道理，朱枫绝望地想。这是不可能的。他不知道这到底是怎么发生的。它就像一匹马，缓慢而温顺，突然站了起来，蹄子长满了尖刺，露出了满嘴锋利的黄色牙齿：我来找你了。

It didn’t make sense, Zhu Feng thought desperately. It wasn’t possible. He didn’t know how it had happened exactly; it was like a horse, plodding and tractable, had abruptly reared up with spike-armed hooves and bared a mouthful of sharp yellow teeth: I’m coming for you.

半个小时后，朱枫的手机再次亮了起来。这是李发来的消息，这次他父亲的一个朋友听说市场崩溃是暂时的，政府随时都会介入。

Zhu Feng’s phone lit up again a half hour later. It was a message from Li, this time saying a friend of his father’s had heard that the market crash was temporary, that the government was going to step in any day now.

那么你在说什么？

So what are you saying?

“坐稳，”李回答道。不用担心。

Sit tight, Li replied. Don’t worry.

一种如释重负的感觉淹没了他，这种感觉只持续了几分钟，然后焦虑就开始吞噬了他。即使市场恢复，他心里嘀咕，自己也可能赚不到钱。经过这几个月的风险和希望，真是可惜。当一名官员在房前喋喋不休时，朱峰看到坐在他前面的人已经把头伏在桌子上睡觉了。几个座位之外的另一位女士正在使劲挖鼻孔。

A great feeling of relief flooded him, one that lingered for only a few minutes before anxiety began to nibble. Even if the market recovered, he thought to himself mutinously, he still likely wouldn’t make any money. After all this time, months of risk and hope, what a shame. As an official droned on at the front of the room, Zhu Feng saw, the man sitting in front of him had put his head down on the table and was sleeping. Another woman a few seats over was vigorously picking her nose.

紧接着，朱枫又产生了一个念头。他起身离开房间，从走廊卫生间给他的朋友打电话。“如果政府介入，那么这是一个很好的买入机会，”他对自己的洞察力感到满意。

Then another thought occurred to Zhu Feng. He got up and left the room and called his friend from the corridor bathroom. “If the government’s going to step in, then it’s a good buying opportunity,” he said, pleased with his insight.

李说：“也许吧。” 听起来他刚刚醒着。朱峰估计自己在开发应​​用程序时熬夜了。

“Maybe,” Li said. He sounded barely awake. Zhu Feng figured he’d been up late working on his app.

“我要进去。”朱枫斩钉截铁的说道。“兄弟，借我点钱好不好？”

“I want in,” Zhu Feng said decisively. “Lend me some money, brother, will you?”

李的声音传来，熟悉的慢吞吞的声音。“再次？多少？”

Li’s voice came, a familiar drawl. “Again? How much?”

“一万五千。”朱枫屏住呼吸，大胆说道。

“Fifteen thousand,” Zhu Feng said boldly, holding his breath.

李哼了一声。

Li snorted.

“来吧。”朱枫说道。李不高兴，朱枫却一再坚持。他们不是好朋友吗？上次他不是还钱了吗？给朋友一点休息，就这一个恩惠。那就一万吧。他很快就会还给他的。“并不是每个人都足够幸运，拥有一个富有的爸爸，”他说。

“Come on,” Zhu Feng said. Li wasn’t happy, but Zhu Feng, for once, was insistent. Weren’t they good friends? Hadn’t he paid him back last time? Give a friend a break, just this one favor. Ten thousand, then. He’d pay him back soon. “Not everyone is lucky enough to have a rich dad,” he said.

他语气中的苦涩无法掩饰，他立刻就后悔了。“我会还你的，”他说。

The bitterness that flooded his tone was impossible to mask, and immediately he regretted it. “I’ll pay you back,” he said.

李说：“随便吧。”

“Whatever,” Li said.

回到会议室，朱枫把手机半藏在桌子底下，等了几分钟，直到李的转接电话接通，才点了买买买。看着新的股票代码出现在他的股票代码上，他试图把与李的谈话抛在脑后。

Back in the conference room, his phone half concealed under the table, Zhu Feng waited a few minutes until Li’s transfer came through before clicking buy, buy, buy. Watching the new stock codes appear on his ticker, he tried to put the conversation with Li out of his mind.

 

回程的火车上，朱峰满怀期待地刷新着手机，等待着行情反弹，但行情却不断下跌。第二天，他在办公室拐角处的粘桌子小摊上午餐和晚餐吃牛肉面汤：牛肉是牛的，牛肉是公牛的，牛市的牛肉。他整个星期都穿着同一条幸运红内衣，等待政府干预，但每次他打开应用程序时，市场都拒绝回升；它一直处于低位，甚至进一步下跌。

All during the train ride back, Zhu Feng expectantly refreshed his phone, waiting for the market to rebound, but it kept falling. The next day, he ate beef noodle soup for lunch and dinner at the sticky-tabled stall around the corner from his office: beef for cows, beef for bulls, for a bull market. He wore the same pair of lucky red underwear all week and waited for the government to intervene, but every time he opened his app, the market had refused to go back up; it stayed stubbornly low and even fell further.

他给李发了短信，让他知道他回到了城里，但没有收到回复。有几次他开始写一条信息，上面写着“我以为是你爸爸的朋友说的”，但他自己停了下来。他很孤独。在家里，他父亲的宠物鸟一直在叫。朱枫戴着耳机，一直待在自己的房间里。

He’d texted Li, letting him know he was back in town, but received no reply. A few times he began writing a message that read I thought your dad’s friend said, but stopped himself. He was lonely. At home, his father’s pet bird cawed at all hours. Zhu Feng kept to his room with his headphones on.

全国各地的投资者都愤怒了，但他们能做什么呢？政府报纸不再为市场欢呼，而是在内页上以极其精确的方式报道了市场的下跌。一些人发表社论，批评那些帮助推高价格的过度贪婪的投资者：他们说，非理性行为、市场谣言需要纠正。

Around the country, investors were furious, but what could they do? The government papers stopped cheerleading the market, and instead reported its decline with clipped precision on their inside pages. A few ran editorials about overly greedy investors who’d helped drive up prices: irrational behavior, market rumormongering, they said, needs correction.

对于朱峰来说，时间已经缩小到只有一个点，即日历上显示季度末的小方格，此时政府的账簿将被清点。无论他做什么，日子都过得飞快、无情。他知道，如果市场进一步下跌，明智的做法可能就是卖出，但然后呢？如果卖掉，他就完全失去了挽回损失的机会，而他现在已经亏了十五万多元了。

For Zhu Feng, time had narrowed to just one point, the small square of calendar that showed the end of the quarter, when the government’s books would be tallied. No matter what he did, the days were moving swiftly, inexorably ahead. If the market dropped further, he knew, the sensible thing to do was probably sell, but then what? If he sold, he’d lose any chance at all of recovering his losses, and he was now more than 150,000 yuan down.

他开始向同事借小笔钱，虽然不多，但每一分钱都很重要。他甚至尝试把最近买的一些衣服带回商店退货，但店主只是奇怪地看了他一眼，摇摇头。

He started borrowing small sums of money from people at work, not much, but every penny counted. He’d even tried taking some of his recently purchased clothes back to stores to return, but the shopkeepers just gave him funny looks and shook their heads.

距离最后7天，市场小幅上涨，但第二天又下跌。第二天早上（还有五天），又经历了一个不眠之夜，他知道是时候埋葬他的骄傲了。实在对不起，兄弟，他写给李了。我有麻烦了。你在吗？

With seven days to go, the market went up slightly, but stumbled again the day after. The morning after that (five days to go), following another sleepless night, he knew it was time to bury his pride. I’m really sorry, brother, he wrote Li. I’m in trouble. Are you there?

发完信息后，他感觉心里的疙瘩松了口气。当李承认自己所做的事情时，他会感到震惊，在他们上次交流后可能仍然很生气，但他会尽力而为；他就是这样的朋友。他告诉自己，李甚至可能会赞同他这个大胆的计划。有一次，六岁的时候，他们从李妈妈的钱包里偷了100元，用它每天给自己买汽水，持续了一年，让同学们羡慕不已；回忆起来，朱枫笑了。

After sending the message, he felt the knot in his stomach relax. Li would be shocked when he confessed what he’d done, was probably still angry after their last exchange, but he’d do his best; he was that kind of friend. It was possible, he told himself, that Li would even approve of the sheer audacity of his scheme. Once, when they were six, they’d stolen 100 yuan out of Li’s mother’s purse and used it to buy themselves sodas every day for a year, to the envy of their classmates; the memory made Zhu Feng smile.

他又在床上躺了一个小时，听着隔墙传来的俗气的打闹声，等待着李的答复。那天是星期六，他不用工作。他拨通了李的电话，一次、两次、三次，每次耳边都是一阵嘻哈音乐，他记得去年夏天他们两个一起买的铃声。

He lay in bed for another hour, listening to the cheesy sound of slapstick coming through the wall and waiting for Li’s reply. It was Saturday and he didn’t have to work. He called Li’s phone, once, twice, three times, each time getting a swarm of hip-hop in his ear, a ringtone he remembered the two of them buying together the previous summer.

但当李最终回复时，他听起来心烦意乱：他和女朋友在机场，准备去国外度假一周。“等我回来再跟你说，”他写道，仅此而已。

But when Li finally replied, he sounded distracted: he was at the airport with his girlfriend, about to leave for a week’s holiday abroad. Talk to you when I’m back, he wrote, and that was all.

 

朱枫的心沉了下去。他再次拨打电话，但李某的手机已关机。他下了床，四肢感觉就像一个被判死刑的人。他脱掉衣服，去洗澡。站在水花下，他有一种类似思乡的感觉，他坐下来，任由水流冲刷着他的头。

Zhu Feng’s heart dropped. He tried calling again, but Li’s phone was powered off. He got out of bed, limbs feeling like those of a condemned man. He made himself undress and went to take a shower. Standing under its spray, he was flooded with a feeling akin to homesickness and he sat down, letting the water pelt his head.

当君凌敲门时，他还坐在那儿，头枕在膝盖上。“你还好吗？” 她叫。

He was still sitting there, head cradled on his knees, when Junling rapped at the door. “Are you okay?” she called.

“我很好。”

“I’m okay.”

“我必须去上班，”她说。

“I have to go to work,” she said.

他关掉水龙头，擦干身体，然后在一团热蒸汽中离开。他的母亲穿着工作服站在那儿，微微皱眉，就像早晨背部特别糟糕时的样子。她推门进去，关上了门。

He turned off the water and dried himself and exited in a cloud of hot steam. His mother was standing there in her scrubs, wincing a little, the way she did in the mornings when her back was especially bad. She pushed her way inside and closed the door.

俊岭走后，他决定出去走走，想出什么办法就出公寓。出了门，他经过了他父亲带鸟去的公园。其他几个人已经出去了，透过棋盘凝视着树上挂着的鸟笼。他路过那家从他童年起就一直存在的老药店，现在换了招牌，换了老板。他经过一个蔬菜摊，退休人员正在那里筛选打折的枯萎蔬菜。

After Junling left, he decided to go for a walk, anything to get out of the apartment. Outside, he passed the park where his father took his bird; a few of the other men were out already, peering over a chessboard, birdcages hanging in the trees. He passed the old drugstore that had been there since his childhood, with a new sign now, under new ownership. He passed a vegetable stand where retirees were sifting through discounted piles of wilted greens.

他决定，那天晚上他会告诉他的父母。他会解释他一直在做什么以及他如何损失了政府的钱，并看看他们可以提供什么帮助。毕竟他们是他的父母。

He would tell his parents that night, he decided. He would explain what he’d been doing and how he’d lost the government’s money, and see what help they could offer. They were his parents, after all.

每隔几分钟，他就会有一种冲动，想刷新一下手机，查看一下市场行情，然后才松了口气，想起今天是周六，市场休市。他继续走着。

Every few minutes, he felt the urge to refresh his phone and check on the market, before remembering with relief that it was Saturday, and the markets were closed. He kept walking.

他经过了公交车站，几栋高楼，几家美发店，一家宠物店。他挺直肩膀，继续向南走。一个半小时后，他到达了市中心，起初他打算停下来，也许可以逛逛一些商店，但他却继续前进——这有一些令人兴奋的东西；他觉得他可以永远走下去，他的双脚几乎感觉不到自己的用力。向西，他可以看到李家现在居住的街区的白色塔楼，但他继续笔直前进，穿过城市向山上走去。

He passed the bus station, a few high-rises, some hairdressing salons, a pet store. He squared his shoulders and continued south. An hour and a half later he hit the downtown, and at first he meant to stop, maybe browse in some of the shops, but instead he pressed on—​there was something exhilarating about it; he could walk forever, he felt, his feet barely aware of their exertions. To the west, he could see the white towers of the neighborhood where Li’s family now lived, but he kept going straight, cutting across the city toward the hills.

天黑后他才回到家。博阳在客厅里看着电视，正播放着昂贵的酒类广告。蓝色的瓶子沐浴着诡异的光芒，在屏幕上旋转，一个男人低沉的声音吟诵着：“老字号品质，中国品质。”

He returned home only after dark. Boyang was in the living room, watching the television as an advertisement for expensive alcohol came on. The bottle was blue and bathed in an eerie light and revolved onscreen as a man’s deep voice intoned, “Time-honored quality, Chinese quality.”

厨房里，朱枫听见锅里传来油的嘶嘶声。他的母亲正在炉子上用醋炒土豆条。她还穿着医院的手术服，白色，带有黄色镶边。这对她来说很不寻常，以至于朱枫询问是不是出了什么事。

From the kitchen, Zhu Feng could hear the sound of oil hissing in a pan. His mother was stir-frying slivered potatoes with vinegar on the stove. She was still wearing her scrubs from the hospital, white with yellow trim. It was unusual for her, so much so that Zhu Feng asked if something was wrong.

“没什么，”她生气地说。“今晚我的时间很紧迫。今天有人排队几个小时。我们用两分钟的时间循环浏览了它们。”

“Nothing,” she said, annoyed. “I was pressed for time tonight. We had people lining up for hours today. We cycled them through in two-minute slots.”

朱枫没有询问就接过大蒜，开始剥皮。作为一名护士，他的母亲手指笨拙，视力也开始衰退。他发现，如果不处理大蒜，烹饪时就会残留一些纸质鳞片。

Zhu Feng took the garlic without being asked and began peeling. For a nurse his mother had clumsy fingers, and her eyesight had begun to fail; he’d found that if he didn’t handle the garlic, bits of the papery scales would wind up in the cooking.

她从他身边擦身而过，拿起柜台上的两块鱼，捞到一盘面粉里。“我不知道你们今晚在这里吃饭，”她说道，厌恶地低头看着他们软弱的身体，作为解释。“你和你父亲可以吃。”

She brushed past him to pick up two pieces of fish that sat on the counter, which she dredged in a plateful of flour. “I didn’t know you were eating here tonight,” she said, looking down at their limp bodies distastefully, by way of explanation. “You and your father can eat it.”

俊岭将鱼放入锅中的热油中，鱼开始发出嘶嘶声。朱枫一看，就看到母亲的一只袖子上有一处污迹。它看起来像是某种体液。他浑身发抖。客厅里传来电视的声音。

Junling slid the fish into the hot oil of a pan, where they began to sizzle. As he watched, Zhu Feng could see a smudge on one of his mother’s sleeves. It looked like some kind of bodily fluid. He shuddered. From the living room, the television blared.

“爸爸今天出去了吗？” 他说。

“Did Dad go out today?” he said.

她在锅里加了一些红辣椒，撒上姜和葱末。“不知道。”

She added a few flecks of red chili to the pan and a sprinkling of ginger and chopped scallions. “Don’t know.”

“我打赌他呆在家里。”

“Bet he stayed home.”

当她翻转鱼时，她的嘴唇绷紧了。“生意很差，”她说。“他以前开出租车的时候好多了。”

Her lips tightened as she flipped the fish. “Business is poor,” she said. “It was better when he used to drive the taxi.”

“他开出租车？我不记得了。” 从朱枫记事起，父亲就一直开着同一辆摩托车，“莫迪，莫迪。”

“He drove a taxi? I don’t remember that.” For as long as Zhu Feng could recall, his father had been driving the same scooter, “Modi, modi.”

“在你出生之前。”

“Before you were born.”

“他为什么停下来？”

“Why did he stop?”

她沉默了。“事情发生后，”她最后说道，一边把鱼捞出来放在一个浅碗里。

She was silent. “It was after the incident,” she said at last, extracting the fish and laying them in a shallow bowl.

“什么事件？” 他说。

“What incident?” he said.

俊岭假装没听见；他仿佛又回到了十岁，想知道为什么他的父亲在大白天躺在床上，窗帘拉着。

Junling pretended not to hear him; it was like he was ten all over again, wondering why his father was lying in bed with the shades drawn in the middle of the day.

“告诉我吧，”他愤怒地说。“到底有什么大不了的？”

“Just tell me,” he said, exasperated. “What’s the big deal, anyway?”

“那是很久以前的事了。”

“It was so long ago.”

他等了。

He waited.

“当时很多学生都在抗议。” 她开始切卷心菜，但是动作很慢，好像她的心思在别处。

“At the time a lot of students were protesting.” She began chopping the cabbage, but slowly, as though her mind were elsewhere.

朱枫皱起眉头；这不是他所期望的。“什么样的抗议？” 他描绘了上周的村民：他们无力的旗帜，成堆的文件，拿着警棍的人。

Zhu Feng frowned; it was not what he had expected. “What kind of protests?” He pictured the villagers that previous week: their feeble banner, their stacks of papers, the men with their batons.

俊岭说，抗议活动正在全国各地发生。成千上万的学生走上街头，谈论民主、腐败和政治改革。许多出租车司机和其他工人也加入了他们的行列。“有很多不满，”她说。“腐败的政府官员太多了。”

The protests were happening all over the country, Junling said. Thousands of students were taking to the streets, talking about democracy, corruption, political reform. A number of taxi drivers joined them, and other workers, too. “A lot of grievances,” she said. “Too many rotten government officials.”

朱枫记得他很早以前就听说过这样的事情，他依稀记得一位历史教授在课堂上提到过这件事，然后就转移了话题。他努力回忆起其他细节。“这是在城里吗？” 他问。

Zhu Feng remembered he’d heard of something like that happening, long ago; he dimly recalled one history professor alluding to it during class before changing the subject. He strained to remember any other details. “This was in the city?” he asked.

“是的，”她一边说，一边把一把苍白的卷心菜端到锅里。“当时很混乱。他们掀翻了两辆警车。这种情况持续了好几天。肯定有数千名抗议者。”

“Yes,” she said, ferrying pale handfuls of cabbage to the pan. “It was chaotic. They flipped two police cars. It went on for days; there must have been thousands of protesters.”

这很难想象；他一生中从未见过这样的抗议。他希望他能看到它。

It was hard to imagine; he’d never seen a protest like that in his life. He wished he could’ve seen it.

“爸爸也参与其中？”

“Dad was involved?”

“那时他就不同了，”她说。有那么一刻，她几乎笑了。“那是一个不同的时代。人们非常理想主义。不像今天。”

“He was different then,” she said. For a moment she almost smiled. “It was a different era. People were very idealistic. Not like today.”

“然后发生了什么？”

“And then what happened?”

他妈妈把大蒜扔进锅里，加了盐。她没有回答，他又重复了一遍他的问题。“妈妈，我不再小了，”他说，她点点头，好像他说得有道理。

His mother threw the garlic into the pan and added salt. She didn’t answer, and he repeated his question. “Ma, I’m not small anymore,” he said, and she nodded, as though he’d made a good point.

有报纸报道称，抗议者携带刀具和炸药。其他人则说这只是放烟花——警察错了。人群不断增加：和平的，但他们举着各种各样的横幅，呼吁投票，呼吁新闻自由，人群自食其果，很快警察就开枪了。博阳当时爬上其中一辆翻倒的汽车，并挥舞着扩音器。他的大腿被击中。

There were newspaper reports that protesters were armed with knives and explosives. Others said it was just fireworks being set off—​the police were mistaken. The crowds kept multiplying: peaceful, but they were bearing all kinds of banners, calling for the vote, for a free press, the crowds fed upon themselves, and soon the police were firing. Boyang had clambered atop one of the tipped-over cars and was brandishing a megaphone at the time. He was hit in the thigh.

朱枫以为自己听错了。他的父亲，整天忙着照顾他的宠物鸟？他的父亲，被打败的摩托车司机，坐在一辆巡逻车上，拿着扩音器？

Zhu Feng thought he’d heard incorrectly. His father, who spent his days fussing over his pet bird? His father, defeated scooter driver, atop a patrol car, with a megaphone?

“警察说是开枪警告，但还是打中了三个人。”俊岭一边用勺子搅拌着白菜一边说道。“他们说这是一次意外。”

“The police said they were warning shots, but three people got hit anyway,” Junling said, stirring the cabbage with a spoon. “They said it was an accident.”

“打？”

“Hit?”

“其中一个被杀了。”

“One of them killed.”

朱枫不知道该说什么。“所以他不再开出租车了？”

Zhu Feng didn’t know what to say. “So he stopped driving a taxi?”

“他们不会给他颁发许可，”她实事求是地说。“他花了很多年才重新站起来。”

“They wouldn’t license him,” she said matter-of-factly. “It took him years to get back on his feet again.”

“无论如何，那是很久以前的事了，”她说。电视外面正在播放奢侈男士古龙水的广告。

“Anyway, it was a long time ago,” she said. Outside the television was playing a commercial for luxury men’s cologne.

她熄灭了锅底的火焰。“来吧，”她说。“我们吃饭吧。”

She extinguished the flame below the pan. “Come on,” she said. “Let’s eat.”

他们吃着饭，没有说话，电视的声音在背景中吵闹。他的母亲盯着她的盘子。博阳眼角的余光看到屏幕上正在发生一场武术打斗，风格很浓重，男人们在空中倒飞，蹲下和踢腿倒带倒转，刀子向后整齐地落回枪套里。 。一个身穿灰衣、盘着发髻的女子站在那里，歇斯底里地叫着，叫道：“伟远！威远！” 朱枫知道这部剧，它的名字叫《时间时钟》，它的中心情节就是时间周期性地以随机的间隔倒退，让所有的人物都感到困惑。这是一场愚蠢的表演。

They ate without speaking, the sound of the television noisy in the background. His mother stared at her plate. Boyang, out of the corner of his eye, watched a martial arts fight happening on the screen, heavily stylized, men flying backward in the sky, their crouches and kicks rewound and shown in reverse, knives going backward and landing neatly back in their holsters. A woman clad in gray with her hair in a topknot stood making hysterical noises as they flew around, calling, “Wei-yuan! Wei-yuan!” Zhu Feng knew the show, it was called Time Clock, and its central plot involved the fact that, periodically, time moved backward at random intervals, confusing all the characters. It was a stupid show.

他不安地看着父亲。“爸爸，”他说，试图回忆起那天下午早些时候的决心，“我想知道我是否可以借点钱。”

He looked uneasily at his father. “Dad,” he said, trying to recall his resolve from earlier that afternoon, “I wondered if I could maybe borrow some money.”

他的父亲咕哝着。“做什么的？”

His father grunted. “What for?”

朱枫没有看他的眼睛。“这很复杂，”他说。他想起母亲在厨房里说过的话——腐败官员太多了——他感到胸口一阵绞痛。也许他们不需要听整个故事。

Zhu Feng didn’t meet his eyes. “It’s complicated,” he said. He thought of what his mother had said in the kitchen—​too many rotten officials—​and felt something twist in his chest. Maybe they didn’t need to hear the whole story.

“我欠一个朋友钱，”他说。

“I owe money to a friend,” he said.

“你没有工作吗？”

“Don’t you have a job?”

“这是以前的事了，”他说。

“This was from before,” he said.

“什么朋友？”

“What friend?”

“李学士。”

“Li Xueshi.”

“你不应该向朋友借钱。难道你不知道你像个乞丐一样到处乱跑是什么感觉吗？”

“You shouldn’t borrow money from friends. Don’t you know how it looks, to have you going around like a beggar?”

“好吧，我知道我不应该这么做，”他说，无法忍受这种悬念，想要结束这一切。“那你能不能——”

“Right, I know I shouldn’t have,” he said, unable to bear the suspense, wanting to get it over with. “So could you—”

他的父亲打断了他的话。“多少？”

His father interrupted him. “How much?”

“十五万元。”

“One hundred fifty thousand yuan.”

伯阳一脸愕然，随即笑而不语。“我哪来那么多钱？” 祝枫等他再说什么，但也仅此而已。

Boyang looked genuinely astonished, then laughed without mirth. “Where would I have that much money?” Zhu Feng waited for him to say something further, but that was all.

君凌“啪”的一声丢掉了筷子。“十五万元。”她说，然后大声重复了这个数字。她看着他，朱枫被她脸上的恐惧所震惊。“我不明白，”她说。“你怎么会欠这么多？”

Junling had dropped her chopsticks with a clatter. “One hundred fifty thousand yuan,” she said, and then repeated the sum out loud. She looked at him, and Zhu Feng was struck by the fear on her face. “I don’t understand,” she said. “How could you owe so much?”

沉默扩大并充满了整个桌子。朱枫等着他们再说什么，献上什么，什么都可以，但什么也没有。一种空虚的感觉悄悄袭上他的心头：他怀疑恐慌即将来临。“算了，”他咕哝道。

The silence expanded and filled the table. Zhu Feng waited for them to say something else, to offer something, anything, but there was nothing. A hollow feeling was stealing over him: panic, he suspected, was not far behind. “Forget it,” he mumbled.

他又给自己端了一些卷心菜，试图掩饰手上的颤抖。他不应该费心去问他们，他怨恨地想。对他们抱有任何期望是没有用的。

He served himself some more cabbage, trying to camouflage the shaking in his hands. He shouldn’t have bothered asking them, he thought resentfully. It was useless to expect anything of them.

又咬了几口后，他推开椅子，离开了桌子。他回到自己的房间，躺了下来，努力不去想刚刚发生的事情。相反，他想到了母亲对博阳所说的话，这个故事几乎不可能与抚养他长大的人相符。他试图想象他父亲的大腿被子弹击中的情景。他在想什么？那时的他是一个什么样的人呢？当然，更加愤怒，更加充满活力。他再次想象了当时的场景，只是现在，就像时间时钟一样，子弹向后移动，从他父亲的大腿中射出，他的大腿被密封起来，裤子上的洞愈合了，子弹扭转了它的轨迹，穿过天空，回到了枪管中。解雇了它。他的父亲可能仍然不会富有。但也许他会坚强。

After a few more bites, he pushed back his chair and left the table. He went to his room and lay down, trying not to think about what had just occurred. Instead he thought about what his mother had said about Boyang, a story nearly impossible to square with the man who had raised him. He tried to picture his father getting struck in the thigh with a bullet. What had he been thinking? What kind of man had he been then? Angrier, surely, more full of life. He pictured the scene again, only now, like Time Clock, the bullets moving backward, out of his father’s thigh, his thigh sealing up, the hole in his pants healing, the bullet reversing its trajectory through the sky, back into the barrel that fired it. His father probably still wouldn’t be rich. But maybe he’d be strong.

外面，他的母亲正在叮叮当当地清理盘子。他听到电视静音了，浴室里传来水声，还有父母关门的声音。他翻身侧身，拉起床单。

Outside, his mother was clearing dishes with a clatter. He heard the television being silenced, water sounding in the bathroom, and the click of his parents’ door as it shut. He turned on his side and pulled the sheet up.

再坚持几天，他告诉自己。只要再坚持几天，你就会好起来的。所有那些令人焦虑的提神，所有那些时间标记——有什么意义呢？他的工作时间由小时、分钟、秒组成——他还年轻，他有时间。这就是世界运转的方式：你不能屈服，不能害怕。他告诉自己，有什么东西会闯入这个缺口。市场会自行调整，政府会干预。当他渐渐入睡时，他想，世界上有无数的机会等待着展开。他只需伸出手即可。

Give it a few more days, he told himself. Just a few more days and you will be fine. All that anxious refreshing, all that marking of time—what was the point? He had days to work with, which were made up of hours, made of minutes, made of seconds—​he was young, he had time. This was the way the world worked: you couldn’t buckle over, couldn’t be afraid. Something would step into the breach, he told himself. The market would straighten itself out, the government was going to intervene. The world was a profusion of opportunities waiting to be unfolded, he thought as he drifted off to sleep. He had only to stretch out his hand.

美丽的国家

Beautiful Country

当我们坐在车里时，他发现了一组摇摇欲坠的摊位，上面挂着手绘标志，然后把车停在了路边。埃里克（Eric）无法抗拒试图向他推销东西的笔迹，无论是儿童柠檬水摊还是小酒馆黑板上的漩涡状文字，或者在这种情况下，高速公路标志上写着“本土工艺品”。

We are riding in the car when he spots a set of ramshackle stalls with hand-painted signs and pulls over. Eric can’t resist the sight of handwriting trying to sell him things, whether it’s a kid’s lemonade stand or swirly script on a bistro chalkboard, or in this case, a highway sign saying NATIVE CRAFTS.

我尽量避免盯着任何一只手镯看太久，但埃里克还是拿起了一只。“这是真正的绿松石，”女人说，并帮助他把它滑过我不情愿的手腕。

I try to avoid looking too long at any one bracelet but Eric picks one up anyway. “It’s genuine turquoise,” the woman says, and helps him slide it over my unwilling wrist.

珠子太大，银色太亮。“我没事，”我告诉他。

The beads are too bulky, the silver too bright. “I’m okay,” I tell him.

“它很漂亮，”他说。“此外，我们正在支持当地经济。” 他不顾我的抗议，递给她二十块钱。

“It’s beautiful,” he says. “Besides, we’re supporting the local economy.” He hands her a twenty over my protests.

我勉强向他道谢，他点点头。“你喜欢绿松石，”他说，他为自己记得我短暂地原谅他的慷慨而感到自豪。

I thank him reluctantly, and he nods. “You like turquoise,” he says, so proud of himself for remembering that I briefly forgive him his generosity.

再往下，一位妇女正在出售用生皮和羽毛制成的捕梦网。他询问有关当地美食的建议，当她推荐附近的一家快餐店时，他似乎很失望。他问她自己是否使用捕梦网，她犹豫了一下才答应。

Farther down, a woman is selling dream catchers made from rawhide and feathers. He asks for tips on good local food, and seems disappointed when she recommends a fast-food joint nearby. He asks whether she uses dream catchers herself, and she hesitates before saying yes.

他买了两件，一件给他的母亲，一件给他的妹妹。因为我对自己对手镯缺乏热情感到内疚，所以在这次旅行中，我买了一幅便宜的明信片大小的沙画，我看到他在注视着，这是一个用粉红色和米色沙子制成的粗糙几何图形。我自己并不欣赏，但我付了钱给那位女士，并仔细数了数她递给我的钞票并将其折进我的钱包里。

He buys two, one for his mother and one for his sister. And because I feel guilty about my lack of enthusiasm for the bracelet, for this trip, I buy a cheap, postcard-size sand painting I see him eyeing, a crude geometric figure made from pink and beige sand. I don’t admire it myself, but I pay the woman and carefully count and fold the bills she hands me into my wallet.

当我们回到车上时，他转向我。“只是想让你知道，你不应该在别人面前计算变化，”他说。

When we get back in the car, he turns to me. “Just so you know, you shouldn’t count the change like that in front of someone,” he says.

“为什么不？” 我疑惑地问道。

“Why not?” I ask, mystified.

“这很粗鲁，”他告诉我。我的脸颊发烫。即使在这个国家呆了十多年，我仍然会被抓住。

“It’s rude,” he tells me. My cheeks get hot. Even after more than a decade in this country, I’m still getting caught out.

“没关系，”他和蔼地说。“你不知道。”

“It’s okay,” he says kindly. “You didn’t know.”

 

当我们开车进入公园时，天空布满了长长的、厚厚的云层。天色已晚，树上闪烁着黄色的光斑。我告诉他我们可能会错过日落。“明天还会有一场，”我说。

The sky is lined with furrows of long, heavy clouds as we drive into the park. It’s late in the day, yellow panels of light in the trees. I tell him we’re probably going to miss the sunset. “There’ll be another one tomorrow,” I say.

他没有回答，而是踩下了油门。在他无忧无虑的外表下，埃里克有一种不能容忍失败的坚强，无论如何，他所爱的人也不能容忍失败。前天晚上，当他下班回家时，我在沙发上迎接他，仍然穿着睡衣，就像我一整天一样。在医院加班一周，我已经筋疲力尽了。“你真干练，”我说，努力让自己的声音听起来很高兴，感觉到他衬衫上的淀粉皱了起来。“就像薯片一样。”

He doesn’t answer, but pushes down on the gas. Beneath his happy-go-lucky air, there’s a hardness in Eric that doesn’t tolerate failure, not in the people he loves, anyway. The night before last, when he got home from work, I greeted him on the couch, still in pajamas, as I’d been all day. It had been a week of extra shifts at the hospital, and I was drained. “You’re so crisp,” I said, trying to sound cheerful, feeling the starch in his shirt crinkle. “Like a potato chip.”

“而你就像一个土豆，”他说，用力地揉乱我的头发。“走吧，我们带你离开家。”

“And you’re like a potato,” he said, ruffling my hair harder than necessary. “Come on, let’s get you out of the house.”

大峡谷的树木参差不齐，在风中摇晃。太阳已经很低了，等待着落下。我们把车停在一个风景区，手拉手朝边缘走去。峡谷在我们面前延伸，到处是阴影和橙色的悬崖，还有一条白色的河流。埃里克用手臂做了一个圈，假装把我困在里面，就像捕蝴蝶的网一样，我假装笑了。

The trees at the Grand Canyon are scraggly and shake in the wind. The sun is low and waiting to fall. We park at an outlook and walk toward the edge, hand in hand. The canyon stretches before us, all shadow and orange cliffs and a white finger of river. Eric makes a hoop with his arm and pretends to catch me in it, like a butterfly net, and I pretend to laugh.

我们周围有戴帽子的退休人员、带着蠕动孩子的家庭以及说着不同语言的游客。我听到了几句普通话：一辆中国年轻旅行者的SUV刚刚停了下来，我强​​忍着立即冲过去打招呼的冲动。经过一天的车程穿过空旷的风景后，人群让人松了口气。我想知道幽闭恐惧症的反面是什么。有什么词可以形容只有在人群中才能放松的感觉？

Around us are retirees in hats, families with squirming children, and tourists speaking different tongues. I catch a few snips of Mandarin: an SUV of young Chinese travelers has just parked, and I stifle the urge to immediately rush over and say hi. After a day’s drive across empty landscapes, the crowds are a relief. What’s the opposite of claustrophobia, I wonder. What’s the word for feeling you can relax only in a crowd?

再往下，一个留着山羊胡的男人拿出一把吉他，啪地一声走开。乐器停顿下来，男人的声音浑厚、柔和、美丽。我抬头对埃里克微笑，但他转过脸去。“我们找个安静点的地方吧，”他说。

Farther down, a man with a goatee takes out a guitar and plunks away. The instrument is halting, the man’s voice rich and creamy and beautiful. I look up to smile at Eric, but he’s turned away. “Let’s find someplace quieter,” he says.

他走向停车场的一侧，也就是护栏的尽头，我跟着他。大地被烧成橙色，崎岖不平。我可以看到引起他注意的东西——一群平坦的岩石从五十英尺外的壁架上伸出，然后陡峭地向下攀爬——然后我翻了个白眼。

He heads to the side of the lot, where the guardrail ends, and I follow. The earth is burnt orange and craggy. I can see what’s caught his eye—​a cluster of flat rocks jutting out from a ledge that’s fifty feet away and a steep scramble down—​and roll my eyes.

“我们就从这里看吧，”我说。

“Let’s just watch it from here,” I say.

“这样好多了，”他说道，已经领先了四步。

“This is better,” he says, already four paces ahead.

我们第一次见面不久，当我刚从护士学校毕业时，他坚持带我去背包旅行。“你会喜欢的，”他告诉我。他带我去冰川徒步，我很害怕每隔几英尺冰川就会破裂，把我送进冰冷的水中。我们在一条森林小路上徒步旅行，那里有很多蚊虫，它们会进入你的眼睛。我尽职尽责地给父母发了照片，比如：“看！树！你的女儿在美国，享受着大自然的美景！” 然而，自从我们搬到图森后，埃里克对户外活动的热爱主要是一个人的事情。大约每年，他和他的伙伴们都会去犹他州或科罗拉多州的某个地方露营。“你应该来，”他会说。“这对你有好处。” 我告诉他我以前见过树。

Not long after we first met, when I was right out of nursing school, he insisted on taking me backpacking. “You’ll love it,” he told me. He took me to hike a glacier, where I was terrified every few feet it would crack and send me into freezing water. We hiked a forest trail with gnats so thick they got in your eyes. I sent dutiful photos to my parents, like: “Look! Trees! Your daughter in America, enjoying nature’s splendors!” Since we moved to Tucson, though, Eric’s love of the great outdoors has been mostly a solo affair. Every year or so, he and his buddies will go camp somewhere, Utah or Colorado. “You should come,” he’ll say. “It’ll be good for you.” I tell him I’ve seen trees before.

我现在跟着他，感觉我的腿开始摇晃。太阳落山后，空气中弥漫着一股新的寒意，我希望我带了一件夹克。

I follow him now, feeling my legs start to wobble. There’s a new chill in the air as the sun retreats, and I wish that I’d brought a jacket.

“颜色太棒了，”他兴奋地回道。“它们让我想起我们小时候参观过这片石化森林的情景。” 埃里克（Eric）的父母大学毕业后驾驶一辆大众 Bug 越野行驶，后来成为股票经纪人，偶尔与十几岁的孩子一起抽烟。他们就是这样的父母。

“The colors are so great,” he calls back exuberantly. “They remind me of when we visited this petrified forest as kids.” Eric’s parents drove a VW Bug cross-country after college, before becoming stockbrokers who occasionally smoked joints with their teenage kids. They were those kinds of parents.

“树木看起来很害怕吗？” 我说。

“Did the trees look scared?” I say.

他笑了，等我爬下来，小心翼翼地向旁边移动。

He laughs, and waits for me as I clamber down, gingerly moving sideways.

“看，你很好，”他说。

“See, you’re fine,” he says.

太阳是一个小小的蛋黄点，在下沉时牵引着天空中所有的亮度。我们找到了一个白垩岩石架，可以坐在距离边缘几英尺远的地方。我深吸了几口气，尽量不低头。风吹不到我们这里。

The sun is a tiny dot of egg yolk, pulling all the brightness in the sky with it as it sinks. We find a shelf of chalky rock to sit on, several feet back from the edge. I take a few deliberate breaths and try not to look down. The wind doesn’t reach us here.

他用手臂搂住我。“很漂亮，不是吗，泡菜？” 他带着专有的光芒低声说道，我点点头。

He puts his arm around me. “Beautiful, isn’t it, pickle?” he whispers with a proprietary glow, and I nod.

从这个角度看，峡谷处于阴影之中，与我之前买的加油站明信片完全不同，明信片上展示着日落时熔化的金色远景，一美元三张。我告诉自己要放松并享受这一刻。我告诉自己今年埃里克会升职，我会找到更好的工作，我们最终会结婚。我告诉自己不要太担心，因为上周我在他车的地板上发现了一个口红盒，但那不是我的。在我们八年的约会中，埃里克只出轨过一次，从那以后，我们一直很幸福。医院里的护士告诉我，我很幸运，他们和更糟糕的人有过关系。

From this angle, the canyon is in shadow, nothing like the gas station postcards I bought earlier showing a molten gold vista at sunset, three for a dollar. I tell myself to relax and enjoy the moment. I tell myself this will be the year that Eric gets his promotion, that I will find a better job, and we will get married at last. I tell myself not to be too concerned that I found a lipstick case on the floor of his car last week, one that wasn’t mine. In our eight years of dating, Eric has been unfaithful just once, and since then, we’ve been happy. There are nurses at the hospital who tell me that I’m lucky, they’ve been in relationships with worse.

“就这样，”他说。我过了一会儿才意识到他在谈论太阳。

“There it goes,” he says. It takes me a moment to realize he’s talking about the sun.

回头望去，一辆旅游巴士已经停了下来，几十名中国游客已经下了车。他们是我以前在美国从未见过的游客：年纪更大，脸色黝黑，满是皱纹，就像中国大城市的农民工一样，戴着配套的红白帽子，手里拿着新的可支配现金。再往下看，一群俄罗斯人拿着大相机在周围转来转去，一对有着一模一样的白金头发、臀部纤细的情侣正在栏杆旁接吻。

Back at the outlook, a tour bus has parked and a couple dozen Chinese tourists have descended. They’re the kind of tourists I never used to see in the U.S.: older, faces dark and wrinkled like those of migrant workers in large Chinese cities, wearing matching red-and-white hats, flush with newly disposable cash. Farther down, a group of Russians are milling around with big cameras, and a slim-hipped couple with identical platinum hair is kissing by the railing.

我们回到车里，埃里克摇下车窗，让山艾树的香味扑面而来。

We get back in the car and Eric rolls down the windows, letting the scent of sagebrush rush in.

“现在所有的国家公园都非常拥挤，”我们继续前行时他说道。“当我们还是孩子的时候，从来没有这样过。”

“All the national parks are so crowded now,” he says as we drive on. “When we were kids, it was never like this.”

我什么也没说。

I don’t say anything.

他说，去年春天的一次公路旅行中，他和朋友们在黄石公园遭遇了长达一个小时的交通堵塞，因为太多的汽车停下来观看草地上嬉戏的小熊。“这太荒谬了，”他摇着头说道。“我的意思是，来吧，人们，别打扰他们。”

During a road trip last spring, he says, he and his buddies hit an hour-long traffic jam in Yellowstone, after too many cars stopped to look at bear cubs gamboling in a meadow. “It was ridiculous,” he says, shaking his head. “I mean, come on, people, leave them alone.”

我心想，我会是拍摄熊的人之一。然后，当埃里克开始谈论走扁带和自由攀登时，我看着窗外，想着冬眠：睡着了，醒来迎接新的季节是多么美妙。

I think to myself, I would have been one of the people photographing the bears. Then, as Eric starts talking about slacklining and free climbs, I look out the window and think about hibernation: how wonderful, to fall asleep and wake up to a new season.

 

我们在一家拥挤的小餐馆吃饭，那里的玻璃杯里装着冰水，杯子有拳击手套那么大，还有一种叫做“Shark-o-Rama”的东西，我们旁边的桌子点了一种电蓝色的饮料，上面放着鲨鱼软糖和生奶油。

We eat at a crowded diner that serves ice water in glasses as big as boxing gloves and something called a Shark-o-Rama, which the table beside us orders, an electric-blue drink with shark gummies and whipped cream on top.

女服务员很长时间不接受我们的订单，以至于我变得不耐烦，把它们推到自己身上，而不是诉诸埃里克喜欢的微妙的眼神交流。“我们很着急，”我告诉她，尽管我们并不匆忙，因为我认为否则还需要一个小时才能得到服务。我对大多数事情都很有耐心，但食物除外。

The waitress doesn’t take our orders for so long that I grow impatient and march them over myself, rather than resort to the delicate ballet of eye contact that Eric prefers. “We’re in a hurry,” I tell her, even though we’re not, because I assume otherwise it’ll take another hour to get served. I am patient about most things, but not food.

我们吃饭时，埃里克向我讲述了他公司的一位董事的故事，他最近从中国出差回来。“他的女朋友想要一个来自中国的花瓶，但他没有时间去购物，”他说。“所以他回来后就从一号码头给她买了一件。”

As we eat, Eric tells me about a director at his firm who recently returned from a business trip to China. “His girlfriend wanted a vase from China, but he didn’t have time to shop,” he said. “So he just bought her one from Pier One when he got back.”

“哈哈，”我说。

“Ha ha,” I say.

去年我们结婚纪念日时，埃里克第一次和我一起来中国。他用他的“坏你好”迷住了我的父母，并给他们带来了好时巧克力棒作为礼物，没有人忍心告诉他当地超市已经卖了很多年了。他拍摄了餐馆里的中式英语和街上下棋的老人的照片。他喜欢这里的食物，但承认自己对长城感到失望，因为长城上挤满了人，他说，人群冲浪比攀爬更容易。“抱歉，我只是想说实话，”他告诉我，我心想，有时候撒谎是可以的。

For our anniversary last year, Eric came with me to visit China for the first time. He charmed my parents with his bad ni haos and brought them gifts of Hershey bars, which no one had the heart to tell him local supermarkets had sold for years. He snapped photos of Chinglish at restaurants and of old men playing chess in the streets. He liked the food but confessed himself disappointed in the Great Wall, which was so crowded with people, he said, that it would’ve been easier to crowd-surf than climb. “Sorry, I just wanted to be honest,” he told me, and I thought to myself, Sometimes it’s okay to lie.

就像我医院的护士一样，每个人都认为他很英俊，尽管我能感觉到我父母的怀疑，因为他已经和他们的女儿在一起这么久了，而且不知何故没有求婚。“我讨厌你长得这么好看。”我们开始约会后，我曾经半开玩笑地告诉他。“这意味着你可以逃脱任何惩罚。” 他没有争辩。

Like the nurses at my hospital, everyone thought he was so handsome, even as I could sense my parents’ skepticism that he had been with their daughter for so long and somehow not proposed. “I hate that you’re so good-looking,” I once told him after we’d started dating, only partly in jest. “It means you can get away with anything.” He didn’t argue.

 

第二天早上，我们在游客中心停留，然后出发去徒步旅行。我装满水瓶并研究一个解释沉积岩和变质岩之间差异的标志。埃里克拿到了一张地图，我们又开了一英里，然后停在步道起点并出发。我们走路时他吹口哨，那声音让我很恼火。

The next morning, we stop at the visitors’ center before heading out for a hike. I fill our water bottles and study a sign explaining the differences between sedimentary and metamorphic rocks. Eric gets a map and we drive another mile before parking at a trailhead and setting out. He is whistling as we walk, and the sound of it grates on me.

“请停下来，”我说，他也这么做了。

“Please stop,” I say, and he does.

在薄薄的晨光下，大峡谷呈现出童话般的橙色、铁锈色和雾蓝色的景象。我们所走的小路沿着它的边缘。这条路已经铺好了，结果很受推着婴儿车的女性和尾部缓慢移动、下垂的退休人员的欢迎，我们经常路过。我能感觉到埃里克想要超越他们的决心，但也知道这不会发生。步道起点停车场挤满了人。无论如何，我不知道为什么他总是如此专注于独处大自然，就像他是一个在聚会上试图围堵一个漂亮女孩的人一样。

Seen in the thin morning light, the Grand Canyon is a vision of fairy-tale orange and rust and misty blue. The trail we’re on follows its rim. It’s paved and turns out to be popular with women with strollers and retirees with slow-moving, pendulous rears, which we keep passing. I can sense Eric’s determination to overtake them all, and also that it’s not going to happen. The trailhead parking lot was packed. I don’t know why he’s always so fixated on getting Mother Nature by herself, anyway, like he’s a guy at a party trying to corner a pretty girl.

有那么一刻，我回想起我在中国东北大连的童年。周末，全家人都会去附近的公园游览，那里有卖风筝和小吃的欢快摊位，有尖叫的孩子和散落的花生壳，还有庄严漫步的老人，手持收音机播放着高亢的中国戏曲。每个人都对10元的票价抱怨不已，但公园每年春天引进数百株郁金香，这还是值得的。这并不自然，但很好。

For a moment I flash back to my childhood in Dalian, northeast China. On weekends, families would visit the nearby park, with its cheerful stands selling kites and snacks, its shrieking children and litter of peanut shells, and elderly men who would stroll solemnly, equipped with handheld radios blasting high-pitched Chinese opera. Everyone grumbled over the 10-yuan ticket price, but it paid for the park to bring in hundreds of tulips, which they planted every spring. It wasn’t natural, but it was nice.

“也许我们可以今年夏天回中国，”他说道，仿佛读懂了我的心思。

“Maybe we could go back to China this summer,” he says, as though reading my mind.

“我愿意，”我说。“你知道，我的父母年纪越来越大了。” 晚上有时我睡不着，担心他们会滑倒或摔倒，而我却在千里之外的这里。每次我看到它们，它们都比上一次更灰暗、更脆弱。

“I’d like that,” I say. “My parents are getting older, you know.” At night sometimes I lie awake and worry that they’ll slip and fall or get into an accident while I am here, so many thousands of miles away. Each time I see them, they are more gray and brittle than the last.

“他们只有六十多岁，”他说。“和我的一样。”

“They’re only in their sixties,” he says. “Same as mine.”

但他的父母是那种六十岁的人，他们计划与其他精力充沛的退休人员一起去马丘比丘徒步旅行，并在朋友的续誓仪式上跳伦巴舞。我的人是这样的人，他们一生的前三十年都在田里工作，然后在半导体工厂里，将微小的零件安装到其他微小的零件中，直到他们的手指和背部都弯曲了。如果不是我在政府工作的叔叔，我永远不会有出国留学的机会。

But his parents are the kind of sixty-year-olds who plan hikes on Machu Picchu with other energetic retirees, and dance the rumba at their friends’ vow-renewal ceremonies. Mine are the kind who worked in the fields the first thirty years of their lives, and then in a semiconductor factory, fitting tiny parts inside of other tiny parts, until their fingers and backs were crooked. If it weren’t for my uncle, who worked for the government, I never would’ve had the chance to study abroad.

我正要告诉他，这时一个身材苗条的女人穿着蓝色紧身裤和洋红色上衣慢跑着经过。她有着锐利的蓝眼睛和灰金色的头发，只有她的皮肤暴露了她的年龄，皱纹很细，看起来就像沙漠龟一样。当我们让开她的路时，她迅速地用指责的目光瞪了我们一眼，她的眼神也像乌龟一样，我们互相看了一眼，都忍住笑了。

I’m about to tell him that when a trim woman jogs by in tight blue leggings and a magenta top. She has piercing blue eyes and ash-blond hair, and only her skin gives her age away, so finely crinkled it looks like that of a desert turtle. She gives us a quick, accusing stare as we move out of her way, also so turtle-like that we look at each other and stifle a laugh.

“年龄只是一个数字，”埃里克说。

“Age is just a number,” Eric says.

 

那天晚上，我给我的老朋友杰西卡打了电话，她即使穿着手术服，也是那么的雕像般美丽，她的声音像男人一样低沉而沙哑，总是让每个人都感到惊讶。她几年前搬走了，我可以从她的语气中听到缅因州的声音：她穿着温暖的毛衣，毛茸茸的靴子，以及她的两个孩子都睡着了的轻松感，就像他们的两个天使一样。我的教女们。我告诉她这里的颜色，云朵在风景上投射出不断变化的形状的方式，就像一个缓慢漂流的蓝色嵌合体。

That night, I call my old friend Jessica, who, even in scrubs, was so statuesque and beautiful that the sound of her voice, deep and throaty like a man’s, always caught everyone by surprise. She moved away years ago, and I can hear the sound of Maine in her tone: the warm sweater she’s wearing, the fuzzy boots, and the ease that comes with the fact that both her children are asleep, like the two angels they are. My goddaughters. I tell her about the colors here, the way the clouds cast ever-shifting shapes on the landscape, a slow-drifting blue chimera.

“所以你原谅了他，”她说。

“So you’re forgiving him,” she says.

“没有什么可以原谅的，”我告诉她。“这只是一管口红。”

“There’s nothing to forgive,” I tell her. “It was just one tube of lipstick.”

她说：“大峡谷很美。这并不意味着他不是一个混蛋。”

She says, “The Grand Canyon is beautiful. That doesn’t mean he isn’t a jerk.”

“关系在于信任，”我说道，并对我声音中的说教语气感到惊讶。这听起来很熟悉，然后我意识到这是从我最近观看的所有日间脱口秀节目中借用的。

“Relationships are about trust,” I say, and wonder at the preachy tone in my voice. It sounds familiar, and then I realize it’s borrowed from all the daytime talk shows that I’ve been watching lately.

我们都很安静。我可以想象她皱着眉头的样子，就像她在编织或做填字游戏时可能把手机塞在肩上的样子，总是很忙，把事情做好。埃里克一直很喜欢她。当我们第一次到达图森时，她还是单身，经历了艰难的一天后，我们会和同一层楼的其他女孩一起出去，她会猛烈地击球，甩动长发，喝得比酒吧里的每个人都喝得多。

We are both quiet. I can picture her frown, the way she’s probably tucking the phone against her shoulder as she knits or maybe does a crossword, always busy, getting things done. Eric always liked her. Back when we’d first arrived in Tucson and she was still single, after a rough day we would go out with the other girls on our floor and she would slam down shots and toss her long hair and outdrink everyone in the bar.

“你们在一起已经八年了，”她说。“他还在等什么？”

“You’ve been together eight years,” she says. “What is he waiting for?”

我回想起埃里克和我第一次搬到一起后的最初几天，看到我们的书排在同一个书架上、共用一袋杂货时，我感到很兴奋。有一次，在图森的一场暴雨中，我们的公寓收到了一张新地毯——这是我们一起买的第一件大东西——我们躺在上面，谈论了我们对未来的希望。我告诉他，我想象孩子们穿着糖果色的衣服在草地上奔跑，在沙箱里玩耍的日子，以及像小兔子一样温柔的幼儿园老师。他说这听起来不错。

I think back to the early days after Eric and I first moved in together, the exhilaration of seeing our books lined up on the same shelves, of a shared bag of groceries. Once, during a rainstorm in Tucson, after a new carpet had been delivered to our apartment—​the first big thing we’d bought together—​we lay on it and talked about our hopes for the future. I told him I pictured children running on grass wearing candy-colored clothes, days spent playing in sandboxes and kindergarten teachers gentle as bunny rabbits. He said that sounded nice.

“他本可以载某人下班回家，”我说。

“He could have given someone a ride home from work,” I say.

 

午餐后，在返回南方的路上，我告诉埃里克，“美国”这个名字在中文中的意思是“美丽的国家”。我向他承认，当我很小的时候，我想象过一片色彩柔和的花地。我说，在电视节目中，看到这么多美国人从事普通工作——教师和杂工——却仍然住在巨大的房子里，草坪就像绿色的护城河，这让我感到震惊。

After lunch, on our way back south, I tell Eric that the name “America” in Chinese, Meiguo, means “beautiful country.” When I was very young, I confess to him, I pictured a pastel-tinted land of flowers. On TV shows, I say, the sight of so many Americans who worked ordinary jobs—​teachers and handymen—​and still lived in enormous houses, with lawns like green moats, astounded me.

“在中国，我们会称它们为别墅，”我说。

“In China, we would’ve called them villas,” I say.

“我知道，”他说。“你已经告诉过我了。”

“I know,” he says. “You’ve told me.”

他心不在焉，扫视着地平线寻找下雨的迹象。空气变得越来越凝重，就像暴风雨来临前一样。我的一部分希望它会倾盆大雨，淹没道路，就像新闻中所说的那样，这是一场真正的“天气事件”。在图森，山洪爆发几乎是圣经中的事。一瞬间，大地干得像骨头一样，仙人掌又干又瘦。接下来，大雨倾盆而下，愤怒的上帝用一千块小石头敲打城市，街道像河流一样蜿蜒。这是我见过的最接近世界末日的事情，它总是一个奇迹，一种解脱。

He is distracted, scanning the horizon for signs of rain. The air has been getting heavy, the way it does before a storm. Part of me hopes it will pour, flood the roads, a real “weather event,” like they say on the news. In Tucson, the flash floods are nearly biblical. One moment, the land is dry as a bone, the saguaros parched and skinny. The next, the rain is lashing down, the sound of an angry god pummeling the city with a thousand tiny stones, and the streets course like rivers. It’s the closest thing I’ve ever seen to an apocalypse, and it’s always a wonder, a relief.

之后，海水退去，仙人掌的褶子长满并消失。太阳落山了，大地再次变成橙色。美国确实很美——非常美丽——但亚利桑那州，我有时告诉我家乡的朋友，就像生活在火星上一样。

Afterward, the waters recede and the saguaros’ pleats grow full and disappear. The sun beats down and the land turns orange once more. America is indeed very mei—​very beautiful—​but Arizona, I sometimes tell my friends back home, is like living on Mars.

我看着埃里克，想知道他在想什么，但没有问。当我们刚开始约会时，我一直问他，最后他告诉我请停止。“我是一本打开的书，”他说。“你所看到的就是你得到的。” 当我第一次发现几年前他见过的那个女人是他的客户时，他也是这样：在我与他对质后，他点点头，以同样直截了当的方式说，他们已经睡过两次了，他很抱歉。“我希望这件事没有发生。”他实事求是地说，仿佛在描述一些与他无关的事情。

I look at Eric and wonder what he’s thinking, but don’t ask. When we first started dating, I’d ask him all the time, and finally he told me to please stop. “I’m an open book,” he said. “What you see is what you get.” He was that way, too, when I first found out about the woman he’d been seeing a few years ago, a client of his: after I confronted him, he had nodded and said, in just as straightforward a manner, that they had slept together twice and he was very sorry. “I wish it hadn’t happened,” he’d said matter-of-factly, as though describing something that hadn’t actually involved him.

外面，雨开始下得又大又快。“我们也许应该找个地方停车，”他说。这是一条狭窄的双车道高速公路，不容许打滑。他曾经告诉我，他祖母的父母都在不同的车祸中丧生，所以从十几岁起，他一直是一个小心的司机。这是我喜欢他的地方之一，他在道路上的谨慎，以及他驾驶时的安全感。有一次我试着向杰西卡解释，当我们一起在车里时，我和他在一起感到多么幸福。

Outside, the rain starts coming down hard and fast. “We should maybe find a place to pull over,” he says. It’s a narrow two-lane highway, not forgiving for skids. He told me once that his grandmother’s parents had both died in separate car crashes, and so he’s always been a careful driver, ever since he was a teenager. It’s one of the things I like about him, his caution on roads, the safety that comes with him behind the wheel. I tried explaining that to Jessica once, how happy I feel with him when we’re together in the car.

“当然，”她说。“这是一种你正在前进的感觉。”

“Sure,” she said. “It’s the feeling that you’re moving forward.”

 

当雨开始倾盆而下时，我们把车停在路边一个巨大的白色建筑里寻求庇护，上面写着“耶稣节省了廉价汽油纪念品”。一侧是一个带有两个加油站的摊位，里面是一家巨大的百花香商店，出售亚利桑那州车牌的廉价磁铁，上面有不同女孩和男孩的名字，杯子上写着“今天有人认为你很棒”等标语没有咖啡，没有员工。玻璃柜里有微型马、牛仔和戴着树脂铸造羽毛头饰的当地人，还有一两只莫名其妙的独角兽。有友谊手镯和心情戒指。出于习惯，我买了一些东西送给家里的家人，这些东西可以很好地包装——一个大峡谷杯垫，一些山艾树形状的磁铁——然后撕下写着“中国制造”的金色小贴纸。当我每年一次去拜访他们时，总会积累一些杂七杂八的东西。到现在为止，我父母的公寓里已经布满了来自美国各地的此类代币的奇怪碎片。

When the rain starts pelting down in earnest, we pull over and seek shelter in a huge white roadside structure that says JESUS SAVES CHEAP GAS SOUVENIRS. On one side is a stand with two gas pumps, and inside, a cavernous potpourri-scented shop selling cheap magnets of Arizona license plates with different girls’ and boys’ names on them and mugs with slogans like TODAY SOMEONE THINKS YOU’RE AWESOME and NO COFFEE, NO WORKEE. There are glass cases of miniature horses and cowboys and natives with feathered headdresses cast in resin, and an inexplicable unicorn or two. There are friendship bracelets and mood rings. Out of habit, I buy a few things to give to family back home, things that will pack well—​a Grand Canyon coaster, some magnets shaped like sagebrush—​and peel off the tiny gold stickers that say MADE IN CHINA. By the time I make my once-a-year trip to see them, a little motley pile has always accumulated. By now my parents’ apartment is covered in the strange flotsam of such tokens from across America.

收银台的女士给我打电话，对我买的东西赞赏地咯咯笑。“我喜欢这些，”她一边说，一边敲击着山艾树磁铁。“总觉得他们有点傻。”

The woman at the cash register rings me up and clucks appreciatively at my purchases. “I love these,” she says, tapping the sagebrush magnets. “Always think they’re kind of goofy.”

我问她是不是店主，并对我们进去时经过的门前生长的树木表示赞赏。“它们很可爱，”我说，它们确实是，一个高大的三棵树，长着松散的黄绿色叶子，树皮也是绿色的。

I ask if she’s the owner and compliment the stand of trees growing out front that we passed on our way in. “They’re lovely,” I say, and they are, a tall trio bearing a loose froth of yellow-green leaves, with bark that’s green, too.

“都是叶绿素，”她说。她告诉我，它们是她三年前种下的，还有后面的花。

“It’s all the chlorophyll,” she says. She tells me she planted them three years ago, along with the flowers out back.

我真的很惊讶。“你是说这些树只有三年树龄？”

I’m genuinely astonished. “You mean the trees are only three years old?”

她笑了。“当然。来自小小的种子。”

She laughs. “Sure. From little bitty seeds.”

我的反应似乎让她觉得好笑。“亲爱的，这是亚利桑那州的州树，”她告诉我。“帕洛沃德。它们长得真快，可以活到一百岁。”

My reaction seems to amuse her. “It’s the Arizona state tree, honey,” she tells me. “Paloverde. They grow real fast, and can live to be a hundred years old.”

“你从哪来？” 她说，当我回复时，她说：“哦，哇。中国。那是什么样子？

“Where are you from?” she says, and when I reply, she says, “Oh, wow. China. What’s that like?”

当我第一次到达美国时，这个问题常常让我困惑，当时我会回顾高中和家庭的记忆，然后僵住，不知道该说什么。现在我明白了。“很远，”我微笑着说。“这是很不错的。食物不错。”

It was a question that used to throw me, back when I first arrived in the U.S., when I would run through memories of high school and family and then freeze, not knowing what to say. Now I know. “It’s far,” I say, smiling. “It’s very nice. Good food.”

埃里克从后面站起来，用双臂搂住我。“她已经有一段时间没有住在那里了，”他说。“我们现在住在图森。” 我知道他想让我感觉更舒服，但也感觉他在打断我。我喜欢这个女人，她头发花白，擅长园艺，杯子上写着可怕的、善意的口号。

Eric comes up from behind and puts his arms around me. “It’s been a while since she’s lived there,” he says. “We live in Tucson now.” I know he’s trying to make me feel more comfortable, but it also feels like he’s interrupting. I like this woman, with her gray hair, green thumb, and mugs with their terrible, well-meaning slogans.

“天哪，我一直以为我很想去中国，”这位女士说道。“从未离开过这个州。”

“Gosh, I always thought I’d love to go to China,” the woman says. “Never left the state.”

“我真的很喜欢亚利桑那州，”我微笑着告诉她，我突然意识到我确实喜欢。我们搬到这里后不久，我的父母来拜访过一次。我带他们参观了购物中心、公园和博物馆，但他们真正无法克服的是炎热、阳光和广阔的蓝天。我一安定下来，他们就打算跟我一起去。

“I really like Arizona,” I tell her, smiling, and it occurs to me that I do. My parents came to visit once, not long after we’d moved here. I showed them malls and parks and museums, but really what they couldn’t get over was the heat and the sun and the big blue sky. As soon as I settle down, they plan to join me.

头顶上，雨下得很大，我们几乎不得不提高声音。结束后，天空会变成金色，然后变成紫色，这是真正的亚利桑那州日落。我们医院七楼有一个休息室，面向西，可以看到山脉全景。我们的癌症患者喜欢在日落时来访，沉迷于静脉注射。它是如此美丽，有时治疗后他们会回来看望那些健康的人。

Overhead, the rain is thundering so hard that we almost have to raise our voices. When it’s over, the sky will turn gold, and then purple, a true Arizona sunset. There’s a lounge on the seventh floor of our hospital that offers a panoramic vista of the mountains, facing west. Our cancer patients like to visit at sundown, hooked to their IV drips. It’s so beautiful that sometimes after treatment they come back to visit, the ones who are well.

 

到了下午4点，避雨的人数逐渐增多，很快这位女士就忙着接待其他顾客。她拿出了一个插电式炉子和一个咖啡壶，所有的游客和卡车司机突然降临，转动她的明信片旋转木马，缓慢地吱吱作响，凝视着一排排彩绘的许愿蜡烛，她看起来脸红了。“哦，天哪，”她不断地说。“欢迎。真是一场暴风雨啊。”

By 4 p.m., the number of people taking refuge from the rain has swelled, and soon the woman is busy attending to other customers. She’s taken out a plug-in burner and a coffeepot and looks flushed from all the tourists and truckers who’ve suddenly descended, turning her postcard carousels with slow creaks and peering over rows of painted votive candles. “Oh, my,” she keeps saying. “Welcome. What a storm.”

我手里拿着两个咖啡杯，四处寻找埃里克。当我找到他时，他已经退到商店的一端了，店里铺着绿地毯，布置得像一座小教堂，有六个木制长椅和一个空的讲坛。角落里有一架钢琴，琴键看起来像真正的象牙。

I wander in search of Eric, two coffee cups in hand. When I find him, he’s retreated to one end of the store, a green-carpeted expanse set up like a small church, with six wooden pews and an empty pulpit. There’s a piano in one corner with what look like real ivory keys.

“你消失了，”我说，然后挤到他旁边的一张长凳上。

“You disappeared,” I say, and edge into one of the pews beside him.

他没有看我就接过一杯咖啡。“我们可能很快就能回到路上。”

He accepts a coffee cup without looking at me. “We can probably get back on the road soon.”

“不用着急，”我告诉他。“店主在后面有一些饼干，她说她会给每个人带来，”我说。“她为这家公司感到非常高兴。”

“There’s no hurry,” I tell him. “The owner has some cookies in the back she says she’ll bring out for everyone,” I say. “She’s so happy for all this company.”

这部分建筑的屋顶是倾斜的，这里的雨声不大；它发出柔和、感性的声音。我将手指放在咖啡杯上，温暖它们，然后将头靠在埃里克的肩膀上。他的眼睛看着前方，好像在看有人布道，他用手臂搂住我，心不在焉地梳理着我的一缕头发。

The roof slants over this part of the building, and here the rain isn’t so loud; it makes a soft, sensuous patter. I spread my fingers over the coffee cup, warming them, and lean my head on Eric’s shoulder. His eyes are to the front, as though watching someone deliver a sermon, and he puts his arm around me and absently tweaks a strand of my hair.

“那个女人说前面的那些树只有三年了，”我告诉他。“这不是很神奇吗？”

“The woman says those trees out front are only three years old,” I tell him. “Isn’t that amazing?”

他说是的。

He says it is.

我们安静了一会儿，听着雨声。在我们身后，我能听到孩子们的笑声，听起来就像是一场聚会正在进行。我回头看向柜台。一个戴着棒球帽的大个子男人买了一罐装饰性的辣椒和焦糖爆米花，并大声敦促其他人吃。他旁边的女人，可能是他的妻子，正在摇头翻白眼。远处传来一声巨大的雷声，人群集体欢呼，一种感激的呼喊，外面是外面，我们在里面。

We are quiet for a while, listening to the rain. Behind us, I can hear children laughing, and what sounds almost like a party in progress. I peek back toward the counter. A large man with a baseball cap has purchased one of those decorative tins of chili and caramel popcorn, and is loudly urging others to dig in. The woman beside him, his wife, probably, is shaking her head and rolling her eyes. There’s a mighty crack of thunder in the distance, and a collective cry from the crowd, an appreciative one, that it is outside and we are in.

我转身再次面向前方。长椅的木质不太舒服，但埃里克似乎并不想移动。

I turn back to face the front again. The wood of the pew isn’t comfortable, but Eric doesn’t seem inclined to move.

“这是一次愉快的旅行，”我最后说道，同时考虑是否应该向他询问口红的事。

“It’s been a good trip,” I offer at last, wondering if I should ask him about the lipstick.

他点点头，亲吻我的头，然后又吻了一下我的肩膀。长椅的一个角落里堆放着一堆平装圣经。我想象着这里安静的周日和礼拜仪式，和平的逝去。有时在肿瘤病房，我会做一些从医院牧师那里学到的祈祷，还有从病人那里学到的其他祈祷。上帝赐予我智慧去接受我无法改变的事情就是其中之一，有一段时间我为病人背诵了这句话，直到有人告诉我这是为酗酒者祈祷。

He nods and kisses my head, then deposits another kiss on one shoulder. The pew has a pile of softcover Bibles stacked in one corner. I imagine quiet Sundays here and the liturgy, the passing of the peace. Sometimes in the oncology ward, I’ll offer a few prayers that I learned from the hospital chaplain, and others from patients, too. God grant me the wisdom to accept the things I cannot change was one, and for a while I recited it for patients, until someone told me it was a prayer for alcoholics.

我把埃里克的手放在我的手里仔细研究，他温暖地握住我的手，将它卷曲在我的手指上。我想，我认识这个人的时间比我认识大多数人的时间还要长。我们一起吃饭、一起乘车无数次，我们的牙刷并排挂了近十年。我认为他很软弱，但也很善良、心肠温柔，在这样的时刻，我告诉自己这就足够了。

I put Eric’s hand in mine and study it, and he curls it around my fingers in a warm grip. I have known this man longer than I have known most people, I think. We have shared countless meals and car rides and our toothbrushes have hung side by side for almost a decade. He is weak, I think, but also kind, and tenderhearted, and in moments like these, I tell myself that’s enough.

雨下了一会儿，然后突然开始下起来。就在我们起身离开之前，埃里克用他那轮廓分明的下巴向小教堂的前面做了个手势。“有一天我们就会成为这样的人，pickle，”他满意地告诉我。

The rain comes down a while longer and then abruptly begins to lift. Just before we stand to leave, Eric gestures toward the front of the small chapel with one movement of his well-cut jaw. “That’ll be us someday, pickle,” he tells me with satisfaction.

他说这话时的神情就像是在观看地平线上美丽的日落，在我停顿了一会儿之后我就同意了。

He says it with the air of watching a beautiful sunset on the horizon, and there is only the slightest of pauses before I agree.

古北口精神

Gubeikou Spirit

潘女士拎着钱包，穿过人群，全速驶入古北口站。时间已经很晚了，她的父亲会变得焦躁不安，容易徘徊。她需要回家，上火车。队伍的末端，一名警卫懒洋洋地在她的粗呢大衣两侧挥舞着他的安全棒，减慢了她的速度。“我很着急，”她哀怨地说。

Pan entered Gubeikou Station at top speed, hurtling through the crowds, hand on her purse. It was late and her father would be getting restless, prone to wandering; she needed to get home, get on the train. At the end of the line a guard lazily waved his security wand over her duffel coat, both sides, slowing her down. “I’m in a hurry,” she said plaintively.

下了台阶，然后快步走上太浅的楼梯，避开反方向的行人，坚定地抓着行李走。“让我过去！” 她哭了。但当时是下午5点，古北口却人头攒动。一列火车刚刚抵达，下了更多的人，现在正朝出口走去。她被人群撞到墙上。

Down the steps, then, quick-stepping on the too-shallow stairs, dodging the march of people headed in the opposite direction, determinedly clutching their bags as they went. “Let me through!” she cried. But it was 5 p.m. and Gubeikou was crowded. A train had just arrived, disgorging more people now headed to the exits; she was beaten back against the wall by the crowds.

当她到达楼梯脚时，火车门已经关上了。它已经离开车站了。

By the time she reached the foot of the stairs the train doors had closed; it had left the station.

没关系，潘想。她会得到下一件。她走到一张长凳前，坐下。她提醒自己，欲速则不达。今天她在收银台算错了零钱，结果少了20元：她必须补上差额。小时候在家里，家人给她起了个绰号“然侯讷？” 因为她总是问“然后呢？” 从她年轻的时候起。

That was all right, Pan thought. She’d get the next one. She made her way to a bench, sat down. Haste didn’t pay, she reminded herself. Today she’d miscounted the change at the register and ended up 20 yuan short: she’d had to make up the difference. At home as a child, her family had nicknamed her Ranhou Ne? because she was always asking “And then?” from the time she was young.

“我今天买了一些韭菜，”她妈妈可能会说。

“I got some leeks today,” her mother might say.

“进而？”

“And then?”

“我去煮点汤。

“I’ll make some soup.

“进而？”

“And then?”

“然后我们就吃掉它。”

“And then we’ll eat it.”

“进而？”

“And then?”

“然后你就会去睡觉，不再问问题，宝贝。”

“And then you’ll go to sleep and stop asking questions, baby.”

车站里挤满了人。一名烫发的中年妇女在她身边坐下，拨弄着她钱包上的扣子。他们对面是一则黄色广告，广告中一只咧着嘴笑的杰克罗素梗犬在空中跳跃，捕捉看起来像世界的东西，一个地球仪。它太大了：潘怀疑狗能否抓住它；它只会从他的鼻子上无害地弹开。

The station filled with people. A middle-aged woman with a perm sat down beside her and fiddled with the clasp on her purse. Opposite them was a yellow ad featuring a grinning Jack Russell terrier jumping in the air to catch what looked like the world, a globe. It was too large: Pan doubted the dog would be able to catch it; it would just bounce harmlessly off his nose.

又过了十分钟。然后，广播通知：“下一班火车将晚点。我们感谢您的理解。”

Another ten minutes passed. Then, an announcement: “The next train will be delayed. We thank you for your understanding.”

这列火车是一个奇迹，只有两年的历史，是最先进的。它的门像一张唱歌的嘴一样打开，发出欢快的铃声，二十秒后精确地关闭。目前已建成 26 条线路，另有 10 条正在建设中。世界上没有其他城市能如此迅速地修建地铁站。
